[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Hi! My name is Grzegorz Gajewski.   I have been playing chess for almost thirty years now. Looking back at my career, there were three defining moments. Achieving a grandmaster title was the first of them. Adding my name to the theory of chess openings with the so-called Gajewski Gambit - the second.   However, without a doubt the most important moment was meeting Viswanathan Anand. When I joined Vishy's team in 2014 before the Sochi match I couldn't have predicted that I would soon become his main second for the next seven years! Seven years of hard work, I must admit.   During this period, I had learnt how to work on openings like a World Champion. How to truly understand them and not just thoughtlessly repeat memorized lines.   Vishy is known to be a wonderful 1. e4 player. Therefore preparing the lines for him against the Berlin, the Marshall or the Petroff was an immense challenge. With time, I began to realize that my understanding of these openings has improved enormously. Today, I am happy to share it with you.      Part 1 of the course covers the Ruy Lopez, Petroff Defence, Philidor Defence Pirc and Modern. Naturally the Ruy Lopez, being much bigger than the other openings combined, is the core part of the course. You may ask why, the Italian is also promising, right? The Scotch Game is also interesting, isn't it? They all are.   The thing is, however, that they have maybe 20 percent of Ruy Lopez's richness. The so-called Spanish Defence has so many different plans and structures that you can never play another opening and still think that chess is fascinating!   I have put my best effort in explaining the plans and ideas in order to make this course accessible to all. Whether you are a 1200 rated player or a 2000 rated player you will benefit from taking it, and in most of the lines I will be discussing the middlegame plans too so you can think of it as an all-in-one course.   Those of you, who consider themselves professionals or would like to become one, will find in my course many new ideas to successfully combat even the toughest variations of the Ruy Lopez, as well as the Petroff, Philidor and Pirc/Modern.   I didn't really hide anything and, as a result, there are many so-called “novelties”. To tell you the truth, at some point I just stopped marking them - only really important ones are highlighted, so you can say that there is more to it than meets the eye @@StartBracket@@pun intended@@EndBracket@@. You will also see how - in my experience - a serious and professional work on openings should look like.   The trends change - Garry Kasparov revolutionized the art of opening preparation and all the greatest players followed suit. Anand, Kramnik or Topalov - they all understood that a real fight starts in the opening.   Then Magnus Carlsen arrived, playing all kinds of openings - the serious ones and not-so-serious ones too - he became a no. 1 player in the world. He has shown that you can do things differently - in particular that you don't necessarily need to fight for an advantage in the opening.   He demonstrated that if you understand the position better or you are simply a better player - and in Carlsen’s case it is usually both - you will get your chances in the middle-game, or perhaps in the endgame. It was an interesting approach and many players started following it, but it was not without its flaws.   One thing that I remember vividly is the Sochi match. When playing Black, Carlsen kept on changing the lines in order to avoid our preparation. He was very clever with his choices but nevertheless, it didn’t let him avoid opening problems as Vishy was well prepared.   Carlsen eventually won the match but I think it was harder for him than the final score might suggest. He also didn’t try it for the second time. During his encounter with Fabiano Caruana, the World Champion was already a different kind of player - extremely well prepared and ready to enter long theoretical disputes with arguably the best-prepared player in the world.   Today, it seems that both trends, i.e. seeking advantage out of the opening preparation as well as betting your chances on outplaying the opponent in the middle/end game co-exist.   Most of the top players are very flexible and you can never be sure what to expect from them. One thing we can be pretty certain on though - their preparation is always top-notch,  In my course, you will find some pretty short lines - twelve moves long, fourteen moves long etc.   When I feel the position is good on positional grounds, I stop my analysis early and focus on explaining the middle game plans, as it is more important than memorizing a few more moves. However, very often this is not possible.   In many variations, the real theory begins on move 14 or even later. Usually such lines are sharp, some of them very sharp. TheMoller,Arkhangelsk, theZaitsev, theOpen, and few more - you can actually win a game in these, thanks to the preparation, or at least get a substantial edge. So don't be afraid of long lines - as difficult as they might seem. I believe it is going to be quite rewarding work for all of you.     On a final note, I hope you will enjoy taking this course, and that it will bring you many tournament wins.   Best of luck!     Grzegorz     PS. I am aware that my name might be quite tricky for most of you to pronounce, so if you want to reach out to me with feedback, or when you will be telling your friends about this awesome course you have just finished, you can refer to me as Greg. All the best! }
*

