[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez,  Steinitz Defense #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6
{ The classical Steinitz Defense did not stand the test of time and already for a long time it has been considered passive and unpromising, though some strong players still try it occasionally. }
4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bd7 6. Nc3 Nf6
{ I guess it's logical but Black's position is just too passive. } 7. O-O
{ It was also possible to play more aggressively for instance  7.Bxc6  bxc6  8.Qf3!?  . }
7... Be7 8. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Recapturing with the Pawn might seem tempting as White has to use a tempo for the Bishop's retreat. }
9. Bd3
{ However, once retreated to d3, White's Bishop is clearly superior to its counterpart. }
9... O-O 10. f4
{ It would be fully justified to stop right now as our position is already pleasant and there are more than one way possible. Let's check it a bit deeper, though - Black has many moves but basically two main ideas - d6-d5 and c6-c5. }
10... d5 { If Black wants to play d6-d5 then there was no point delaying it. }
11. e5 Ng4 12. Kh1 { Defending against 12...Bc5+. } 12... g6
{ Black's position is already difficult, the Knight won't stay on g4 for long so it was about time to secure f5 and prepare Nh6 - Nf5. }
13. Qe2 { Now f4-f5 is a threat. } 13... Nh6
{ Black managed to defend against our most direct threat but his position remains tough. Black will struggle with finding a reasonable plan while we won't have that problem. }
14. b3
{ The Bishop will do great on b2. After that we have a couple of interesting plans - Nc3-a4 followed by c2-c4 is one of them. It is also possible prepare f4-f5 and this we can do in two ways @@StartBracket@@which can be combined, if necessary@@EndBracket@@: h2-h3 and g2-g4 or Nc3-d1-e3. }
