[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Open Spanish #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variants to be a real challenge for black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each variant does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variants, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you fight the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Nxe4
{ Open Ruy is a bit different than other variations of Ruy Lopez. While in Chigorin, Breyer, Zaitsev or others the position is usually closed or semi-open, here it's usually open - hence then name. }
6. d4
{ The only way to challenge 5...Nxe4. White takes advantage of the e-file. }
6... b5
{ The main continuation - Black wants to go d7-d5 but he is pushing our Bishop away from a4-e8 diagonal first. }
7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6
{ I find the Open Ruy Lopez one of the most difficult but rewarding openings for Black. After  9.c3  Be7  @@StartBracket@@there is also  9...Bc5  but it's not simpler at all!@@EndBracket@@  10.Nbd2  Black can choose mainly between  10...O-O  11.Bc2  f5  . Both lines promise full equality but no matter which one Black chooses - the number of variations, that have to be memorized, is scary.  Therefore I wouldn't recommend this system to players under 2500 Elo points - you guys are still at the learning stage and it's far better to learn by understanding rather than memorizing. 'Ok, but this a repertoire for White not Black, so what should I do?' - the reader will ask.  I am happy to provide you with answer that - with a little bit of luck - will stand for more than one game. }
9. c3
{ In my opinion this is more accurate than 9. Nbd2. What is the difference between the two move-orders?   9.Nbd2  allows immediate  9...Nc5  10.c3  d4!?  The line has been extensively covered by Swiercz who claims that White has slight edge. I will not dwell into the details but I simply believe otherwise - Black can achieve a draw fairly easily and in more than one way.   9. c3 cuts off this line completely. What is the downside? The Dilworth Variation! Is it? Not for us! }
9... Bc5
{ Instead of normal e7 Black is choosing an active square - c5. It is a clear sign that the Knight is not going to step back. }
10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Bc2 Nxf2
{ This is how the Dilworth Variation begins. It is a fun line, though currently it is fun for White mostly. }
12. Rxf2 f6 13. Nf1
{ For a long time  13.exf6  was played almost automatically but the recent practice has shown that after  13...Bxf2+  14.Kxf2  Qxf6  Black should be ok so most of the players shifted to another direction. White sacrifices a Pawn in order to catch up with development. }
13... Bxf2+
{ Since White was ready to go 14. Be3 Black could not wait any longer. } 14.
Kxf2 fxe5 15. Kg1
{ For us this is the main position of the line. Black has a Rook and two Paws for two pieces but I think that more important thing is whether White can force Black to push one of the central Pawns and then set up a blockade on the squares of the opposite color.   For now the hardest part is to learn all the possibilities for Black and there are a few that we should know. But first let's take another look at the position - 16. Bxh7+ is a threat. }
15... Bg4
{ I am not sure if it's the best continuation but it's the main one. Black is dragging White's Knight to the wrong position. }
16. Ne3 Be6
{ But not  16...Bxf3?  17.gxf3  with big advantage. Now the problem is - how to develop the dark-squared Bishop? }
17. b3
{ Why not? White wants to play Bc1-a3 but also Bc1-b2 is there. Additionally at some point we might want to undermine Black's pawn center with c3-c4. }
17... b4
{ Black wants to fight for the center but the result will be opposite: } 18. c4
dxc4 { 18...d4??  19.Qd3  g6  20.Nd5  would be just winning. } 19. Nxc4
{ White's minor pieces are clearly stronger than black Rooks. } *

