[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez, Moller #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variants to be a real challenge for black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each variant does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variants, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you fight the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Bc5 6. c3 b5
{ By developing the Bishop first and only then placing the Pawn on b5, Black is playing against a2-a4 line. I mean we can still go a2-a4 @@StartBracket@@and we will@@EndBracket@@ but he will no longer have to settle for Ra8-b8. }
7. Bb3
{ For many years  7.Bc2  was considered more accurate with  7...d5!?  being a nice way of surprising the opponent but no more than that. In recent years it became clear that  7.Bc2  d5  is a very serious @@StartBracket@@and complicated!@@EndBracket@@ line.   Most of the players still use it occasionally as they don't want to lose the surprise value. What does it mean for us? In my opinion it's just not practical to allow it. I saw Swiercz's analysis after 7...d5 - many pages of extensive analysis in very sharp positions where first mistake of is usually the last one.   It can be useful if you are expecting the line but are you willing to memorize it, refresh it every week or so and then still risk forgetting it? I am not. It is a very pragmatic choice as we don't need two separate lines for 5...Bc5 and 5...b5. But - as you will see - it doesn’t mean we are willing to compromise. }
7... d6 8. a4
{ The bad news is that - compared with 5...b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 move order - Black has two extra options:   8...Bb7  and  8...Bg4  . The good news is that, even combined, they are still much smaller and overall less annoying than the 7. Bc2 d5 line is. }
8... Bb7
{ This is the main reason that discourages White from playing 7. Bb3. Recently  9.d3  h6  10.Nh4  has been tested in some top level games but not very successfully. I actually believe that this is great news for White - we can easily challenge this line and, although Black should be able to equalize with accurate play, it is going to be a very difficult task for him, as you shall see. }
9. d4 Bb6 10. Re1
{ The Rook defends central Pawn but the real intentions are less peaceful - when Black castles we want to develop the Bishop to g5. }
10... O-O 11. Bg5
{ This is a very committal decision as it will most likely be connected with a piece sacrifice. }
11... h6 12. Bh4 Qe7
{ This was Swiercz's try in his game against John Bryant in Las Vegas Open 2018. White reacted with  13.Na3  and this is also what Swiercz recommended in his book.   The lines he gave however, were very complicated why the final evaluation somewhat optimistic. Luckily I think I managed to find something both simpler and stronger. Black's main thesis is that White can't develop the Knight to d2. Can't we? }
13. Nbd2 { As it turns out - we can! } 13... g5
{ Moves like that always have to be considered. } 14. Nxg5 hxg5 15. Bxg5 exd4
{ Black has to take Pawn in order to gain access to some central squares. } 16.
e5
{ It is based on tactics but by just looking at our Rook on e1 we can sense that this is the way. }
16... Nxe5 { But not  16...dxe5??  17.Ne4  and White is winning. } 17. cxd4
{ There are other moves but this is strong and simple, so why bother? } 17...
Bxd4 18. Ne4 { Basically the only move but it was part of ourplan all along. }
