9. d3 { 9.c3  would still be met with  9...d5!  with even bigger effect. } 9...
d6
{ This position has already appeared in thousands of games from both Anti-Marshall and Archangelsk. Both sides have agreed to slow down the action and develop the pieces first. }
10. h3
{ For a long time  10.Nbd2  was considered to be the most critical continuation. However, the recent games after  10...Nd7!  have proven that Black can fully solve his opening problems in that line.  Peter Svidler's recent win against Dariusz Swiercz in Sinquefield Cup was rather an exception as Black badly blundered in that game. Therefore I believe we should move our attention to another possibility. }
10... Na5
{ Basically this is the only sensible continuation. I will only note that  10...Nd7  doesn't work now - white can simply reply with  11.Be3! }
11. Ba2 c5 12. Nbd2
{ This is basically the 10. Nbd2 Na5 line with h2-h3 committed. Still a good enough try. }
12... bxa4
{ This an improved version of Evgenij Tomashevsky's old love @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1bp1bppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/P3P3/1B1P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.Nbd2  Na5  11.Ba2  c5  12.Nf1  bxa4  . Here we played h3 instead of Nf1 which should improve things for Black, however White can still fight for the advantage. }
13. Nf1 Bc8 14. Ne3 Rb8 15. Bd2
{ White is threatening  15...--  16.Bxa5  Qxa5  and  17.Bb3! } 15... Bd7
{ So the Bishop comes with help... } 16. b3
{ A difficult decision but the right one! } 16... a3
{ I think it's a better practical choice than  16...axb3  . Black ignores the pawn sacrifice choosing to lock our light-squared Bishop instead.  On the other hand White's pawn structure will be superior. The game will slow down from now on. }
17. Bb1 Nc6
{ The Knight had no future on a5. On c6 it controls some important squares. }
18. Rxa3
{ The position is quite different from what were seeing after 16...axb3. Still the main factor remains the same - the weak Pawn on a6. }
18... a5 19. Nc4 Ra8 20. c3
{ The Bishop will no longer attack the Pawn but other things are more important: b4 and d4 are now covered while the funnily looking Bishop on b1 will now be able to move to c2, which - as a result - will allow the other Rook to move to the a file as well.   In the long run we want to place the Knight on d5 in such a way that taking it would force the Black Knight to retreat from c6. Black, on the other hand, is forced to adjust to White's moves which is always more difficult. }
*

