{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6. Re1 is better than 6. d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6. d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening 7. Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 O-O
{ Black is hoping to get a famous Marshall Gambit with 8. c3 d5! @@StartBracket@@or not so famous Upgraded Gajewski Gambit with 8. c3 Na5!? :-@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@.   My little thing is probably not enough reason to abandon 8. c3 but Marshall definitely can be.   After  8.c3  d5!  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Rxe5  c6  - long story short - Black gets a sufficient compensation for the Pawn thanks to the strong Bishop pair and underdevelopment of White's pieces @@StartBracket@@look at the queenside@@EndBracket@@.   What used to be an exciting line has, at some point, become a large collection of long forced lines leading to one outcome only. Definitely not what we are looking for. }
8. a4
{ This is one of the most serious Anti-Marshall Systems out there. By our last move we have created a direct challenge for Black - should he develop the Bishop to b7 or push the Pawn to b4? }
8... b4
{ The main continuation. It makes a lot of sense as well as Black takes control over important c3 square. At the same time the light-squared Bishop is being kept on c8 so - depending on White's follow-up - it can go to b7, e6 and @@StartBracket@@in some cases@@EndBracket@@ g4.   Why doesn't everyone go for it all the time then? I think the main reason is that there are many possible lines White can choose from and the solutions to those lines aren't always that simple. }
9. d4
{ In 2020 most of the top players were keener to go for  9.a5  instead but it is understandable - everyone looks for some fresh territory where the theory is still not that developed. In that sense  9.a5  has caught up with the mainline which - without a doubt - our choice is. }
9... d6 10. dxe5
{ The strategic explanation of White's last move is that - while the pawn structure on the kingside might become symmetrical - it will slightly differ on the queenside and the change is in our favour. Black queenside Pawns are potential targets, White has a better light-squared Bishop and one day we might try opening up the c file. }
10... Nxe5
{ This move became fashionable once Black realized that after  10...dxe5  it was very easy to mix up the lines which on many occasions led to Black's severe opening problems.   Recapturing with the Knight is also quite sound - after 10...dxe5 it's the Knight on c6 has always been sort of the problem for Black. What is the downside then? We don't have to take on e5! }
11. Bf4
{ I was surprised to see this natural move on the periphery of the opening theory. I am pretty sure that the top players have it covered @@StartBracket@@whether they remember it is a different story@@EndBracket@@ but I am also quite sure that the majority of the rest of us - don't :-@@EndBracket@@ .   11.Nbd2  is also interesting, however once you get through Nepomniachtchi - So from the Jerusalem Grand Prix 2019 @@StartBracket@@a fine example of how serious preparation should look like@@EndBracket@@, it is not easy to come up with something fresh. Against 11. Bf4   I am going to consider three possible continuations for Black:  11...Nfd7  ,  11...Nxf3+  and  11...Ng6  .   The fourth possibility  11...Bb7  will transpose to one of the above after  11.Nbd2  Nxf3+  12.Qxf3  or if 11...Ng6 White can play 12. Bg3 . }
11... Ng6
{ This is the most popular continuation but I am not sure it's the best practical choice for Black. }
12. Bg3
{ Not a perfect square for the Bishop but it does control some important squares in the center. }
12... Bb7 { Putting the Bishop on b7 is part of Black's setup. } 13. Nbd2 Nd7
{ This is stronger than  13...Nh5  . The Knight is coming to c5. } 14. Nc4
{ White Knight takes the central square. We know threaten both 15. Na4 and 15. e5. }
14... a5 { This natural move prevents 15. Na5 but it doesn't stop 15. e5! } 15.
e5 Nc5 16. exd6 cxd6 17. Qe2
{ White has a small advantage in this interesting position. We are playing against the isolani here so our next move would be 18. Rad1.   It might be tempting for Black to take  17...Nxb3  18.cxb3  and then go  18...d5  . However after simple  19.Rad1  he doesn't really have a good square for his Queen. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez, Anti-Marshall #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variants to be a real challenge for black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each variant does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variants, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you fight the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Be7
{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6. Re1 is better than 6. d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6. d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening 7. Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 O-O
{ Black is hoping to get a famous Marshall Gambit with 8. c3 d5! @@StartBracket@@or not so famous Upgraded Gajewski Gambit with 8. c3 Na5!? :-@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@.   My little thing is probably not enough reason to abandon 8. c3 but Marshall definitely can be.   After  8.c3  d5!  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Rxe5  c6  - long story short - Black gets a sufficient compensation for the Pawn thanks to the strong Bishop pair and underdevelopment of White's pieces @@StartBracket@@look at the queenside@@EndBracket@@.   What used to be an exciting line has, at some point, become a large collection of long forced lines leading to one outcome only. Definitely not what we are looking for. }
8. a4
{ This is one of the most serious Anti-Marshall Systems out there. By our last move we have created a direct challenge for Black - should he develop the Bishop to b7 or push the Pawn to b4? }
8... b4
{ The main continuation. It makes a lot of sense as well as Black takes control over important c3 square. At the same time the light-squared Bishop is being kept on c8 so - depending on White's follow-up - it can go to b7, e6 and @@StartBracket@@in some cases@@EndBracket@@ g4.   Why doesn't everyone go for it all the time then? I think the main reason is that there are many possible lines White can choose from and the solutions to those lines aren't always that simple. }
9. d4
{ In 2020 most of the top players were keener to go for  9.a5  instead but it is understandable - everyone looks for some fresh territory where the theory is still not that developed. In that sense  9.a5  has caught up with the mainline which - without a doubt - is our choice. }
9... d6 10. dxe5
{ The strategic explanation of White's last move is that - while the pawn structure on the kingside might become symmetrical - it will slightly differ on the queenside and the change is in our favour. Black queenside Pawns are potential targets, White has a better light-squared Bishop and one day we might try opening up the c file. }
10... dxe5
{ This line is difficult for White and incredibly difficult for Black. It is caused by multiple possible move orders and lots of nuances which combined together make even the best players in the world stumble. }
11. Nbd2
{ We have almost symmetrical Pawn structure with small differences on the queenside. These differences however determine the plans for both sides. White has a beautiful square on c4.   It is a long lasting asset which he can use by placing on this square his Knight, Bishop and - in some cases - the Queen. There are also potential outposts on d5 and c5 but these two are quite tricky as Black controls them quite well.   Black queenside Pawns are potential targets and occasionally we might get a chance to open the c file with c2-c3. On the other hand Black controls d4, he will also activate his dark-squared Bishop on the next move. }
11... Bc5
{ Any other move would be a clear sign that our opponent doesn't have a clue about the line. For instance  11...Bg4?!  12.h3  Bxf3   or  12...Bh5  13.Nc4  and the Bishop is out of the real game  13.Nxf3  Qxd1  14.Rxd1  with a clear advantage for White. In general Black should be careful with swapping the light-squared Bishop as his light squares are weak enough. }
12. a5 h6
{ This is what the majority of the players do. Black is waiting for White to put the Queen on e2 if we do that he will then be able to put his own Queen on e7 as Bb3-d5 will no longer work. We are going to try to undermine that logic. }
13. Qe2
{ Almost everyone goes  13.h3  here basically playing against  13...Qe7  as  14.Bd5  is still there. But firstly -  14.Bd5  is not so strong anymore and secondly - we are not afraid of  13...Qe7  , we actually welcome it! }
13... Qd6
{ Ironically this still looks like the best choice for Black. At least it would be my choice. }
14. h3
{ The immediate  14.Nc4  is not as strong - it only gives Black more options. }
14... Be6 { This is by far the most popular continuation. } 15. Nc4
{ Here Black was ready for 15. Bc4 as he didn't spend time for Rf8-d8. } 15...
Qe7 16. Be3 { We now want to play 17. Ba4 so Black has to prepare. } 16... Rad8
{ This inaccurate move was played in Sevian - Swiercz in St. Louis Winter 2017. Black is more or less ready for  17.Ba4  as he has  17...Bxe3  18.Nxe3  @@StartBracket@@with the Rook on a8 there would be 18. Bxc6!@@EndBracket@@  18...Qc5  . However, he is not prepared for... }
17. Bxc5 { In the source game White played weaker  17.Ncd2  . } 17... Qxc5 18.
Ncd2 { The Pawn is hanging and also White threatens with 19. Bxe6. } 18... Bc8
{ Surely this is not the most pleasant move to make but  18...Bxb3  19.Nxb3  Qb5  20.Qxb5  axb5  would give White a strong passed Pawn. }
19. Qe3
{ White has a very nice positional advantage, his pieces are better placed and he has a couple of good plans such as c2-c3 @@StartBracket@@especially after 19... Qxe3 20. Rxe3@@EndBracket@@ or standard Bb3-c4 and Nd2-b3-c5. }
