5... Be7
{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6. Re1 is better than 6. d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6. d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening 7. Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 d6
{ A general rule is that if Black doesn't want to go for the Marshall Gambit, he should play 7...d6 before castling as it avoids some Anti-Marshall lines, mainly  8.a4  where Black can now simply go  8...Bd7  . }
8. c3
{ White is preparing d2-d4 but also securing his light-squared Bishop against  8...Na5  - we can now go  9.Bc2  . }
8... O-O 9. h3
{ Before advancing the d-pawn it is useful to cover the g4-square. Immediate  9.d4  allows  9...Bg4  leading to interesting play but - once again speaking in concepts - it would be a small victory for Black. }
9... h6
{ The Smyslov Variation really is a worse version of the Zaitsev. Black wants to achieve the same setup @@StartBracket@@Re8 and Bf8@@EndBracket@@ but first he wants to prevent Nf3-g5. However, it gives White enough time to complete our desirable setup - Nbd2-f1-g3. }
10. d4 Re8 11. Nbd2 Bf8 12. Nf1
{ The e4-pawn is indirectly defended with Bb3-d5 fork. } 12... Bd7
{ In most cases the Bishop is better off here. } 13. Ng3 Na5
{ Once again it is hard to think of some other plan for Black. } 14. Bc2 c5 15.
b3
{ 15.d5  was also possible. After  15...Nc4  16.a4  Nb6  17.a5  Nc4  18.b4  cxb4  19.cxb4  , This is clearly an interesting position with the evaluation resting in the 'slightly better' range - for White, of course. }
15... cxd4
{ It looks like some strange version of Chigorin Variation but White clearly benefits from it. }
16. cxd4 Nc6 17. d5 Nb4 18. Bb1
{ Notice that Black usually wants to activate his dark-square Bishop via d8. From this perspective the whole h7-h6, Rf8-e8, Be7-f8 setup was not very successful, don't you agree?   We will push the Knight back to a6 @@StartBracket@@Black has to go 18...a5 now@@EndBracket@@ with 19. a3 and then we can develop the Bishop to e3 and place the Knight on d2. Then Qd1-f3 and Re1-c1 seems like a good plan. }
