9... Nd7
{ Black wants to bring the Knight to b6 while the Bishop can take his place on f6. However, just like in 9...a5 line - White will dominate in the center. }
10. d4 Bf6
{ This allows us to close the position ensuring White's advantage in the center and on the Queenside. }
11. a4 Bb7 12. d5 Ne7 13. Be3
{ This is less popular than  13.axb5  but equally strong. Never mind the consequences Black just has to bring the Knight to c5. Otherwise White will quickly increase the pressure with c3-c4 or Nb1-a3. }
13... Nc5 14. Bc2
{ This is more ambitious than  14.Bxc5  @@StartBracket@@which would be slightly better for White@@EndBracket@@. }
14... c6
{ Trying to fight back.  14...Nxa4  15.Bxa4  bxa4  16.c4  would be easily better for White. }
15. c4 { The beginning of an excellent idea. } 15... bxc4 16. Bxc5 dxc5 17. d6
Nc8 18. d7
{ This Pawn is a real hero, sacrificing his life for the greater good. } 18...
Nb6 19. a5 Nxd7 20. Nbd2
{ Despite being a Pawn up Black's position is ugly - just look at his pieces. Our Knight will soon land on c4 where it will be supported by the light-squared Bishop on b3. The Queen will come to c2 and the Rook will move from e1 to d1. }
