[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez, Breyer "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variants to be a real challenge for black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each variant does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variants, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you fight the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Be7
{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6. Re1 is better than 6. d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6. d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening 7. Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 d6
{ A general rule is that if Black doesn't want to go for the Marshall Gambit, he should play 7...d6 before castling as it avoids some Anti-Marshall lines, mainly  8.a4  where Black can now simply go  8...Bd7  . }
8. c3
{ White is preparing d2-d4 but also securing his light-squared Bishop against  8...Na5  - we can now go  9.Bc2  . }
8... O-O 9. h3
{ Before advancing the d-pawn it is useful to cover the g4-square. Immediate  9.d4  allows  9...Bg4  leading to interesting play but - once again speaking in concepts - it would be a small victory for Black. }
9... Nb8
{ The Breyer Variation has always been considered one of the most solid openings for Black. But solidity is not its only virtue - it is also very flexible. Therefore it quickly became one of the favorite shelters for players who wanted to avoid a sharp fight right after the opening without compromising Black's position.   The main idea of Black's last move is to improve the position of the Knight as it will be much safer and sounder on d7. It is also good news for the light-squared Bishop as, once it is developed on b7, it won't be covered by that Knight.   But all of this, along with the further follow-up @@StartBracket@@Rf8-e8 and Be7-f8 and very likely g7-g6 and Bf8-g7@@EndBracket@@ has been well known for decades. I see this as one of the main disadvantages of the Breyer - its once hidden and often misunderstood subtleties are now comprehensible for the majority of players.   The other one is purely chess-related - The line is simply passive. }
10. d4 { As usual, we take control over the center when we are allowed to. }
10... Nbd7 11. Nbd2
{ This is a temporary square for the Knight as it is heading to g3. } 11... Bb7
{ The main continuation. Black is developing the Bishop to a natural square targeting our central Pawn. }
12. Bc2
{ It is necessary to do it as we want to be able to move the Knight from d2. }
12... Re8 { Starting a typical maneuver of fianchettoing the Bishop. } 13. Nf1
{ Finally the Knight can move. } 13... Bf8 14. Ng3 g6
{ Apart from a couple of sidelines which we had already seen, this is basically the starting position of the Breyer with thousands of games and numerous plans for both sides.   Learning and understanding those plans should be an important part of development for every chess player. Nonetheless, this is not the topic of the course so let's move on. }
15. Bd2
{ Why develop the Bishop to such a strange square? Let me answer this one -  15.Be3  is not really an option because the Bishop is covering the Rook so after  15...exd4  White can't recapture  16.cxd4  as it would cost us the Pawn on e4.   15.Bg5!?  h6  16.Bd2  is another interesting line, where White wants to provoke h7-h6 as it weakens the position of the black King. We, however, don't want to provoke it but rather prevent it as then both Bh6 and Bg5 will be at our disposal and both of them can be useful.   It is also worth noting that tempi are not so important anymore because both sides don't really have a lot of good moves - almost every choice is connected with creating some target for the opponent: a2-a4 weakens a4 and b3, c7-c5 weakens d5, d6, and also allows d4-d5 @@StartBracket@@otherwise there would be c7-c6@@EndBracket@@ and so on... }
15... Bg7
{ I will not discuss  15...h6  as it simply transposes to the 15.Bg5 h6 16.Bd2 line with an extra tempo for White. }
16. Qc1
{ So we have got it! If Black doesn't do anything we will simply play Bd2-h6. Strategically, it is a good trade for White as Black will not be able to cover some dark squares in his camp: h6, f6 but also a5 will become weak. In case of c7-c5, he would also have to deal with the weakness on d6. }
16... c5
{ I am not a big fan of this move - it makes sense when a2-a4 is played as after d4-d5 Black has c5-c4! gaining a nice square for the Knight on c5 from where it would attack White's fresh weaknesses - a4 and b3. However, here this is not the case. }
17. d5 Qc7
{ 17...c4  would be answered by  18.b4!  with total control over the queenside. White can start thinking about the other side... }
18. b3
{ Not the most pleasant position for Black as he doesn't have a good plan on the queenside -  18...c4  can be answered with both  19.b4  a5  20.a4!  and  19.bxc4!?   After slower  18...a5  White can just clear the situation out with  19.c4  b4  20.a3  and soon White's attention will move to the kingside. }
