[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez, Schliemann Defense #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ Black is fighting for the center in a very aggressive and risky @@StartBracket@@dubious@@EndBracket@@ way. The Jaenisch or the Schliemann Gambit was always considered a surprise line and nothing has changed in this regard.   However in the recent years there were some interesting developments for both sides which brought attention of some top level players. }
4. d3
{ This choice is solid but also quite challenging - no surprise it is so popular. }
4... fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O Bc5
{ Black is ready to sacrifice a Pawn in order to quickly develop his Bishop to a good square. }
7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. Nxe5
{ Accepting the sacrifice has a long-standing reputation of a good and solid continuation. As the following lines will show, Black struggles to find compensation for the Pawn and even if he manages, it usually means that he might fight for a draw at best. }
8... O-O 9. Nc3
{ Whenever I look at this position, I am thinking: 'Gaju, there has to be something, at least a quarter of an idea for black. Pair of Bishops, 'f' file, come on!'. And then, I am failing to find it, every single time... }
9... d6
{ This is clearly the main continuation. It is based on a simple tactical motif -  10.Nxc6?!  Qe8  - and Black wins an important Pawn on e4. }
10. Na4
{ Tactics in the service of strategy! With help of this little trick White eliminates Black's most active piece leaving him without the initiative he was hoping for. However this means the opposite-color Bishops will remain on the board so we will be facing the drawing tendencies from now on.   It is worth mentioning that the other option is  10.Nd3  - after  10...Bd4!  11.Ne2  Bb6  12.Bg5  Qe8  13.Bxf6  Rxf6  14.Ng3  we have reached the position from Anand-Carlsen, Bilbao 2008 - back in a day it was considered to be the mainline. }
10... Qe8
{ Good multi-purpose move, Black defends the Pawn, attacks the Knight, well at least he can catch a breath now. }
11. Nd3 { 11.Nxc5?!  Qxe5  would satisfy Black. Weaker would be } 11... Bg4
{ Developing the Bishop with a tempo. } 12. Qe1 Bd4
{ Good move. Black provokes c2-c3 which will weaken White's light squares on the queenside }
13. c3 { We should not tolerate this Bishop } 13... Bb6 14. Nxb6 axb6 15. f3
Be6 16. a3
{ Black is solid, but we have a comfortable space advantage and now weaknesses that would give Black clear plans. Whereas White has at least two ways of playing for an advantage, as I go on to explain in thedesignated chapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez, Schliemann Defense #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ Black is fighting for the center in a very aggressive and risky @@StartBracket@@dubious@@EndBracket@@ way. The Jaenisch or the Schliemann Gambit was always considered a surprise line and nothing has changed in this regard.   However in the recent years there were some interesting developments for both sides which brought attention of some top level players. }
4. d3
{ This choice is solid but also quite challenging - no surprise it is so popular. }
4... fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O d6
{ This is the line we should be expecting from the Jeanisch players right now. White has a slight positional advantage due to the weak light squares in black's camp as well as the passive Bishop on f8.   However the complex character of a position will make it difficult to exploit these weaknesses. }
7. Bc4
{ The Bishop was not very useful on b5 and here it is ideally placed, also stopping Be6. }
7... Bg4
{ Black immediately occupies the 2nd best square for their light-squared Bishop }
8. h3 Bh5 9. Nc3 Qd7 { Stopping g2-g4 but also making long castle possible. }
10. Be3
{ On most of the occasions following Fabiano Caruana can't be wrong and this time it is no different. The engines recommend  10.Nd5  O-O-O  11.Qd3  , however once you get deeper you realize it is difficult to prove White's advantage while the lines are getting really complicated. }
10... O-O-O { White is more than ready for this. } 11. Rb1
{ It might look slow but once the Pawn gets to b5... } 11... Bg6 12. b4
{ The attack is strong enough to give up on our central Pawn. That said,  12.Nd2  or  12.Bd3  would be also fine. }
12... Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. b5 Na5 15. Bd5 Bxd5 16. Qxd5
{ White has a simple yet deadly threat - Be3-d2. } 16... Re8 17. b6 axb6 18.
Bxb6 Nc6 19. Be3
{ White has a very simple and powerfulplan of doubling the Rooks on the b file. }
