[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petroff Defense has always been one of the most solid lines out there but it has also had a reputation of boring. I think today it would be unfair to call it boring.   Sure, it is not the Najdorf Variation but still many lines are really sharp and dynamic. Hence, it should not surprise us that there are many strong and aggressive players, that use it as part of their repertoire. }
3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4
{ 5.Nc3  is another fashionable possibility but I wouldn't recommend it to everyone. The lines can often be quite difficult and computer-ish and - if I have a choice - I prefer something more natural. }
5... d5 6. Bd3 Bd6
{ This is, no doubt, the most interesting line in 5.d4 Petroff, but it is also the least solid one. }
7. O-O O-O 8. c4
{ Undermining Black's position in the center. Other moves don't really matter. }
8... c6 { No other move deserved even an honorable mention. } 9. Nc3
{ In recent years it has become the most topical continuation in the 6...Bd6 variation. White immediately challenges the black Knight. }
9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 dxc4 11. Bxc4 Bf5
{ This is the best continuation for Black and I am pretty sure it's not just my opinion. }
12. Bg5 Qa5
{ White has so many good moves - Ra1-e1 or f2-f4 or both. Black is in big trouble. }
13. d5
{ The best practical try in my opinion. White is trying to take advantage of the fact that he is still ahead in development. }
13... Qc7 { This is not a bad line but Black scores terribly here. } 14. Re1 h6
15. Bh4 Bg6 16. Bb3
{ A novelty. Kasimdzhanov chose the calmer  16.Bd3  which shouldn't promise much after  16...Bxd3  17.Qxd3  Nd7  and if  18.dxc6  then  18...Nc5!  Notice that both sides refuse to clarify the situation in the center. Instead, they are correcting their Bishop's positions... }
16... cxd5 17. Qxd5
{ The position is solid for Black but White should be able tokeep the pressure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Petroff  Defense #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petroff Defense has always been one of the most solid lines out there but it has also had a reputation of boring. I think today it would be unfair to call it boring.   Sure, it is not the Najdorf Variation but still many lines are really sharp and dynamic. Hence, it should not surprise us that there are many strong and aggressive players, that use it as part of their repertoire. }
3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4
{ 5.Nc3  is another fashionable possibility but I wouldn't recommend it to everyone. The lines can often be quite difficult and computer-ish and - if I have a choice - I prefer something more natural. }
5... d5 6. Bd3 Nc6
{ Historically, this is the main continuation. The point of developing the Knight to c6 is to be able to react to c2-c4 with Nc6-b4. }
7. O-O Be7 8. Nbd2
{ One of the changes in the modern theory - for years  8.c4  has been considered topical but in the last decade  8.Nbd2  came into play. White is basically saying that symmetrical structure doesn't mean equality. }
8... Nxd2
{ The mainline, although I think that with Black I would prefer 8...Bf5. It's a matter of taste, I guess. }
9. Bxd2 Bg4
{ Black could still wait with this -  9...O-O  and now  10.h3  can be met with  10...Nb4!  But White can play @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1bppp/2n5/3p4/3P4/3B1N2/PPPB1PPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10.c3  instead and after  10...Bg4  we have a transposition. }
10. c3 O-O 11. h3 Bh5 12. g3
{ This is how we deal with the pin - the King can now come to g2 freeing the Queen. }
12... Bg6 { This is too soft. } 13. Bxg6 fxg6
{ 13...hxg6  would be even better news.  We bring the King to g2, put the Bishop on f4 and the Pawn on h4. We can play on both sides with Qd1-b3 and h4-h5 at our disposal. }
14. Ne1
{ The Knight is coming to d3 but what is also important we can activate our Queen now. }
14... Qd7 15. Qg4 Qxg4 16. hxg4
{ The endgame is very nice for White - just put the Knight on d3 and then go f2-f4. }
