[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Philidor Defense #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Philidor Defense has recently gained some popularity partially thanks to the modern engines as new ideas have been generated.  The other reason is a boom of chess on the Internet - shorter time controls create opportunities to experiment with openings as the objective evaluation is not that relevant. }
3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 Nbd7
{ I was never an admirer of this line - Black's setup is as solid as passive. }
5. Bc4 { The most natural square for the Bishop. } 5... Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4
{ This is a very useful move - White anticipates b7-b5 while also making room for the Bishop. We can start with  7.Re1  too, though I slightly prefer  7.a4  - in some lines, we can put the Queen on e2, and then the Rook will move to d1. }
7... c6
{ The main move in the position. Black makes the room for the Queen and also controls the sensitive d5-square. }
8. Re1
{ If 7.a4 was more accurate than 8.Re1 then 8.Re1 is slightly more accurate than  8.h3  , which allows  8...exd4  9.Nxd4  Re8  @@StartBracket@@with the Rook on e1 we would just go Nd4-f5@@EndBracket@@. }
8... h6
{ Securing the g5-square means that the Rook will come to e8. Actually, Black can play  8...Re8  right away but we can just ignore it and play  9.h3  - it is hard to imagine Black skipping h7-h6 for long. }
9. h3 { We can't develop the Bishop to e3 until we stop Nf6-g4. } 9... Re8
{ 9...Qc7  10.Be3  would be less accurate. Black's point is that after  10.Be3  exd4  11.Nxd4  Re8  we have to defend the pawn on e4. Therefore they usually play 11.Qxd4 in that line. }
10. a5
{ I prefer this to  10.Be3  . White makes one more useful move before developing the Bishop. }
10... Qc7 11. Be3 { Finally the Bishop arrives on e3. } 11... exd4 12. Nxd4 Bf8
13. Bf4 { This is stronger than  13.f3  . } 13... Rb8
{ Black is preparing b7-b5. } 14. Bg3 b5 15. axb6 axb6 16. b4
{ The point of this move is to prevent b5-b4. At the same time we would love to play b4-b5, if available, so he should not delay it.   After  16...b5  we can retreat the Bishop to the b3-square. White has a small but stable advantage as all our pieces are nicely placed. }
