1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3
{ The Classical System has never been doing better against the Pirc. Black seems to be struggling everywhere, while the main challenge for White is that it is quite easy to mix up some moves in the beginning.   With his last move, White develops the piece to a natural square. We can feel that the exciting long castle is coming, but what I like about this line is its flexibility - we can easily adapt to Black's plans so whenever it suits us, we can also castle short. }
4... Bg7
{ The coolest reaction to 4.Be3 - Black keeps all options on the table while making the move that has to be made anyway. }
5. Qd2
{ We are intending to castle long but this move does not burn any bridges so - depending on Black's reaction - we can still castle short too! }
5... c6
{ Black is ready to meet  6.Bh6  with  6...Bxh6  7.Qxh6  e5  8.O-O-O  Qe7  . It doesn't mean White can't try it but I think I found a better and definitely simpler solution. }
6. a4 { White is preventing b7-b5. } 6... O-O
{ Black could go  6...Ng4  7.Bg5  or  6...Nbd7  7.h3  but I saw no independent value in those moves. }
7. h3 { Now Nf6-g4 is stopped as well. } 7... Nbd7 8. Nf3
{ This should lead to a simple and pleasant position for White. } 8... e5 9.
dxe5 dxe5 10. Qd6
{ The Queen acts as a disturber here. Normally Black would be happy to finish his development with Qd8-e7 and Nd7-c5 but now he has to contrive. }
10... Ne8 { Trying to chase away our Queen. } 11. Qa3
{ The Queen still controls e7. } 11... Nc7 12. O-O-O
{ Those of you, who worry about the Pawn on a4 - do you remember when we played a2-a4 with a long castle already on board? It is not a weakness! We will develop the Bishop to c4 and then try pushing the h-Pawn. Black struggles to find the right setup for his pieces. }
