{ The pawn structure is almost identical so the activity of the pieces decide - We have a clear edge here as more white pieces have already been developed plus Black's dark-squared Bishop is cut off from the game. He also has to defend c6. }
9... Qd6 10. Nc4
{ It's really cool that Black didn't have any other move than Qd6 allowing the white Knight to regroup with a tempo. }
10... Qe7 11. Ne3
{ Once again - in open positions   @@StartBracket@@especially symmetrical ones@@EndBracket@@ the activity of the pieces is the most important factor. Black is going to have a huge problem with his dark-squared Bishop but right now he has more pressing problems as d5 is hanging.   One more thing:  11...Be6  can be met with  12.a4!  a5   @@StartBracket@@forced as  12...a6  costs Black a Pawn after  13.Bxc6  bxc6  14.a5  Ba7  15.Qxa6  , not to mention the dark-squared Bishop...@@EndBracket@@  13.Ne5  and Black may be - once again - forced to sacrificing the Pawn. So, the Queen is coming to e6 after all? }
