1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bb4
{ That's a cool move, especially for rapid or blitz games. If White plays normally it might very quickly turn out that Black equalized without too much effort.  If you are still not convinced, I will just add that it was played three times by Magnus Carlsen@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@. What is the point of the move itself?   Compared with Bf8-c5 Black's Bishop will most likely also end up on the same diagonal but in the meantime Black doesn't allow White to get d2-d4 with tempo.   Why this might be important will become clear in the line arising after  4.c3  Ba5  5.O-O  . }
4. c3 Ba5 5. Na3
{ From c4 the Knight will attack both the Bishop and the Pawn. It is worth noting that after the usual  5.O-O  Nge7  6.d4  exd4!  7.cxd4  d5  Black's little experiment would fully pay off.   Our choice is not the only good response to 3...Bb4 - for instance  5.Qa4  is also strong. However the idea of bringing the Knight to c4 seems very logical to me, which 'I believe' should make the line quite easy to remember. }
5... Bb6 6. Nc4 Nf6 { Counterattacking e4 but it runs into: } 7. d4 Nxe4
{ After  7...O-O  8.dxe5  Nxe4  9.Qd5  White would be clearly better. } 8. Qe2
{ Now Black is solidly worse. } 8... d5 9. Ncxe5
{ The pawn structure is almost identical so the activity of the pieces decide - We have a clear edge here as more white pieces have already been developed plus Black's dark-squared Bishop is cut off from the game. He also has to defend c6. }
9... Qd6 10. Nc4
{ It's really cool that Black didn't have any other move than Qd6 allowing the white Knight to regroup with a tempo. }
10... Qe6
{ This move looks horrible but at least now the d5 Pawn is defended so  11.Ne3  doesn't have the same effect as it did after 10...Qe7. }
11. Nxb6
{ But now we can simply play for the Bishop pair. Compared with 10...Qe7 Black will have to spend a tempo to correct the position of the Queen. }
11... axb6 12. O-O
{ We will develop the Bishop to f4, occupy the e-file with the Rook and then perhaps try to undermine the position of the Black's Knight with Nf3-d2. The Bishop pair guarantees us a long-term advantage. }
