[Round "?"]
[White "1. Alapin Defense (3...Bb4) and Rare 3rd Moves"]
[Black "3... Bb4 (Alapin) #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bb4
{ That's a cool move, especially for rapid or blitz games. If White plays normally it might very quickly turn out that Black equalized without too much effort.  If you are still not convinced, I will just add that it was played three times by Magnus Carlsen@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@. What is the point of the move itself?   Compared with Bf8-c5 Black's Bishop will most likely also end up on the same diagonal but in the meantime Black doesn't allow White to get d2-d4 with tempo.   Why this might be important will become clear in the line arising after  4.c3  Ba5  5.O-O  . }
4. c3 Ba5 5. Na3
{ From c4 the Knight will attack both the Bishop and the Pawn. It is worth noting that after the usual  5.O-O  Nge7  6.d4  exd4!  7.cxd4  d5  Black's little experiment would fully pay off.   Our choice is not the only good response to 3...Bb4 - for instance  5.Qa4  is also strong. However the idea of bringing the Knight to c4 seems very logical to me, which 'I believe' should make the line quite easy to remember. }
5... Bb6 6. Nc4 d6 7. O-O
{ Delaying d2-d4 is part of our plan - we want to find out where Black is going to develop his Knight first. }
7... Ne7
{ The main idea of this move is that it works well against  8.d4  : after  8...exd4  9.cxd4  d5  Black's position is quite acceptable despite losing a tempo for d7-d6-d5. }
8. a4 { Played with an obvious threat of winning the Bishop with a4-a5... }
8... O-O
{ Though he doesn't have to defend yet  9.a5?  is met with  9...Nxa5!  10.Nxa5  Bxa5  11.Rxa5  c6  and Black wins the piece back which means he will be a Pawn up.   9.Bxc6  Nxc6  10.a5  would normally work but in this case Black has  10...Be6!  which gets him out of trouble. }
9. d3 a6 { One of the ways in which Black can defend against a4-a5. } 10. Nxb6
cxb6 11. Bc4
{ The only thing that Black has achieved with his Bishop maneuver is a ruined pawn structure. We can prepare d3-d4 with Rf1-e1.   In case of  11...Be6  we can always take on e6 and then place the Bishop on e3, the Queen on b3, targeting b6. }
