[Black "Steinitz Defense 4...Bd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6
{ The classical Steinitz Defense did not stand the test of time and already for a long time it has been considered passive and unpromising, though some strong players still try it occasionally. }
4. d4 Bd7
{ The most popular continuation according to Mega Database though it does not deserve to be one. It is hard to understand what Black could possibly hope for other than a chance that White wouldn't know the best continuation. }
5. Bxc6
{ Important nuance: after  5.Nc3  exd4  6.Nxd4  Nf6  7.Bxc6  Black can recapture with a Pawn but now doesn't have that option. }
5... Bxc6 6. Nc3 f6
{ The passive/solid approach sometimes works, but here the disproportion between the two sides is simply too big. }
7. Be3 Ne7 8. Qe2
{ White will castle long in the next move creating a very unpleasant threat of taking on e5. It is going to be difficult for Black to finish the development in such circumstances. }
