1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6
{ The classical Steinitz Defense did not stand the test of time and already for a long time it has been considered passive and unpromising, though some strong players still try it occasionally. }
4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Ne7 6. Be3
{ White deliberately delays developing the queen's Knight to keep c2-c4 advance available. }
6... a6 7. Be2
{ No need to give away the Bishop pair especially after Black had committed his Knight to e7. }
7... Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Nc6 9. Qd2 Be6 10. c4
{ A useful Pawn advance that would not be possible had White started with 6. Nc3 instead of the text move. With its help White is improving his control over the d5 square. Making b7-b5 harder for Black is also helpful. }
10... g6 11. Nc3 Bg7 12. O-O O-O 13. Rad1
{ White has a clear advantage as he controls the most important central squares. He can slowly improve his position with little moves like b3 or h3 and, when ready, advance with f4-f5 and Nd5 in any order. }
