{ The classical Steinitz Defense did not stand the test of time and already for a long time it has been considered passive and unpromising, though some strong players still try it occasionally. }
4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bd7 6. Nc3 Nxd4
{ As black is struggling with a lack of space he wants to exchange as many pieces as possible. However, on this occasion, he is also developing our pieces! }
7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 8. Qxd4 Ne7 { The Knight takes his friend's place. } 9. Be3 Nc6
10. Qd3 { This square in not coincidental as the following line will show: }
10... g6 { 10...Be7  11.O-O-O  would be horrible for Black. } 11. Nd5 Bg7 12.
Bh6
{ Black can't of course take the Bishop due to Nd5-f6+. It is now clear why it was important to retreat the Queen to d3 instead of d2. }
12... f6
{ Not a pleasant move to make but Black didn't really have a good choice. } 13.
Bxg7 Qxg7 14. O-O
{ White's position is not only visually superior - he has some nice follow-ups such as b4-b5 and f4-f5. The knight on d5 is really powerful while Black has to consider Qb3 if he decides to finish his development with a short castle. }
