1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6
{ The classical Steinitz Defense did not stand the test of time and already for a long time it has been considered passive and unpromising, though some strong players still try it occasionally. }
4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bd7 6. Nc3 Nf6
{ I guess it's logical but Black's position is just too passive. } 7. O-O
{ It was also possible to play more aggressively for instance  7.Bxc6  bxc6  8.Qf3!?  . }
7... Nxd4
{ Played with the same intentions as 6...Nxd4, the drawbacks are also the same. }
8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. Qxd4 Be7
{ Black has managed to exchange a few pieces but his problems are far from over as he is still one tempo away from being 'only slightly worse'. }
10. Rd1 { Slightly unusual but we have a good point. } 10... O-O
{ 10...Qe6  11.Nd5  would be clearly better for White too. } 11. e5 Ne8 12. Bf4
{ In open positions the activity of the pieces is the most important factor. In this sense we have a very basic example as White's activity is clearly superior. Black can't really move the Queen's Rook as a7 would fall.   He can try moving the Queen to e6 or c6 to which we can reply with either Nc3-d5 or Rd1-e1 followed by Ra1-d1. }
