1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6
{ The classical Steinitz Defense did not stand the test of time and already for a long time it has been considered passive and unpromising, though some strong players still try it occasionally. }
4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bd7 6. Nc3 Nf6
{ I guess it's logical but Black's position is just too passive. } 7. O-O
{ It was also possible to play more aggressively for instance  7.Bxc6  bxc6  8.Qf3!?  . }
7... Be7 8. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Recapturing with the Pawn might seem tempting as White has to use a tempo for the Bishop's retreat. }
9. Bd3
{ However, once retreated to d3, White's Bishop is clearly superior to its counterpart. }
9... O-O 10. f4
{ It would be fully justified to stop right now as our position is already pleasant and there are more than one way possible. Let's check it a bit deeper, though - Black has many moves but basically two main ideas - d6-d5 and c6-c5. }
10... Re8
{ Black is aiming to achieve the following setup: Bf8, c5 and Bc6. A healthy setup in an unhealthy position. }
11. h3
{ The move might seem a bit mysterious as neither Bd7-g4 nor Nf6-g4 were serious. Let's see the alternatives then:   11.b3?  is met with  11...Ng4!  and Black's point is that he can mee  12.h3  with  12...Bf6!  with an unclear game.   11.Qf3  is possible, here however Black can go  11...Be6  hoping for  12.b3  Nd7!  . Normally Black can never get this setup because of f4-f5. Here however  13.f5  is met with  13...Ne5  . Instead of 12. b3 White can play  @@StartFEN@@r2qr1k1/p1p1bppp/2ppbn2/8/4PP2/2NB1Q2/PPP3PP/R1B2RK1 w - - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Qg3  with an advantage but still - I prefer our choice. }
11... Bf8 12. Qf3
{ Wait, didn't we just allow  12...Be6  again? We did, but there is a big difference: after  13.b3  Nd7  White can go  14.Be3!  stopping  14...Nc5  . In the previous line Black would have had Be7-f6 pinning our Knight but now the Bishop is on f8 so... }
12... c5 13. b3 Bc6 14. Bb2
{ We will put the queen's Rook on e1, and move the Queen to g3, preparing e4-e5. }
