[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Ruy Lopez Deferred Steinitz (4...d6)"]
[Black "Deferred Steinitz 6...g5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 d6
{ Deferred Steinitz has been consistently used by players seeking a complicated game. Hence, we should not be surprised to see Mamedyarov, Nakamura, or recently Artemiev and Firouzja having this line as part of their repertoire.   More surprising is the fact that the engines - instead of killing the line - have actually elevated it to a full-fledged system. }
5. O-O Bd7
{ Instead of developing the dark-squared Bishop to e7 and then spending time trying to improve its position, Black wants to place it on g7 right away. Putting the other Bishop on d7 first is necessary as otherwise White would always answer g7-g6 with d2-d4!   For instance  5...g6  6.d4!  ;-@@EndBracket@@. It is a serious downside - the light-squared Bishop is better of on b7 not d7. }
6. c4
{ This might not be mathematically the strongest, but it has this big practical value as White is refusing to enter the area that Black wants him to enter but at the same time he is creating actual problems! The idea is quite standard - White is building a strong Pawn center. }
6... g5
{ Not really correct but it's catching up with aggression ;-@@EndBracket@@. }
7. d4 { A counter-thrust in the center is the best reply to a wing attack! }
7... g4 8. d5 { This comes with in a package with 7. d4. } 8... gxf3
{ 8...Nce7  wouldn't make any sense -  9.Bxd7+  Qxd7  10.Nh4  and Black only managed to compromise his light squares with this advance. }
9. dxc6 bxc6 10. Qxf3
{ Black doesn't really have any attack here, only weaknesses. Two things are worth remembering -  10...Qh4  is best answered with  11.Re1  and the Knight, instead of normal development to c3, can come to f1 or g3 securing the position of the King.   The second thing -  10...Qf6  should be met with  11.Qb3!  and Black has to reckon with Qb3-b7. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Ruy Lopez Deferred Steinitz (4...d6)"]
[Black "Deferred Steinitz 6...Nge7 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 d6
{ Deferred Steinitz has been consistently used by players seeking a complicated game. Hence, we should not be surprised to see Mamedyarov, Nakamura, or recently Artemiev and Firouzja having this line as part of their repertoire.   More surprising is the fact that the engines - instead of killing the line - have actually elevated it to a full-fledged system. }
5. O-O Bd7
{ Instead of developing the dark-squared Bishop to e7 and then spending time trying to improve its position, Black wants to place it on g7 right away. Putting the other Bishop on d7 first is necessary as otherwise White would always answer g7-g6 with d2-d4!   For instance  5...g6  6.d4!  ;-@@EndBracket@@. It is a serious downside - the light-squared Bishop is better of on b7 not d7. }
6. c4
{ This might not be mathematically the strongest, but it has this big practical value as White is refusing to enter the area that Black wants him to enter but at the same time he is creating actual problems! The idea is quite standard - White is building a strong Pawn center. }
6... Nge7
{ Black wants to fianchetto the dark-squared Bishop but first, he prevents Ba4xc6. }
7. Nc3 { Waiting for g7-g6 to be played first. } 7... g6 8. d4 Bg7
{ 8...exd4?!  would meet a typical reaction:  9.Nd5!  Bg7  10.Bg5  and Black is in trouble.   After  8...exd4?!  9.Nd5  Nxd5  is a lesser evil but  10.exd5  Ne5  11.Nxd4  gives White a huge advantage. Now White can choose between two equally good continuations which, however, lead to different kinds of positions. }
9. dxe5
{ If Black was hoping for some King's Indian style activity, he will be disappointed. }
9... Nxe5
{ 9...dxe5  10.Nd5  and  10...O-O  11.Bg5  f6  12.Be3  is much better for White,   while  9...dxe5  10.Nd5  with  10...Nxd5  11.cxd5  is definitely not what Black is looking for. }
10. Nxe5 Bxe5
{ Sad necessity -  10...dxe5  11.Bg5  would be too strong for White. } 11. Bc2
Nc6 12. Nd5
{ Black was threatening Be5xc3 followed by Qd8-e7 and long castle so it is important to move the Knight first. We can continue with Bc1-e3 and f2-f4. White's plan will probably be connected with f4-f5 but let's be flexible - we have an advantage on the whole board. }
