[White "3. Ruy Lopez Deferred Steinitz (4...d6)"]
[Black "Deferred Steinitz 6...Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 d6
{ Deferred Steinitz has been consistently used by players seeking a complicated game. Hence, we should not be surprised to see Mamedyarov, Nakamura, or recently Artemiev and Firouzja having this line as part of their repertoire.   More surprising is the fact that the engines - instead of killing the line - have actually elevated it to a full-fledged system. }
5. O-O Bd7
{ Instead of developing the dark-squared Bishop to e7 and then spending time trying to improve its position, Black wants to place it on g7 right away. Putting the other Bishop on d7 first is necessary as otherwise White would always answer g7-g6 with d2-d4!   For instance  5...g6  6.d4!  ;-@@EndBracket@@. It is a serious downside - the light-squared Bishop is better of on b7 not d7. }
6. c4
{ This might not be mathematically the strongest, but it has this big practical value as White is refusing to enter the area that Black wants him to enter but at the same time he is creating actual problems! The idea is quite standard - White is building a strong Pawn center. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3 Nd4
{ Trying to prevent d2-d4 is understandable but it doesn't improve Black's position, on the contrary, it's only making things worse. }
8. Bxd7+
{ Generally the exchange of light-squared Bishops works for us - with Pawns on c4 and e4 our a4 Bishop would never become a monster. }
8... Nxd7 { This makes more sense than  8...Qxd7  . } 9. Nxd4
{ Whenever you evaluate such exchanges always consider the pawn structure, squares and the Bishops. It is a good trade in this case because we are forcing our opponent to defend d4-Pawn with c7-c5, which puts another Black Pawn on the color of his own Bishop and also happens to weaken d5.   If Black were able to defend that Pawn with, let's say Bf8-g7 @@StartBracket@@so his Pawn is on g6 not g7@@EndBracket@@ then he would have been just fine. }
9... exd4 10. Ne2
{ Interestingly, this position appeared in a game between Magnus Carlsen and Jan Timman, Reykjavik Blitz 2004 - yes it's that tournament where then, the thirteen years old Norwegian managed to draw with Garry Kasparov himself and everything got recorded on tape! The recording is available online with something around ten million views.   Coming back to Timman's game - Black played  10...Qf6?  in a sense agreeing with my previous statement. The game continued with  11.d3  g6  and now White could have played  12.Bd2!  threatening 13. Nxd4 more or less forcing Black to do something as ugly as 12...Rg8 . }
10... c5 11. d3 b5
{ Black will anyway play it at some point so we might as well start with this. }
12. b3 Be7 13. Ng3
{ This game should go in our desired direction but we should take it slowly. We want to play f2-f4 and develop the Queen to g4. }
