{ Deferred Steinitz has been consistently used by players seeking a complicated game. Hence, we should not be surprised to see Mamedyarov, Nakamura, or recently Artemiev and Firouzja having this line as part of their repertoire.   More surprising is the fact that the engines - instead of killing the line - have actually elevated it to a full-fledged system. }
5. O-O Bd7
{ Instead of developing the dark-squared Bishop to e7 and then spending time trying to improve its position, Black wants to place it on g7 right away. Putting the other Bishop on d7 first is necessary as otherwise White would always answer g7-g6 with d2-d4!   For instance  5...g6  6.d4!  ;-@@EndBracket@@. It is a serious downside - the light-squared Bishop is better of on b7 not d7. }
6. c4
