{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 d6
{ Deferred Steinitz has been consistently used by players seeking a complicated game. Hence, we should not be surprised to see Mamedyarov, Nakamura, or recently Artemiev and Firouzja having this line as part of their repertoire.   More surprising is the fact that the engines - instead of killing the line - have actually elevated it to a full-fledged system. }
5. O-O Bd7
{ Instead of developing the dark-squared Bishop to e7 and then spending time trying to improve its position, Black wants to place it on g7 right away. Putting the other Bishop on d7 first is necessary as otherwise White would always answer g7-g6 with d2-d4!   For instance  5...g6  6.d4!  ;-@@EndBracket@@. It is a serious downside - the light-squared Bishop is better of on b7 not d7. }
6. c4
{ This might not be mathematically the strongest, but it has this big practical value as White is refusing to enter the area that Black wants him to enter but at the same time he is creating actual problems! The idea is quite standard - White is building a strong Pawn center. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3 Bg4
{ Smart move - Black is preventing d2-d4 but also fighting for the d4 square in general. }
8. d3
{ The immediate  8.h3  would be inaccurate:  8...Bxf3  9.Qxf3  Nd7  - Black is ready to occupy d4 -  10.Bxc6  bxc6  11.b4  @@StartBracket@@stopping Nd7-c5-e6@@EndBracket@@  11...Be7  and Black benefits from not castling yet as he can play Nd7-f8-e6 first. }
8... Nd7
{ Starting with  8...Be7  has only one significant difference - we can and should play  9.h3  right away. The point is that if we start with  9.Be3  then after  9...O-O  10.h3  Black can consider  10...Bh5!?  since  11.g4??  Nxg4  12.hxg4  Bxg4  followed by 13...f5 is crushing.   After  8...Be7  9.h3  Bh5  10.g4  he can't do the same -  10...Nxg4?  11.hxg4  Bxg4  12.Nd5!  and if Black tries the same -  12...O-O  then the Knight will come to e3 just in time -  13.Ne3!  taking f5 under control. }
9. Be3 Be7 { Now, once d4 is controlled, we can deal with the annoying pin. }
10. h3 Bxf3 { 10...Bh5?!  11.g4!  and White is much better. } 11. Qxf3 O-O
{ 11...Nd4?!  12.Bxd4  exd4  13.Bxd7+  Qxd7  14.Ne2  would be better for White. Notice that the Knight is clearly superior to the Bishop }
12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. b4
{ Taking control over c5 but also it's a beginning of the bigger plan on the queenside. }
13... Bg5 14. Qd1
{ The Queen is heading to a4 from where it would attack c6. If Black waits for Qd1 and then just plays c6-c5 - we can calmly reply with a2-a3 and Black has to deal with the pressure of defending that pawn as c5xb4 a3xb4 would only create a serious weakness on a6. If he goes a6-a5?! then after b4-b5! White gains control over d5. }
