1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 d6
{ Deferred Steinitz has been consistently used by players seeking a complicated game. Hence, we should not be surprised to see Mamedyarov, Nakamura, or recently Artemiev and Firouzja having this line as part of their repertoire.   More surprising is the fact that the engines - instead of killing the line - have actually elevated it to a full-fledged system. }
5. O-O Bd7
{ Instead of developing the dark-squared Bishop to e7 and then spending time trying to improve its position, Black wants to place it on g7 right away. Putting the other Bishop on d7 first is necessary as otherwise White would always answer g7-g6 with d2-d4!   For instance  5...g6  6.d4!  ;-@@EndBracket@@. It is a serious downside - the light-squared Bishop is better of on b7 not d7. }
6. c4
{ This might not be mathematically the strongest, but it has this big practical value as White is refusing to enter the area that Black wants him to enter but at the same time he is creating actual problems! The idea is quite standard - White is building a strong Pawn center. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3 Be7 8. Bxc6 Bxc6
{ Once again recapturing with the Bishop gives White a nice advantage. It is true that Black avoids breaking his Pawn structure @@StartBracket@@which would be the case after  8...bxc6  @@EndBracket@@ but now he will be left with no counterplay. }
9. Qc2
{ 9.Re1  would be also fine but I prefer the text move as it is already connected with the plan. }
9... O-O 10. d4 exd4 11. Nxd4 Re8 12. h3
{ Preparing 13. Bf4 @@StartBracket@@why worry about Nf6-h5?@@EndBracket@@ . Once we move the Bishop we can develop the Rooks - e1 and d1 look perfectly reasonable. In some cases Rf1-d1 might be possible too, leaving the other one on the queenside. }
