1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 d6
{ Deferred Steinitz has been consistently used by players seeking a complicated game. Hence, we should not be surprised to see Mamedyarov, Nakamura, or recently Artemiev and Firouzja having this line as part of their repertoire.   More surprising is the fact that the engines - instead of killing the line - have actually elevated it to a full-fledged system. }
5. O-O Bd7
{ Instead of developing the dark-squared Bishop to e7 and then spending time trying to improve its position, Black wants to place it on g7 right away. Putting the other Bishop on d7 first is necessary as otherwise White would always answer g7-g6 with d2-d4!   For instance  5...g6  6.d4!  ;-@@EndBracket@@. It is a serious downside - the light-squared Bishop is better of on b7 not d7. }
6. c4
{ This might not be mathematically the strongest, but it has this big practical value as White is refusing to enter the area that Black wants him to enter but at the same time he is creating actual problems! The idea is quite standard - White is building a strong Pawn center. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3 Be7 8. Bxc6 bxc6
{ Once again recapturing with the Bishop gives White a nice advantage. It is true that Black avoids breaking his Pawn structure @@StartBracket@@which would be the case after  8...bxc6  @@EndBracket@@ but now he will be left with no counterplay. }
9. d4 exd4 10. Qxd4
{ The idea of capturing the Pawn with the Queen rather than the Knight is actually very sensible - the Knight on d4 is waiting for Black to play c6-c5 but the thing is - he doesn't need to rush it. The Queen on d4 doesn't care - we will soon be threatening with e4-e5 anyway. }
10... O-O
{ We should be aware of this move-order. The key is not to get excited about  11.e5  -  11...c5  12.Qd3  dxe5  13.Nxe5  Bd6  is only a bit better for White. }
11. Qd3 { It looks slow but can Black live long without c6-c5? } 11... Re8 12.
Re1 c5 { I just can't think of anything else than this... } 13. Bf4 Bc6 14.
Rad1 { transposes back to the game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Ruy Lopez Deferred Steinitz (4...d6)"]
[Black "Deferred Steinitz 6...Nf6 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 d6
{ Deferred Steinitz has been consistently used by players seeking a complicated game. Hence, we should not be surprised to see Mamedyarov, Nakamura, or recently Artemiev and Firouzja having this line as part of their repertoire.   More surprising is the fact that the engines - instead of killing the line - have actually elevated it to a full-fledged system. }
5. O-O Bd7
{ Instead of developing the dark-squared Bishop to e7 and then spending time trying to improve its position, Black wants to place it on g7 right away. Putting the other Bishop on d7 first is necessary as otherwise White would always answer g7-g6 with d2-d4!   For instance  5...g6  6.d4!  ;-@@EndBracket@@. It is a serious downside - the light-squared Bishop is better of on b7 not d7. }
6. c4
{ This might not be mathematically the strongest, but it has this big practical value as White is refusing to enter the area that Black wants him to enter but at the same time he is creating actual problems! The idea is quite standard - White is building a strong Pawn center. }
6... Nf6 7. Nc3 Be7 8. Bxc6 bxc6
{ Once again recapturing with the Bishop gives White a nice advantage. It is true that Black avoids breaking his Pawn structure @@StartBracket@@which would be the case after  8...bxc6  @@EndBracket@@ but now he will be left with no counterplay. }
9. d4 exd4 10. Qxd4
{ The idea of capturing the Pawn with the Queen rather than the Knight is actually very sensible - the Knight on d4 is waiting for Black to play c6-c5 but the thing is - he doesn't need to rush it. The Queen on d4 doesn't care - we will soon be threatening with e4-e5 anyway. }
10... c5 11. Qd3 O-O 12. Bf4
{ Fianchettoing the Bishop might seem more natural but the problem is that once b2-b3 and Bc1-b2 is played, a6-a5 might be annoying - after a2-a4 the Bishop covers the b-file so it takes more effort to protect the b3 Pawn. }
12... Bc6 13. Rad1
{ If you switch on the engine after 6. c4 then forget about it and go out for lunch then this is what you are going to get once you come back.   This is also a game between Kiril Alekseenko and Arval Alonso Rosell from the French League 2021, which tells us a lot about modern preparation. }
13... Re8
{ It is debatable whether white should go  14.e5  here but Black could have started with  13...Nd7 so why bother? }
14. Rfe1 Nd7 { Finally Black can improve the position of the Bishop. } 15. b3
Bf6 16. Nd5
{ Still in the game, but I think it's a good moment to stop. It is hard to point at one specific plan here - White is in control but making progress is not simple. We can start with h2-h3 which is useful for a couple of reasons:   a@@EndBracket@@ the King will never get mated on the back rank :P   b@@EndBracket@@ we might consider g2-g4 at some point.   c@@EndBracket@@ it prevents g7-g5-g4 - as vague as it looks right now. Qd3-c2 is another useful move - a small adjustment which puts the e4-e5 threat back on the table.   In case of a6-a5 we should answer with a2-a4! not worrying about the b3 Pawn - a5 is a bigger weakness plus the Knight might come to b5. If Black takes the Knight on d5 then most likely e4xd5 is the way to go which should give us a small but long-term advantage.   Notice that especially in the endgame our dark-squared Bishop might be relocated to a5 targeting a weak c7 Pawn. }
