[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Ruy Lopez Jaenisch/Schliemann (3...f5)"]
[Black "Schliemann 4...Nf6 5.exf5  #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ Black is fighting for the center in a very aggressive and risky @@StartBracket@@dubious@@EndBracket@@ way. The Jaenisch or the Schliemann Gambit was always considered a surprise line and nothing has changed in this regard.   However in the recent years there were some interesting developments for both sides which brought attention of some top level players. }
4. d3
{ This choice is solid but also quite challenging - no surprise it is so popular. }
4... Nf6 { Now we can get a good position without entering the mainlines. } 5.
exf5 Ne7
{ Clever try. Black wants to capture on f5 with the Knight and undermine the position of White's Bishop. }
6. d4
{ At least for a moment Black's pieces are cramped so White is acting immediately. It might seem that white can just take another Pawn with  6.Nxe5  since after  6...c6  there is  7.Bg5!  and the Bishop can't be taken. However, after the surprising  7...h5!!  nothing is clear! }
6... e4 7. Nh4 { Knight on the rim is dim, is it? } 7... c6 8. Be2 Nxf5
{ Black was hoping for this trick.  8...d5  9.g4  would be much better for White. }
9. Nxf5 Qa5+ 10. Nd2
{ This is very important - the Knight will be much stronger here, than on c3. }
10... Qxf5 11. O-O { We could also start with  11.f3  . } 11... d5 12. f3
{ If the Knight had been placed on c3 instead of d2, Black would have retreated the Queen to g6 with a decent position.   It is not possible now, though -  12...Qg6?  13.fxe4  dxe4  14.Nc4!  followed by 15. Ne5 is practically winning for White! }
12... e3 { The only chance to stay in the game. } 13. Nb3
{ White simply wins this Pawn. } 13... Qg5 14. f4
{ at least this way Black can provoke f4 to gain some light squares. } 14...
Qg6 15. Bd3 { This would be anyway forced after Bc8-f5. } 15... Bf5 16. Bxf5
Qxf5 17. Bxe3 O-O-O
{ The material imbalance on the Kingside will be a bit less problematic for Black now, that the King has escaped to the other side. }
18. Nc1
{ Black has some counterplay on the light squares, also the white Bishop is weak. However, once the Knight reaches its outpost on e5 Black will have to fight for a draw. }
*

