{ Black is fighting for the center in a very aggressive and risky @@StartBracket@@dubious@@EndBracket@@ way. The Jaenisch or the Schliemann Gambit was always considered a surprise line and nothing has changed in this regard.   However in the recent years there were some interesting developments for both sides which brought attention of some top level players. }
4. d3
{ This choice is solid but also quite challenging - no surprise it is so popular. }
4... Nf6 { Now we can get a good position without entering the mainlines. } 5.
exf5 Nd4 { This move can be confusing so let's see how White should react. } 6.
Ba4
{ 6.Nxd4?!  exd4  offer Black good chances:  7.O-O  Be7  8.Nd2  O-O  9.Nf3  d5  and Black wins the Pawn back. }
6... c6 { Preparing 7...d5. } 7. O-O
{ White benefits from the fact that he didn't take the Knight on d4 - e5 is now the target. }
7... d5 8. Re1
{ This is even stronger than  8.Nxe5  . Black has no choice, he has to take the Knight. }
8... Nxf3+ 9. Qxf3
{ The Pawn is still hanging but after  9...Bd6  we can go  10.c4!  followed by 11. Nc3 - fighting for the light squares. White is a full pawn up. }
