1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ Black is fighting for the center in a very aggressive and risky @@StartBracket@@dubious@@EndBracket@@ way. The Jaenisch or the Schliemann Gambit was always considered a surprise line and nothing has changed in this regard.   However in the recent years there were some interesting developments for both sides which brought attention of some top level players. }
4. d3
{ This choice is solid but also quite challenging - no surprise it is so popular. }
4... d6
{ In general all non 4...dxe4 lines should be bad for Black - the whole point of playing 3...f5 was the White could not play  4.exf5  due to  4...e4  - this is no longer the case after 4. d3. }
5. exf5 a6 { More accurate then immediate  5...Bxf5?!  7.d4! } 6. Ba4 Bxf5 7.
O-O
{ 7.d4?!  wouldn't be so strong now - after  7...e4  8.d5  exf3  9.dxc6  Black has  9...b5  . }
7... Nf6 8. d4 { Black is simply late! } 8... e4 9. d5 b5
{ compared with the line after 7.d4?! -  9...exf3  would be a different story -  10.dxc6  b5  11.Bb3  fxg2  12.Re1+  is easily winning for White - it's quite a difference to have castled already! }
10. Bb3 { 10.dxc6  was equally strong but our choice is simpler. } 10... Na5
11. Nd4 Bd7 12. Nd2
{ The Pawn on e4 is lost. One nuance - after  12...Be7  13.Re1  O-O  14.Nxe4  Nxb3  15.axb3  Nxd5  White has  16.Nxb5! }
