[White "4. Ruy Lopez Jaenisch/Schliemann (3...f5)"]
[Black "Schliemann 4...Bc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ Black is fighting for the center in a very aggressive and risky @@StartBracket@@dubious@@EndBracket@@ way. The Jaenisch or the Schliemann Gambit was always considered a surprise line and nothing has changed in this regard.   However in the recent years there were some interesting developments for both sides which brought attention of some top level players. }
4. d3
{ This choice is solid but also quite challenging - no surprise it is so popular. }
4... Bc5 { This is too optimistic } 5. exf5 { Why not? } 5... Nge7
{ Otherwise White is just a Pawn up. } 6. Bg5
{ Important move, but also quite a simple one. } 6... h6 7. Bh4 d6 8. d4
{ Otherwise Black's setup might work. } 8... exd4 9. Nxd4
{ Now in order to win the Pawn back, Black has to give up his dark-squared Bishop, one of the very few developed pieces. }
9... Bxd4 10. Qxd4 Nxf5 11. Qe4+
{ So much for the counterplay, the Knight has to come back. } 11... Ne7 12. Nc3
Bf5 13. Qe3 g5 { Black had no choice, there were simply too many pins. } 14.
Bg3 Qd7 15. Bxc6
{ We have to take now, while he can't recapture with the other Knight. } 15...
Qxc6 16. O-O-O Qb6 17. Qe1
{ Of course we prefer to keep the Queens as Black still hasn't castled. We want to continue with  17...--  18.h4  g4  19.h5  winning some nice squares for the Bishop but also sealing Black's weakness on h6. }
