[White "4. Ruy Lopez Jaenisch/Schliemann (3...f5)"]
[Black "Schliemann 4...fxe4, 6...Bc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ Black is fighting for the center in a very aggressive and risky @@StartBracket@@dubious@@EndBracket@@ way. The Jaenisch or the Schliemann Gambit was always considered a surprise line and nothing has changed in this regard.   However in the recent years there were some interesting developments for both sides which brought attention of some top level players. }
4. d3
{ This choice is solid but also quite challenging - no surprise it is so popular. }
4... fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O Bc5
{ Black is ready to sacrifice a Pawn in order to quickly develop his Bishop to a good square. }
7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. Nxe5
{ Accepting the sacrifice has a long-standing reputation of a good and solid continuation. As the following lines will show, Black struggles to find compensation for the Pawn and even if he gets any, it usually means that he might catch a draw at best. }
8... O-O 9. Nc3
{ Whenever I look at this position, I am thinking: 'Gaju, there has to be something, at least a quarter of an idea for black. Pair of Bishops, 'f-file, come on!'. And then, I am failing to find it, every single time... }
9... Ba6 { Attacking the Rook. } 10. Nd3
{ This square is incredibly useful! Attacking c5, defending f2, covering f1... }
10... Bd4 11. Re1
{ You will see the difference in the comments to 10...Bb6 11. Re1. } 11... d5
{ This is a better try  11...d6  12.Nf4  with a big advantage for White. } 12.
exd5 cxd5 13. Nf4 { The Bishop is hanging but also Nf4-e6 is there. } 13... Re8
{ Black might have hoped for  14.Be3  Bxe3  15.Rxe3  Rxe3  16.fxe3  c6  where he has some compensation for the Pawn as White has to watch out for e3. We have a stronger move, though. }
14. Re6
{ Black doesn't have anything better than  14...Bxc3  15.Rxe8+  Qxe8  16.bxc3  with a huge advantage for White. }
*

