{ Whenever I look at this position, I am thinking: 'Gaju, there has to be something, at least a quarter of an idea for black. Pair of Bishops, 'f' file, come on!'. And then, I am failing to find it, every single time... }
9... Ba6 { Attacking the Rook. } 10. Nd3
{ This square is incredibly useful! Attacking c5, defending f2, covering f1... }
10... Bb6 11. Bg5
{ It makes sense to pin the Knight, especially when e3 was not available for our Bishop. We should also learn, why 11.Re1?! wouldn't be good now:   11.Re1?!  d5!  12.exd5  Bxd3!  13.cxd3   but not  13.Qxd3??  Ng4-+  , this wouldn't be possible with the Black's Bishop on d4!  13...Bxf2+!  14.Kxf2  Ng4+  15.Kg1  Qh4  16.h3  Nf2  17.Qe2  Nxh3  18.gxh3  Qg3+  with a perpetual check. }
11... Qe7
{ A clever try. Both  11...d6  12.Kh1  @@StartBracket@@preparing f2-f3@@EndBracket@@ and  11...Qe8  12.Re1  would be easily better for White. }
12. e5
{ After the text move the next moves are forced. Before that, let's quickly have a look at the alternatives:  12.Re1??  would be a terrible  12...Bxd3  13.Qxd3  Bxf2+  14.Kxf2  Ng4  15.Kg1  Qxg5  and White is on the verge of losing;   And  12.Kh1  looks logical, however after  12...h6!  White can't go  13.Bh4  because of  13...g5!  14.Bg3  Nxe4  15.Nxe4  Qxe4  and Black is fine.  12.Kh1  h6!  13.Bxf6  Qxf6  instead, should give Black decent compensation for the Pawn. }
12... Bxd3
{ The only move. The Bishop has eliminated the defender of the Pawn so we don't really have the choice too. }
13. exf6 gxf6
{ 14.Qxd3  fxg5  would be ok for Black, but why should we allow him to fix his Pawn structure?! }
14. Bh6 Bxf1 15. Qg4+ Kh8 16. Bxf8 Rxf8 17. Kxf1
{ White has a safer King and a better pawn-structure and nice possibilities to activate the Rook. }
