[White "4. Ruy Lopez Jaenisch/Schliemann (3...f5)"]
[Black "Schliemann 4...fxe4, 6...Bc5 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ Black is fighting for the center in a very aggressive and risky @@StartBracket@@dubious@@EndBracket@@ way. The Jaenisch or the Schliemann Gambit was always considered a surprise line and nothing has changed in this regard.   However in the recent years there were some interesting developments for both sides which brought attention of some top level players. }
4. d3
{ This choice is solid but also quite challenging - no surprise it is so popular. }
4... fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O Bc5
{ Black is ready to sacrifice a Pawn in order to quickly develop his Bishop to a good square. }
7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. Nxe5
{ Accepting the sacrifice has a long-standing reputation of a good and solid continuation. As the following lines will show, Black struggles to find a compensation for the Pawn and even if he gets one, it usually means that he might catch a draw at best. }
8... O-O 9. Nc3
{ Whenever I look at this position, I am thinking: 'Gaju, there has to be something, at least a quarter of an idea for black. Pair of Bishops, 'f' file, come on!'. And then, I am failing to find it, every single time... }
9... d5
{ It makes a lot of sense for Black to open up the position so I was surprised to see that this move is practically ignored, although - after taking a closer look - Black is not doing well at all. }
10. Bf4
{ The strongest move. White takes advantage of the fact that Black can't really take on e4 - after Queens exchange white would just take on c6. Are there any other moves instead of 10. Bf4?   Immediate  10.Nxc6  would be greedy - after  10...Qe8  Black should get nice compensation for the Pawn.   And  10.exd5  cxd5  11.Bg5  is a solid alternative, but - as I wrote - our choice is stronger. }
10... Qe8 { This is too slow. } 11. Nd3
{ White benefits from the fact that the Knight can retreat with a tempo. }
11... Bb6 12. exd5 cxd5 13. Re1
{ We can place the Bishop on g3 which should secure the position of the King. White is a clear Pawn up. }
