[Round "?"]
[White "4. Ruy Lopez Jaenisch/Schliemann (3...f5)"]
[Black "Schliemann 4...fxe4, 6...Bc5 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ Black is fighting for the center in a very aggressive and risky @@StartBracket@@dubious@@EndBracket@@ way. The Jaenisch or the Schliemann Gambit was always considered a surprise line and nothing has changed in this regard.   However in the recent years there were some interesting developments for both sides which brought attention of some top level players. }
4. d3
{ This choice is solid but also quite challenging - no surprise it is so popular. }
4... fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O Bc5
{ Black is ready to sacrifice a Pawn in order to quickly develop his Bishop to a good square. }
7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. Nxe5
{ Accepting the sacrifice has a long-standing reputation of a good and solid continuation. As the following lines will show, Black struggles to find a compensation for the Pawn and even if he gets one, it usually means that he might catch a draw at best. }
8... O-O 9. Nc3
{ Whenever I look at this position, I am thinking: 'Gaju, there has to be something, at least a quarter of an idea for black. Pair of Bishops, 'f' file, come on!'. And then, I am failing to find it, every single time... }
9... d6
{ This is clearly the main continuation. It is based on a simple tactical motif -  10.Nxc6?!  Qe8  - and Black wins an important Pawn on e4. }
10. Na4
{ Tactics in the service of strategy! With help of this little trick White eliminates Black's most active piece leaving him without the initiative he was hoping for. However this means the opposite-color Bishops will remain on the board so we will be facing the drawing tendencies from now on.   It is worth mentioning that the other option is  10.Nd3  - after  10...Bd4!  11.Ne2  Bb6  12.Bg5  Qe8  13.Bxf6  Rxf6  14.Ng3  we have reached the position from Anand-Carlsen, Bilbao 2008 - back in a day it was considered to be the mainline. }
10... Bxf2+
{ wins the Pawn back, however the resulting endgame will be difficult for Black as we shall see. }
11. Rxf2 dxe5 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Bg5
{ We would be more than happy to play the N vs B. } 13... Rd4
{ The only sensible way. Otherwise the White's Knight would dominate the Black's Bishop for example:  13...Rd6  14.Nc5  and White can build a solid Pawn blockade on the queenside - a2, b3, c4. Black's position is objectively bad and practically terrible. }
14. Bxf6 Rxa4 15. Bxe5 Rxe4 16. Bxc7
{ White is a Pawn up. We should place the Pawns on the light squares, the Bishop would feel great on c3. }
