7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. Nxe5
{ Accepting the sacrifice has a long-standing reputation of a good and solid continuation. As the following lines will show, Black struggles to find a compensation for the Pawn and even if he gets one, it usually means that he might catch a draw at best. }
8... O-O 9. Nc3
{ Whenever I look at this position, I am thinking: 'Gaju, there has to be something, at least a quarter of an idea for black. Pair of Bishops, 'f' file, come on!'. And then, I am failing to find it, every single time... }
9... d6
{ This is clearly the main continuation. It is based on a simple tactical motif -  10.Nxc6?!  Qe8  - and Black wins an important Pawn on e4. }
10. Na4
{ Tactics in the service of strategy! With help of this little trick White eliminates Black's most active piece leaving him without the initiative he was hoping for. However this means the opposite-color Bishops will remain on the board so we will be facing the drawing tendencies from now on.   It is worth mentioning that the other option is  10.Nd3  - after  10...Bd4!  11.Ne2  Bb6  12.Bg5  Qe8  13.Bxf6  Rxf6  14.Ng3  we have reached the position from Anand-Carlsen, Bilbao 2008 - back in a day it was considered to be the mainline. }
