[White "4. Ruy Lopez Jaenisch/Schliemann (3...f5)"]
[Black "Schliemann 4...fxe4, 6...d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ Black is fighting for the center in a very aggressive and risky @@StartBracket@@dubious@@EndBracket@@ way. The Jaenisch or the Schliemann Gambit was always considered a surprise line and nothing has changed in this regard.   However in the recent years there were some interesting developments for both sides which brought attention of some top level players. }
4. d3
{ This choice is solid but also quite challenging - no surprise it is so popular. }
4... fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O d6
{ This is the line we should be expecting from the Jeanisch players right now. White has a slight positional advantage due to the weak light squares in black's camp as well as the passive Bishop on f8.   However the complex character of the position will make it difficult to exploit these weaknesses. }
7. Bc4
{ The Bishop was not very useful on b5 and here it is ideally placed, also stopping Be6. }
7... Bg4
{ Black immediately occupies the 2nd best square for their light-squared Bishop. }
8. h3 Bh5 9. Nc3 Nd4
{ This move, played in Caruana-Aronian game in London 2018, disregards one of the fundamental rules of chess - develop your pieces first! Aronian got away, he actually won the game. Let's see where Caruana could have improved. }
10. g4 Nxg4 { This not only looses to 11. Nxd4. It turns out that } 11. hxg4
{ is winning as well thanks to the old trick. } 11... Bxg4 12. Nxe5
{ and capturing the queen leads to mate in two. } 12... Bxd1 13. Bf7+ Ke7 14.
Nd5# *

