{ This is the line we should be expecting from the Jeanisch players right now. White has a slight positional advantage due to the weak light squares in black's camp as well as the passive Bishop on f8.   However the complex character of a position will make it difficult to exploit these weaknesses. }
7. Bc4
{ The Bishop was not very useful on b5 and here it is ideally placed, also stopping Be6. }
7... Bg4
{ Black immediately occupies the 2nd best square for their light-squared Bishop. }
8. h3 Bh5 9. Nc3 Qd7 { Stopping g2-g4 but also making long castle possible. }
10. Be3
{ On most of the occasions following Fabiano Caruana can't be wrong and this time it is no different. The engines recommend  10.Nd5  O-O-O  11.Qd3  , however once you get deeper you realize it is difficult to prove White's advantage while the lines are getting really complicated. }
10... O-O-O { White is more than ready for this. } 11. Rb1
{ It might look slow but once the Pawn gets to b5... } 11... Bg6 12. b4
{ The attack is strong enough to give up on our central Pawn. That said,  12.Nd2  or  12.Bd3  would be also fine. }
12... Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. b5 Na5 15. Bd5 Bxd5 16. Qxd5
{ White has a simple yet deadly threat - Be3-d2. } 16... Re8 17. b6 axb6 18.
Bxb6 Nc6 { A right choice. } 19. Be3
{ White has a very simple and powerful plan of doubling the Rooks on the b file. }
19... e4
{ Seeking a counterplay is perfectly natural but this weakens a crucial square. }
20. Rxb7
{ This was not possible a move ago. However the Knight can join the attack via d4 which changes the position completely. }
20... exf3 { 21.Rfb1  Re5  is not at all clear so what shall we do? } 21. Ra7
{ Seeing this tactic in advance @@StartBracket@@or learning it from our course :P@@EndBracket@@ was absolutely necessary to go for 20. Rxb7 in the first place. }
*

