[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Ruy Lopez Jaenisch/Schliemann (3...f5)"]
[Black "Schliemann 4...fxe4, 6...d6 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 f5
{ Black is fighting for the center in a very aggressive and risky @@StartBracket@@dubious@@EndBracket@@ way. The Jaenisch or the Schliemann Gambit was always considered a surprise line and nothing has changed in this regard.   However in the recent years there were some interesting developments for both sides which brought attention of some top level players. }
4. d3
{ This choice is solid but also quite challenging - no surprise it is so popular. }
4... fxe4 5. dxe4 Nf6 6. O-O d6
{ This is the line we should be expecting from the Jeanisch players right now. White has a slight positional advantage due to the weak light squares in black's camp as well as the passive Bishop on f8.   However the complex character of a position will make it difficult to exploit these weaknesses. }
7. Bc4
{ The Bishop was not very useful on b5 and here it is ideally placed, also stopping Be6. }
7... Bg4
{ Black immediately occupies the 2nd best square for their light-squared Bishop. }
8. h3 Bh5 9. Nc3 Qd7 { Stopping g2-g4 but also making long castle possible. }
10. Be3
{ On most of the occasions following Fabiano Caruana can't be wrong and this time it is no different. The engines recommend  10.Nd5  O-O-O  11.Qd3  , however once you get deeper you realize it is difficult to prove White's advantage while the lines are getting really complicated. }
10... Be7
{ Black delays a decision to castle queenside while making a useful move. } 11.
a4
{ This Pawn advance is quite typical. In fact it is most often seen in the Be7 setup in Giuco Piano. One point is to make some room for the Bishop so white wouldn't have to worry about Na5. The other one is to advance the Pawn as far as possible in order to create a weakness in Black's camp. }
11... a5
{ This move weakens b5 and also takes a5 away from the Knight - seems irrelevant right now but let's make a few moves. }
12. Re1 { preparing Nd5. } 12... h6
{ Black has to cover g5 or he won't be able to play Bf7 when necessary . } 13.
Nd5 Nxe4 { Not only this looks bad but blunders some tricks as well. } 14. Nxe5
{ 14.Bb6!? wouldn't be bad as well but this is just winning. } 14... Bxd1 15.
Nxd7 Bxc2
{ 15...Kxd7  16.Raxd1  would be too simple - with threats like Be3-b6 or Nd5-f4 White easily wins. }
16. N7b6 cxb6 17. Re2
{ White wins the piece back and Black's position should collapse soon. I was considering highlighting some squares in Black's camp but I quickly gave up on that idea as I would practically have to highlight half of the board. }
