[Black "Cozio Defense 3...a6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nge7 5. Nc3
{ 5.d4  exd4  6.Nxd4  is weaker now - White has already committed to Bb5-a4 which helps Black. We could go 6.O-O!? but I want to give Black a chance to use a bad line. }
5... d6 { It looks like Cozio is playing Delayed the Schliemann! } 6. O-O Bd7
{ The main point of this setup is that Black is more or less prepared for  7.d4  -  7...b5  followed by 8...Nxd4 gives him a decent position. }
7. Re1 { Hence, the waiting move instead! } 7... g6
{ Here this setup doesn't work well. } 8. d4
{ if  8...exd4  then  9.Nd5  Bg7  10.Bg5  h6  11.Bf6  with advantage. } 8...
Bg7 9. dxe5
{ Going for a symmetrical structure makes sense as the Black pieces won't be well placed. }
9... Nxe5
{ Trying to get rid of the Knight. True, it is a bit crowded in Black's camp. }
10. Nxe5 dxe5 { or  10...Bxe5  11.Bb3  with advantage. } 11. Bb3
{ Our light-squared Bishop is stronger so why swap it? } 11... Nc6
{ After normal  11...O-O  12.h4!  would be strong. Besides h4-h5 the point is that  12...Nc6  is now met with  13.Bg5! }
12. Nd5 { Followed by c2-c3. White has a clear advantage. } *

