[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Ruy Lopez Cozio Defense (3...Nge7)"]
[Black "Cozio Defense 3...a6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nge7 5. Nc3
{ 5.d4  exd4  6.Nxd4  is weaker now - White has already committed to Bb5-a4 which helps Black. We could go 6.O-O!? but I want to give Black a chance to use a bad line. }
5... d6 { It looks like Cozio is playing Delayed the Schliemann! } 6. O-O Bd7
{ The main point of this setup is that Black is more or less prepared for  7.d4  -  7...b5  followed by 8...Nxd4 gives him a decent position. }
7. Re1 { Hence, the waiting move instead! } 7... Ng6 8. Nd5
{ The takes the central outpost making room for c2-c3. } 8... Be7
{ Natural move but it allows us to execute our plan. } 9. c3 O-O 10. Bc2
{ This is more accurate than  10.d4  Bg4! } 10... Kh8
{ Black is preparing f7-f5. Immediate  10...f5?!  would be met with  11.exf5  Rxf5  12.Bxf5  Bxf5  13.Qb3!  and Black is losing the Pawn on b7. }
11. d4 { Due to f7-f5 threat we could not wait any longer. } 11... Bg4 12. h3
{ It is just my preference.  12.Nxe7  Qxe7  13.d5  would be good enough - White has a slight advantage thanks to a space advantage. The plan is quite typical - we will advance the queenside pawns. }
12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3 exd4
{ The idea of sacrificing the central pawn for the long term compensation is already well known in the Ruy Lopez. Probably the most famous example is Bronstein - Keres from the Candidates tournament in 1950.   What is white getting in return? Quite a lot, actually - a Bishop pair is nice but more importantly he gets a lot of space while Black will struggle to find the right places for his pieces. }
14. Qd3
{ Creating a nice battery on b1-h7 diagonal but also enabling the f pawn march. }
14... Bf6 15. f4
{ The g2 pawn will join the march. Basically our plan is to push the g Pawn - simple and dangerous. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Ruy Lopez Cozio Defense (3...Nge7)"]
[Black "Cozio Defense 3...a6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nge7 5. Nc3
{ 5.d4  exd4  6.Nxd4  is weaker now - White has already committed to Bb5-a4 which helps Black. We could go 6.O-O!? but I want to give Black a chance to use a bad line. }
5... d6 { It looks like Cozio is playing Delayed the Schliemann! } 6. O-O Bd7
{ The main point of this setup is that Black is more or less prepared for  7.d4  -  7...b5  followed by 8...Nxd4 gives him a decent position. }
7. Re1 { Hence, the waiting move instead! } 7... Ng6 8. Nd5
{ The takes the central outpost making room for c2-c3. } 8... b5
{ Black uses the opportunity to trade our light-squared Bishop but it comes with a price. }
9. Bb3 Na5 10. d4
{ The black Knight no longer controls d4 so we don't need c2-c3. } 10... Nxb3
11. axb3 c6
{ The Knight must have been really annoying on d5 but it's going to be strong enough on e3. }
12. Ne3 Be7 13. Nf5
{ Here immediate  13.g3!?  intending h2-h4-h5 was also possible. The difference was that after  13...f6  @@StartBracket@@preparing Ng6-h8 in case of h2-h4@@EndBracket@@ White could no longer open the d file as after  14.dxe5  Black had  14...fxe5  . Instead, 14.d5 was preferable with a slight edge for White. }
13... O-O 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. Be3
{ Our follow-up plan is to move the Rook to d2, then capture the dark-squared Bishop and move the Knight via e1 to d3 - there is a potential outpost on c5! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Ruy Lopez Cozio Defense (3...Nge7)"]
[Black "Cozio Defense 3...a6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nge7 5. Nc3
{ 5.d4  exd4  6.Nxd4  is weaker now - White has already committed to Bb5-a4 which helps Black. We could go 6.O-O!? but I want to give Black a chance to use a bad line. }
5... g6 { Now we are more or less forced to push the Pawn to d4. } 6. d4 exd4
7. Nd5 { The normal 7. Nxd4 was also possible but I like this more. } 7... Nxd5
{ Taking the Knight is a big mistake but, according to database, it has been made more than a dozen of times already so let's have a quick look. }
8. exd5 Qe7+ { The only possible explanation I can think of. } 9. Kf1
{ Black's Queen looks really awkward on e7. } 9... Ne5 10. Bf4 Bg7
{ 10...Nxf3??  11.Qxf3  and 12. Re1 is coming. } 11. Qxd4 f6 12. Re1
{ After  12...O-O  we simply collect the Pawn with  13.Nxe5  fxe5  14.Bxe5  . }
