1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7
{ To those of you who aren't too familiar with Cozio Defense - it is a serious line and it's not a coincidence that some strong players have incorporated it into their repertoires.   If you consider doing the same - I recommend Erwin l'Ami's course - it took me quite some time to find a challenge that he hasn't solved already! }
4. d4
{ I don't like  4.O-O  too much - Black can choose between  4...g6  and  4...Ng6  setups which means more work for us.   And  4.Nc3!?  is another interesting direction but - as I mentioned - Erwin hasn't left too much room for discoveries. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Nxd4 6. Qxd4 c6
{ This plan doesn't work well mainly because of Black's Knight being developed to e7 instead of normal f6. }
7. Bc4
{ 7.Bd3  would be equally good but since Black has this funny move-order - 4...Nxd4 5. Nxd4 c6 - he can bypass this option. }
7... d5 8. Bb3 Qb6
{ If we swaps the Queens now Black might actually get a decent position. } 9.
Qd1
{ A bit unusual but the Queen will be nicely placed here with the d1-h5 diagonal available. }
9... dxe4 10. Nc3 Nf5 { 10...Ng6  wouldn't change anything. } 11. O-O
{ The Pawn will be captured on the next move. } 11... Be7 12. Nxe4 O-O 13. c3
{ Black's main problem is that he can't develop the light-squared Bishop without ruining anything. }
