[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Ruy Lopez Cozio Defense (3...Nge7)"]
[Black "Cozio Defense 3...Nge7 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7
{ To those of you who aren't too familiar with Cozio Defense - it is a serious line and it's not a coincidence that some strong players have incorporated it into their repertoires.   If you consider doing the same - I recommend Erwin l'Ami's course - it took me quite some time to find a challenge that he hasn't solved already! }
4. d4
{ I don't like  4.O-O  too much - Black can choose between  4...g6  and  4...Ng6  setups which means more work for us.   And  4.Nc3!?  is another interesting direction but - as I mentioned - Erwin hasn't left too much room for discoveries. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Nxd4 6. Qxd4 Nc6 7. Qe3 { Preventing 7...Bc5. } 7... Be7 8.
Nc3 O-O 9. O-O { The last few moves were rather automatic. } 9... Re8
{ l'Ami's recommendation. Black's last move is very flexible - the Pawn might still go to d6 but in some cases White has to reckon with d7-d5 too. Another benefit is that Black's dark-squared Bishop might still use a3-f8 diagonal at some point.   Finally the Rook is simply well positioned on e8 - especially with our Queen on e3. There is a big question - how should White play?   I learned from Erwin's course that  10.Nd5  is successfully met with  10...Nb4!  or  10...Bd6!?  intending Nc6-e7,   while  10.Bd2  Bf6  is not clear at all - I definitely want to play  11.Nd5  but I am not sure if I am willing to give away a Pawn for it. }
10. Rd1
{ This was missing in Erwin's course. Now we welcome both  10...d6  11.Nd5   and  10...Bf6  11.Nd5  . }
10... Ne5 { The Knight moves to the center making room for the Pawns. } 11. a4
{ White's last move prevents a potential counterplay on the Queenside. } 11...
c6 12. Be2 { Covering g4 is useful. } 12... d6 13. Qd4
{ Already f7-f5 was there so it's better to remove the Queen from the e file. }
13... Bf8 14. Bf4
{ Black's position is very solid and has no weaknesses. But so is ours plus our pieces are quite active and Black's pieces aren't. We should consider correcting the position of our Rooks - they would be best placed on e1 and d1! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Ruy Lopez Cozio Defense (3...Nge7)"]
[Black "Cozio Defense 3...Nge7 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7
{ To those of you who aren't too familiar with Cozio Defense - it is a serious line and it's not a coincidence that some strong players have incorporated it into their repertoires.   If you consider doing the same - I recommend Erwin l'Ami's course - it took me quite some time to find a challenge that he hasn't solved already! }
4. d4
{ I don't like  4.O-O  too much - Black can choose between  4...g6  and  4...Ng6  setups which means more work for us.   And  4.Nc3!?  is another interesting direction but - as I mentioned - Erwin hasn't left too much room for discoveries. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Nxd4 6. Qxd4 Nc6 7. Qe3 { Preventing 7...Bc5. } 7... Be7 8.
Nc3 O-O 9. O-O { The last few moves were rather automatic. } 9... Re8
{ l'Ami's recommendation. Black's last move is very flexible - the Pawn might still go to d6 but in some cases White has to reckon with d7-d5 too. Another benefit is that Black's dark-squared Bishop might still use a3-f8 diagonal at some point.   Finally the Rook is simply well positioned on e8 - especially with our Queen on e3. There is a big question - how should White play?   I learned from Erwin's course that  10.Nd5  is successfully met with  10...Nb4!  or  10...Bd6!?  intending Nc6-e7,   while  10.Bd2  Bf6  is not clear at all - I definitely want to play  11.Nd5  but I am not sure if I am willing to give away a Pawn for it. }
10. Rd1
{ This was missing in Erwin's course. Now we welcome both  10...d6  11.Nd5   and  10...Bf6  11.Nd5  . }
10... d6 11. Nd5 { Nc6-b4 is no longer available. } 11... Bh4
{ Black is trying to provoke g2-g3 which would weaken the light squares in our camp. }
12. Bd2
{ Simply ignoring Black's last move is the best answer. I also like  12.a4!?  preventing potential counterplay on the Queenside. After  12...a6  13.Bf1  Ne7  13.Nc3!  White is slightly better. }
12... a6 13. Bf1 Ne7 { Black wants to eliminate our strongest piece. } 14. Qb3
Nxd5 15. exd5
{ The pawn structure has changed - it now resembles the Berlin Defense @@StartBracket@@5.Re1 line specifically@@EndBracket@@ but it is a good version for us! }
15... Bf6 16. Re1
{ The light-squared Bishop is Black's main problem - it is simply not easy to find a place for it. We don't mind exchanging the dark-squared Bishops and, after that, we have a lot of useful Pawn moves such as g2-g3 and h2-h4 or a2-a4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Ruy Lopez Fianchetto Defense"]
[Black "Fianchetto Defense 3...a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 g6 { An inaccurate move-order as you shall see. } 5. d4 exd4 6. Nxd4 Bg7
7. Nxc6
{ Compared with 3...g6 @@StartBracket@@so without a7-a6 - Bb5-Ba4@@EndBracket@@, after Black recaptures on c6, the White Bishop will not be attacked so we basically gain a tempo. }
7... bxc6
{ So many games have been played in this position but it's just terrible for Black. }
8. Nc3 Ne7 9. Be3
{ We will castle long and launch an attack on the Kingside. White's light-squared Bishop is a great defender. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Ruy Lopez Fianchetto Defense"]
[Black "Fianchetto Defense 3...a6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 g6 { An inaccurate move-order as you shall see. } 5. d4 exd4 6. Nxd4 Bg7
7. Nxc6
{ Compared with 3...g6 @@StartBracket@@so without a7-a6 - Bb5-Ba4@@EndBracket@@, after Black recaptures on c6, white Bishop will not be attacked so we basically gain a tempo. }
7... dxc6
{ Objectively the best, although White will enjoy a nice edge in the endgame. }
8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Bb3
{ After  9...Nf6  we can follow-up with  10.f3  and then put the King on e2, Knight on c3 and the Bishop on f4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Ruy Lopez Fianchetto Defense"]
[Black "Fianchetto Defense 3...a6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 g6 { An inaccurate move-order as you shall see. } 5. d4 b5
{ It's an interesting line if White doesn't know how to react. If he does - it is not fun for Black at all. }
6. Bb3 exd4 7. a4
{ The most accurate.  7.Nxd4  gives Black an extra option:  7...Bb7  8.a4  Bg7!?  . The point is that after  9.Nxc6  dxc6  10.Qxd8+  @@StartBracket@@he can recapture with the Rook@@EndBracket@@, or  10.Qf3!?  . White is still nice but it is an upgrade for Black compared with 5...exd4 line. }
7... Bb7
{ This was only tried once - in a game between Anna Muzychuk and Antoneta Stefanova - FIDE GP, Lausanne 2020. }
8. axb5 axb5 9. Rxa8 Bxa8 10. c3
{ Black is underdeveloped so we should play actively. } 10... dxc3
{ Accepting the sacrifice is risky but possible. } 11. Nxc3 Bg7 12. Bg5
{ Surely an unpleasant moment for Black who just can't catch a breath. } 12...
Qb8
{ The Queen protects the Pawn but actually Black had no choice -  12...Nge7  13.Nd5  would be untenable. }
13. O-O h6 { Trying to chase away the Bishop only helps White: } 14. Bf4 Nge7
15. Re1
{ Black is in a very difficult situation - he can't castle because of 16.Qxd7,  15...d6?  runs into  16.e5!  destroying Black's position. He can try  15...g5  but after  16.Be3  his light squares are weakened - just imagine Nc3-e2-g3. Also  16...O-O  is still not possible -  17.Bxg5!  wins. }
*

