[White "6. Ruy Lopez Fianchetto Defense"]
[Black "Fianchetto Defense 3...a6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 g6 { An inaccurate move-order as you shall see. } 5. d4 b5
{ It's an interesting line if White doesn't know how to react. If he does - it is not fun for Black at all. }
6. Bb3 exd4 7. a4
{ The most accurate.  7.Nxd4  gives Black an extra option:  7...Bb7  8.a4  Bg7!?  . The point is that after  9.Nxc6  dxc6  10.Qxd8+  @@StartBracket@@he can recapture with the Rook@@EndBracket@@, or  10.Qf3!?  . White is still nice but it is an upgrade for Black compared with 5...exd4 line. }
7... Bb7
{ This was only tried once - in a game between Anna Muzychuk and Antoneta Stefanova - FIDE GP, Lausanne 2020. }
8. axb5 axb5 9. Rxa8 Bxa8 10. c3
{ Black is underdeveloped so we should play actively. } 10... Bg7
{ Finishing development seems like the right thing to do. } 11. cxd4 Na5 12.
O-O
{ In the aforementioned game Muzychuk played the slower  12.Bc2  and after  12....Nf6  13.O-O  O-O  Black was ok.   Our point is that  12...Nf6  gives White a strong initiative after  13.e5  Nd5  14.Bg5  . }
12... Nxb3
{ Swapping our light-squared Bishop is usually a success for Black. } 13. Qxb3
{ Here, however, we simply win the Pawn on b5 as Black has no time to defend it. }
13... Nf6 14. Nc3 { The Pawn on e4 is untouchable, Black has to castle first. }
14... O-O 15. e5 Ne4 16. Qxb5
{ As usual, with the pair of Bishops, Black has some drawing chances but otherwise, this is clear Pawn up. We can place the Rook on e1 and develop the Bishop to f4 or g5 or even d2 - depending on Black's play. }
