7... b4 8. Nxd4
{ The main upgrade for White is that our light-squared Bishop gained the a2 and c4 squares. Also  8...Bb7  is not possible now -  9.Nxc6  dxc6  is an entirely different story - Normally Black would never weaken the c4 square voluntarily.  10.Nd2  gives White an overwhelming edge. }
8... Na5 9. Bd5
{ 9.Ba2  was also possible but this is cutting some extra options for Black. }
9... c6 10. Ba2
{ Black's position already looks akward but he does have some reasonable counterplay thanks to c6-c5. For now he has to catch up with the development. }
10... Bg7 11. O-O Ne7
{ If Black manages to play d7-d6 and c6-c5 without our interference he might actually get a decent game. Therefore we are going to interfere. }
12. c3 { Speeding up the events. } 12... c5 13. cxb4
{ In Dominguez - Nakamura, Opera euro rapid, 2020,  13.Nb3  was played. It is also what Swiercz recommends. After careful investigation I wasn't sure - White was is fighting for advantage but not always succeeding. }
13... cxb4 14. Nd2
{ This is an inherent part of the plan. Yes, White does seem to have dropped a Knight but these are just appearances. }
14... Bxd4 { Let's see where the 'obvious' continuation leads us... } 15. Nc4
{ So far this is quite simple, White threatens 16. Qxd4 and 16. Nd6+. } 15...
Bc5 { But Black can defend against both of them, so what now? } 16. Qd6
{ A beautiful strike! It is also a great example of how important a fianchettoed Bishop can be for the King's safety - as soon as it leaves its spot the problems arrive. Black's position is collapsing. }
16... Nxc4 { The only way to keep fighting. } 17. Qxc5
{ White is a piece down however, our Bishops are extremally powerful while Black's forces are still not ready for a fight. }
17... Na5 { The Knight is coming back to c6. } 18. Qxb4
{ It's not a usual pawn-grabbing - we had to stop b4-b3. Black is in some serious trouble - he can't castle -  18...O-O  19.Bh6  is just winning for White. }
18... d6 { I really can't think of anything else. } 19. Rd1 Be6
{ It's totally understandable that Black wants to simplify the position as it might diminish White's initiative. In a way he is unlucky - this would work if we didn't have a very specific solution: }
20. Bf4
{ Not falling for the trick:  20.Rxd6?  Qxd6!  21.Qxd6  Rd8  and thanks to back rank problem Black is getting out of trouble. }
20... Bxa2 { This looks risky but what is the refutation? } 21. Rxd6 Qc7 22.
Rxa6 { It is actually quite simple. } 22... Qd8 23. Bc7
{ This is a nice double attack. } 23... Qc8 24. Rxa5 Rxa5 25. Bxa5 Be6
{ White has three Pawns for the piece and a much better position - Black still hasn't castled and all his dark squares are weak. }
26. Qb5+
{ Nice, disturbing move. Neither  26...Nc6  27.Rc1   nor  26...Kf8  27.Bc3  looks favorable for Black. }
26... Qc6 27. Bc3
{ This surprising resource is practically winning by force, so let's see a few more moves: }
27... Qxb5 28. axb5 O-O
{ Black is missing one move to coordinate @@StartBracket@@as always!@@EndBracket@@. }
29. Bb4 Re8 30. b6 { The Pawn will decide. } 30... Nc6 31. b7
{ The Bishop cannot be taken -  31...Nxb4  32.Ra8  wins. } 31... Rb8 32. Ra8
Kg7 33. Rxb8 Nxb8 34. Bd6
{ The Bishop endgame will be easily winning for White - just play f2-f3 and bring the King to the center. }
