[White "6. Ruy Lopez Fianchetto Defense"]
[Black "Fianchetto Defense 3...a6 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 g6 { An inaccurate move-order as you shall see. } 5. d4 b5
{ It's an interesting line if White doesn't know how to react. If he does - it is not fun for Black at all. }
6. Bb3 exd4 7. a4
{ The most accurate.  7.Nxd4  gives Black an extra option:  7...Bb7  8.a4  Bg7!?  . The point is that after  9.Nxc6  dxc6  10.Qxd8+  @@StartBracket@@he can recapture with the Rook@@EndBracket@@, or  10.Qf3!?  . White is still nice but it is an upgrade for Black compared with 5...exd4 line. }
7... b4 8. Nxd4
{ The main upgrade for White is that our light-squared Bishop gained the a2 and c4 squares. Also  8...Bb7  is not possible now -  9.Nxc6  dxc6  is an entirely different story - Normally Black would never weaken the c4 square voluntarily.  10.Nd2  gives White an overwhelming edge. }
8... Na5 9. Bd5
{ 9.Ba2  was also possible but this is cutting some extra options for Black. }
9... c6 10. Ba2
{ Black's position already looks akward but he does have some reasonable counterplay thanks to c6-c5. For now he has to catch up with the development. }
10... Bg7 11. O-O Ne7
{ If Black manages to play d7-d6 and c6-c5 without our interference he might actually get a decent game. Therefore we are going to interfere. }
12. c3 { Speeding up the events. } 12... c5 13. cxb4
{ In Dominguez - Nakamura, Opera euro rapid, 2020,  13.Nb3  was played. It is also what Swiercz recommends. After careful investigation I wasn't sure - White was is fighting for advantage but not always succeeding. }
13... cxb4 14. Nd2
{ This is an inherent part of the plan. Yes, White does seem to have dropped a Knight but these are just appearances. }
14... O-O
{ As we have seen, the Knight on d4 - despite a very appetizing look - was badly poisoned. Therefore this should be played. }
15. N2b3
{ 15.N2f3  was very serious - maybe even a bit stronger than our choice. It was also much more complicated and since this is not exactly the main position of the Marshall Gambit we should remain pragmatic. }
15... Nxb3 16. Bxb3 d5
{ Black's idea makes sense - after  17.exd5  he will go  17...Bb7  and White can't keep the Pawn. }
17. Bg5 { Luckily we don't need to take this Pawn. } 17... Bb7 18. e5
{ The best way - White doesn't let Black open up the position and activate his pieces - even at the cost of a Pawn. }
18... Bxe5 19. Re1 Qd6
{ Solid choice but now we will get a small and safe advantage: } 20. Bxe7 Qxe7
21. Nf3 { There is only one way to save the Bishop... } 21... f6 22. Bxd5+ Bxd5
23. Qxd5+ Qf7 24. Qd2
{ Black can now go  24...Rad8  25.Qxb4  Rb8  . The thing is that after  26.Qe4  Bxb2  27.Rab1  White is still a bit better - The Bishop struggles to find the right place on the board while White can try some advance on the Kingside - h2-h4-h5 specifically.   Of course going for a Rook endgame with a Pawn up is possible too but Black should be able to defend it quite easily. }
