[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Ruy Lopez Fianchetto Defense"]
[Black "Fianchetto Defense 3...g6, 5...f6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6
{ Black's main idea is to fianchetto the dark-squared Bishop not so it could defend the Pawn on e5 but rather to attack the white Pawn on d4. The Knight is usually developed to e7 so it doesn't go in the Bishop's way.   Black has no hurry with advancing the 'd' Pawn as it can move both to d6 and d5 - depending on the circumstances. In general this is an interesting line and we frequently see some aggressive players using it. For White I see two main challenges:   1@@EndBracket@@ in the main setup @@StartBracket@@c3, d4@@EndBracket@@ Black can use various move orders @@StartBracket@@g6, Bg7, Nge7 and a6 can be mixed in many ways@@EndBracket@@ and each of them has its own nuances, hence it is very easy to get confused;   2@@EndBracket@@ in many positions, even if White is objectively better, it may not last long due to their complicated nature, so many Black players won't mind '+=' at all. With our choice I will try to deal with both those challenges. }
4. d4
{ So the number one challenge is gone - Black won't get to confuse us with move-orders as we don't go for the main setup, at all! }
4... exd4 { There was no sensible alternative to this one. } 5. Bg5
{ This is a very healthy idea - White prevents Black from fianchettoing the dark-squared Bishop - the coolest thing in the whole line! Also Black has already managed to place the Pawn on g6 so he will have to deal with some weak dark squares from now on. }
5... f6
{ Ambitious, but mostly dubious. Black will hardly benefit from the Bishop on g7 with the Pawn on f6. }
6. Bf4 Bg7 7. O-O
{ Immediate  7.Nxd4  would allow  7...f5!  - the point is that after  8.e5  Black can go  8...Nxd4  9.Qxd4  c6!  followed by 10...d5 or 10...d6 with unclear an position. }
7... Nge7 8. Bc4
{ 8.Nxd4  was also possible but I prefer this one - Black has a big problem now as he can't castle. }
8... Ne5
{ Seemingly attractive as the other Knight can go to c6. It doesn't solve the main problem, though. }
9. Bb3 Nxf3+ 10. Qxf3 d6 11. c3
{ We don't mind being a Pawn down - White's pieces are clearly superior and our King placement in comparison is a big edge. }
11... Nc6 12. Qd3
{ Leaving Black with an unpleasant choice -  12...dxc3  13.Nxc3  is great for White while otherwise we win the Pawn back keeping the advantage too. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Ruy Lopez Fianchetto Defense"]
[Black "Fianchetto Defense 3...g6, 5...Be7, 7...Qb4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6
{ Black's main idea is to fianchetto the dark-squared Bishop not so it could defend the Pawn on e5 but rather to attack the white Pawn on d4. The Knight is usually developed to e7 so it doesn't go in the Bishop's way.   Black is not hurry with advancing the 'd' Pawn as it can move both to d6 and d5 - depending on the circumstances. In general this is an interesting line and we frequently see some aggressive players using it. For White I see two main challenges:   1@@EndBracket@@ in main setup @@StartBracket@@c3, d4@@EndBracket@@ Black can use various move orders @@StartBracket@@g6, Bg7, Nge7 and a6 can be mixed in many ways@@EndBracket@@ and each of them has its own nuances, hence it is very easy to get confused;   2@@EndBracket@@ in many positions, even if White is objectively better, it may not last long due to their complicated nature, so many Black players won't mind '+=' at all. With our choice I will try to deal with both those challenges. }
4. d4
{ So the number one challenge is gone - Black won't get to confuse us with move-orders as we don't go for the main setup, at all! }
4... exd4 { There was no sensible alternative to this one. } 5. Bg5
{ This is a very healthy idea - White prevents Black from fianchettoing the dark-squared Bishop - the coolest thing in the whole line! Also Black has already managed to place the Pawn on g6 so he will have to deal with some weak dark squares from now on. }
5... Be7
{ This is how Black should react, though I don't think it is an exciting decision. }
6. Bxe7 Qxe7 7. O-O
{ I believe the second challenge has already been overcome - there is nothing exciting in Black's position anymore and he can only fight for equality. In my opinion this is the strongest reaction although for Black the road to equality is long and bumpy. }
7... Qb4
{ One of several moves. Black is trying to simplify the game but the resulting endgame will be favourable for White. }
8. Bxc6 bxc6
{ Although recapturing with a b-Pawn is quite popular it is actually a serious mistake. Black was already behind in development and now it will become a serious issue for him. }
9. Nbd2
{ Initiative is more important than the material. We are hoping to get e4-e5 and Nd2-e4. }
9... c5
{ The move is logical - he can now meet  10.e5  with  10...Bb7  . However there is a more straightforward continuation: }
10. c3 { Black's position should collapse after this. } 10... Qxb2
{ White is much better here, also quite easily. } 11. cxd4 Ne7
{ But not  11...cxd4??  12.Nc4+-  . } 12. Rb1 Qxa2 13. e5
{ The Knight will get to e4 sealing White's big advantage. } *

