{ This is how Black should react, though I don't think it is an exciting decision. }
6. Bxe7 Qxe7 7. O-O
{ I believe the second challenge has already been overcome - there is nothing exciting in Black's position anymore and he can only fight for equality. In my opinion this is the strongest reaction although for Black the road to equality is long and bumpy. }
7... Nf6 8. e5 { The most challenging try. } 8... Nd5
{ On one hand the Knight is better in the center, on the other one it does stand in front of the d7 Pawn. }
9. Nbd2
{ 9.Re1  is another possibility but it allows  9...Qb4!?  leading to an interesting game.   Our choice eliminates this option -  9.Nbd2  Qb4?!  10.Bc4! }
9... O-O { A solid choice but also quite pleasant for us. } 10. Re1
{ It is an unpleasant situation for Black - his usual freeing move -  10...d6  - doesn't work here due to  11.exd6  Qxd6  12.Ne4  followed by Bxc6 and Qxd4. }
10... a6
{ It was better to do this a move ago. Now we have a simple solution: } 11.
Bxc6
{ 11.Bc4  was also possible but after  11...Nf4!  @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1pppqp1p/p1n3p1/3nP3/2Bp4/5N2/PPPN1PPP/R2QR1K1 b - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Nb6  would transpose to the  9...a6 line@@EndBracket@@  12.Qc1  Kg7!  13.Ne4  Nh5  Black survived. }
11... dxc6 12. Nxd4
{ Once again we can enjoy a small but but long-lasting advantage thanks to a better Pawn structure. }
12... c5 13. N4f3
{ The other Knight will come to e4 leaving Black with a dilemma how to face c2-c4. As long as the Queens are on board we can try to exploit the dark squares with Qd1-c1.   Whenever Bc8-f5 is bothering us we can play h2-h3 - the point is in a typical sequence Bc8-f5 Ne4-g3 the Bishop can't move to g4. In some cases we can also just play g2-g4. }
