[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6
{ Black's main idea is to fianchetto the dark-squared Bishop not so it could defend the Pawn on e5 but rather to attack the white Pawn on d4. The Knight is usually developed to e7 so it doesn't go in the Bishop's way.   Black is not hurry with advancing the 'd' Pawn as it can move both to d6 and d5 - depending on the circumstances. In general this is an interesting line and we frequently see some aggressive players using it. For White I see two main challenges:   1@@EndBracket@@ in main setup @@StartBracket@@c3, d4@@EndBracket@@ Black can use various move orders @@StartBracket@@g6, Bg7, Nge7 and a6 can be mixed in many ways@@EndBracket@@ and each of them has its own nuances, hence it is very easy to get confused;   2@@EndBracket@@ in many positions, even if White is objectively better, it may not last long due to their complicated nature, so many Black players won't mind '+=' at all. With our choice I will try to deal with both those challenges. }
4. d4
{ So the number one challenge is gone - Black won't get to confuse us with move-orders as we don't go for the main setup, at all! }
4... exd4 { There was no sensible alternative to this one. } 5. Bg5
{ This is a very healthy idea - White prevents Black from fianchettoing the dark-squared Bishop - the coolest thing in the whole line! Also Black has already managed to place the Pawn on g6 so he will have to deal with some weak dark squares from now on. }
5... Be7
{ This is how Black should react, though I don't think it is an exciting decision. }
6. Bxe7 Qxe7 7. O-O
{ I believe the second challenge has already been overcome - there is nothing exciting in Black's position anymore and he can only fight for equality. In my opinion this is the strongest reaction although for Black the road to equality is long and bumpy. }
7... Nf6 8. e5 { The most challenging try. } 8... Nh5
{ Ambitious response. Black's point is that after  9.Nbd2  b6!  is strong -  10.Ne4  Bb7  and  11.g4??  is easily refuted with  11...Nxe5  . Notice that with the Knight on d5 White could play 11. c4 or 11. Bc4.   9.Re1  once again is met with  9...Qb4!?  with a complicated game. }
9. c3
{ Funnily I would normally think this has to be a good reaction to 8...Nd5 but of course it was not possible -  9.c3?!  dxc3!  White can simply play  10.Nxc3  and the Knight is once again coming to d5. }
9... a6
{ Black wants to push our Bishop away from this diagonal but he might also fianchetto his own Bishop. }
10. Ba4 b5
{ White is facing a typical dilemma -  11.Bb3  will later allow Nc6-a5 while  11.Bc2  will later allow Nc6-b4. }
11. Bc2 { It was a close call but I prefer this. } 11... Bb7
{ Allowing  12.cxd4  might look wrong but Black is relying on his light-squared Bishop and the counterplay it can bring. }
12. cxd4 Nb4 13. Bb3
{ Although  13.Nbd2  was also possible this looks critical.   If Black now goes  13...O-O  then after  14.Nc3  it won't be easy for him to deal with a2-a3 and d4-d5 threats. Therefore he is more or less forced to go... }
13... a5 { Since a5-a4 is coming the next few moves are very natural. } 14. a3
a4 { Retreating the Knight was not an option. } 15. axb4 axb3 { Nice Pawns! }
16. Rxa8+ Bxa8 17. Qxb3
{ We reached an interesting position - White is a Pawn up but Black has some compensation mainly thanks to the light-squared Bishop. }
17... Nf4 { Aggressive but otherwise not fully accurate. } 18. Rd1
{ It is about time for Black to realize there is no real attack on the kingside.  18...g5  can be easily parried with  19.Ne1! }
18... Nd5 19. Nc3 Qxb4 20. Qxb4 Nxb4
{ Now  21.Nxb5?!  Bxf3  22.gxf3  c6  23.Nc3  Ke7  would give Black nice compensation for the Pawn. }
21. d5
{ Locking away the Bishop. After the most natural  21...Ke7  we can go  22.Ng5!  The point is that after  22...d6?  White has  23.Rd4!  Nc2  24.Rf4!  .   After  21...Ke7  22.Ng5!  instead Black can go  22...f6!?  where after  23.exf6+  Kxf6  25.f4  White maintains a small plus. }
