4... exd4 { There was no sensible alternative to this one. } 5. Bg5
{ This is a very healthy idea - White prevents Black from fianchettoing the dark-squared Bishop - the coolest thing in the whole line! Also Black has already managed to place the Pawn on g6 so he will have to deal with some weak dark squares from now on. }
5... Be7
{ This is how Black should react, though I don't think it is an exciting decision. }
6. Bxe7 Qxe7 7. O-O
{ I believe the second challenge has already been overcome - there is nothing exciting in Black's position anymore and he can only fight for equality. In my opinion this is the strongest reaction although for Black the road to equality is long and bumpy. }
7... Nf6 8. e5 { The most challenging try. } 8... Nh5
{ Ambitious response. Black's point is that after  9.Nbd2  b6!  is strong -  10.Ne4  Bb7  and  11.g4??  is easily refuted with  11...Nxe5  . Notice that with the Knight on d5 White could play 11. c4 or 11. Bc4.   9.Re1  once again is met with  9...Qb4!?  with a complicated game. }
9. c3
{ Funnily I would normally think this has to be a good reaction to 8...Nd5 but of course it was not possible -  9.c3?!  dxc3!  White can simply play  10.Nxc3  and the Knight is once again coming to d5. }
9... a6
{ Black wants to push our Bishop away from this diagonal but he might also fianchetto his own Bishop. }
10. Ba4 d3 11. Re1 b5
{ Developing the light-squared Bishop is @@StartBracket@@again!@@EndBracket@@ the right plan. }
12. Bb3 Bb7 13. Qxd3
{ White looks just better here but Black has a way of complicating things which we should be aware of. }
13... Nf4 14. Qe3 g5 { Clearly there will be no castling kingside after this! }
15. Nbd2 O-O-O
{ With the Bishop on b7 and the Knight on f4 Black has fair counterplay. } 16.
a4 b4 17. h4 { Important intermezzo - we need h2 for the King. } 17... h6 18.
g3
{ It is important to chase away that Knight. Notice that without h2-h4 Black would have had the annoying Nf4-h3+ but it's not possible now as we have Kg1-h2. }
18... Rhg8
{ For a moment it can't be taken -  19.gxf4??  gxf4+  and Black wins our Queen. }
19. Kf1 { Black can no longer hold this outpost. } 19... Ne6 20. Ne4
{ White's position looks great for example  20...gxh4?  21.Nxh4  Nxe5  loses to  22.Nf5  Qf8  23.Ned6+!  cxd6  24.Qb6  .   White's main threat is to go Bb3-d5 which would deprive Black of any counterplay hence,  20...Na5  seems like the best move to which White should reply with  21.Bd1!   This is stronger than  21.Bc2  b3  . The Bishop is heading to e2 from where it covers some important squares on both sides. Also Black has to watch out for Qe3-a7. Finally, h4-h5 can be played at some point closing the position on the Kingside. }
