[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Ruy Lopez Classical Defense (3...Bc5)"]
[Black "Classical Defense 4...f5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5 4. c3 f5
{ One of the ideas that are always scary to face over the board but once you check them at home they are not scary at all. }
5. d4 { Usually the simplest means are the best. } 5... fxe4 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7.
Nxe5
{ One look at the pawn structure is enough to realize that White is simply better here. }
7... Bd6 8. Qh5+
{ Useful inclusion as Black has to weaken f6 square. That said White's position would be slightly better after any normal move such as  8.O-O  or  8.Bf4  . }
8... g6 9. Qe2
{ 9...Bxe5  10.Qxe4  is just clearly better for White so Black has to defend the Pawn. }
9... Qh4
{ The engines are laughing now but it used to be a serious line with more than a hundred games in the database! }
10. Nd2 Nf6
{ The Pawn is protected, Black is also ready to castle. Only the Queen looks a bit exposed... }
11. h3
{ Taking g4 under control is useful but this time we actually have bigger plans... }
11... O-O 12. g3 { Chasing away the defender of e4 Pawn... } 12... Qh5
{ Had Black predicted our next move he would have gone  12...Qh6  but of course  13.Nxe4  is just clearly better for White. }
13. g4 Qh4 { It was still not too late for  13...Qh6  , but why suffer? } 14.
Ndf3 { Black can resign. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Ruy Lopez Classical Defense (3...Bc5)"]
[Black "Classical Defense 4...f5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5 4. c3 f5
{ One of the ideas that are always scary to face over the board but once you check them at home they are not scary at all. }
5. d4 { Usually the simplest means are the best. } 5... fxe4 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7.
Nxe5
{ One look at the pawn structure is enough to realize that White just have to better here. }
7... Bd6 8. Qh5+
{ Useful inclusion as Black has to weaken f6 square. That said White's position would be slightly better after any normal move such as  8.O-O  or  8.Bf4  . }
8... g6 9. Qe2
{ 9...Bxe5  10.Qxe4  is just clearly better for White so Black has to defend the Pawn. }
9... Qh4
{ The engines are laughing now but it used to be a serious line with more than a hundred games in the database! }
10. Nd2 Bf5 11. h3
{ White is preparing 12.g4. Immediate  11.g4  Bxe5  12.dxe5  was also possible. }
11... Bxe5 { 11...h5  12.g3  and White wins the Pawn on e4. } 12. dxe5 Nh6
{ He is now ready to meet  13.g3  with  13...Qh5  while  13.g4  can't be played at all. }
13. Nxe4 { The whole 11. h3 line is based on this tactic. } 13... Qxe4
{ 13...Bxe4  14.g3!  and 15.Qxe4 +-. } 14. Bxh6 Qxg2 15. O-O-O
{ Black's King is very weak and with the opposite-colour Bishops on board it's usually the critical factor. }
15... Qe4 { Trading the Queens won't save Black. } 16. Qxe4 Bxe4 17. Rhe1
{ We will push the Pawn to e6 on the next move. Black can't set up a blockade, not with the King in the center plus there will always be c3-c4. }
