[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Ruy Lopez Classical Defense (3...Bc5)"]
[Black "Classical Defense 4...f5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5 4. c3 f5
{ One of the ideas that are always scary to face over the board but once you check them at home they are not scary at all. }
5. d4 { Usually the simplest means are the best. } 5... fxe4 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7.
Nxe5
{ One look at the pawn structure is enough to realize that White just have to better here. }
7... Bd6 8. Qh5+
{ Useful inclusion as Black has to weaken f6 square. That said White's position would be slightly better after any normal move such as  8.O-O  or  8.Bf4  . }
8... g6 9. Qe2
{ 9...Bxe5  10.Qxe4  is just clearly better for White so Black has to defend the Pawn. }
9... Bf5 { Objectively the strongest move. } 10. Bf4 Nf6 11. Nd2 Qe7
{ Long castle is a better choice for Black as White has an advantage on the Kingside. }
12. O-O O-O-O 13. f3
{ Opening up the position makes sense - our powerful Knight will dictate terms. }
13... exf3 14. Ndxf3
{ It is going to take some manouvering to make progress but White's advantage is undisputable - The Knight on e5 is too strong. Let's bring the queen's Rook to e1 and remove the Queen from the e file.   At some point we might consider chasing away the light-squared Bishop with Nf3-h4. We should watch out for c6-c5 so b2-b4 makes a lot of sense too. One more possible idea - c3-c4-c5. }
