[White "7. Ruy Lopez Classical Defense (3...Bc5)"]
[Black "Classical Defense 4...Nge7 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5 4. c3 Nge7
{ There have been a few top level games in recent years but I am not sure why. }
5. O-O
{ In my opinion this is more accurate than immediate  5.d4  exd4  6.cxd4  Bb4+  . }
5... Bb6 6. d4
{ Sometimes Black is trying this setup but look at the position - it just can't be playable. }
6... exd4 7. cxd4 d5 8. exd5
{ Taking advantage of the fact that Black hasn't castled yet, White manages to develop a serious initiative. }
8... Nxd5 9. Re1+ Be6 10. Bg5
{ Notice that most of are moves are played with a tempo. } 10... Qd6 11. Nbd2
O-O 12. Nc4 { 12.Ne4  would be also nice. } 12... Qb4 13. a4 a6
{ The most popular move in the position turns out to be a serious mistake. }
14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Qc2 { Threatening with 16. Bd2 and 17. Ng5. } 15... h6
{ This is already a losing mistake but it's also the most important move as it allows us to understand the difference between 13...a6 and 13...a5. }
16. Bxh6 gxh6 17. Rxe6 { Nice but already typical blow. } 17... fxe6 18. Qg6+
Kh8 19. Qxh6+ Kg8 20. Qxe6+
{ If  20...Kh8  then we bring the Queen to g4 with checks and then after Kg8-h8 - Nc4-e5 wins. }
20... Rf7 21. Nce5 Qe7 22. Qxc6 { Most of Black's pieces are hanging... } 22...
Rd8 23. Nxf7 Qxf7
{ With the pawn on a5 Black could still hope for surviving this but now White has... }
24. a5
{ Winning another Pawn and also create another problem for Black - their dark-squared Bishop. }
