[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 { The main continuation. } 5. d4
{ With the Knight on e7 it was best to castle first. Now however,  5.O-O  allows  5...O-O  6.d4  Bb6!  and I am not sure if White has any advantage at all. The difference will become clear once we see 5...Bb6 line. }
5... exd4 6. e5 Ne4
{ Despite a good number of strong players using this line with Black, I have no respect for it - it is Giuoco Piano with c2-c3 and d2-d4 @@StartBracket@@yes, the one from Wesley So's course@@EndBracket@@ a tempo up for White! }
7. O-O dxc3 { Weak continuation but we should be ready for it. } 8. Qd5
{ Black can't hold the Knight on e4. } 8... Bxf2+
{ Had Black started with  8...cxb2??  9.Bxb2  Bxf2+  then simple  10.Kh1!  would have won. }
9. Rxf2 { But now  9.Kh1?  would blunder  9...Be3!  with unclear position. }
9... Nxf2 10. Nxc3 { The Knight is not that important! } 10... Ng4 11. Qe4
{ 12. Bg5 is almost as big a threat as 12. Qxg4. } 11... O-O
{ Black gives up the Knight in order to finish the development. } 12. Qxg4 d6
{ Given how much behind in development Black is, having a tempo move must mean a lot for him. }
13. Qg3 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. Be3
{ Let's not be greedy - opening up the e file with  15.Qxe5?!  would give Black a decent counterplay after  15...c6  followed by 16...Re8. After the text move White is clearly better - e5 needs protection while we can also activate our Rook. }
