1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 { The main continuation. } 5. d4
{ With the Knight on e7 it was best to castle first. Now however,  5.O-O  allows  5...O-O  6.d4  Bb6!  and I am not sure if White has any advantage at all. The difference will become clear once we see 5...Bb6 line. }
5... exd4 6. e5 Ne4
{ Despite a good number of strong players using this line with Black, I have no respect for it - it is Giuoco Piano with c2-c3 and d2-d4 @@StartBracket@@yes, the one from Wesley So's course@@EndBracket@@ a tempo up for White! }
7. O-O dxc3 { Weak continuation but we should be ready for it. } 8. Qd5
{ Black can't hold the Knight on e4. } 8... Bxf2+
{ Had Black started with  8...cxb2??  9.Bxb2  Bxf2+  then simple  10.Kh1!  would have won. }
9. Rxf2 { But now  9.Kh1?  would blunder  9...Be3!  with unclear position. }
9... Nxf2 10. Nxc3 { The Knight is not that important! } 10... Ng4 11. Qe4
{ 12. Bg5 is almost as big a threat as 12. Qxg4. } 11... d5
{ An attempt to shake things up. } 12. exd6+ Kf8 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. h3
{ It is important to kick back the Knight first:  14.Qxc6?  would run into  14...Qxd6!  and  15.Qxa8  would end with smothered mate after  15...Qc5+  . }
14... Nf6 15. Qxc6 Bd7 16. Qxc7
{ White only has a Pawn for an exchange but a dominant position of his pieces and d6 Pawn gives him more than enough compensation.   We can develop our Bishop to...actually all the squares @@StartBracket@@except d2 and h6!@@EndBracket@@ look equally good to me, so let's just wait for Black's move first. Our king's Knight will probably end up on e5 quite soon - quite an outpost! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Ruy Lopez Classical Defense (3...Bc5)"]
[Black "Classical Defense 4...Nf6 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 { The main continuation. } 5. d4
{ With the Knight on e7 it was best to castle first. Now however,  5.O-O  allows  5...O-O  6.d4  Bb6!  and I am not sure if White has any advantage at all. The difference will become clear once we see 5...Bb6 line. }
5... exd4 6. e5 Ne4
{ Despite a good number of strong players using this line with Black, I have no respect for it - it is Giuoco Piano with c2-c3 and d2-d4 @@StartBracket@@yes, the one from Wesley So's course@@EndBracket@@ a tempo up for White! }
7. O-O d5 8. cxd4 Bb6
{ These structures with the strong Knight on e4 often attract Black. They were surely attractive enough for me to come up with the 9...Rb8 line but it's a story for another chapter... }
9. h3
{ We didn't have to do it right now but preventing Bc8-g4 so just not to forget it... }
9... O-O 10. Nc3 Be6 { This is what I would do, although without excitement. }
11. Be3
{ The best square for the Bishop as it improves the protection of our most important Pawn. }
11... f5 12. exf6
{ Taking this Pawn is rarely mandatory but usually best anyway and also practical - why to worry about f5-f4? }
12... Qxf6 13. a4 a5
{ This is a useful inclusion - a5 will now be potentially weak. } 14. Bxc6 bxc6
15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Ne5
{ We will move the Queen to c2 and then the king's Rook can come to c1 while the other one can be activated via a3. Black Pawns are permanently weak and most likely he will have to give away at least one of them at some point. }
*

