[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 { The main continuation. } 5. d4
{ With the Knight on e7 it was best to castle first. Now however,  5.O-O  allows  5...O-O  6.d4  Bb6!  and I am not sure if White has any advantage at all. The difference will become clear once we see 5...Bb6 line. }
5... exd4 6. e5 Nd5 7. cxd4 Bb4+ 8. Nbd2
{ As many different lines and openings @@StartBracket@@for instance QGA @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/8/2pP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e4  e5  4.Nf3  exd4  5.Bxc4  Bb4+  6.Nbd2!  @@EndBracket@@  - covering with Knight is considered to be more ambitious. The point is that once White castles the Bishop will just look silly on b4. }
8... a6
{ A novelty but it is the best move for Black - he will now be able to retreat the d5 Knight with a tempo. }
9. Bc4 Nb6 10. O-O { Stronger than  10.Bb3  d5  or  10.Bd3  d6! } 10... O-O
{ 10...Nxc4?!  would be too slow -  11.Nxc4  is already threatening with 12. d5. }
11. Bd3 { It makes more sense now as we have an answer to Black's next move. }
11... d6 12. Nb3 dxe5 13. Nxe5
{ 13.dxe5  Bg4  would have been fine for Black. } 13... Nxe5
{ or  13...Be6  14.Nxc6  with a small advantage. } 14. dxe5
{ We want to place the Queen on c2 and then bring the Knight to the center - e4 or f3. We can chase the annoying Bishop with a2-a3 any time we want. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Ruy Lopez Norwegian Defense (5...Na5)"]
[Black "Norwegian Defense 7...Nxb3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 b5 5. Bb3 Na5
{ This line is a pure provocation and therefore - apart from its objective value - we should not be surprised that it has been part of the repertoire of some of the most provocative players in the world - Morozevich and Mamedyarov being the finest examples.   In 2017 it was picked up by another original player - Paco Vallejo Pons. Strategically the idea makes a lot of sense - after all, the light-squared bishop is White's most precious minor piece as it covers the light squares once c3-d4 setup is achieved.   Why is it a provocation then? Well, chess is a game of tempos and Black doesn't seem to care much about it - that Knight was his only developed piece. }
6. O-O { There is no need for rush here, castle will be useful in any case. }
6... d6
{ Black deliberately delays taking the Bishop. Now white has to reckon with c5-c4 as well. }
7. d4
{ White is ahead in development so opening up the position is fully justified. }
7... Nxb3 8. axb3 f6
{ When a player is desperate to play for a win with Black he might sometimes play like that but this is just great news! The Bishop pair might look tempting but not when the position is closed. }
9. Qe2
{ This is a good square for the Queen but more importantly d1 square is now awaiting the Rook. Swiercz suggested  9.Nc3  Ne7  10.Qd3  which seems a bit artificial to me @@StartBracket@@although it does give advantage too@@EndBracket@@.   I think that our choice seems more natural. He pointed out one valuable thing though -  9.c4  allows  9...b4!  restricting b1-Knight. }
9... Ne7 10. Rd1
{ 11.dxe5  fxe5  12.Nxe5  is the threat but anyway black Knight was heading to g6. }
10... Ng6 11. c4
{ Just a few moves ago this move would be inaccurate due to  11...b4  so what has changed? }
11... b4
{ After  11...Bd7  12.Nc3  Be7  13.Be3  Black has to deal with the problem of b5 Pawn - I am not sure how. }
12. c5
{ The point of the whole operation. The Knight can be developed to c4 now. At the same time Black can do nothing about our advance as both  12...dxc5  13.dxe5  and  12...exd4  13.Nxd4  are clearly better for White. }
12... Be7 13. cxd6 cxd6 14. Nbd2
{ We want to place the Knight on c4 @@StartBracket@@threatening with winning the Pawn on e5@@EndBracket@@. The Bishop will come to e3. }
14... Nf4 { The only way to disturb us. } 15. Qf1 Bb7
{ By attacking the Pawn on e4 Black is trying to stop Nd2-c4. } 16. Nc4
{ Not the only good reaction but definitely my choice. White sacrifices a Pawn for positional trumps. }
16... Bxe4 { Black didn't really have a choice. } 17. Bxf4 exf4
{ 17...Bxf3  was possible but it makes no difference to us as we allow it anyway. }
18. d5
{ The point - we are playing on the light squares and against the dark-squared Bishop. }
18... Bxf3
{ Not the most exciting move to make as now c6 and especially e6 will be permanently weakened but  18...f5  19.Qe2  followed by Nf3-e1 and f2-f3 would be a different kind of a problem. }
19. gxf3 O-O 20. Re1 { The e file is crucial for the course of the game. }
20... f5 21. Qe2 { Now he can't move the Bishop - it has to defend d6 Pawn. }
21... Rf7 22. Qd2
{ We will win the Pawn back @@StartBracket@@  22...g5  would be too much - just  23.Re6  @@EndBracket@@  and then try to place the Rook on e6. White is better, of course, but more importantly it will very hard for black to handle this over the board. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Ruy Lopez Norwegian Defense (5...Na5)"]
[Black "Norwegian Defense 7...exd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 b5 5. Bb3 Na5
{ This line is a pure provocation and therefore - apart from its objective value - we should not be surprised that it has been part of the repertoire of some of the most provocative players in the world - Morozevich and Mamedyarov being the finest examples.   In 2017 it was picked up by another original player - Paco Vallejo Pons. Strategically the idea makes a lot of sense - after all, the light-squared bishop is White's most precious minor piece as it covers the light squares once c3-d4 setup is achieved.   Why is it a provocation then? Well, chess is a game of tempos and Black doesn't seem to care much about it - that Knight was his only developed piece. }
6. O-O { There is no need for rush here, castle will be useful in any case. }
6... d6
{ Black deliberately delays taking the Bishop. Now white has to reckon with c5-c4 as well. }
7. d4
{ White is ahead of in development so opening up the position is fully justified. }
7... exd4 8. Re1
{ White delays recapturing the pawn and he does it for a good reason - he still has to watch out for c5-c4. After a natural  8.Nxd4  Bb7!   immediate  8...c5  wouldn't work because of  9.Bd5!  Black threatens with c5-c4 forcing White to take actions:  9.c4  c5!  10.Nf5  g6  11.Ng3  and after  11...h5  I am not sure what is happening. }
8... Be7 9. Qxd4
{ 9.Nxd4  is also possible but the line that I have are more complicated and there is no need for complications here. }
9... Nf6 10. e5 { We just have to do it quickly. } 10... dxe5 11. Qxe5
{ Black has to deal with the pinned Bishop now. } 11... Nc6
{ 11...Qd6  12.Qxd6  cxd6  13.Nd4  with a clear advantage in the endgame. } 12.
Qc3 { Now it is the Knight that needs help. } 12... Bb7 13. Ne5
{ Eliminating the key defender. } 13... Nxe5 14. Qxe5 Kf8
{ Black had a cool idea here -  14...Qd7  15.Bf4  O-O-O!?  and due to a weakness of the back rank White can't take the Bishop. However, simple  16.Qxc7+  wins the Pawn. }
15. Bf4
{ The Pawn is hanging and  15...Bd6  16.Qe3  is just clearly better for White. If you are worried about Black's light-squared Bishop then simple f2-f3 will do. }
*

