[Black "Norwegian Defense 7...exd4 #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 b5 5. Bb3 Na5
{ This line is a pure provocation and therefore - apart from its objective value - we should not be surprised that it has been part of the repertoire of some of the most provocative players in the world - Morozevich and Mamedyarov being the finest examples.   In 2017 it was picked up by another original player - Paco Vallejo Pons. Strategically the idea makes a lot of sense - after all, the light-squared bishop is White's most precious minor piece as it covers the light squares once c3-d4 setup is achieved.   Why is it a provocation then? Well, chess is a game of tempos and Black doesn't seem to care much about it - that Knight was his only developed piece. }
6. O-O { There is no need for rush here, castle will be useful in any case. }
6... d6
{ Black deliberately delays taking the Bishop. Now white has to reckon with c5-c4 as well. }
7. d4
{ White is ahead of in development so opening up the position is fully justified. }
7... exd4 8. Re1
{ White delays recapturing the pawn and he does it for a good reason - he still has to watch out for c5-c4. After a natural  8.Nxd4  Bb7!   immediate  8...c5  wouldn't work because of  9.Bd5!  Black threatens with c5-c4 forcing White to take actions:  9.c4  c5!  10.Nf5  g6  11.Ng3  and after  11...h5  I am not sure what is happening. }
8... Nxb3 { It's best to take that Bishop while it's still there. } 9. axb3 c5
10. c3 Bb7
{ He could play  10...Nf6  or  10...Be7  instead but anyway we are doing the same - recapture the Pawn, develop the Knight. }
11. cxd4 Nf6 12. Nc3 Be7
{ Black is only missing one tempo to finish his development. This is all we need. }
13. Nh4
{ The Knight is heading to a beautiful outpost. Normally black would have had g7-g6 but since he hasn't castled yet  13...g6  is easily refuted with  14.Bh6  . }
13... b4
{ The only challenging response,  13...O-O  14.Nf5  or  13...cxd4  14.Qxd4  would be so much better for White. }
14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5
{ The Pawn is untouchable as  15...Bxd5  16.Nf5  wins on spot. } 15... O-O 16.
Nf5 Bf6 { The best answer but not an easy decision for sure. } 17. Bf4 cxd4
{ Clever try. The point is that  18.Bxd6?!  can be met with  18...g6!  19.Bxf8  Qxd5  and Black is great. However, chess isn't checkers and we don't have to take this Pawn right away. }
18. Qf3 { Our d5 Pawn is defended while d6 will fall anyway. } 18... Re8
{ Black moves the Rook while he still can. } 19. Nxd6 Rxe1+ 20. Rxe1 Qd7
{ He is planning to go Ra8-d8 after which it won't be easy for us to make progress. }
21. h4
{ Excellent idea - White is preparing Bf4-g5. The idea is not only to trade Black's dark-squared Bishop - a crucial defender controlling both d4 and d8 - but also to weaken the position of Black's King - I will explain it in a few moves. }
21... Rd8
{ 21...Bxh4??  22.Be5!  would be already winning for White. Despite threatening with Nd6xb7 and Qf3-g4 we can just further improve with Qf3-e4. Black's dark-squared Bishop is no longer a 'crucial defender', it looks more like a lost soul. }
22. Nxb7 { This is necessary in order to free the Bishop. } 22... Qxb7 23. Bg5
Bxg5
{ He could play  23...Qb6  24.Qe4  h6  but then simple  25.Bxf6  Qxf6  26.Rd1  wins the Pawn. }
24. hxg5
{ For Black the main problem is that he can't play h7-h6 but at the same time he has to do something about the back rank problem.   Perhaps g7-g6 will be necessary at some point, despite weakening the position badly. White can secure the position of the King with g2-g3. Our passed Pawn can be always defended with Re1-e5. }
