[Black "Delayed Classical  8...b5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Bc5
{ We can already smell something unusual about Black's play. Why else would he encourage us to go  5.c3  right away? The line has caught up some real attention this year so we should take it seriously. }
5. c3 Nge7
{ There it is. Black wants to get an improved version of the Cozio Defense. After  6.O-O  Ng6  7.d4  Ba7  8.Bg5  f6!  things might get really interesting. I don't think there is a need for complications here as White has an easy solution to the line. }
6. d4 { Now Black has no choice but to take on d4. } 6... exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+
{ Otherwise we would just go 8. d5 with great advantage. } 8. Bd2 b5
{ It is not a bad line although it has some downsides, as we shall see. Interestingly this move was first played in Steiner,L - Pitcher,J Perth 1937@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Bb3 { This is more accurate than  9.Bxb4  played by Steiner. } 9... d5
{ The point of Black's previous move - the Bishop is now defended by the Knight. }
10. O-O
{ 10.Bxb4  Nxb4  11.e5  would not be accurate -  11...a5!  12.a3  Nbc6  followed by a5-a4 and Nc6-a5-c4 with unclear position.   Now Black can't take  10...dxe4  due to  11.Ng5  . }
10... O-O { Now the Pawn advance works nicely. } 11. Bxb4 Nxb4 12. e5
{ In such a structure Black is usually more active - his Knight begins on f6 so after e4-e5 it can come to e4. }
12... a5
{ After normal  12...Bg4  13.h3  Bh5  14.Nc3  it is not clear what Black is trying to achieve. }
13. a3 Nbc6 14. Bc2
{ Now however, it is not possible -  14...Bg4?  15.Bxh7+!  and White simply wins a Pawn.   Black is also too slow to achieve a5-a4 and Nc6-a5-c4 setup -  14...a4  15.Nc3  and he has to defend the b5-pawn.   14...f6  is a lesser evil but anyway -  15.h3!  fxe5  16.dxe5  Bf5  17.Nbd2  and White is better. As usually in this line, the c-file proves quite useful for White.   This is an important nuance -  14.Nc3  Bg4!  would allow Black to obtain an excellent position. }
