[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Ruy Lopez Open (4.Ba4 Nf6 5.O-O Nxe4 6.d4)"]
[Black "Open 6...Be7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Nxe4
{ The Open Ruy is a bit different than other variations of Ruy Lopez. While in Chigorin, Breyer, Zaitsev or others the position is usually closed or semi-open, here it's usually open - hence then name. }
6. d4
{ The only way to challenge 5...Nxe4. White takes advantage of the e-file. }
6... Be7
{ The point of this developing move is that if now White now takes on e5 Black will have 7...Nc5 forcing an exchange of White's Bishop. Therefore White should not take the Pawn yet but first undermine the position of Black's Knight. }
7. Re1
{ Black can now defend the Knight in two ways however only one of them is serious. }
7... f5
{ This romantic move has a nice historical background as it was first played by my countryman, Szymon Winawer in 1896. However it did not survive a computer revolution in chess - in the last five years there were no games played in it! }
8. dxe5 O-O
{ After  8...Nc5  9.c4!  O-O  10.Nc3  Black's position is really ugly. In general it is better choose the opening where you can actually finish the development. }
9. Nc3
{ It is more accurate than  9.Bb3+  as we don't want to commit the Bishop to b3. }
9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 Qe8
{ This is what Black normally does with Bb3+ and Kh8 included. } 11. c4
{ But now - once b7-b5 is stopped - he won't be able to execute his plan - transferring the Knight to e6.   The move  11...Nd8??  loses to  12.e6! }
11... Qh5 12. Rb1 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Ruy Lopez Open (4.Ba4 Nf6 5.O-O Nxe4 6.d4)"]
[Black "Open 6...Be7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Nxe4
{ The Open Ruy is a bit different than other variations of Ruy Lopez. While in Chigorin, Breyer, Zaitsev or others the position is usually closed or semi-open, here it's usually open - hence then name. }
6. d4
{ The only way to challenge 5...Nxe4. White takes advantage of the e-file. }
6... Be7
{ The point of this developing move is that if now White now takes on e5 Black will have 7...Nc5 forcing an exchange of White's Bishop. Therefore White should not take the Pawn yet but first undermine the position of Black's Knight. }
7. Re1
{ Black can now defend the Knight in two ways however only one of them is serious. }
7... f5
{ This romantic move has a nice historical background as it was first played by my countryman, Szymon Winawer in 1896. However it did not survive a computer revolution in chess - in the last five years there were no games played in it! }
8. dxe5 O-O
{ After  8...Nc5  9.c4!  O-O  10.Nc3  Black's position is really ugly. In general it is better choose the opening where you can actually finish the development. }
9. Nc3
{ It is more accurate than  9.Bb3+  as we don't want to commit the Bishop to b3. }
9... Nc5
{ I guess this is the reason why most of the players played 9. Bb3+ first. }
10. Bb3+ { 10...Ne6  11.Nd5  would be much better for White as well. } 10...
Nxb3 11. Qd5+ { The Queen will take the Bishop's place. } 11... Kh8 12. Qxb3
{ We can just develop the rest of the pieces - Bd2 and Rad1 - or more aggressively: Nd5 and Bf4 @@StartBracket@@Nd5 is necessary to prevent Bf4 g5! - White will have Nxe7@@EndBracket@@. In any case white has a big advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Ruy Lopez Open (4.Ba4 Nf6 5.O-O Nxe4 6.d4)"]
[Black "Open 6...Be7 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Nxe4
{ The Open Ruy is a bit different than other variations of Ruy Lopez. While in Chigorin, Breyer, Zaitsev or others the position is usually closed or semi-open, here it's usually open - hence then name. }
6. d4
{ The only way to challenge 5...Nxe4. White takes advantage of the e-file. }
6... Be7
{ The point of this developing move is that if now White now takes on e5 Black will have 7...Nc5 forcing an exchange of White's Bishop. Therefore White should not take the Pawn yet but first undermine the position of Black's Knight. }
7. Re1
{ Black can now defend the Knight in two ways however only one of them is serious. }
7... b5
{ This move was introduced by the famous, Siegbert Tarrasch during the last game of his exhibition match with Emmanuel Lasker in Berlin 1916. The beginnings weren't easy: Tarrasch got crushed so badly that nobody dared to repeat the line for the next forty years.   Since then it slowly began gaining attention of more and more strong players and today it already has a reputation of a very interesting line. Let me just mention a few names that have recently adopted 6...Be7: Carlsen, Caruana, Gajewski :-@@EndBracket@@.   Now the reader may ask: 'Why is Black doing all this? Why not just start with b7-b5?'. When we go through the Open mainlines you will see that White usually wants to go Nbd2 c3 and Bc2. Re1 is not really a part of the setup.   In other words White is facing dilemma: he can eithertranspose to the main Open with 8. Bb3 but with the Rook to e1 committed, or take the Knight and try to challenge this interesting setup. }
8. Rxe4 d5
{ 8...bxa4  9.d5!  Nb8  10.Nxe5  and - as a4 will fall - Black will be left a Pawn down with no compensation. }
9. Nxe5
{ For a moment it looks like a complete chaos but this will get settled really quick. }
9... Nxe5 10. Rxe5 bxa4
{ This is the starting position of the line. Black has a broken Pawn structure on the queenside and he is also slightly behind in development which - in some lines - makes castling a bit tricky.   On the other hand, he has a Bishop pair which gives him good prospects for a long-term compensation that will often come down to some simplifications, possibly an opposite color Bishop endgame or something like that.   The trouble with this line is that it is still not that popular so we rarely expect it and - as a result - we don't anticipate it in our preparation. Therefore in my opinion we should have a simple solution, something that can be easily remembered and does not involve unnecessary risk. }
11. b3
{ This move makes me feel ok and will hopefully discourage Black from entering this variation in the first place. White wants to swap the dark-squared Bishops as his Knight will be stronger than his opponent's remaining Bishop. }
11... O-O 12. Ba3
{ Once the trade is done Black will have to deal with weak queenside Pawns as well as the c5 square. }
12... Bxa3 13. Nxa3 Re8
{ This should mainly be done not because White's Rook is covering the e-file but because it is annoying. }
14. Rxe8+ Qxe8 15. Nb1
{ Rarely a move back is as obvious as in this case. The Knight had no perspectives on a3. }
15... axb3 16. cxb3
{ Previously only  16.axb3  was played in Balogh, C - Radjabov, T, EU-ch Warsaw 2011. Taking with the c Pawn does weaken White's Pawn structure but it also opens the c file. }
16... Qc6
{ Black is improving the position of his Queen while trying to disturb White. }
17. Qd2
{ The Queen is well placed on d2 and it will also allow the Knight to occupy c3 square. }
17... Bd7
{ The Bishop should be placed on d7 from where it controls an important a4 square. }
18. Nc3
{ White's position is a bit better and it will definitely be much easier to handle for us as Black's weaknesses are permanent. There's no point going any deeper as the game is closer to the endgame rather than the opening.   I will only note that after  18...Re8  19.Na4?!  is going nowhere as Black has  19...Qf6  20.Nc5  Bb5  threatening with 21...Re2. Perhaps we should just swap the Rooks and then try bringing the Knight to c5. }
*

