18. cxd4 exd4
{ It makes less sense than  18...Nxd4  - after all, the Knight on f3 is far more important. }
19. Qd3 g6
{ The Knight cannot be captured -  19...dxe3  20.Qxh7+  attacking both the Rook and the Bishop, not to mention the long diagonal... }
20. Bb2 Rf4
{ Quite a way to defend the Pawn.  20...Nb4  21.Qxd4  Qxd4  22.Bxd4  would give White a substantial edge in the endgame. }
21. Re1 { Increasing the pressure. } 21... Qd6
{ 21...Nb4  still wouldn't work -  22.Qd2! } 22. Bd1
{ This is a mysterious move indeed so allow me to explain - White's Knight won't stand on e3 for much longer - we will need to retreat it soon, which will allow Black to centralize his Bishop with Be6-d5 - attacking on f3. The other reason is to walk away from a possible fork - Nc6-b4.   After  22...Rd8  we can go  23.Nf1  Bd5  24.Bc1  and then stop Nc6-b4 with a2-a3. }
*

