{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Nxe4
{ The Open Ruy is a bit different than other variations of Ruy Lopez. While in Chigorin, Breyer, Zaitsev or others the position is usually closed or semi-open, here it's usually open - hence then name. }
6. d4
{ The only way to challenge 5...Nxe4. White takes advantage of the e-file. }
6... b5
{ The main continuation - Black wants to go d7-d5 but he is pushing our Bishop away from a4-e8 diagonal first. }
7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6
{ I find the Open Ruy Lopez one of the most difficult but rewarding openings for Black. After  9.c3  Be7  @@StartBracket@@there is also  9...Bc5  but it's not simpler at all!@@EndBracket@@  10.Nbd2  Black can choose mainly  10...O-O  11.Bc2  f5  . Both lines promise full equality but no matter which one Black chooses - the number of variations, that have to be memorized, is scary.  Therefore I wouldn't recommend this system to players under 2500 Elo points - you guys are still at the learning stage and it's far better to learn by understanding rather than memorizing. 'Ok, but this a repertoire for White not Black, so what should I do?' - the reader will ask.  I am happy to provide you with answer that - with a little bit of luck - will stand for more than one game. }
9. c3
{ In my opinion this is more accurate than 9. Nbd2. What is the difference between the two move-orders?   9.Nbd2  allows immediate  9...Nc5  10.c3  d4!?  The line has been extensively covered by Swiercz who claims that White has slight edge. I will not dwell into the details but I simply believe otherwise - Black can achieve a draw fairly easily and in more than one way.   9. c3 cuts off this line completely. What is the downside? TheDilworth Variation! Is it? Not for us! }
9... Be7 10. Nbd2 Nc5
{ Black Knight retreats from e4. His main idea is now d5-d4. } 11. Bc2 d4
{ Controlling the d4 square is usually White's most valuable asset in the Open, so you can see that this move makes a lot of sense. Of course Black has to hurry with d5-d4 - after  11...O-O?!  12.Nb3  the window is already closed. }
12. Nb3 d3
{ The cornerstone of 11...d4 line. Black will hugely depend on this Pawn as it's successfully disturbing White's coordination but at the same time it is becoming a target. }
13. Bb1 Nxb3 14. axb3 Bf5
{ Apart from a few alternatives @@StartBracket@@such as 13. Nxc5@@EndBracket@@ this is a starting position of the most complicated but also the strongest line in the whole Open Variation.   Black's advanced Pawn on d3 is sabotaging White's forces however it can be easily lost so Black's next moves will be aimed in its defense.   At the same time White usually adopts one of two plans - he can either try playing somehow around the Pawn @@StartBracket@@in that case his setup involves moves like Bc1-f4 Rf1-e1 and b3-b4@@EndBracket@@ or put the Bishop on d4 intending to collect the d3 Pawn. }
15. b4
{ This move prepares Bb1-a2, which means that we are giving up on the d3-pawn. }
15... O-O 16. Re1
{ The Rook defends the e5-pawn which means it will also support its potential advance. For Black this is a first tricky moment. }
16... Qd5
{ The problem with Black's last move is that it only helps White as now Bb1-a2 will be played with a tempo.   You might think nobody would make such a mistake but then, think again - not only it was already played but it was played by one of the biggest specialist in Open Ruy and arguably one of the best players in the world - Shakhriyar Mamedyarov in his game against Sergey Karjakin, World Cup 2009.   How did this happen? In some lines the black Queen goes to d5 so he probably mixed them up. }
17. h3 { Preparing g2-g4. } 17... Rfd8
{ The Azeri star continued as if nothing happened.  17...Qd7  back would have been the lesser evil but anyway it's just a tempo up for White. }
18. g4
{ Black has an ugly choice - either he goes  18...Bg6  allowing  19.Ba2  Qd7  20.e6  or gives up on the d3-pawn. Mamedyarov chose the latter one. }
18... Be6 19. Re3
{ White collects Black's crucial Pawn gaining practically a decisive advantage. }
*

