{ The most likely continuation. } 24. Rxa8 Rxa8 25. Qf3
{ Now both attacking the pawn on f7 but the Knight is also shaky. On the other side we shouldn't forget about the d3-pawn. }
25... bxc3 26. bxc3 d2
{ This seems like the most natural response from Black - instead of spending resources for defense he simply advances the Pawn creating a real counterplay. The only problem is - it's a mistake! }
27. e6 fxe6 28. Rxe6 { The Knight is pinned and it can't be defended. } 28...
Rd8 29. Rxc6 { This is more accurate than  29.Qxc6  . } 29... d1=Q+
{ The position simplifies now. } 30. Bxd1 Qxd1+ 31. Qxd1 Rxd1+ 32. Kh2
{ Staying away from the light squares. } 32... Rd7 33. Ne6 Rd6
{ The only way to keep the Pawn. } 34. Rxd6 cxd6 35. Kg3
{ Despite the limited material the ending is far from drawn - The Knight is clearly stronger than the Bishop, black queenside Pawns are not very useful, they are just the targets basically. At the same time White has a free hand on the kingside - we should just advance our Pawns. }
