[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Ruy Lopez Janowski System (7...Bg4 9...Nd7)"]
[Black "Janowski System 9...b5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Be7
{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6.Re1 is better than 6.d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6.d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... d6
{ This setup is far from impressive, for example simple  7.Bxc6+  bxc6  8.d4  is pleasant for White. }
7. c3
{ I prefer  7.c3  especially I don't really see any other explanation for Black than  7...Bg4  which in my opinion is just weak. }
7... Bg4
{ Besides having a 'cool' Bishop, Black's only idea @@StartBracket@@at least the only I can think of@@EndBracket@@ is to go Nf6-d7 and Be7-g5. Swapping the dark-squared Bishop would be a good thing for Black. }
8. d3 O-O 9. Nbd2
{ Before going h2-h3 we want to be able to take on f3 with the Knight so it could control g5. }
9... b5 { I guess it's another plan but it just makes no sense to me. } 10. Bc2
d5 { it is not a good combination. } 11. h3 Bh5 12. g4 Bg6 13. Nh4
{ We can put the other Knight on f3 and the Queen on e2. White has a long-term advantage thanks to the control over the light squares. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Ruy Lopez Janowski System (7...Bg4 9...Nd7)"]
[Black "Janowski System 9...Nd7 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Be7
{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6.Re1 is better than 6.d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6.d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... d6
{ This setup is far from impressive, for example simple  7.Bxc6+  bxc6  8.d4  is pleasant for White. }
7. c3
{ I prefer  7.c3  especially I don't really see any other explanation for Black than  7...Bg4  which in my opinion is just weak. }
7... Bg4
{ Besides having a 'cool' Bishop, Black's only idea @@StartBracket@@at least the only I can think of@@EndBracket@@ is to go Nf6-d7 and Be7-g5. Swapping the dark-squared Bishop would be a good thing for Black. }
8. d3 O-O 9. Nbd2
{ Before going h2-h3 we want to be able to take on f3 with the Knight so it could control g5. }
9... Nd7 10. h3 Bh5 11. Bc2
{ This is stronger than  11.Nf1  - White still wants to play it but at the same time he anticipates  11...Nc5  . }
11... Nc5
{ As I wrote, after some other move like  11...Re8  we would go  12.Nf1  ,   but after  11...Nc5  12.Nf1  is not so strong -  12...Ne6  and Black is controlling some squares too! }
12. g4
{ It is true that our dark squares ware getting weakened but it is more important to prevent Nc5-e6. }
12... Bg6 13. d4
{ Black's whole plan was for nothing as the Knight has to come back... } 13...
exd4 { 13...Nd7  14.d5  would be even more depressing for Black. } 14. cxd4 Nd7
{ Despite dominating in the center we still have to be careful - Black is now threatening with d6-d5 as after exd5 he has Bxc2 and Nb4. }
15. a3 { So much for d6-d5. } 15... Re8 16. Nf1
{ White is in full control, both in the center and on the kingside. Our plan is to bring the Knight to f5. }
*

