5... Bc5 6. c3 O-O 7. d4 Ba7
{ It is a very interesting but shaky line. Black's point is to avoid/delay b7-b5 - why to improve the position of the opponent's Bishop, right?   Of course this is not that simple - in some lines Black can benefit from not playing b7-b5 but in some - on the contrary - we might have Bxc6 for instance. }
8. Bg5
{ In my opinion this is by far the most ambitious try. Naturally White has to be ready to sacrifice this Bishop in some cases. }
8... h6 9. Bh4 d6
{ This line brought Jordan Van Forrest a very easy draw against Maxime Vachier-Lagrave in Tata Steel 2021. }
10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nbd2
{ Instead of taking the Pawn @@StartBracket@@as Maxime did@@EndBracket@@ White simply finishes his development. This is the latest trend - Alexeenko, K - Sarin, N - Biel 2021. }
11... Re8 12. Re1
{ Black is still dealing with the same problem -  12...exd4  is met with  13.Nxd4! }
12... Re6
{ This was Sarin's choice. The Rook defends the Knight, releasing the Queen from the pin - it can now go to e8. This move doesn't look very human which suggests that Nihal might have been still in his preparation or at least he saw this idea in some other line etc. }
13. Qc2
{ After this simple move @@StartBracket@@which was played in the game@@EndBracket@@ I don't see anything satisfactory for Black. It doesn't even matter if in the end White is clearly better or just a bit better or maybe Black is just holding. What matters for me is that the line is no longer fun for Black. }
13... g5 { Once again we should consider it. } 14. Bg3 Nh5
{ This wasn't possible with the Queen on d1 as White had Nf3xe5!. } 15. dxe5
{ Simple means again... } 15... dxe5 16. Rad1 f6 { Defending the e5-pawn. } 17.
Nc4 Qe8 18. Nfd2
{ White is a bit better as Black has both weak Pawns and squares. We shall bring the Knights to f1 and e3. Perhaps the next step will be to go f3 and Bf2. }
