[White "12. Ruy Lopez Moller"]
[Black "Moller 6...O-O #17"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Bc5 6. c3 O-O 7. d4 Ba7
{ It is a very interesting but shaky line. Black's point is to avoid/delay b7-b5 - why to improve the position of the opponent's Bishop, right?   Of course this is not that simple - in some lines Black can benefit from not playing b7-b5 but in some - on the contrary - we might have Bxc6 for instance. }
8. Bg5
{ In my opinion this is by far the most ambitious try. Naturally White has to be ready to sacrifice this Bishop in some cases. }
8... h6 9. Bh4 exd4
{ The main continuation. Black's argument is that after 10. cxd4 d6 he will be able to compensate white's pawn's center with moves such as Bc8-g4 or g5. }
10. Re1
{ We agree with Black's arguments and therefore White is not going to take on d4 right away. White's last move is really smart - we are waiting for Black to go d7-d6 and then we will take Bxc6 and not cxd4 but Nxd4!. Black basically has 3 options:   a@@EndBracket@@ he can anyway go  10...d6  allowing  11.Bxc6  bxc6  12.Nxd4  ;   b@@EndBracket@@ he can prevent Bxc6 with  10...b5  , but then he improves White's Bishops position, wasn't the initial idea - not to improve White's Bishop's position?;   c@@EndBracket@@ he can take the Pawn on c3 - in this case our Knight will get nicely developed to c3 which will foreshadow some serious compensation. }
10... d6 11. Bxc6 dxc3
{ Clever idea - Black provoked us to take on c6 and only now he collects the Pawn. It is not enough, though. }
12. Nxc3 bxc6 13. h3 { Preventing 13...Bg4 was important. } 13... Be6
{ White has a nice compensation for the Pawn but it's almost exclusively based on the pinned Knight on f6. }
14. Qd2
{ White is developing the Queen in such away so it would control the c1-h6 diagonal, preventing g7-g5. }
14... Kh8 { Naturally Black doesn't need to cooperate with us. } 15. Rad1 g5
{ There was no more time for preparations - after  15...Rg8  16.e5!  dxe5  17.Qc1  Qf8  18.Nxe5  White would be much better. }
16. Nxg5
{ I don't think there was a single case in which we refused to sacrifice the piece on g5. }
16... hxg5 17. Qxg5 { 17.Bxg5  was possible but this is a better try. } 17...
Nh7 18. Qh6 f6 19. e5 { Important resource but also quite easy to spot. } 19...
Qd7 20. exf6 Rf7 21. Ne4
{ I say we should stop here. White definitely has enough compensation for the piece, perhaps more than that. Our plan is to bring the King to h2 and then advance the Pawn to g4 restricting Black's possibilities even more. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Ruy Lopez Moller"]
[Black "Moller 6...b5, 8...Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Bc5 6. c3 b5
{ By developing the Bishop first and only then placing the Pawn on b5, Black is playing against a2-a4 line. I mean we can still go a2-a4 @@StartBracket@@and we will@@EndBracket@@ but he will no longer have to settle for Ra8-b8. }
7. Bb3
{ For many years  7.Bc2  was considered more accurate with  7...d5!?  being a nice way of surprising the opponent but no more than that. In recent years it became clear that  7.Bc2  d5  is a very serious @@StartBracket@@and complicated!@@EndBracket@@ line.   Most of the players still use it occasionally as they don't want to lose the surprise value. What does it mean for us? In my opinion it's just not practical to allow it. I saw Swiercz's analysis after 7...d5 - many pages of extensive analysis in very sharp positions where first mistake of is usually the last one.   It can be useful if you are expecting the line but are you willing to memorize it, refresh it every week or so and then still risk forgetting it? I am not. It is a very pragmatic choice as we don't need two separate lines for 5...Bc5 and 5...b5. But - as you will see - it doesn’t mean we are willing to compromise. }
7... d6 8. a4
{ The bad news is that - compared with 5...b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 move order - Black has two extra options:   8...Bb7  and  8...Bg4  . The good news is that, even combined, they are still much smaller and overall less annoying than 7. Bc2 d5 line is. }
8... Bg4
{ By pinning the Knight Black prevents d2-d4 although it doesn't come for free - his queenside is weakened now and he will have to face a tough dilemma very soon. }
9. h3
{ It is more flexible than  9.d3  as in some lines we might get a chance to play d2-d4. By the way, this is the dilemma I was telling you about - should Black trade the Bishop, weakening his light squares and giving White a Bishop pair advantage? Or should Black retreat it to h5 allowing White to shut it out with g2-g4? }
9... Bh5 10. axb5
{ Clearing out the situation on the queenside will allow us to focus on the rest of the board. }
10... axb5 11. Rxa8 Qxa8 12. d3
{ We are now threatening 13. Bg5 which would bring some chaos to Black's position - the Knight is best on f6 from where it controls d5. }
12... O-O
{ The most popular continuation although I believe that White has an easy game. }
13. Bg5
{ Allowing Bxf6 would be like playing with fire so what should Black do? }
13... Nd7 14. Bd5
{ Another disturbing move. We are using the fact that Black can't play  14...Nb6??  as it drops the piece after  15.Bxc6  Qxc6  16.b4  . }
14... h6 15. Bh4 Qa6 16. b4 { Now Black won't be able to play b5-b4. } 16...
Ba7 17. Nbd2
{ We can play g2-g4 in the next move but we can also just go 18. Qa1 - yes we can actually trade the Queens using the a-file in the endgame. Black is facing some serious problems as the camp lacks coordination. }
*

