9. h3
{ It is more flexible than  9.d3  as in some lines we might get a chance to play d2-d4. By the way, this is the dilemma I was telling you about - should he trade the Bishop, weakening his light squares and giving White a Bishop pair advantage? Or should he retreat it to h5 allowing White to shut it out with g2-g4? }
9... Bh5 10. axb5
{ Clearing out the situation on the queenside will allow us to focus on the rest of the board. Just so you could see the difference:  10.Nbd2  Na5!  and both  11.Bc2  and  11.Ba2  are met with 11...b4 giving Black fair counterplay on the queenside. }
10... axb5 11. Rxa8 Qxa8 12. d3
{ We are now threatening with 12. Bg5 which would bring some chaos to Black's position - the Knight is best on f6 from where it controls d5. }
12... Qa1 { Looking for direct counterplay is quite risky here. } 13. g4
{ We don't have to worry about the Knight. } 13... Bg6
{ 13...Qxb1??  would be very bad for Black after simple  14.gxh5  but  14.Qe2!  instead, threatening with 15. Bh6 would be just winning. }
14. Qe2 { The Queen is not safe in the corner. } 14... Qa6 15. Nh4
{ I assume that Black will castle, after  15...O-O  we can go  16.Bg5  which will force him to move the Knight. After that we can bring the queen's Knight to f3. In the future we should most likely launch an attack on the kingside. }
*

