11. Bc2 b4 12. Qd1 { Now White can play d2-d4 at once. } 12... O-O
{ Now we can finally advance the Pawn to d4. } 13. d4 exd4
{ Black is giving up on the center in order to make it a target. } 14. cxd4 Bb6
{ 14...Ba7  wouldn't change the way we continue. } 15. Be3
{ Natural move - the Bishop protects central Pawn which allows us to develop the Knight. }
15... c5 { Black forgot to take control over e5 first. } 16. dxc5 dxc5
{ He is clearly hoping to get some counterplay with c5-c4. } 17. Nd2
{ This is stronger than  17.e5  Nd5  with unclear position. } 17... c4
{ It was already too late for covering e5 with  17...Re8  as after  18.Qe2  White would take control over c4 effectively shutting of Black's Bishop. }
18. e5
{ Black could not move the Knight to d5 -  18...Nd5  would be met with  19.Bxb6  and now:  a@@EndBracket@@  19...Qxb6  drops the Pawn after  20.Nxc4!  Nxc4  21.Qxd5  and  21...Nxb2??  would cost him a piece after  22.Rab1  ;  b@@EndBracket@@  19...Nxb6??  has far worse consequences -  20.Bxh7+!  Kxh7  21.Qh5+  Kg8  22.Ne4  and  22...f6  won't work -  23.exf6  and the Knight on a5 is hanging! }
18... Bxe3 19. fxe3
{ The Pawns might look ugly but the f-file is now open @@StartBracket@@for us@@EndBracket@@ and the initiative is far more important. }
19... Nd7
{ After  19...Nd5  simple  20.Qf3  would work - the Knight isn't safe in the center. }
20. e6 { White is making a good use of that Pawn. } 20... Nf6
{ 20...fxe6?  21.Qh5  and Black is in trouble he can't play  21...g6  22.Bxg6  while  21...h6  terribly weakens the crucial diagonal. }
21. exf7+ Rxf7 22. Qe2
{ White is clearly better as Black's position is weakened on both sides. Right now the Pawn on c4 is hanging but White has many good moves - we can activate the Rook via f4, bring the other Rook to d1 or eliminate King's defender with Nd2-e4. }
