{ This is the main reason that discourages White from playing 7. Bb3. Recently  9.d3  h6  10.Nh4  has been tested in some top level games but not very successfully. I actually believe that this is great news for White - we can easily challenge this line and, although Black should be able to equalize with accurate play, it is going to be a very difficult task for him, as you shall see. }
9. d4 Bb6 10. Re1
{ The Rook defends central Pawn but the real intentions are less peaceful - when Black castles we want to develop the Bishop to g5. }
10... O-O 11. Bg5
{ This is a very committal decision as it will most likely be connected with a piece sacrifice. }
11... h6 12. Bh4 Qe7
{ This was Swiercz's try in his game against John Bryant in Las Vegas Open 2018. White reacted with  13.Na3  and this is also what Swiercz recommended in his book.   The lines he gave however, were very complicated why the final evaluation somewhat optimistic. Luckily I think I managed to find something both simpler and stronger. Black's main thesis is that White can't develop the Knight to d2. Can't we? }
13. Nbd2 { As it turns out - we can! } 13... g5
{ Moves like that always have to be considered. } 14. Nxg5 hxg5 15. Bxg5 exd4
{ Black has to take Pawn in order to gain access to some central squares. } 16.
e5
{ It is based on tactics but by just looking at our Rook on e1 we can sense that this is the way. }
16... Nxe5 { But not  16...dxe5??  17.Ne4  and White is winning. } 17. cxd4
{ There are other moves but this is strong and simple, so why bother? } 17...
Bxd4 18. Ne4 { Basically the only move but it was part of our plan all along. }
18... Bxe4 19. Qxd4
{ The Bishop is hanging but at the same time Black can't move it because of Qd4-h4. }
19... Ned7 { It stops Re1xe4 but it won't save the Bishop. } 20. f3
{ Black can't just wait. } 20... c5 21. Qxe4 Qxe4 22. fxe4
{ White has advantage in the ending - the Bishops are stronger than the Knights, Black also has to watch out for his King.   After  22...Rfe8  we can simply defend the Pawn with  23.Bc2  . Our queenside Rook can move to d1 but we should also keep Ra1-a3!? in mind. }
