{ A study-like defense as the ugliest possible move in the position turns out to be the only one. }
29. a5
{ Swiercz only considered  29.Qh6+  but our choice is a much better try. White keeps the b file closed. }
29... Qa7+ 30. Bd4
{ We can also try  30.Kg2  but after  30...Qc5!  winning the Rook won't be enough as Black can catch perpetual. }
30... Qb7 31. Qg5
{ Again this is a tricky moment for Black. 32. Bf6 is dangerous but 32. h4! is better. The point is that White wants to play the following sequence - and here to make things easier I am just going to do nothing with Black -   31...Rb8  32.h4  Ra8  and now:  33.Qg7+  Ke8  34.Qg8+  Ke7  and thanks to our h4-pawn we have  35.Bf6+!  with an inevitable mate. }
31... c6
{ Opening the c-file and the 7th rank for the Queen is important for Black as it will allow him to catch a perpetual.   By comparison,  31...c5??  would lose after  32.Bf6! }
32. h4
{ 32.Bf6  wouldn't work now, Black can just take on  d5  and then use the c-file. }
32... Qe7 33. Bf6 Qe1+ 34. Kg2 { With a big attack which was well earned. } *

