{ Black will be able to use that Knight to defend another one. } 19. Qf3 Re8
20. Nc3 { 20.Nd2  would transpose. } 20... Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 Bd4
{ Finally Black doesn't have to deal with e4-e5! In his book on the Ruy Lopez, Swiercz devoted 6 pages only for this position. High quality work but I see no need for it - as I said there is only a handful of players ready to play this line with Black. }
22. Re4 { It is simple, it is risk-free and it is challenging. } 22... Bxf2+
{ Suddenly the pin works in Black's favour. } 23. Qxf2 Nxe4 24. Nxe4 Qc8
{ One of many only moves. Black wants to activate his Queen via f5. } 25. Nf6+
Kf8 26. g4
{ Preventing  26...Qf5  . As Swiercz pointed out, Black can save it in two ways. They are both difficult. }
26... bxa4
{ This is the most natural way - Black will get a chance to grab some counterplay on the b-file. }
27. Bg5
{ Swiercz only considered  27.Qe3  where after  27...a3!  28.bxa3  Qb7  Black can catch a perpetual quite easily. With the text move we are threatening with 28. Qh4 but if he prevents that then we can at least pin the Knight again. }
27... Qb7 { or  27...a3  28.bxa3  Qb7  29.Bh6  transposing to the mainline. }
28. Bh6
{ The Knight will be gone - Black has no way of stopping us from Nh5. By the way -  28.Qh4  didn't work - Black had no problems after  28...Qb6+  29.Kh1  Qb5  or  28...a3  . }
28... a3 { All these moves are the only ones. } 29. bxa3 Qb1+
{ Starting with a check changes a lot. } 30. Kg2 Rb8 31. Nd7+
{ We are happy to take the Rook. } 31... Kg8 32. Nxb8 Qxb8 33. Qd4
{ Having the King on g2 instead of g1 makes all the difference as Black has no checks. }
33... Ne8 34. Bd2
{ The Bishop will move to the long diagonal. White has good winning chances thanks to this powerful battery. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Ruy Lopez Moller"]
[Black "Moller 6...b5, 8...Bb7 #23"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Bc5 6. c3 b5
{ By developing the Bishop first and only then placing the Pawn on b5, Black is playing against a2-a4 line. I mean we can still go a2-a4 @@StartBracket@@and we will@@EndBracket@@ but he will no longer have to settle for Ra8-b8. }
7. Bb3
{ For many years  7.Bc2  was considered more accurate with  7...d5!?  being a nice way of surprising the opponent but no more than that. In recent years it became clear that  7.Bc2  d5  is a very serious @@StartBracket@@and complicated!@@EndBracket@@ line.   Most of the players still use it occasionally as they don't want to lose the surprise value. What does it mean for us? In my opinion it's just not practical to allow it. I saw Swiercz's analysis after 7...d5 - many pages of extensive analysis in very sharp positions where first mistake of is usually the last one.   It can be useful if you are expecting the line but are you willing to memorize it, refresh it every week or so and then still risk forgetting it? I am not. It is a very pragmatic choice as we don't need two separate lines for 5...Bc5 and 5...b5. But - as you will see - it doesn’t mean we are willing to compromise. }
7... d6 8. a4
{ The bad news is that - compared with 5...b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 move order - Black has two extra options:   8...Bb7  and  8...Bg4  . The good news is that, even combined, they are still much smaller and overall less annoying than 7. Bc2 d5 line is. }
8... Bb7
{ This is the main reason that discourages White from playing 7. Bb3. Recently  9.d3  h6  10.Nh4  has been tested in some top level games but not very successfully. I actually believe that this is great news for White - we can easily challenge this line and, although Black should be able to equalize with accurate play, it is going to be a very difficult task for him, as you shall see. }
9. d4 Bb6 10. Re1
{ The Rook defends central Pawn but the real intentions are less peaceful - when Black castles we want to develop the Bishop to g5. }
10... O-O 11. Bg5
{ This is a very responsible decision as it will most likely be connected with a piece sacrifice. }
11... h6 12. Bh4 exd4 { Black should accept the challenge. } 13. cxd4 g5 14.
Nxg5
{ Despite entering such a sharp variation I am quite relaxed here - this line is very unpopular. The reason for that is that Black has to memorize many difficult lines and in most of them he can only fight for a draw while the first mistake is usually the late one.   In other words - it is just not practical. Since we don't really expect it, all we need is something that will allow us to calmly sleep at night. }
14... hxg5 15. Bxg5 Nxd4 16. Bd5
{ It's basically the only move so you'd better not forget it. ;-@@EndBracket@@ }
16... Ne6 17. Bh4 Bxd5 { The main continuation. } 18. exd5 Ng7
{ Black will be able to use that Knight to defend another one. } 19. Qf3 Re8
20. Nc3 { 20.Nd2  would transpose. } 20... Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 Bd4
{ Finally Black doesn't have to deal with e4-e5! In his book on the Ruy Lopez, Swiercz devoted 6 pages only for this position. High quality work but I see no need for it - as I said there is only a handful of players ready to play this line with Black. }
22. Re4 { It is simple, it is risk-free and it is challenging. } 22... Bxf2+
{ Suddenly the pin works in Black's favour. } 23. Qxf2 Nxe4 24. Nxe4 Qc8
{ One of many only moves. Black wants to activate his Queen via f5. } 25. Nf6+
Kf8 26. g4
{ Preventing  26...Qf5  . As Swiercz pointed out, Black can save it in two ways. They are both difficult. }
26... bxa4
{ This is the most natural way - Black will get a chance to grab some counterplay on the b-file. }
27. Bg5
{ Swiercz only considered  27.Qe3  where after  27...a3!  28.bxa3  Qb7  Black can catch a perpetual quite easily. With the text move we are threatening with 28. Qh4 but if he prevents that then we can at least pin the Knight again. }
27... Qb7 { or  27...a3  28.bxa3  Qb7  29.Bh6  transposing to the mainline. }
28. Bh6
{ The Knight will be gone - Black has no way of stopping us from Nh5. By the way -  28.Qh4  didn't work - Black had no problems after  28...Qb6+  29.Kh1  Qb5  or  28...a3  . }
28... a3 { All these moves are the only ones. } 29. bxa3 Rb8
{ Important nuance. } 30. Nh5 Qb1+ 31. Kg2
{ Since the Bishop will capture the Knight with check Black has to forget about  31...Rb2  , }
31... Rb3
{ Beautiful resource! By cutting of the King from the 3rd rank Black creates enough counterplay to catch the draw. }
32. Bxg7+ Kg8
{ But not  32...Ke8?  33.Qe2+  Kd8  34.a4  with great winning chances. } 33.
Qe2 { Threatening 34. Qe8+. } 33... Kh7 { Now we have to be careful too. } 34.
Bd4 { Black has two possibilities now. } 34... Rxa3
{ 35...Ra2 is a serious threat, I admit. } 35. Qe8
{ We can also end the game with a little bit of humor:  35.Nf6+  Kg6  36.h4  Ra2  37.h5+  Kg5  38.Be3  Kxf6  39.Bd4  +=. But seriously speaking we should try  35.Qe8  as Black has only one saving move. }
35... Qa2+
{ Both  35...Qc2+  36.Bf2  and  35...Ra2+  36.Kg3  Qd3+  37.Be3  would be winning for White as Black is running out of checks. }
36. Kg1 Qb1+ 37. Kg2 { Nothing to be done. } *

