7. a4
{ This is not a random move-order. Starting with  7.c3  is in my opinion just inaccurate as it allows  7...d6  8.d4  Bb6  9.a4  Bg4!?  which I consider to be a very interesting line @@StartBracket@@for Black mostly@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Rb8
{ Black wants to keep the Pawn on b5 but at the same time doesn't want to commit his light-squared Bishop to b7 yet. }
8. c3 d6 9. d4 Bb6 10. a5
{ 10.axb5  axb5  11.Na3  used to be considered the mainline but in the recent years theoretical trends have shifted towards our line. The point of White's last move is to push the Black's Bishop to a7 where it is not going to feel too comfortable. }
10... Ba7 11. h3
{ We have to stop Bc8-g4 first. The pawn on e4 is indirectly protected as  11...Nxe4??  loses to the typical  12.Bd5! }
11... Bb7
{ By defending the Knight Black is attacking the Pawn on e4 as Bb3-d5 is no longer there. This is a very ambitious approach and we must react accordingly. }
12. Be3
{ Both sides are flexing their muscles. Black should now accept the challenge. }
12... Nxe4
{ Swiercz thought this was a mistake but it seems that he was wrong about this one. However, it doesn't change my attitude - we should go for it as the lines aren't easy for Black. In this position White has two main tries: 13. Re1 and 13. d5.   13. Re1 scores well but I do expect this trend to change as it is quite easy to improve Black. My initial intention was to go for the most principal variation -   13. d5 I was aware that Black could equalize in that line but it was still quite challenging so though you wouldn't mind. Then, the game Grischuk - Giri happened @@StartBracket@@Zagreb 2021@@EndBracket@@ and at this point it was no longer challenging anymore - it was just a common knowledge. I had to come up with something new. }
13. Nbd2
{ A novelty! It's a really nice feeling that it is still possible to discover new ideas at the early stages of the opening. White is sacrificing a Pawn in order to complete his development. Black can either accept it or not. }
13... Nxd2 { A solid reaction. Black wants to finish his development too. } 14.
Qxd2 { 14...exd4?  would be a bad idea -  15.Bg5!  with a strong attack. }
14... O-O { Now we will take the Pawn back. } 15. dxe5 Bxe3
{ It feels natural to include this as Black doesn't want his Knight on the edge of the board. However now white pieces will become very active. }
16. Qxe3 dxe5 17. Nxe5 Nxe5 18. Qxe5
{ After  18...Re8  we can go  19.Qf5  Re7  20.Rfe1  followed by 21.Qc5. Black has many little problems here: he has problems on the central files, especially that his Queen is exposed. His f7-pawn needs constant attention. Finally all the Bishop endgames should be better for White as the black Pawn on a6 will be permanently weak. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Ruy Lopez Archangelsk"]
[Black "Archangelsk 10...Ba7, 11...Bb7 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... b5
{ The idea of starting with 5...b5 is to prevent White from playing Ba4-c2 in one move. }
6. Bb3 Bc5
{ It is probably the most favored line among the aggressive players. No wonder Caruana or - one of the most popular Chessable authors - Sethuraman - use it so often.   Of course the Bishop on c5 doesn't stop d2-d4 - it's not even close. However once chased to b6 it will become a very powerful piece, keeping his eye on d4 and - potentially - f2. }
7. a4
{ This is not a random move-order. Starting with  7.c3  is in my opinion just inaccurate as it allows  7...d6  8.d4  Bb6  9.a4  Bg4!?  which I consider to be a very interesting line @@StartBracket@@for Black mostly@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Rb8
{ Black wants to keep the Pawn on b5 but at the same time doesn't want to commit his light-squared Bishop to b7 yet. }
8. c3 d6 9. d4 Bb6 10. a5
{ 10.axb5  axb5  11.Na3  used to be considered the mainline but in the recent years theoretical trends have shifted towards our line. The point of White's last move is to push the Black's Bishop to a7 where it is not going to feel too comfortable. }
10... Ba7 11. h3
{ We have to stop Bc8-g4 first. The pawn on e4 is indirectly protected as  11...Nxe4??  loses to the typical  12.Bd5! }
11... Bb7
{ By defending the Knight Black is attacking the Pawn on e4 as Bb3-d5 is no longer there. This is a very ambitious approach and we must react accordingly. }
12. Be3
{ Both sides are flexing their muscles. Black should now accept the challenge. }
12... Nxe4
{ Swiercz thought this was a mistake but it seems that he was wrong about this one. However, it doesn't change my attitude - we should go for it as the lines aren't easy for Black. In this position White has two main tries: 13. Re1 and 13. d5.   13. Re1 scores well but I do expect this trend to change as it is quite easy to improve Black. My initial intention was to go for the most principal variation -   13. d5 I was aware that Black could equalize in that line but it was still quite challenging so though you wouldn't mind. Then, the game Grischuk - Giri happened @@StartBracket@@Zagreb 2021@@EndBracket@@ and at this point it was no longer challenging anymore - it was just a common knowledge. I had to come up with something new. }
13. Nbd2
{ A novelty! It's a really nice feeling that it is still possible to discover new ideas at the early stages of the opening. White is sacrificing a Pawn in order to complete his development. Black can either accept it or not. }
13... Nxd2 { A solid reaction. Black wants to finish his development too. } 14.
Qxd2 { 14...exd4?  would be a bad idea -  15.Bg5!  with a strong attack. }
14... O-O { Now we will take the Pawn back. } 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Qxd8 Rbxd8 17.
Bxa7 Nxa7 18. Nxe5
{ With accurate play Black should be able to defend this. Despite of that it seems like a good practical try - my comments from the previous variation are still valid - if we manage to get a Bishop endgame we might get some serious winning chances. }
