7. a4
{ This is not a random move-order. Starting with  7.c3  is in my opinion just inaccurate as it allows  7...d6  8.d4  Bb6  9.a4  Bg4!?  which I consider to be a very interesting line @@StartBracket@@for Black mostly@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Rb8
{ Black wants to keep the Pawn on b5 but at the same time doesn't want to commit his light-squared Bishop to b7 yet. }
8. c3 d6 9. d4 Bb6 10. a5
{ 10.axb5  axb5  11.Na3  used to be considered the mainline but in the recent years theoretical trends have shifted towards our line. The point of White's last move is to push the Black's Bishop to a7 where it is not going to feel too comfortable. }
10... Ba7 11. h3
{ We have to stop Bc8-g4 first. The pawn on e4 is indirectly protected as  11...Nxe4??  loses to the typical  12.Bd5! }
11... O-O 12. Be3 Nxe4
{ This move has a very modest history but it is a top level history - it was introduced by Grischuk in 2007 and then repeated by Anand and Shirov in 2009. }
13. Bd5 { Double attack so Black has no choice now. } 13... exd4 14. Bxe4
{ 14.cxd4  Qe8  15.Re1  is of course tempting but after  15...Nf6  16.Bg5  Nxd5!  17.Rxe8  Rxe8  the position is not clear at all! }
14... d5
{ After  14...dxe3  15.Bxc6  exf2  16.Kh1  Black wouldn’t have enough compensation for the piece. }
15. Bxh7+
{ There were quite a few alternatives but let's just keep it as simple as possible. }
15... Kxh7 16. cxd4 Bf5 17. Nbd2
{ We can place the Knight on b3 and then develop the Rooks to c1 and e1. You can probably feel the dark squares all over the board... }
