7. a4
{ This is not a random move-order. Starting with  7.c3  is in my opinion just inaccurate as it allows  7...d6  8.d4  Bb6  9.a4  Bg4!?  which I consider to be a very interesting line @@StartBracket@@for Black mostly@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Rb8
{ Black wants to keep the Pawn on b5 but at the same time doesn't want to commit his light-squared Bishop to b7 yet. }
8. c3 d6 9. d4 Bb6 10. a5
{ 10.axb5  axb5  11.Na3  used to be considered the mainline but in the recent years theoretical trends have shifted towards our line. The point of White's last move is to push the Black's Bishop to a7 where it is not going to feel too comfortable. }
10... Ba7 11. h3
{ We have to stop Bc8-g4 first. The pawn on e4 is indirectly protected as  11...Nxe4??  loses to the typical  12.Bd5! }
11... O-O 12. Be3 Ra8
{ One of the ideas that I had learned from Swiercz's book was that this natural @@StartBracket@@and most popular@@EndBracket@@ move is not fully accurate. }
13. Nbd2 h6 { Now White can execute Swiercz's idea: } 14. Qe2
{ Instead of normal Rf1-e1 White wants to place his King's Rook on d1. Although mathematically Black should equalize eventually, this setup seems very unpleasant which makes it worthwhile even though Black can avoid this idea by choosing better move-orders. }
14... Re8 { It is hard to imagine Black skipping this move. } 15. Rfd1 Qe7
{ Once you see  15...Bb7  , this might seem more logical - Black wants to provoke  16.d5  while keeping the Bishop on  c8  . }
16. d5 Bxe3 17. Qxe3 Nb8 18. Nf1
{ The position looks very pleasant for White. We want to put the Knight on g3 but in case of  18...Nh5  we can always just play  19.c4  . If Black tries to lock the Queenside with  19...c5  then after  20.dxc6  Nxc6  21.Ng3  intending 22.Nh4 White has a pleasant edge - Black has no easy life with a weak d6 Pawn. }
