{ We have to stop Bc8-g4 first. The pawn on e4 is indirectly protected as  11...Nxe4??  loses to the typical  12.Bd5! }
11... O-O 12. Be3 exd4
{ Black's last move may be connected with a couple of directions. } 13. cxd4
Ne7
{ Not a popular continuation but it used to be played by some strong players. Black is removing the Knight from exposed position but bringing it to e7 looks a bit passive to me. White has to defend his central Pawn now. }
14. Qc2
{ Interestingly this is a novelty - so far everyone defended the Pawn with  14.Nbd2  where, I believe Black has no problems after  14...c5  . The point of our last move is quite simple - the Knight will be better placed on c3. }
14... Bb7
{ This move is inextricably linked with what happens next @@StartBracket@@otherwise it would be just wrong@@EndBracket@@. }
15. Nc3 b4 16. e5
{ The idea is quite simple but it's quite comforting to know that it is working. }
16... bxc3 17. exf6 gxf6 18. bxc3
{ Black's Pawn structure is ruined so at least he can pay us back. } 18... Bxf3
19. gxf3
{ Our position is bad but Black's position is even worse :-@@EndBracket@@. What happens next depends strongly on Black's plan -  19...Kh8  I would answer with  20.Rfb1!?  - the Rook defends the Bishop freeing up the Queen, while the King can now safely hide on f1.    19...d5  on the other hand requires a different reaction. Black shutting down our light-squared Bishop but also planning to undermine White's position in the center with c7-c5.  20.Qd1!  takes care of both - the Queen supports d4 while the Bishop can be moved to c2 @@StartBracket@@creating another idea - f3-f4 and Qd1-h5@@EndBracket@@. }
