{ We have to stop Bc8-g4 first. The pawn on e4 is indirectly protected as  11...Nxe4??  loses to the typical  12.Bd5! }
11... O-O 12. Be3 exd4
{ Black's last move may be connected with a couple of directions. } 13. cxd4
Nxe4
{ It is just a worse version of 12...Nxe4 but it still attracted a good number of players. }
14. Qc2 { This is why connecting 12... exd4 and 13...Nxe4 was a bad idea. }
14... Qe8 { The only move as  14...Bb7  fails to  15.d5!+- } 15. Nc3
{ This simple move might seem as some kind of a concession but actually it's really strong - we are developing our last minor piece after all. I should mention that  15...Ng3  makes no sense as White can simply play  16.Rfe1  ,   while  15...Bf5  loses to  16.Nd5!  threatening 17. Qxc6 as well as simple 17. Rfc1. }
15... Nxc3 16. Qxc3 { Black can't hold the c file. } 16... Ne7
{ Black is offering the Pawn. He is clearly hoping to recover after  17.Qxc7  Rb7  and if  18.Qxd6  then after  18...Nf5  suddenly he gets a real compensation for the Pawn. }
17. Rac1
{ Strengthening the grip. For Black the main problem is that he doesn't really have a good move while White is in hurry to win the Pawn back. }
17... c6 { 17...Bb7  18.Qxc7  would be much better for White. } 18. Rfe1
{ Another piece is joining the game. Be3-g5 is a deadly threat now but Be3-f4 might be there as well. }
18... Be6 19. Bg5
{ Black's position is collapsing. In Nijoboer, F - Bok, B - Eindhoven 2010,  19...d5  was played to which  20.Bc2!  would be the strongest response. }
