{ Now  22.Qg4  Qb6  works for Black. } 22. Nxd5 exd5 23. Bd2
{ 24. Bxb4 is only one of many threats - 24. Qe4 is another one. } 23... c4
{ This might look attractive but the pin of the Knight on b4 will now become a real thing. }
24. Nxh7
{ A surprising blow! The point is that after  24...Kxh7  White can simply play  25.Bc2+  followed by 26. Qh5 @@StartBracket@@or the reverse@@EndBracket@@ with a mating attack. }
24... cxb3 25. Nxf8 Rxf8
{ Black has two pieces for the Rook but - unfortunately for him - one of those pieces is trapped. }
26. Qe5
{ The Knight will fall, we should now make sure that the Queens won't get exchanged too soon. For instance -  26.Qe1?!  Nc2!  27.Bxa5  Nxe1  28.Bxe1  d4!  would not be at all clear. }
26... Rf7
{ Black is anticipating  27.Bc3  but also  27.Ra1?  - he would now have  27...Qc7!  28.Qxc7  Rxc7  29.Bxb4  Rc2  with an excellent compensation for an exchange, perhaps a winning one. }
27. Qe1
{ But now  27...Nc2??  fails to  28.Qe8+  +-. As you can see this position is full of nuances! }
27... Qd8 28. Bxb4 { White will also win another Pawn with Rd1-d3xb3. } *

