{ I had quite a dilemma here as  20.Nxd5  Bxd5  21.Bxd5  Rxd5  22.Ng5!  looked also good. }
20... fxe6 21. Ng5 { Targeting e6 but also h7. } 21... Bc8
{ Now  22.Qg4  Qb6  works for Black. } 22. Nxd5 exd5 23. Bd2
{ 24. Bxb4 is only one of many threats - 24. Qe4 is another one. } 23... h6
{ The best response. At first sight it might seem like White is running out of gas here... }
24. Qe5
{ At the cost of a piece we are able to continue the attack. The a1-h8 diagonal will now become essential. }
24... hxg5 25. Bc3 Rf6 { 25...Rf7??  would lose to  26.Rxd5! } 26. Rxd5
{ The Bishops really can be powerful pieces. } 26... Rxd5 27. Bxd5+ Kf8
{ One of many only moves that Black has to make. } 28. Qxg5 Qb6
{ 28...Qd8  would be met with  29.Rd1  with a strong attack. } 29. Be4
{ We don't want to trade this Bishop for the Knight, of course. White now has a simple plan of activating the Rook. Black, on the other side, is walking on the thin ice here. }
29... Bd7 30. Rd1 Be8
{ 31.Re1  will now be answered with  31...Qd6!  and Black seems to be holding. Remember this short line as it will help us understand White's next moves. }
31. Qh4 { Threatening 32. Qh8+. } 31... Rh6
{ 31...Qe6  would lose to  32.Re1  - Black can't defend against White's threats. }
32. Qg4 Rf6 { All this hustle to move the Queen from g5 to g4 - but why? } 33.
Re1
{ 33...Qd6  won't work now -  34.Bxf6  Qxf6  35.Re3  wins! The key difference is that the Black Queen on f6 is not contact with ours.   33...Qe6  also fails -  34.Qh4!  Rh6  35.Qg5!  @@StartBracket@@the Queen comes back to g5@@EndBracket@@  35...Rf6  36.Re3+-  . }
33... Bb8 { The Bishop covers some important squares now. } 34. Bxf6 Qxf6 35.
Re3
{ 35...Qxb2  36.g3!  is now winning as Black can't defend against all threats. Where should the Queen go then? }
35... Qd8
{ The only saving move! The Queen covers important c8 square but also White has to watch out for Qd8-d1+! }
36. Qf5+ Bf7 37. g3
{ Now that Black is no longer threatening with mate on the back rank he has once again to find a defense or Re3-f3 will decide the game. }
37... g6 { Once again, this is the only way to save the game! } 38. Qxc5+
{ After  38...Qd6  White can either swap the Queens or retreat to c3. In both cases however the position is dynamically balanced. }
*

