18. Rxd2
{ White is threatening with e4-e5. Black can either cover the d file or take the central Pawn. }
18... Nxe4
{ It is a very difficult decision as White's Rook will now enter the 7th rank. }
19. Nxe4 Bxe4 20. Rd7
{ White's initiative is unquestionable: the Rook is dominating, the Pawn on f7 is a clear target and there is this Bishop on a7... }
20... Rb7
{ He is lucky to have this one. After  20...Nc6??  21.Ng5  Bg6  22.Bd5  White would win a piece and a game. }
21. Rfd1 Rxd7 22. Rxd7 Nc6
{ A moment ago this would be a losing mistake so what has changed? Black's point is that now after  23.Ng5  he has  23...c4!  24.Bxa7  Bf5!  and after  25.Rc7  Nxa7  26.Rxa7  h6  or  25...Rc8!?  Black should equalize. These variations show pretty clearly how difficult and challenging the whole line is for Black. }
23. Nd2
{ Since  23...c4  is happening anyway and there is no hope for winning the Pawn on f7 it is a safer choice for White. }
23... c4 24. Bxa7 Bf5 25. Rd6
{ After  25.Rc7  Black would equalize with  25...Rc8! } 25... Nxa7 26. Rxa6 Nc8
{ Now it is White who has to be careful since after  27.Ba2?!  Rd8  Black is taking over the initiative. }
27. g4
{ Pushing the Bishop away from the perfect square. The point is that after  27...Bg6  the Bishop no longer defends the Knight. White can then play  28.Bd1!  as  28...Rd8  fails to  29.Ra8! }
27... Be6 28. Bc2 Rd8 29. Nf1
{ White maintains some initiative - our pieces are simply more active. We want to continue with 30. Ne3 but we also have to look out for  29...Bd5  as our Rook might get trapped. We should then play  30.Bf5!  to have  30...Bb7  31.Bxc8! }
