{ It is probably the most favored line among the aggressive players. No wonder Caruana or - one of the most popular Chessable authors - Sethuraman - use it so often.   Of course the Bishop on c5 doesn't stop d2-d4 - it's not even close. However once chased to b6 it will become a very powerful piece, keeping his eye on d4 and - potentially - f2. }
7. a4
{ This is not a random move-order. Starting with  7.c3  is in my opinion just inaccurate as it allows  7...d6  8.d4  Bb6  9.a4  Bg4!?  which I consider to be a very interesting line @@StartBracket@@for Black mostly@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Rb8
{ Black wants to keep the Pawn on b5 but at the same time doesn't want to commit his light-squared Bishop to b7 yet. }
8. c3 d6 9. d4 Bb6 10. a5
{ 10.axb5  axb5  11.Na3  used to be considered the mainline but in the recent years theoretical trends have shifted towards our line. The point of White's last move is to push the Black's Bishop to a7 where it is not going to feel too comfortable. }
10... Ba7 11. h3
{ We have to stop Bc8-g4 first. The pawn on e4 is indirectly protected as  11...Nxe4??  loses to the typical  12.Bd5! }
11... O-O 12. Be3 Re8
{ The most accurate move-order. We can now forget about Qe2 setup. } 13. Ng5
{ In my opinion this is the cleanest way to keep things under control. As an example -  13.Nbd2  h6  14.Re1  would allow  14...Bb7  skipping Rb8-a8 completely. }
13... Rf8 14. Re1 Ra8 { 14...h6  15.Nf3  would soon transpose. } 15. Nf3
{ Otherwise we could not develop our Queen's Knight. } 15... Re8 16. Nbd2 Bb7
{ It seems that Black can live without h7-h6. The other thing is whether the Bishop on b7 is such a strong piece. }
17. g4
{ It might seem unusual if you haven't seen Caruana-Carlsen game from Isle of Man 2017, but otherwise it is a typical idea already it just hasn't been executed in this exact position yet! We should also be aware of the threat -  17...--  18.g5  exd4  19.cxd4  Nxe4  20.Nxe4  Rxe4  21.g6!  hxg6  22.Bxf7+  Kxf7  23.Ng5+  . }
17... exd4
{ One of the possible reactions. By opening up the position Black is hoping to activate his Bishops as well as the Rook. On the other hand now d4-d5 or e4-e5 might be possible in some lines. }
18. cxd4 Qd7
{ Not just developing the Queen but also targeting White's kingside Pawns. }
19. d5
{ Already a thematic advance - Black's light-squared Bishop is now passive again. }
19... Nb4
{ 19...Ne7  20.Bxa7  Rxa7  21.Nh4!  would be clearly better for White. } 20.
Bxa7 Rxa7 21. Nd4 { 21.Nh4  would lead to the same position after  21...c5  . }
21... c5 22. dxc6 Nxc6 23. Nf5
{ White pieces are very active. We can now think of developing the Queen to e2 or f3. In case of 23...Ne7 we should retreat the Knight to g3. }
