17... d5
{ When attacking on the side we always have to consider counterattack in the center! }
18. exd5 exd4 { 18...Nxd5  19.Bg5  would give White a strong initiative. } 19.
Bg5 { Skipping h7-h6 was not so bad for us after all... } 19... Rxe1+ 20. Qxe1
dxc3
{ 20...Ne7  21.Bxf6  gxf6  22.cxd4  would leave Black in a terrible situation.   After the text move it might seem that Black is just busted after  21.bxc3  . However he has surprising  21...Qd6!  threatening with 22...Qg3+ which allows him to keep the position balanced. However, we have our own tricks. }
21. dxc6 cxd2 22. Bxd2 Bxc6
{ 22...Qd6  is not satisfactory now - after  23.cxb7  Qg3+  23.Kf1  Qxh3+  White can play  24.Ke2  Re8  25.Be3  Bxe3  26.b8=Q!  Rxb8  27.fxe3  and Black doesn't have enough compensation for the piece. }
23. Bxf7+ Kh8
{ After  23...Kxf7  we could go  24.Ne5+  but instead  24.Ng5+!  is stronger -  24...Kg6  25.Qb1+  Be4  26.Nxe4  Kf7  27.Bc3  and White has a winning advantage. }
24. Ne5
{ Not only the Bishop is hanging but White is also threatening with something as simple as 25. Bb3 followed by 26. Nf7+. }
24... Qd6 25. Bf4
{ Avoiding a trap:  25.Bb3?  runs into  25...Bxf2+!  and in view of  26.Kxf2  Ne4+  or  26.Qxf2  Qxe5  suddenly Black is winning! }
25... Ne4 { Forcing the events but we don't mind. } 26. Ng6+ Qxg6 27. Bxg6
Bxf2+ { Quite an original way of exchanging the Queens. } 28. Qxf2 Nxf2 29.
Kxf2 hxg6 30. Rc1
{ After  30...Rf8  we can just go  31.Kg3  . White has a nice advantage in the endgame. The c7 Pawn is lost while the remaining black Pawns are weak, especially g7 and a6. }
