17. Ba2
{ A novelty. There are two ideas behind White's last move - the first one is to play Bb1. Once the Pawn on e4 is protected we can then move the Knight to g3  @@StartBracket@@via f1@@EndBracket@@ - exd4 cxd4 Nxe4 is never possible due to d4-d5.   The second one is to react to  17...Bb7  with  18.Qb3!  This explains why we didn't choose 17. Bc2 instead - after  17...Bb7  White doesn't have a good move -  18.Nf1  is met with  18...exd4  19.cxd4  Nb4  while  18.Bb1  Nb8!  worked for Black in Gashimov - Caruana, Wijk aan Zee 2012. Of course now we have to consider 17...Nxa5 as well. }
17... Nxa5 { The most critical response. } 18. Bxf7+ Kxf7 19. Rxa5
{ Black has now a Bishop pair however it's not going to be easy for him to make a good use of it. White has a better Pawn structure and the black King might be vulnerable, though it might not seem obvious right now. }
19... c5
{ It is better to do it right away - after  19...Kg8  White may consider  20.dxe5  dxe5  21.c4!?  c6  22.b4  with a small advantage mainly thanks to the weak Pawn on e5. }
20. dxe5 dxe5
{ 20...Qxa5  was out of the question - after  21.exf6  Black's position would collapse immediately, for example  21...Kxf6  22.e5!  dxe5  23.Ne4+  +- . }
21. Ra1 Kg8
{ The King comes back home.  22...c4?  - apart from being a questionable choice in general - blunders  23.Bxa7  Rxa7  24.Nxc4!  and after  24...bxc4  25.Nxe5+  Kf8  26.Nc6  White has a winning advantage. }
22. c4 { Locking up Black's dark-squared Bishop for good. } 22... b4 23. Nh4
{ Our plan is to put the Queen on f3, the other Knight on f1 and try g2-g4. Nh4-f5 is always a possible idea. Black has an inferior Pawn structure, his weak light squares are clearly visible plus he is struggling to find a plan other than adjusting to our play. }
