9. axb5 axb5 10. c3 d6 11. d4 { This time there was no need for h2-h3. } 11...
exd4 12. cxd4 d5
{ Just like in the normal 9...Rb8 line only it can not be easily refuted this time. }
13. e5 { Going for an isolani instead wouldn't cause Black too much trouble. }
13... Ne4 14. Nc3 { At least we will get rid of this strong Knight. } 14...
Nxc3 15. bxc3 Bf5
{ Normally Black shouldn't have any problems in this structure. However here we take some profit from the a file - The knight on c6 can't be transferred to c4 as it usually is. }
16. Qe2 Qd7 17. Be3
{ We developed the remaining pieces and now we can wait and see what Black will do. }
17... Nd8
{ This seems the most logical, the Knight wasn't very well placed on c6. } 18.
Ra7
{ It's not like the white Rook is so dangerous on a7 but it's always kind of a pressure. }
18... Ne6 19. Rea1
{ There is nothing specific but White pieces are more active. Another Rook can be advanced to a6, limiting Black's possibilities. Then we can start thinking about the kingside activity: one idea is to play h2-h4 and Nf3-g5.   The other one would be to remove the Knight from f3 @@StartBracket@@maybe Ne1-d3?@@EndBracket@@ and advance g2 and f2. In the latter case we have to be very careful and anticipate b5-b4 as it might undermine our Pawn on d4. }
