{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6.Re1 is better than 6.d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6.d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 O-O
{ Black is hoping to get a famous Marshall Gambit with 8. c3 d5! @@StartBracket@@or not so famous Upgraded Gajewski Gambit with 8. c3 Na5!? :-@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@.   My little thing is probably not enough reason to abandon 8. c3 but Marshall definitely can be.   After  8.c3  d5!  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Rxe5  c6  - long story short - Black gets a sufficient compensation for the Pawn thanks to the strong Bishop pair and underdevelopment of White's pieces @@StartBracket@@look at the queenside@@EndBracket@@.   What used to be an exciting line has, at some point, become a large collection of long forced lines leading to one outcome only. Definitely not what we are looking for. }
8. a4
{ This is one of the most serious Anti-Marshall Systems out there. By our last move we have created a direct challenge for Black - should he develop the Bishop to b7 or push the Pawn to b4? }
8... Bb7
{ If you look at the recent games you might get an impression that there is only one important move after 8. a4 - 8...b4. In fact this seems to be the fashion mostly as 8...Bb7 is equally serious. }
9. d3 { 9.c3  would still be met with  9...d5!  with even bigger effect. } 9...
d5
{ This typical pawn sacrifice is occasionally used by strong players to surprise their opponents. It is not strong enough to enter the mainstream, though. }
10. axb5
{ Winning the Pawn immediately is less accurate - after  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxe5  11...Nd4  whenever we take on b5 and a8 Black will be able to recapture with the Queen since the Knight on d5 is protected. }
10... axb5 11. Rxa8 Bxa8
{ 11....Qxa8?  was not an option now because of a simple  12.exd5  . } 12. exd5
Nxd5 13. Nxe5
{ So we have a typical scenario: White is a Pawn up while Black is hoping for nice compensation thanks to the powerful Bishop pair. He can now take the Knight on e5 or invest a tempo and swap the Bishop instead - also quite a typical choice. }
13... Nxe5 14. Rxe5
{ White Rook actually feels quite comfortable in the center, disrupting Black's forces. }
14... c5 15. h3
{ 15.Nd2?  was not possible due to  15...Nf4!  but we don't want to give up on our disruptor on e5, not yet! Gregory Serper once called h2-h3 a useful waste of time - the description fits like a glove to our case!   White doesn't seem to be making much progress, however the Pawn on h2 was a potential target @@StartBracket@@Qd8-c7 and Be7-d6 or Nd5-f6-g4@@EndBracket@@ and the back rank problems are prevented as well. }
15... Nf6
{ Sad necessity - Black could no longer tolerate the White Rook attacking the Knight.  15...Qd6  would be answered with  16.Qe2!  with big advantage. }
16. Re1 { The Rook did its job - it can now go back home. } 16... Bd6 17. Nd2
Qc7 18. Qe2
{ Black definitely has some compensation for the Pawn however it is a defensive kind of compensation - there is no real attack on the white King. White can put the c Pawn on c3 or even c4 @@StartBracket@@fighting the d5 square@@EndBracket@@. The Knight has also some good options - depending on Black's play we can put it on f1 or f3. }
*

