6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 O-O
{ Black is hoping to get a famous Marshall Gambit with 8. c3 d5! @@StartBracket@@or not so famous Upgraded Gajewski Gambit with 8. c3 Na5!? :-@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@.   My little thing is probably not enough reason to abandon 8. c3 but Marshall definitely can be.   After  8.c3  d5!  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Rxe5  c6  - long story short - Black gets a sufficient compensation for the Pawn thanks to the strong Bishop pair and underdevelopment of White's pieces @@StartBracket@@look at the queenside@@EndBracket@@.   What used to be an exciting line has, at some point, become a large collection of long forced lines leading to one outcome only. Definitely not what we are looking for. }
8. a4
{ This is one of the most serious Anti-Marshall Systems out there. By our last move we have created a direct challenge for Black - should he develop the Bishop to b7 or push the Pawn to b4? }
8... Bb7
{ If you look at the recent games you might get an impression that there is only one important move after 8. a4 - 8...b4. In fact this seems to be the fashion mostly as 8...Bb7 is equally serious. }
9. d3 { 9.c3  would still be met with  9...d5!  with even bigger effect. } 9...
d5
{ This typical pawn sacrifice is occasionally used by strong players to surprise their opponents. It is not strong enough to enter the mainstream, though. }
10. axb5
{ Winning the Pawn immediately is less accurate - after  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Nxe5  11...Nd4  whenever we take on b5 and a8 Black will be able to recapture with the Queen since the Knight on d5 is protected. }
10... axb5 11. Rxa8 Bxa8
{ 11....Qxa8?  was not an option now because of a simple  12.exd5  . } 12. exd5
Nxd5 13. Nxe5
{ So we have a typical scenario: White is a Pawn up while Black is hoping for a nice compensation thanks to the powerful Bishop pair. He can now take the Knight on e5 or invest a tempo and swap the Bishop instead - also quite a typical choice. }
13... Nd4 14. c3 Nxb3 15. Qxb3 b4
{ Generally speaking Black should be able to hold this in one of the possible endgames. It still says a lot about the position - we are playing for two results here. }
16. Nd2
{ I prefer this over  16.d4  played in Kokarev, V - Moiseenko, V - Khanty-Manisysk 2017 - White should be very careful with putting the Pawns on the dark squares as it improves Black's chances of escaping to the opposite color bishop endgame. }
16... c5 17. Ndf3 Bd6 18. Bd2
{ White maintains winning chances. It is hard to talk about specific plans here - all our pieces are placed optimally and there is no obvious follow-up  @@StartBracket@@for either of sides@@EndBracket@@. We might usefully waste some time with h2-h3 but in general it is all about reacting to each other's moves - easier to do when you are a pawn up. }
