6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 O-O
{ Black is hoping to get a famous Marshall Gambit with 8. c3 d5! @@StartBracket@@or not so famous Upgraded Gajewski Gambit with 8. c3 Na5!? :-@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@.   My little thing is probably not enough reason to abandon 8. c3 but Marshall definitely can be.   After  8.c3  d5!  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Rxe5  c6  - long story short - Black gets a sufficient compensation for the Pawn thanks to the strong Bishop pair and underdevelopment of White's pieces @@StartBracket@@look at the queenside@@EndBracket@@.   What used to be an exciting line has, at some point, become a large collection of long forced lines leading to one outcome only. Definitely not what we are looking for. }
8. a4
{ This is one of the most serious Anti-Marshall Systems out there. By our last move we have created a direct challenge for Black - should he develop the Bishop to b7 or push the Pawn to b4? }
8... Bb7
{ If you look at the recent games you might get an impression that there is only one important move after 8. a4 - 8...b4. In fact this seems to be the fashion mostly as 8...Bb7 is equally serious. }
9. d3 { 9.c3  would still be met with  9...d5!  with even bigger effect. } 9...
Re8
{ This continuation is not very popular compared with 9... d6 but some great players, including the current World Champion, use it occasionally. Black's idea is to skip d7-d6 and - with h7-h6 and Be7-f8 - prepare d7-d5! }
10. h3
{ While the move itself is useful in general it is hard to point out to the specific point behind it in this case but, believe me, it will become clear later on! }
10... d6
{ The combination of Rf8-e8 and d7-d6 doesn't make much sense now. Especially if White can play: }
11. Bd2
{ The point of White's move is to prevent Nc6-a5. It also prepares Nc3 as after b4 Nd5, Black's Pawn on b4 will become a target. I seriously considered this idea on the previous move @@StartBracket@@10.Bd2@@EndBracket@@ but eventually decided that 10.h3 was a better try.   Now - compared with 10. Bd2 - in most of the lines Black plays d6-d5 which means we get a useful h2-h3 move for free. }
11... b4 12. a5 d5
{ Since Nc6-a5 is no longer an option this seems like the most reasonable plan. Any alternatives?   I thought  12...Rb8  might be sensible too. We can then go  13.Bc1!?  making the room for the Knight. It might look like a loss of tempo but remember that - unless d6-d5 is played - Black's Bishop on b7 is misplaced so might want to lose some tempos as well and transfer it to e6. }
13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Bc1
{ We can actually afford it! The Knight will now have some beautiful outposts in the center. }
14... Qd7
{ Black Bishop on b7 has some real potential and therefore he would love to see  15.Nxe5?!  16.Nxe5  16.Rxe5  . After  16...Bc5!  Black's compensation is undisputable. }
15. Nbd2 { We continue with our plan instead } 15... Rad8
{ Black is finishing the development by bringing the rook to the center. } 16.
Ne4
{ The position is very complex of course but I believe that White's chances are slightly preferable as our position has no weaknesses. Usually White continues with Bc1-d2 and c3 building the pressure on the c file.   We can also consider Bb3-a4 as well. Black's counterplay usually involves advancing the f7 Pawn but, although f7-f5 looks great, it should not be overestimated.   Firstly it weakens the a2-g8 diagonal so it might backfire. Secondly even if we simply retreat with the Knight to g3 it's not easy for Black to find a good follow-up while the central Pawns do require constant attention. }
