{ I suggest checking this line because Black's follow-up is quite natural and most of all I find White's plan very instructive. }
13. Ne4 Rad8 14. c3 { The White Pawn takes the control over the d4 square. }
14... f5
{ Now is not the best time to do it. White's pressure will further increase. }
15. Ng3 Bf6 16. axb5
{ It is important to include this as it takes the a5 square away from the black Knight. }
16... axb5 17. d4 exd4
{ 17...e4?!  might look tempting. However after  18.Ng5  h6  19.h4!  not only the Knight can hardly be taken but also the other one soon join the attack with Ng3-h5! }
18. Rxe8+ Rxe8 { This trade brings the black Rook away from the Knight on d5. }
19. Nh5 { Which we can immediately use to our advantage! } 19... Kh8
{ Finally Black gets to move the King away from the diagonal... } 20. cxd4
{ White has some nice initiative thanks to the active pieces as well as the weakened position of the black King @@StartBracket@@a2-g8 diagonal!@@EndBracket@@. We will probably take the Bishop on f6 and try to make some good use of our dark-square Bishop since it won't be easy for Black to neutralize it. }
