{ Once again - it's useful to take control over the a5 square. I think the general rule is that as long as the Black rook stays on a8, taking on b5 has to be calculated and each time the decision will depend on the details.   Once the black Rook leaves the a file, we can just take that Pawn and open the file. }
15... axb5 16. Nh2
{ Now that's a beautiful move! White wants to put the Queen on h5. } 16... Qf5
{ Black is right not to allow it. But now his Queen is exposed in the center. }
17. Ng3 Qg6 18. Nf3
{ As soon as Black solves one problem, another one appears. Not only the Pawn on e5 requires protection but also he has to reckon with d3-d4! - not only undermining Black's position in the center but also opening the b1-h7 diagonal for the white Bishop. }
