{ Black is hoping to get a famous Marshall Gambit with 8. c3 d5! @@StartBracket@@or not so famous Upgraded Gajewski Gambit with 8. c3 Na5!? :-@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@.   My little thing is probably not enough reason to abandon 8. c3 but Marshall definitely can be.   After  8.c3  d5!  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Rxe5  c6  - long story short - Black gets a sufficient compensation for the Pawn thanks to the strong Bishop pair and underdevelopment of White's pieces @@StartBracket@@look at the queenside@@EndBracket@@.   What used to be an exciting line has, at some point, become a large collection of long forced lines leading to one outcome only. Definitely not what we are looking for. }
8. a4
{ This is one of the most serious Anti-Marshall Systems out there. By our last move we have created a direct challenge for Black - should he develop the Bishop to b7 or push the Pawn to b4? }
8... Bb7
{ If you look at the recent games you might get an impression that there is only one important move after 8. a4 - 8...b4. In fact this seems to be the fashion mostly as 8...Bb7 is equally serious. }
9. d3 { 9.c3  would still be met with  9...d5!  with even bigger effect. } 9...
Re8
{ This continuation is not very popular compared with 9... d6 but some great players, including the current World Champion, use it occasionally. Black's idea is to skip d7-d6 and - with h7-h6 and Be7-f8 - prepare d7-d5! }
10. h3
{ While the move itself is useful in general it is hard to point out to the specific point behind it in this case but, believe me, it will become clear later on! }
10... d5
{ Although this is a novelty, it is good to know about the move, before somebody plays it, especially that it's a standard idea and the timing is correct. }
11. exd5
{ I have also considered  11.axb5  axb5  12.Rxa8  Bxa8  13.exd5  Nxd5  14.Nxe5  but after  14...Nd4  15.Nd2  Nxb3  16.Nxb3  c5  Black's compensation seemed sufficient. }
11... Nxd5 12. Nbd2
{ Ignoring the Pawn is the best choice here especially that we do have some useful moves left. }
12... Bf8 { Now, that everything is protected, Black seems to be just fine. }
13. axb5
{ A pragmatic choice. There is also  13.Ng5!?  which might lead to some interesting complications. However I see no reason for a difficult solution when there is an easy one, especially in a position that is purely hypothetical since it has not been played yet. }
13... axb5 14. Rxa8 Bxa8 15. c3
{ Now c3-d4 is a threat and is not easy to prevent. } 15... h6
{ The best response. It is worth noting that pseudo-active  15...Nf4??  leads to some unsolvable problems after  16.Ne4!  The point is that after  16...h6   16...Nxd3  17.Nfg5  is a quick end.  White has some beautiful and strong tactics:  17.Nfg5!!  hxg5  18.Bxf4  exf4  19.Qh5  Qd7  20.Bxf7+!  Qxf7  21.Qxf7+  Kxf7  22.Nxg5+  Kg6  23.Rxe8  and the endgame should be winning for White. }
16. d4 { Executing our plan. } 16... Na5
{ So this is Black's point. He is willing to sacrifice the central Pawn in order to gain control over the light squares by swapping the Knight for the Bishop. }
17. Nxe5 Nxb3 18. Nxb3
{ 18.Qxb3  is also possible. The game might continue with  18...f6  19.Nef3  Rxe1+  20.Nxe1  with a slight edge. }
18... Nb6 19. Nd2
{ The Knight was not very useful on b3. Black has very good chances for a successful defense but it doesn't change the fact that White is a pawn up while having a safe position - by definition we should not be avoiding such positions. We will regroup the Knight to f3 or f1 and then try to activate the Bishop. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Anti-Marshall (8...Bb7) and Sidelines"]
[Black "Anti-Marshall 8...Bb7 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Be7
{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6.Re1 is better than 6.d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6.d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 O-O
{ Black is hoping to get a famous Marshall Gambit with 8. c3 d5! @@StartBracket@@or not so famous Upgraded Gajewski Gambit with 8. c3 Na5!? :-@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@.   My little thing is probably not enough reason to abandon 8. c3 but Marshall definitely can be.   After  8.c3  d5!  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Rxe5  c6  - long story short - Black gets a sufficient compensation for the Pawn thanks to the strong Bishop pair and underdevelopment of White's pieces @@StartBracket@@look at the queenside@@EndBracket@@.   What used to be an exciting line has, at some point, become a large collection of long forced lines leading to one outcome only. Definitely not what we are looking for. }
8. a4
{ This is one of the most serious Anti-Marshall Systems out there. By our last move we have created a direct challenge for Black - should he develop the Bishop to b7 or push the Pawn to b4? }
8... Bb7
{ If you look at the recent games you might get an impression that there is only one important move after 8. a4 - 8...b4. In fact this seems to be the fashion mostly as 8...Bb7 is equally serious. }
9. d3 { 9.c3  would still be met with  9...d5!  with even bigger effect. } 9...
Re8
{ This continuation is not very popular compared with 9... d6 but some great players, including the current World Champion, use it occasionally. Black's idea is to skip d7-d6 and - with h7-h6 and Be7-f8 - prepare d7-d5! }
10. h3
{ While the move itself is useful in general it is hard to point out to the specific point behind it in this case but, believe me, it will become clear later on! }
10... h6
{ Black continues with his plan. It is worth noting that  10...Bf8?!  would be premature and White can answer with  11.Bg5!  with a nice edge. }
11. Nc3
{ Why are we doing this now and not on the 10th move when the Pawns were still on h2 and h7? We are going to find out in a few moves. }
11... b4 { No real choice here. } 12. Nd5 Na5
{ Again, there were no good alternatives. Black's Knight takes the a5-square while it is still available. }
13. Nxf6+
{ The dark-squared Bishop won't be too powerful on f6 so it's ok to take the Knight instead. }
13... Bxf6 14. Ba2 d5
{ or  14...c5  15.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@preparing c2-c3@@EndBracket@@ and Black should play  15...d5  anyway. }
15. Bd2 dxe4 16. dxe4 Qe7
{ White has a slight edge here thanks to the Bishop on a2 and weak black Pawns on b4 and a6. }
17. Qe2 Red8
{ It makes sense to keep the Rook on a8 as it protects the Pawn on a6. } 18.
Nh2
{ White Knight is heading to g4. Of it would not be possible had the players not included h2-h3 and h7-h6 on the 10th move. }
18... Rd4 { Bold and correct! Otherwise this would be just better for White. }
19. Be3 Rxe4
{ Definitely, a difficult decision to make and one that had to be taken a move earlier. It's true that Black has won a pawn but now all his pieces look like they have been randomly scattered all over the board. Strangely enough, he can get away with it. }
20. Rad1
{ 20.f3  Rxe3  21.Qxe3  e4!  would give Black a nice compensation for the exchange. It is very instructive to see how little it takes from a miserable bishop to become a powerful one. }
20... Bg5 { The most natural continuation. } 21. Ng4 Bxe3 22. fxe3
{ Slightly unusual but makes perfect sense - the e3 pawn controls some central squares plus White can use the f file now. }
22... b3 { Black gives the Pawn back in order to activate the Rook. } 23. cxb3
Rb4 24. Rf1 Rf8 25. Qe1
{ This is a rare case when both positions are bad! White has an ugly Pawn structure but I think that Black's position is even worse :-@@EndBracket@@   We have some nice follow-ups as we can activate the Bishop with Ba2-b1 and the Queen with Qe1-g3. This can create quite a serious attack so Black really has to be careful. }
*

