{ Typical reaction - Black offers a Pawn hoping to obtain a decent compensation thanks to his Bishop pair and White's broken Pawn structure. Fair enough, but we don't really have to go for it. }
11. Bd5
{ This is a very important trick. The immediate  11.Ba2?!  would leave the black Bishop open allowing something like  11...b4  12.Ne2  d5!? }
11... Nxd5 12. Nxd5
{ White's Knight fully dominates the black pieces and it can't really be captured as it would take away the c6-square from Black's Knight. }
12... Nc6
{ 12...d6?  13.Bxh6!  gxh6  14.Qd2  would give White a winning attack on the kingside. }
13. c3 d6 14. h3
{ White can improve his position with Bc1-e3 and d3-d4 or Qd1-b3. Black has to reckon with axb5 all the time.   Also the most natural move -  14...Qd7  runs into  15.d4!  and Nd5-f6+ trick is waiting... }
