[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Be7
{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6.Re1 is better than 6.d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6.d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 O-O
{ Black is hoping to get a famous Marshall Gambit with 8. c3 d5! @@StartBracket@@or not so famous Upgraded Gajewski Gambit with 8. c3 Na5!? :-@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@.   My little thing is probably not enough reason to abandon 8. c3 but Marshall definitely can be.   After  8.c3  d5!  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Rxe5  c6  - long story short - Black gets a sufficient compensation for the Pawn thanks to the strong Bishop pair and underdevelopment of White's pieces @@StartBracket@@look at the queenside@@EndBracket@@.   What used to be an exciting line has, at some point, become a large collection of long forced lines leading to one outcome only. Definitely not what we are looking for. }
8. a4
{ This is one of the most serious Anti-Marshall Systems out there. By our last move we have created a direct challenge for Black - should he develop the Bishop to b7 or push the Pawn to b4? }
8... Bb7
{ If you look at the recent games you might get an impression that there is only one important move after 8. a4 - 8...b4. In fact this seems to be the fashion mostly as 8...Bb7 is equally serious. }
9. d3 { 9.c3  would still be met with  9...d5!  with even bigger effect. } 9...
d6
{ This position has already appeared in thousands of games from both Anti-Marshall and Archangelsk. Both sides have agreed to slow down the action and develop the pieces first. }
10. h3
{ For a long time  10.Nbd2  was considered to be the most critical continuation. However, the recent games after  10...Nd7!  have proven that Black can fully solve his opening problems in that line.  Peter Svidler's recent win against Dariusz Swiercz in Sinquefield Cup was rather an exception as Black badly blundered in that game. Therefore I believe we should move our attention to another possibility. }
10... Na5
{ Basically this is the only sensible continuation. I will only note that  10...Nd7  doesn't work now - white can simply reply with  11.Be3! }
11. Ba2 c5 12. Nbd2
{ This is basically 10. Nbd2 Na5 line with h2-h3 committed. Still a good enough try. }
12... b4
{ This is quite a typical approach - Black wants to shut down the queenside basically claiming that his position will become impregnable. }
13. c3 { This is more flexible then immediate  13.Nf1 } 13... Rc8
{ Black is trying to oppose White's plan. This move was first played by Levon Aronian in his game against Peter Svidler in Wijk Aan Zee 2007 and then repeated two months later by Vishy Anand also against Peter Svidler in Melody Amber - rapid part of the tournament.   The Russian superstar continued  14.cxb4  cxb4  15.Nf1  twice but both his opponents reacted with the strong  15...d5!  16.exd5  b3!  obtaining a nice compensation for the Pawn.  Two years later Svidler got the same position for the third time. This time he was facing a Finnish grandmaster - Tomy Nyback. }
14. Nf1
{ This time Svidler decided to skip cxb4 but otherwise his plan hasn't changed.  14.Nc4  would be a bit better for White but Black's position would indeed remain very solid. }
14... bxc3 15. bxc3 d5
{ This breakthrough worked in a similar position so it has to be considered here as well. White should be better but only with some precise moves. }
16. Nxe5 dxe4 17. Ng3 { At the cost of a Pawn the Knight enters the game. }
17... exd3 18. Nf5
{ You have to admit it, the white Knights look pretty cool! They are also very dangerous. In order to neutralize White's initiative Black has to give the Pawns back: }
18... c4
{ Such a blockade cannot be ignored so we take this Pawn while we still can. }
19. Nxe7+ Qxe7 20. Nxc4 { The game is becoming pretty forced after this } 20...
Qd8 21. Nxa5 Qxa5 22. Qxd3 Rxc3 23. Bd2 Rxd3 24. Bxa5
{ White has a small advantage in the endgame as the Bishop pair will always be superior to Black's minor pieces. }
*

