Rxe3 Bg5
{ The only equalizing move for Black and it's definitely a challenge to see that after  19.Rg3  there is a strong response:  19...Bh4!  White has to come back to e3 then because  20.Rg4?  Bf6!  would lead to Black's advantage. }
19. Qh5
{ This is another good reason for Black not to go 18...Bg5 in the first place. It looks like White might be just winning and after  19...Bxe3  20.Bxf7+  Rxf7  21.Qxf7+  Kh8  21.Bxe3  he certainly is... }
19... c4 { Great resource. Black blocks the diagonal with the pawn. } 20. Rg3
Bxc1
{ This is a natural choice for Black although it does look risky as well - dark-squared Bishop was an important defender of Black's King. }
21. Rxc1 cxb2 22. Re1
{ The Rook moves to the most active square. For a moment the Black Pawns pose no danger as neither of them can advance. }
22... f6
{ Not an easy move to make but Black has to do something about White's activity. Additionally he can now defend g7 using the 7th rank.   22...Rc5  instead might look tempting however White has  23.dxc4  Nc6  24.Qh6  g6  25.Ng4!  maintaining the attack. }
23. Nxc4 Bd5
{ The number of precise moves which Black has to make in order to survive the opening stage really is astounding. }
24. Bb1 { Quitely hoping to get some more action on b1-h7 diagonal... } 24...
f5 25. Nxb2
{ White is a Pawn up but we should not hang on to it too strong. It is far more important to regain the coordination of the pieces - for that purpose we should quickly advance the Pawn to d4. The position shall remain unclear though. }
