{ So the Bishop comes with help... } 16. b3
{ A difficult decision but the right one! } 16... a3
{ I think it's a better practical choice than  16...axb3  . Black ignores the pawn sacrifice choosing to lock our light-squared Bishop instead.  On the other hand White's pawn structure will be superior. The game will slow down from now on. }
17. Bb1 Nc6
{ The Knight had no future on a5. On c6 it controls some important squares. }
18. Rxa3
{ The position is quite different from what we are were seeking after 16...axb3. Still the main factor remains the same - the weak Pawn on a6. }
18... a5 19. Nc4 Ra8 20. c3
{ The Bishop will no longer attack the Pawn but other things are more important: b4 and d4 are now covered while the odd looking Bishop on b1 will now be able to move to c2, which - as a result - will allow the other Rook to move to the a file as well.   In the long run we want to place the Knight on d5 in such a way that taking it would force the Black Knight to retreat from c6. Black, on the other hand, is forced to adjust to White's moves which is always more difficult. }
