d6
{ This position has already appeared in thousands of games from both Anti-Marshall and Archangelsk. Both sides have agreed to slow down the action and develop the pieces first. }
10. h3
{ For a long time  10.Nbd2  was considered to be the most critical continuation. However, the recent games after  10...Nd7!  have proven that Black can fully solve his opening problems in that line.  Peter Svidler's recent win against Dariusz Swiercz in Sinquefield Cup was rather an exception as Black badly blundered in that game. Therefore I believe we should move our attention to another possibility. }
10... Na5
{ Basically this is the only sensible continuation. I will only note that  10...Nd7  doesn't work now - white can simply reply with  11.Be3! }
11. Ba2 c5 12. Nbd2
{ This is basically 10. Nbd2 Na5 line with h2-h3 committed. Still a good enough try. }
12... Bc8 { I think this is the best continuation. The Bishop belongs to e6. }
13. Nf1 Be6
{ There's usually a dilemma what to do with the Knight on f1 - would it be better placed on e3 or g3? }
14. Ng3
{ After  14.Ne3  I didn't like  14...b4  . For a moment I thought maybe  15.Nc4  Nxc4  16.Bxc4  would be a bit better for White.   Then I saw  14...b4  15.Nc4  and Black can play  15...Nc6!?  and after  16.Ng5  Bd7  17.f4  exf4  18.Bxf4  h6  19.Nf3  Be6  the position would be totally unclear. }
14... Qc7
{ After  14...b4  we would react the same way:  15.Bxe6  fxe6  16.c3  bxc3  17.bxc3  . I think this is an improved version of what we are getting in the mainline as the Pawn on a6 might become the target in the future. }
15. Bxe6 { There was no point delaying this exchange any longer. } 15... fxe6
{ No matter the circumstances, this structure is almost always a bit unpleasant for Black, mostly because of his dark-squared Bishop. }
16. Be3
{ Trying to keep the tension for a bit more. If Black now comes back  16...Nc6  then after  17.c3  we will threaten Qd1-b3. }
16... Rfb8 17. axb5 axb5 18. Qe2
{ White is connecting the rooks anticipating Na5-c6. Immediate  18.c3  would be inaccurate as it would allow  18...c4!? }
18... Nc6 19. c3
{ White has a couple plans he can try. He can try to play d3-d4 or f2-f4 but they are usually connected with simplifications so we should be very careful with these. There also possible ideas on the kingside that might involve advancing the h pawn.   Exchanging the Knight on f6 is one more typical idea. White can achieve that through Nh2 @@StartBracket@@d2@@EndBracket@@ and Nh5 @@StartBracket@@g4@@EndBracket@@. The point is that once the black Knight is gone there is more space for our pieces, the Queen can go to g4, the h pawn is easier to advance and so on.   Overall Black is extremely solid so it will be difficult to make progress but if you were given a choice - which side would you take? }
*

