12. a5 { Especially with the Bishop on b7 preventing Nc6-a5 makes sense. }
12... Bc5 13. Qe2 Nd4
{ Otherwise it would be hard to justify Black's play - we could just play Bb3-c4 and Nd2-b3 with an advantage. }
14. Nxd4 Bxd4
{ Black has targeted e4 temporarily tying our Knight to defending it. } 15. Bc4
{ But now the Bishop comes with help. } 15... Qd6 16. Bd3
{ White wants to play  17.Nb3  after which he will have a nice edge. Notice that once e4 is defended, the Bishop on b7 does not really contribute to Black's position. It would be stronger on e6 from where it would control many important squares - d5, c4, f5 and g4. }
