5... Be7
{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6.Re1 is better than 6.d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6.d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 O-O
{ Black is hoping to get a famous Marshall Gambit with 8. c3 d5! @@StartBracket@@or not so famous Upgraded Gajewski Gambit with 8. c3 Na5!? :-@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@.   My little thing is probably not enough reason to abandon 8. c3 but Marshall definitely can be.   After  8.c3  d5!  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Rxe5  c6  - long story short - Black gets a sufficient compensation for the Pawn thanks to the strong Bishop pair and underdevelopment of White's pieces @@StartBracket@@look at the queenside@@EndBracket@@.   What used to be an exciting line has, at some point, become a large collection of long forced lines leading to one outcome only. Definitely not what we are looking for. }
8. a4
{ This is one of the most serious Anti-Marshall Systems out there. By our last move we have created a direct challenge for Black - should he develop the Bishop to b7 or push the Pawn to b4? }
8... b4
{ The main continuation. It makes a lot of sense as well as Black takes control over important c3 square. At the same time the light-squared Bishop is being kept on c8 so - depending on White's follow-up - it can go to b7, e6 and @@StartBracket@@in some cases@@EndBracket@@ g4.   Why doesn't everyone go for it all the time then? I think the main reason is that there are many possible lines White can choose from and the solutions to those lines aren't always that simple. }
9. d4
{ In 2020 most of the top players were keener to go for  9.a5  instead but it is understandable - everyone looks for some fresh territory where the theory is still not that developed. In that sense  9.a5  has caught up with the mainline which - without a doubt - is our choice. }
9... d6 10. dxe5 dxe5
{ This line is difficult for White and incredibly difficult for Black. It is caused by multiple possible move orders and lots of nuances which combined together make even the best players in the world stumble. }
11. Nbd2
{ We have almost symmetrical Pawn structure with small differences on the queenside. These differences however determine the plans for both sides. White has a beautiful square on c4.   It is a long lasting asset which he can use by placing on this square his Knight, Bishop and - in some cases - the Queen. There are also potential outposts on d5 and c5 but these two are quite tricky as Black controls them quite well.   Black queenside Pawns are potential targets and occasionally we might get a chance to open the c file with c2-c3. On the other hand Black controls d4, he will also activate his dark-squared Bishop on the next move. }
11... Bc5
{ Any other move would be a clear sign that our opponent doesn't have a clue about the line. For instance  11...Bg4?!  12.h3  Bxf3   or  12...Bh5  13.Nc4  and the Bishop is out of the real game  13.Nxf3  Qxd1  14.Rxd1  with a clear advantage for White. In general Black should be careful with swapping the light-squared Bishop as his light squares are weak enough. }
12. a5 Be6
{ Black is not afraid of damaging his own Pawn structure as he thinks that the activity, he will get on the f file, will fully compensate it. Indeed it looks very interesting at first sight!   This sharp continuation was first used by Rustam Kasimdzhanov in 2014 and for a while it seemed to be working well for Black. Only in 2017 Wesley So improved White in his game with Levon Aronian in London Chess Classic and although the Armenian quickly mixed up the lines and went astray, the post mortem analysis proved that indeed Black's position was not so nice after all. }
13. Bxe6 { We have to challenge Black's setup just like Wesley So did. } 13...
fxe6 14. Qe2
{ White is threatening 15. Qc4 but also with the simple developing 15. Nb3 which would guarantee us a great advantage. This forces Black to act quickly. }
14... Ng4 15. Rf1 Bxf2+
{ This was played by Aronian in the aforementioned game. White has to react precisely but he will get nicely rewarded for that. }
16. Rxf2 Nd4
{ This was Black's point. The Knight cannot be captured as the Rook would fall. Where should we move our Queen then? }
17. Qd3
{ This is where So stumbled. He went  17.Qc4?  and after  17...Nxf2  18.Kxf2  Qh4+   18...Qg5  would be even stronger - notice the White Queen does not control e3!  19.Kg1  Qg4!  Black's initiative was strong enough to keep the game balanced.  White's problem was that  20.Nxd4  wouldn't have worked because of  20...Qd1+  21.Nf1  exd4  22.b3  @@StartBracket@@hoping for 23. Bb2 on the next move@@EndBracket@@  22...d3!  23.Qxd3  Rad8  24.Qc4  @@StartBracket@@all this was forced@@EndBracket@@  24...Rxf1+!  25.Qxf1  Qd4+  @@StartBracket@@double attack@@EndBracket@@  26.Be3  Qxe3+  27.Kh1  Rd6  and Black is slightly better. Our choice works because the Queen can control both e3 and d1, it is also protecting the Knight on f3. }
17... Nxf2 18. Kxf2
{ Both  18...Qh4+  and  18...Qg5  can be calmly answered with  19.Kg1  . Otherwise  19.c3  will put an end to Black's initiative leaving him in a critical condition. }
*

