11. Nbd2
{ We have almost symmetrical Pawn structure with small differences on the queenside. These differences however determine the plans for both sides. White has a beautiful square on c4.   It is a long lasting asset which he can use by placing on this square his Knight, Bishop and - in some cases - the Queen. There are also potential outposts on d5 and c5 but these two are quite tricky as Black controls them quite well.   Black queenside Pawns are potential targets and occasionally we might get a chance to open the c file with c2-c3. On the other hand Black controls d4, he will also activate his dark-squared Bishop on the next move. }
11... Bc5
{ Any other move would be a clear sign that our opponent doesn't have a clue about the line. For instance  11...Bg4?!  12.h3  Bxf3   or  12...Bh5  13.Nc4  and the Bishop is out of the real game  13.Nxf3  Qxd1  14.Rxd1  with a clear advantage for White. In general Black should be careful with swapping the light-squared Bishop as his light squares are weak enough. }
12. a5 Qe7 { This is already inaccurate as it allows an unexpected trick. } 13.
Bd5
{ White takes advantage of the pin on h1-a8 diagonal and the x-ray on the e file - especially the latter one was well hidden.   If Black now takes the Bishop  13...Nxd5  then after  14.exd5  Nd4  White just wins the Pawn with  15.Nxe5  . Already a couple of strong grandmaster have fallen into this little trap. Black is not lost or anything like that but White has very good chances for advantage here. }
13... Bb7 14. Nb3 { Again Black can not take the Bishop. } 14... Ba7
{ The Bishop wasn't feeling very comfortable on c5 anymore being attacked by the Knight. }
15. Bc4
{ The Bishop has done its duty and now it can safely retreat. White has a couple of plans here. He can try to put the Knight on f5. He can put the Queen on e2 and then the Bishop on e3 - swapping the dark-squared Bishops works in our favour as we would love to have our Knight on c5.   In some cases it is also possible to put the Bishop on g5 but we should always watch out for h7-h6 and g7-g5 followed by Nf6-h5.   What we are going to choose will depend on our opponent's moves for instance after  15...h6  16.Nh4!  is strong, threatening not only 17. Nf5 but 17. Ng6 as well.   After  15...Rfe8  on the other hand  16.Nh4  will no longer be effective - Black has  16...Nd4!  17.Nxd4  exd4!?  with good prospects. Therefore simple 16. h3 is preferable. }
