14. Bc4
{ The best try in my opinion. Once again - the Knight is coming to b3. } 14...
Bg4 15. Nb3
{ I was also considering  15.h3  Nd4  16.Qd1  however, after  16...Bh5  17.g4  Bg6  18.Nxd4  Bxd4  Black's position was quite comfortable as he bring can his Rook to d6 @@StartBracket@@typical plan@@EndBracket@@ and try to exploit the weakened position of our King. }
15... Nd4 { I don't think Black has any reasonable alternatives to this one. }
16. Nbxd4 Bxd4 17. h3 { We have tolerated it for long enough. } 17... Bxf3
{ 17...Bh5?  is now a bad idea -  18.g4  Bg6  19.Nxd4  exd4  20.e5  followed by f4 would give White a great advantage. }
18. Qxf3
{ I actually believe that White is just better here. Sure, the engines can defend Black but all his moves are just so difficult that I can't imagine a normal player even a grandmaster, doing well with Black here. Why do I have such a strong conviction about White's position?   1. We have the Bishop pair which is nice.   2. The Bishop on c4 is extremely strong, targeting both a6 and f7 and it is going to remotely impossible for Black to deprive it of its activity.   3. It is very difficult for Black to make good moves - he doesn't have a clear plan and most of the time he is forced to anticipate White's threats.   4. In contrast to Black, we do have a plan here, actually even more than one:   a@@EndBracket@@ we can try to swap the dark-squared Bishops leaving Black with the Knight - clearly inferior to our light-squared Bishop;   b@@EndBracket@@ we can try c2-c3 opening an additional file, the Bishops like open positions so they are going to benefit for it;   c@@EndBracket@@ in some cases we can try the Pawn advance on the Kingside - g2-g4, h3-h4 and g4-g5. }
