13. Qe2
{ Almost everyone goes  13.h3  here basically playing against  13...Qe7  as  14.Bd5  is still there. But first able -  14.Bd5  is not so strong anymore and secondly - we are not afraid of  13...Qe7  , we actually welcome it! }
13... Qd6
{ Ironically this still looks like the best choice for Black. At least it would be my choice. }
14. h3
{ The immediate  14.Nc4  is not as strong - it only gives Black more options. }
14... Rd8
{ This is quite a good line for Black but luckily for us - only correspondence players seem to be attracted to it. The point is that after  15.Nc4  Qe7  16.Be3  he can now develop the Bishop to b7 instead of normal e6. }
15. Bc4
{ I thought it's a nice try to confuse Black. As I mentioned in the beginning it is very hard for Black to handle this position and it's precisely what we are counting on.   The idea itself is the same as described earlier - we want to place the Knight on b3. Now the question is: how should Black respond? }
15... Nd4
{ This move looks natural but it doesn't fully solve Black's problems. } 16.
Nxd4 Bxd4 17. Nf3
{ Once the f3 square has become vacant we change our plans. The Knight is stronger here as it cannot be attacked by the black Bishop.   After  17.Nb3  Be6!  we would be forced to swap the Bishop as we could not tolerate Be6xb3 damaging our Pawn structure. }
17... Be6 18. Bd3
{ I wouldn't say that White is better here but it's certainly easier to handle this with White, so yeah maybe White is a bit better after all. :-@@EndBracket@@ }
18... Bc5
{ The active  18...c5  would run into  19.Nxd4  cxd4  20.f4!  and suddenly White is having good prospects on the Kingside. }
19. Rd1
{ Despite the innocent look of this position it is very dangerous for Black. We want to play 20. b3 and 21. Bb2 Black's position will deteriorate quickly if there is a lackluster reaction from the first player. }
19... Nd7
{ 20.b3  will be now answered with  20...Qc6!  and after  21.Bb2  Bd6  Black will be on the on the path to equality. }
20. Be3
{ Change of plans - we now want to take advantage of the Black Knight's position and double on the d-file. }
20... Bxe3 21. Qxe3 Qc6 { Black's Queen walks away from the x-ray. } 22. Rd2
{ Executing our plan. } 22... f6 { Black is preparing Qc6-c5. } 23. Rad1 Qc5
24. Be2
{ There's a new problem he has to solve. The Knight is pinned so the King has to come to help. We don't mind damaging our Pawn structure, as you will see it is only temporary. }
24... Qxe3
{ 24...Qxa5?  would be a really bad idea. After  25.Nh4!  followed by 26. Bg4 it would be virtually impossible for Black to solve the Knight problem. }
25. fxe3 Kf8 26. Nh4
{ White maintains the initiative as Black has to tackle with a pin, White's activity on the light-squares and in - the long run - the weak a6-pawn. }
