{ Ironically this still looks like the best choice for Black. At least it would be my choice. }
14. h3
{ The immediate  14.Nc4  is not as strong - it only gives Black more options. }
14... Rd8
{ This is quite a good line for Black but luckily for us - only correspondence players seem to be attracted to it. The point is that after  15.Nc4  Qe7  16.Be3  he can now develop the Bishop to b7 instead of normal e6. }
15. Bc4
{ I thought it's a nice try to confuse Black. As I mentioned in the beginning it is very hard for Black to handle this position and it's precisely what we are counting on.   The idea itself is the same as described earlier - we want to place the Knight on b3. Now the question is: how should Black respond? }
15... Be6
{ It looks like Black has just blundered a Pawn! However this is not that simple. After  16.Bxa6  Ra7!  White has no way of saving his own Pawn on  a5  and therefore the balance will be restored quickly.  It takes some imagination though, to even consider such a move @@StartBracket@@or buying my course@@EndBracket@@. }
16. Nb3
{ The best try. We've managed to achieve our setup now the big question is - how should Black react? }
16... Nd4 { This is decent but I believe White can still enjoy some pressure. }
17. Nbxd4 Bxc4
{ Please note that after  17...Bxd4  18.Bd3  we would transpose back to 15...Nd4 which was nice for White. }
18. Qxc4 Bxd4
{ Black still has his usual weaknesses but he is catching up with the activity. Everything thanks to his strong Bishop. }
19. Ra4
{ How should he protect the Pawn now?  19...Rab8?!  will be answered with  20.Nxd4!  and he has to recapture with the Queen leaving the Pawn on a6 unprotected  20...exd4  21.e5  .   19...Rdb8  would be a better choice but it is still not good enough! After  20.Nxd4  Qxd4  21.Qc6!  Qd6  22.Qxd6  cxd6  23.Bd2  b3  24.c3  White will bring his King to the center and then it might be unpleasant for the black Pawn on b3. }
19... Qc5
{ He should not protect it at all! At the moment our own Pawn on f2 is hanging so we have to swap the Queens. }
20. Qxc5 Bxc5 21. Bd2 { But not  21.Nxe5?  Nxe4!  and Black is even better. }
21... Rab8 22. c3
{ Black should be able to equalize here however it is still a bit easier to play with White as e5 is weak. We will take on b4 if he allows us and otherwise after  22...bxc3  23.Bxc3  let him worry about the Pawn on e5 while we can also think about Ra4-c4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Anti-Marshall (8...b4 / 10...dxe5)"]
[Black "Anti-Marshall 11...Bc5 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Be7
{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6.Re1 is better than 6.d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6.d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 O-O
{ Black is hoping to get a famous Marshall Gambit with 8. c3 d5! @@StartBracket@@or not so famous Upgraded Gajewski Gambit with 8. c3 Na5!? :-@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@.   My little thing is probably not enough reason to abandon 8. c3 but Marshall definitely can be.   After  8.c3  d5!  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Rxe5  c6  - long story short - Black gets a sufficient compensation for the Pawn thanks to the strong Bishop pair and underdevelopment of White's pieces @@StartBracket@@look at the queenside@@EndBracket@@.   What used to be an exciting line has, at some point, become a large collection of long forced lines leading to one outcome only. Definitely not what we are looking for. }
8. a4
{ This is one of the most serious Anti-Marshall Systems out there. By our last move we have created a direct challenge for Black - should he develop the Bishop to b7 or push the Pawn to b4? }
8... b4
{ The main continuation. It makes a lot of sense as well as Black takes control over important c3 square. At the same time the light-squared Bishop is being kept on c8 so - depending on White's follow-up - it can go to b7, e6 and @@StartBracket@@in some cases@@EndBracket@@ g4.   Why doesn't everyone go for it all the time then? I think the main reason is that there are many possible lines White can choose from and the solutions to those lines aren't always that simple. }
9. d4
{ In 2020 most of the top players were keener to go for  9.a5  instead but it is understandable - everyone looks for some fresh territory where the theory is still not that developed. In that sense  9.a5  has caught up with the mainline which - without a doubt - is our choice. }
9... d6 10. dxe5 dxe5
{ This line is difficult for White and incredibly difficult for Black. It is caused by multiple possible move orders and lots of nuances which combined together make even the best players in the world stumble. }
11. Nbd2
{ We have almost symmetrical Pawn structure with small differences on the queenside. These differences however determine the plans for both sides. White has a beautiful square on c4.   It is a long lasting asset which he can use by placing on this square his Knight, Bishop and - in some cases - the Queen. There are also potential outposts on d5 and c5 but these two are quite tricky as Black controls them quite well.   Black queenside Pawns are potential targets and occasionally we might get a chance to open the c file with c2-c3. On the other hand Black controls d4, he will also activate his dark-squared Bishop on the next move. }
11... Bc5
{ Any other move would be a clear sign that our opponent doesn't have a clue about the line. For instance  11...Bg4?!  12.h3  Bxf3   or  12...Bh5  13.Nc4  and the Bishop is out of the real game  13.Nxf3  Qxd1  14.Rxd1  with a clear advantage for White. In general Black should be careful with swapping the light-squared Bishop as his light squares are weak enough. }
12. a5 h6
{ This is what the majority of the players do. Black is waiting for White to put the Queen on e2 if we do that he will then be able to put his own Queen on e7 as Bb3-d5 will no longer work. We are going to try to undermine that logic. }
13. Qe2
{ Almost everyone goes  13.h3  here basically playing against  13...Qe7  as  14.Bd5  is still there. But first able -  14.Bd5  is not so strong anymore and secondly - we are not afraid of  13...Qe7  , we actually welcome it! }
13... Qd6
{ Ironically this still looks like the best choice for Black. At least it would be my choice. }
14. h3
{ The immediate  14.Nc4  is not as strong - it only gives Black more options. }
14... Rd8
{ This is quite a good line for Black but luckily for us - only correspondence players seem to be attracted to it. The point is that after  15.Nc4  Qe7  16.Be3  he can now develop the Bishop to b7 instead of normal e6. }
15. Bc4
{ I thought it's a nice try to confuse Black. As I mentioned in the beginning it is very hard for Black to handle this position and it's precisely what we are counting on.   The idea itself is the same as described earlier - we want to place the Knight on b3. Now the question is: how should Black respond? }
15... Be6
{ It looks like Black has just blundered a Pawn! However this is not that simple. After  16.Bxa6  Ra7!  White has no way of saving his own Pawn on  a5  and therefore the balance will be restored quickly.  It takes some imagination though, to even consider such a move @@StartBracket@@or buying my course@@EndBracket@@. }
16. Nb3
{ The best try. We've managed to achieve our setup now the big question is - how should Black react? }
16... Bd4 { Ok if Black can play like that then there is nothing we can do. }
17. Nfxd4 { It is the right moment to give up. } 17... Nxd4 18. Nxd4 Bxc4
{ One last nuance. After  18...exd4?  19.Bd3  White would get a nice advantage on the Kingside with the possible advance of the f Pawn. }
19. Qxc4 Qxd4 20. Qc6
{ White could go  20.Qe2  if wanted to continue but the position would remain equal. }
20... Qd6 21. Qc4 { It is a fair end. } *

