13... Qd6
{ Ironically this still looks like the best choice for Black. At least it would be my choice. }
14. h3
{ The immediate  14.Nc4  is not as strong - it only gives Black more options. }
14... Nh5
{ This was played by Peter Svidler in his game against Sergey Karjakin in Fide Grand Prix in Baku 2014. The black Knight wants to take advantage of the dark squres - f4 and possibly g3. }
15. Nf1
{ This is stronger than  15.Nc4  played by Karjakin. The point is that now we are threatening 16. Bd5. }
15... Rb8 { Anticipating our threat. } 16. Rd1
{ The Rook is taking the control over the d file. Now Black must decide where to move his Queen. }
16... Qg6
{ Now Black is threatening  16...Bxh3  so we should remove our King from the g file. }
17. Kh1 Nf4
{ Attacking the Queen and threatening with mate so really no room for a choice here. }
18. Bxf4 exf4 19. Rd5 { This is a very nice way of activating the Rook. } 19...
Bd6
{ Keeping the Bishop on the g1-a7 diagonal would do no good for Black.   After  19...Ba7  20.Rad1  he could not play  20...Be6  because of  21.Qxa6! }
20. N1d2 { The Knight is heading to c4. } 20... Be6
{ Black is trying to disrupt our plan. } 21. Qxa6
{ The exchange sacrifice was part of our plan all along. } 21... Bxd5 22. Bxd5
Ne7 23. Bb3
{ White has only a Pawn for an exchange but what a Pawn that is! Additionally our pieces are far superior to our opponent's. }
23... Qf6 { The Queen is stopping e4-e5 as well as attacking b2. } 24. Ra2
{ We can come back with the Queen to e2 and then try advancing our Pawn to a6. Once this is done the Rook might join the game with Ra2-a5. }
