15... Rb8 { Anticipating our threat. } 16. Rd1
{ The Rook is taking the control over the d file. Now Black must decide where to move his Queen. }
16... Qf6 { This is softer but also safer than  16...Qg6  . } 17. Rd5
{ Once again we are trying the same idea only this time it's not going to be as effective. }
17... Ba7
{ After  17...Bd6  White can play  18.Bc4  targeting the Pawn on a6. After the text move 18. Bc4 is not dangerous - whenever White takes on a6 Black has Nc6-d4! and the Queen attacks the Bishop as well. }
18. Ba4 { We are going for the e5 Pawn instead! } 18... Bb7
{ Black sacrifices the Pawn in order to activate the Bishop. } 19. Bxc6 Bxc6
20. Rxe5 Rb5
{ This is much stronger than  20...Bb5  21.Qe1  as the White Rook was much more active. }
21. Rxb5 Bxb5 22. Qe1
{ We are threatening 23. Qxb4 but we also want to play e4-e5 and Bc1-e3. The position is far from clear but it is always nice to be a Pawn up. }
