8. a4
{ This is one of the most serious Anti-Marshall Systems out there. By our last move we have created a direct challenge for Black - should he develop the Bishop to b7 or push the Pawn to b4? }
8... b4
{ The main continuation. It makes a lot of sense as well as Black takes control over important c3 square. At the same time the light-squared Bishop is being kept on c8 so - depending on White's follow-up - it can go to b7, e6 and @@StartBracket@@in some cases@@EndBracket@@ g4.   Why doesn't everyone go for it all the time then? I think the main reason is that there are many possible lines White can choose from and the solutions to those lines aren't always that simple. }
9. d4
{ In 2020 most of the top players were keener to go for  9.a5  instead but it is understandable - everyone looks for some fresh territory where the theory is still not that developed. In that sense  9.a5  has caught up with the mainline in popularity - our choice is. }
9... Nxd4
{ This is just a blunder, the idea might be playable in some other lines but not here. }
10. Bxf7+ { The simple  10.Nxd4  exd4  11.e5  would be also nice. } 10... Rxf7
11. Nxe5 { The usual point - both the Rook and the Knight are under attack. }
11... Rf8
{ Giving up an exchange wouldn't work - after  11...Ne6  12.Nxf7  Kxf7  13.e5  would be winning for White. 11...Nc6 would be met in the same way and with the same effect. }
12. Qxd4 { Black is a Pawn down with no compensation. } 12... Bb7 13. Nd2 d5
{ Opening up the position is Black's only chance - he has a pair of Bishops after all. }
14. exd5 Qxd5 15. Qxd5+ Nxd5 16. Nb3
{ It is not yet hopeless for Black but nevertheless White is clearly better here. We will continue with Bc1-d2 and Ne5 to d3 or c4. Both our Knights have very nice perspectives on the queenside. }
