9. d4
{ In 2020 most of the top players were keener to go for  9.a5  instead but it is understandable - everyone looks for some fresh territory where the theory is still not that developed. In that sense  9.a5  has caught up with the mainline which - without a doubt - our choice is. }
9... d6 10. dxe5
{ The strategic explanation of White's last move is that - while the pawn structure on the kingside might become symmetrical - it will slightly differ on the queenside to our favour. Black queenside Pawns are potential targets, White has a better light-squared Bishop and one day we might try opening up the c file. }
10... Nxe5
{ This move became fashionable once Black realized that after  10...dxe5  it was very easy to mix up the lines which on many occasions led to Black's severe opening problems.   Recapturing with the Knight is also quite sound - after 10...dxe5 it's the Knight on c6 has always been sort of the problem for Black. What is the downside then? We don't have to take on e5! }
11. Bf4
{ I was surprised to see this natural move on the periphery of opening theory. I am pretty sure that the top players have it covered @@StartBracket@@whether they remember it is a different story@@EndBracket@@ but I am also quite sure that the majority of the rest of us - don't :-@@EndBracket@@ .   11.Nbd2  is also interesting, however once you get through Nepomniachtchi - So from the Jerusalem Grand Prix 2019 @@StartBracket@@a fine example of how serious preparation should look like@@EndBracket@@, it is not easy to come up with something fresh. I am going to consider three possible continuations for Black:  11...Nfd7  ,  11...Nxf3+  and  11...Ng6  .   The fourth possibility  11...Bb7  will transpose to one of the above after  11.Nbd2  Nxf3+  12.Qxf3  or if 11...Ng6 White can play 12. Bg3 . }
11... Nfd7
{ This is solid but at the same time White gets a pleasant position for free. }
12. Bxe5 { 12.Nxe5  gives Black an extra option:  12....dxe5  . } 12... Nxe5
{ 12...dxe5  would now be simply answered with  13.Nbd2  with small but long-lasting advantage. }
13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. Nd2
{ Black's main problem lies in a combination of the dark-squared Bishop and the Pawns on b4, c7 and e5. White has a strong Bishop while the Knight will occupy one of the nice outposts on c4 @@StartBracket@@possibly e3@@EndBracket@@ or f3. }
