11... Nxf3+ { This move is not very popular but actually it's quite strong. }
12. Qxf3 Bb7
{ Natural but at the same time after  13.Nd2  it feels like White is just better. }
13. Nd2 Nd7 14. Qh5
{ White is improving the position of the Queen while setting a small trap at the same time. }
14... Nc5
{ It is a perfectly natural move but at the same time Black is moving his Knight away from the King right after we put our Queen near to it. }
15. Re3 { The not-so-hidden point of White's previous move. } 15... Nxb3
{ There really wasn’t any good alternative as after  15...Bc8  covering  h3  White could simply play  16.Bd5  . }
16. Rh3 h6
{ 17.Bxh6??  is no good now as Black can simply reply with  17...g6!  and White is already lost! So what was it all about? }
17. Rxb3
{ Simple as that. Now that Pawn is hanging and Black has no time to defend it! }
17... Bf6
{ 17...a5?  would be answered with  18.Bxh6!  and after  18...gxh6  19.Qxh6  the Rook is coming to g3 winning the game. }
18. Rxb4
{ White is a Pawn up but converting it won't be easy as with a Bishop pair Black has some reasonable hopes for simplification. Let's put the Rook on e1 while the slightly odd looking one on b4 should come back to the third rank from where it can comfortably operate. }
