11... Ng6
{ This is the most popular continuation but I am not sure it's the best practical choice for Black. }
12. Bg3
{ Not a perfect square for the Bishop but it does control some important squares in the center. }
12... Bb7 { Putting the Bishop on b7 is part of Black's setup. } 13. Nbd2 Nh5
{ Black wants to eliminate White's Bishop. Apparently it is a good excuse because so far almost everyone including some really strong players chose this objectively not the strongest move. }
14. Nc4 Nxg3 15. hxg3
{ White pieces are clearly superior - Both Knights and the Bishop are very strong. At the moment we are threatening with Nc4-a5. }
15... a5 { Black might have anticipated one plan but we have another... } 16.
e5
{ Taking advantage of the activity of our Pieces we are trying to open up the position. The normal 'Bishop pair is stronger in open positions' rule does not apply here - no need to explain this just look at those Bishops! }
16... d5 { This is relatively the best but by no means enough for equality. }
17. Ne3 { Black has to defend his central Pawn. } 17... c6 18. c4
{ With this strong move White solves the problem of a passive light-squared Bishop. }
18... bxc3 19. bxc3
{ White should now transfer the Knight from e3 to d4 while the Bishop can come to c2. We should always keep e5-e6 possibility on the radar. }
*

