5... Be7
{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6.Re1 is better than 6.d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6.d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 O-O
{ Black is hoping to get a famous Marshall Gambit with 8. c3 d5! @@StartBracket@@or not so famous Upgraded Gajewski Gambit with 8. c3 Na5!? :-@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@.   My little thing is probably not enough reason to abandon 8. c3 but Marshall definitely can be.   After  8.c3  d5!  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Rxe5  c6  - long story short - Black gets a sufficient compensation for the Pawn thanks to the strong Bishop pair and underdevelopment of White's pieces @@StartBracket@@look at the queenside@@EndBracket@@.   What used to be an exciting line has, at some point, become a large collection of long forced lines leading to one outcome only. Definitely not what we are looking for. }
8. a4
{ This is one of the most serious Anti-Marshall Systems out there. By our last move we have created a direct challenge for Black - should he develop the Bishop to b7 or push the Pawn to b4? }
8... b4
{ The main continuation. It makes a lot of sense as well as Black takes control over important c3 square. At the same time the light-squared Bishop is being kept on c8 so - depending on White's follow-up - it can go to b7, e6 and @@StartBracket@@in some cases@@EndBracket@@ g4.   Why doesn't everyone go for it all the time then? I think the main reason is that there are many possible lines White can choose from and the solutions to those lines aren't always that simple. }
9. d4
{ In 2020 most of the top players were keener to go for  9.a5  instead but it is understandable - everyone looks for some fresh territory where the theory is still not that developed. In that sense  9.a5  has caught up with the mainline which - without a doubt - our choice is. }
9... d6 10. dxe5
{ The strategic explanation of White's last move is that - while the pawn structure on the kingside might become symmetrical - it will slightly differ on the queenside to our favour. Black queenside Pawns are potential targets, White has a better light-squared Bishop and one day we might try opening up the c file. }
10... Nxe5
{ This move became fashionable once Black realized that after  10...dxe5  it was very easy to mix up the lines which on many occasions led to Black's severe opening problems.   Recapturing with the Knight is also quite sound - after 10...dxe5 it's the Knight on c6 has always been sort of the problem for Black. What is the downside then? We don't have to take on e5! }
11. Bf4
{ I was surprised to see this natural move on the periphery of the opening theory. I am pretty sure that the top players have it covered @@StartBracket@@whether they remember it is a different story@@EndBracket@@ but I am also quite sure that the majority of the rest of us - don't :-@@EndBracket@@ .   11.Nbd2  is also interesting, however once you get through Nepomniachtchi - So from the Jerusalem Grand Prix 2019 @@StartBracket@@a fine example of how serious preparation should look like@@EndBracket@@, it is not easy to come up with something fresh. I am going to consider three possible continuations for Black:  11...Nfd7  ,  11...Nxf3+  and  11...Ng6  .   The fourth possibility  11...Bb7  will transpose to one of the above after  11.Nbd2  Nxf3+  12.Qxf3  or if 11...Ng6 White can play 12. Bg3 . }
11... Ng6
{ This is the most popular continuation but I am not sure it's the best practical choice for Black. }
12. Bg3
{ Not a perfect square for the Bishop but it does control some important squares in the center. }
12... Bb7 { Putting the Bishop on b7 is part of Black's setup. } 13. Nbd2 Nh5
{ Black wants to eliminate White's Bishop. Apparently it is a good excuse because so far almost everyone including some really strong players chose this objectively not the strongest move. }
14. Nc4 Nxg3 15. hxg3
{ White pieces are clearly superior - Both Knights and the Bishop are very strong. At the moment we are threatening with Nc4-a5. }
15... a5 { Black might have anticipated one plan but we have another... } 16.
e5
{ Taking the advantage of the activity of our Pieces we are are trying to open up the position. The normal 'Bishop pair is stronger in open positions' rule does not apply here - no need to explain this just look at those Bishops! }
16... Bxf3
{ There are 3 games in the database in this position and in all three  17.Qxf3  was played. We will not follow those games. }
17. gxf3
{ White is not afraid of the endgame - as long as the Rooks are on board there are good winning chances. Our new Pawn structure on the kingside has a much bigger potential than the previous one as we can easily play f3-f4 and the King is safer too. }
17... Nxe5 18. Nxe5 dxe5 19. Rxe5 Bd6
{ This is much stronger than  19...Qxd1+  20.Rxd1  with a clear edge. } 20. Rd5
Qf6 { Now the Pawn is attacked. } 21. Qd4
{ I was considering something like  21.Kg2!?  Qxb2  22.Qh1  but although White's compensation was nice it wasn't easy to make progress. }
21... Qxd4 22. Rxd4 Rfd8 23. Rad1
{ Black's main problem is that he can't really move the Bishop without allowing White rook to occupy d7. At the same time White can slowly advance - move the Rook from d1 to d3, put the Bishop on c4 and play b2-b3 etc... }
*

