11. Bf4
{ I was surprised to see this natural move on the periphery of the opening theory. I am pretty sure that the top players have it covered @@StartBracket@@whether they remember it is a different story@@EndBracket@@ but I am also quite sure that the majority of the rest of us - don't :-@@EndBracket@@ .   11.Nbd2  is also interesting, however once you get through Nepomniachtchi - So from the Jerusalem Grand Prix 2019 @@StartBracket@@a fine example of how serious preparation should look like@@EndBracket@@, it is not easy to come up with something fresh. I am going to consider three possible continuations for Black:  11...Nfd7  ,  11...Nxf3+  and  11...Ng6  .   The fourth possibility  11...Bb7  will transpose to one of the above after  11.Nbd2  Nxf3+  12.Qxf3  or if 11...Ng6 White can play 12. Bg3 . }
11... Ng6
{ This is the most popular continuation but I am not sure it's the best practical choice for Black. }
12. Bg3
{ Not a perfect square for the Bishop but it does control some important squares in the center. }
12... Bb7 { Putting the Bishop on b7 is part of Black's setup. } 13. Nbd2 Nd7
{ This is stronger than  13...Nh5  . The Knight is coming to c5. } 14. Nc4
{ The white Knight takes the central square. We now threaten both 15. Na4 and 15. e5. }
14... a5 { This natural move prevents 15. Na5 but it doesn't stop 15. e5! } 15.
e5 dxe5 { Simplifying the game is not going to solve Black's problems. } 16.
Nfxe5 Ndxe5 17. Bxe5
{ This is stronger than the natural  17.Nxe5  Nxe5  18.Bxe5  where after  18...Bd6  Black manages to neutralize most of White's initiative. }
17... Qe8
{ Black is trying to grab a counterplay on the long diagonal. I should mention that  17...Nxe5  18.Nxe5  would give White a big advantage. Black has a huge problem with the Pawn on f7. }
18. Bg3 Qc6 19. Ne3 { White is threatening  19...--  20.Bd5  . } 19... Rad8 20.
Qe2
{ This is much stronger than the active  20.Qh5?!  where after  20...Bc5  Black's counterplay is becoming quite serious. }
20... Bf6
{ 20...Bc5  wouldn't have much sense now as after  20.Rad1  Bxe3  White would simply recapture with the Pawn  21.fxe3  using the fact that the Queen protects the Pawn on g2. }
21. Rad1
{ White's advantage is based on the activity of the pieces so we have to maintain this activity. Even at the cost of the Pawn. }
21... Bxb2 22. Rxd8 Rxd8 23. Rd1
{ Once the Rooks are gone our Queen will be free to torment Black. Notice that all critical squares in our camp are covered and the same thing can not be said about Black - he has to watch out for his Pawns on a5, c7 and f7. The back rank might also become a problem. }
23... Rxd1+ 24. Qxd1 Bf6 { The Bishop takes the d8 square under control. } 25.
Qg4
{ White has very nice compensation for the Pawn. We want to play  25...--  26.Qf5  or  26.Qc4  but even a quiet move like  26.h3  can be unpleasant for Black who doesn't really have any active moves. }
