{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 O-O
{ Black is hoping to get a famous Marshall Gambit with 8. c3 d5! @@StartBracket@@or not so famous Upgraded Gajewski Gambit with 8. c3 Na5!? :-@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@.   My little thing is probably not enough reason to abandon 8. c3 but Marshall definitely can be.   After  8.c3  d5!  9.exd5  Nxd5  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Rxe5  c6  - long story short - Black gets a sufficient compensation for the Pawn thanks to the strong Bishop pair and underdevelopment of White's pieces @@StartBracket@@look at the queenside@@EndBracket@@.   What used to be an exciting line has, at some point, become a large collection of long forced lines leading to one outcome only. Definitely not what we are looking for. }
8. a4
{ This is one of the most serious Anti-Marshall Systems out there. By our last move we have created a direct challenge for Black - should he develop the Bishop to b7 or push the Pawn to b4? }
8... b4
{ The main continuation. It makes a lot of sense as well as Black takes control over important c3 square. At the same time the light-squared Bishop is being kept on c8 so - depending on White's follow-up - it can go to b7, e6 and @@StartBracket@@in some cases@@EndBracket@@ g4.   Why doesn't everyone go for it all the time then? I think the main reason is that there are many possible lines White can choose from and the solutions to those lines aren't always that simple. }
9. d4
{ In 2020 most of the top players were keener to go for  9.a5  instead but it is understandable - everyone looks for some fresh territory where the theory is still not that developed. In that sense  9.a5  has caught up with the mainline which - without a doubt - our choice is. }
9... d6 10. dxe5
{ The strategic explanation of White's last move is that - while the pawn structure on the kingside might become symmetrical - it will slightly differ on the queenside to our favour. Black queenside Pawns are potential targets, White has a better light-squared Bishop and one day we might try opening up the c file. }
10... Nxe5
{ This move became fashionable once Black realized that after  10...dxe5  it was very easy to mix up the lines which on many occasions led to Black's severe opening problems.   Recapturing with the Knight is also quite sound - after 10...dxe5 it's the Knight on c6 has always been sort of the problem for Black. What is the downside then? We don't have to take on e5! }
11. Bf4
{ I was surprised to see this natural move on the periphery of the opening theory. I am pretty sure that the top players have it covered @@StartBracket@@whether they remember it is a different story@@EndBracket@@ but I am also quite sure that the majority of the rest of us - don't :-@@EndBracket@@ .   11.Nbd2  is also interesting, however once you get through Nepomniachtchi - So from the Jerusalem Grand Prix 2019 @@StartBracket@@a fine example of how serious preparation should look like@@EndBracket@@, it is not easy to come up with something fresh. I am going to consider three possible continuations for Black:  11...Nfd7  ,  11...Nxf3+  and  11...Ng6  .   The fourth possibility  11...Bb7  will transpose to one of the above after  11.Nbd2  Nxf3+  12.Qxf3  or if 11...Ng6 White can play 12. Bg3 . }
11... Ng6
{ This is the most popular continuation but I am not sure it's the best practical choice for Black. }
12. Bg3
{ Not a perfect square for the Bishop but it does control some important squares in the center. }
12... Bb7 { Putting the Bishop on b7 is part of Black's setup. } 13. Nbd2 Nd7
{ This is stronger than  13...Nh5  . The Knight is coming to c5. } 14. Nc4
{ White Knight takes the central square. We know threaten with both 15. Na4 and 15. e5. }
14... Nc5
{ Black activates the Knight and more importantly - attacks the White Bishop. Why this is critical for Black we will find out very soon. }
15. e5 { The Pawn was hanging so there was no time for  15.Na5 } 15... Nxb3
{ This swap will make perfect sense once you see the follow-up } 16. cxb3 f5
{ This is a great counterattack! Suddenly the White Bishop is in trouble so we have to act. }
17. exd6
{ I was also considering  17.exf6  but after  17...Bxf6  18.Na5  Bxf3!  19.Qxf3  Bxb2  20.Qd5  Kh8  21.Nc6  Qf6  White's compensation allows them to maintain the balance but nothing more. }
17... cxd6 18. Bxd6
{ Our ambitions should already be limited here as Black can achieve a draw fairly easily. }
18... Bxd6 19. Qxd6 Bxf3
{ The Bishop was nice but ruining White's Pawn structure is nicer. } 20. gxf3
Qxd6
{ Black could go  20...Qg5+  instead, though after  21.Qg3  Qh5  22.Ne5=  White takes no risk. }
21. Nxd6 Nh4
{ Black wins the Pawn back and has a slightly better Pawn structure but the active position of our Knight will prevent him from thinking about anything more than a draw. }
22. Red1
{ Removing the Rook so it could protect the Knight and cover some squares on the d file restraining the Black's Knight. }
22... Nxf3+ 23. Kg2 Nh4+ 24. Kf1
{ We can double on the d file or develop the remaining Rook to c1. Objectively both sides have nothing to worry about and neither of them should be getting ambitious as it could easily backfire. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. Gajewski Gambit"]
[Black "Gajewski Gambit  10...d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Be7
{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6.Re1 is better than 6.d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6.d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 d6
{ A general rule is that if Black doesn't want to go for the Marshall Gambit, he should play 7...d6 before castling as it avoids some Anti-Marshall lines, mainly  8.a4  where Black can now simply go  8...Bd7  . }
8. c3
{ White is preparing d2-d4 but also securing his light-squared Bishop against  8...Na5  - we can now go  9.Bc2  . }
8... O-O 9. h3
{ Before advancing the d-pawn it is useful to cover the g4-square. The immediate  9.d4  allows  9...Bg4  leading to interesting play but - once again speaking in concepts - it would be a small victory for Black. }
9... Na5 10. Bc2
{ The Knight chases away the Bishop to a less active square while making c7-c5 possible.   Black's intention is to challenge White's Pawn center but the current theoretical status is that Black has to release the tension in the center very early, or allow White to close the position with d4-d5, giving White the more comfortable position in either case.  The Chigorin Defense is, in my opinion, slightly outdated in a sense that it is not a bad line but there are better ones. }
10... d5
{ The time has come to deal with my own 'child'. It was fun for a while but as the theory developed and the common knowledge became deeper and deeper the line has simply lost its attractiveness. }
11. exd5
{ 11.d4  is perhaps even more challenging but at the same time it is more complicated and gives Black more opportunities to surprise us. }
11... e4
{ The cornerstone of the line - Black is willing to sacrifice the Pawn in return for our light-squared Bishop. This will guarantee him some compensation but - as we shall see - it will not be enough. }
12. Bxe4
{ 12.Ng5?!  seems like the most natural choice as White is trying to keep the light-squared Bishop. I had the pleasure to demonstrate why it was not a good idea:  12...Nxd5  13.Nxe4  f5!  14.Ng3  f4!  15.Ne4  f3!  and the black Pawn successfully ruins his opponent's King's defense. Black had an excellent compensation in Kuznetsov, V - Gajewski, G - Pardubice Open 2007. }
12... Nxe4 13. Rxe4 Bb7
{ White has some weak light squares and is behind in development - we need to catch up. }
14. d4
{ Although  14.d3  would cover some weak light squares I still prefer  14.d4  as it's grabbing more space. }
14... Re8
{ There are two ideas behind this move:   a@@EndBracket@@ Black can @@StartBracket@@but doesn't have to!@@EndBracket@@ capture the Pawn with the Queen;   b@@EndBracket@@ he is waiting for us to develop the Knight to d2 first, blocking the dark-squared Bishop. }
15. Nbd2 { Nevertheless it seems like the best choice. } 15... Bxd5
{ Interesting try - Black wants to put the Queen on d7 and - if possible - the Bishop on d6. }
16. Re1 f6 { It was necessary to cover the e5-square first. } 17. b3 Qd7 18.
Bb2
{ 18.Nf1  would allow Black to execute his plan with  18...Bd6  . After the text move 18...Bd6 is weaker as  19.Qc2  can be played, threatening with 20.c4! }
18... Bf7
{ By retreating the Bishop to this specific square Black anticipates  19.Qc2  as he has  19...Bg6! }
19. Nf1
{ Now  19...Bd6  won't be that effective as White can simply play  20.Ne3  , taking away the long diagonal from Black's light-squared Bishop.   Black can play  19...c5  but after  20.dxc5  the position will simplify, bringing Black's opening concept to a pawn down ending with chances for a draw. }
*

