14. d4
{ Although  14.d3  would cover some weak light squares I still prefer  14.d4  as it's grabbing more space. }
14... Re8
{ There are two ideas behind this move:   a@@EndBracket@@ Black can @@StartBracket@@but doesn't have to!@@EndBracket@@ capture the Pawn with the Queen;   b@@EndBracket@@ he is waiting for us to develop the Knight to d2 first, blocking the dark-squared Bishop. }
15. Nbd2 { Nevertheless it seems like the best choice. } 15... Qxd5
{ Instinctively we might want to retreat the Rook to a safer location - we must not do that! As long as Black's Queen is blocking his own Bishop the Rook will be safe on e4. Let's the time we have to finish our development. }
16. b3
{ Fianchettoing the Bishop is one idea but this move is useful also because the Pawn covers the c4-square, restricting the black Knight. }
16... c5
{ The best choice for Black. Alternatively,  16...Bd6  would be met with  17.Rxe8+  Rxe8  and now both  18.Bb2  and  18.Nf1!?  give White a small advantage. }
17. Ba3
{ With his last move White provokes b5-b4 which will gain him an access to c4. }
17... b4
{ 17...Qd7  18.Re1  would transpose as Black has nothing better than  18...b4  19.Bb2  . }
18. Bb2 Qd7 19. Re1 cxd4 20. cxd4
{ Black's compensation would be quite nice if the Knight were somewhere else than a5 - even h8 would be much better. ;-@@EndBracket@@   After  20...Rad8  @@StartBracket@@what else?@@EndBracket@@ we can play  21.Rc1  preparing 22.Nc4. }
