{ Before advancing the d-pawn it is useful to cover the g4-square. The immediate  9.d4  allows  9...Bg4  leading to interesting play but - once again speaking in concepts - it would be a small victory for Black. }
9... a5
{ Instead of fighting for the center Black is trying to grab some space on the Queenside. I believe this is a wrong approach in general - the center matters more. }
10. d4 a4 11. Bc2 Bd7
{ Black needs the b-file for the Rook or the Queen as b5 will require protection. }
12. Na3
{ This is stronger than normal  12.Nbd2  . The Knight is attacking the b5-pawn but it is also stopping Black's pawn advance on the Queenside. }
12... Rb8 { Not the best choice in my opinion. } 13. d5 Na5
{ Now the Knight will risk further restrictions. } 14. b4 axb3 15. axb3 c5
{ Otherwise White would have played @@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/2pbbppp/3p1n2/np1Pp3/4P3/NPP2N1P/2B2PP1/R1BQR1K1 w - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.b4  . }
16. Be3 { We still want to play b3-b4 but we have to prepare it first. } 16...
b4 17. cxb4 cxb4 18. Nc4
{ I turns out that the b4-pawn will be just a weakness. } 18... Nxc4 19. bxc4
Qc7 20. Bd3
{ We want to continue with 21.Qd2 and 22.Reb1. If Black tries to double on the b-file, then we should bring our Knight to b3 instead. Black has no clear way of bringing his Knight or the dark-squared Bishop to the Queenside. }
