10. d4 a4 11. Bc2 Bd7
{ Black needs the b-file for the Rook or the Queen as b5 will require protection. }
12. Na3
{ This is stronger than normal  12.Nbd2  . The Knight is attacking the b5-pawn but it is also stopping Black's pawn advance on the Queenside. }
12... Rb8 { Not the best choice in my opinion. } 13. d5 Na5
{ Now the Knight will risk further restrictions. } 14. b4 axb3 15. axb3 c5
{ Otherwise White would have played @@StartFEN@@1r1q1rk1/2pbbppp/3p1n2/np1Pp3/4P3/NPP2N1P/2B2PP1/R1BQR1K1 w - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.b4  . }
16. Be3 { We still want to play b3-b4 but we have to prepare it first. } 16...
Qc7 17. Nd2 { Again we are threatening 18.b4. } 17... b4
{ 17...Rfc8  18.Bd3  wouldn't help Black. } 18. cxb4 cxb4 19. Nac4 Nxc4 20.
bxc4
{ 20.Nxc4  was possible but I still prefer taking with the Pawn. The same principle applies as after 17...b4. }
