{ A general rule is that if Black doesn't want to go for the Marshall Gambit, he should play 7...d6 before castling as it avoids some Anti-Marshall lines, mainly  8.a4  where Black can now simply go  8...Bd7  . }
8. c3
{ White is preparing d2-d4 but also securing his light-squared Bishop against  8...Na5  - we can now go  9.Bc2  . }
8... O-O 9. h3
{ Before advancing the d-pawn it is useful to cover the g4-square. The immediate  9.d4  allows  9...Bg4  leading to interesting play but - once again speaking in concepts - it would be a small victory for Black. }
9... Nd7
{ Black wants to bring the Knight to b6 while the Bishop can take his place on f6. However, just like in the9...a5 line - White will dominate in the center.   9...Bb7  10.d4  Nd7  11.Nbd2  transposes. }
10. d4 Bb7 { Black's plan is more or less the same as in the10...Nb6 line. }
11. Nbd2 exd4 12. cxd4 Bf6
{ This is a sharp and dubious line. Again, Black is starting a fight with the wrong guy. }
13. Nf1 Na5 14. Bc2 Re8 15. Ng3
{ There are other tries too but I like this most - it's relatively simple. }
15... g6 { Anticipating Ng3-h5. } 16. Bh6 { Knocking on the castle's door. }
16... Nc4
{ Black is now threatening 17...Nxb2 while after  17.b3  he can play  17...Na3  .   16...c5?!  would be met with  17.e5!  dxe5  18.dxc5  . }
17. a4
{ Undermining Black's strong position on the Queenside. He can now take one of the Pawns or just play  17...c5  which would not be the best choice as you shall see. }
17... bxa4
{ Black is accepting the Pawn sacrifice. Let's see where the compensation is. }
18. b3 axb3 19. Bxb3 Ncb6 20. Qd2
{ White has compensation for the invested material and is mostly focused on the Kingside. We now want to go Nf3-g5. }
20... c5 { Black needs to close that diagonal. } 21. Ng5 c4 22. Bc2
{ Now our plan is quite simple - we want to push the f-pawn. } 22... a5
{ Looking for any kind of counterplay. } 23. f4 a4 24. Ra3
{ Objectively,  24.Kh2  is stronger but then Black can keep pushing that Pawn. }
24... c3 25. Rxc3
{ Again,  25.Qf2  was better but it's already clear that things are getting out of control.  25.Qxc3  Qc8!  is great for Black. }
25... Nd5
{ Using all the files and diagonals, Black manages to create valid counterplay. }
26. exd5 Rxe1+ 27. Qxe1 a3
{ I wouldn't dare to evaluate this position. All I know is that I don't want it. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. Ruy Lopez Karpov Variation (9...Nd7)"]
[Black "Karpov Variation 9...Nd7 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Be7
{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6.Re1 is better than 6.d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6.d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 d6
{ A general rule is that if Black doesn't want to go for the Marshall Gambit, he should play 7...d6 before castling as it avoids some Anti-Marshall lines, mainly  8.a4  where Black can now simply go  8...Bd7  . }
8. c3
{ White is preparing d2-d4 but also securing his light-squared Bishop against  8...Na5  - we can now go  9.Bc2  . }
8... O-O 9. h3
{ Before advancing the d-pawn it is useful to cover the g4-square. The immediate  9.d4  allows  9...Bg4  leading to interesting play but - once again speaking in concepts - it would be a small victory for Black. }
9... Nd7
{ Black wants to bring the Knight to b6 while the Bishop can take his place on f6. However, just like in the9...a5 line - White will dominate in the center.   9...Bb7  10.d4  Nd7  11.Nbd2  transposes. }
10. d4 Bb7 { Black's plan is more or less the same as in the10...Nb6 line. }
11. Nbd2 exd4 12. cxd4 Bf6
{ This is a sharp and dubious line. Again, Black is starting a fight with the wrong guy. }
13. Nf1 Na5 14. Bc2 Re8 15. Ng3
{ There are other tries too but I like this most - it's relatively simple. }
15... g6 { Anticipating Ng3-h5. } 16. Bh6 { Knocking on the castle's door. }
16... Nc4
{ Black is now threatening 17...Nxb2 while after  17.b3  he can play  17...Na3  .   16...c5?!  would be met with  17.e5!  dxe5  18.dxc5  . }
17. a4
{ Undermining Black's strong position on the Queenside. He can now take one of the Pawns or just play  17...c5  which would not be the best choice as you shall see. }
17... c5 18. b3
{ Now the Knight has to come back as the a3-square is unavailable. } 18... Na5
19. axb5 axb5 20. e5 { The same trick works again. } 20... dxe5 21. dxc5 Nxc5
{ At least this is challenging. After other moves White is just better. } 22.
b4 e4 23. Nh2 { 23...Bxa1  24.Qxa1  is out of question. } 23... Qxd1 24. Raxd1
Bc3 { Otherwise Black will lose a piece for nothing. } 25. bxc5 Bxe1 26. Rxe1
f5 27. Rb1
{ We don't necessarily need to win that Pawn, stopping it is more important. We now want to bring one Knight to e3 and the other one to e2. Then g2-g4 will be possible. It should be technically winning. }
