{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Be7
{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6.Re1 is better than 6.d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6.d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 d6
{ A general rule is that if Black doesn't want to go for the Marshall Gambit, he should play 7...d6 before castling as it avoids some Anti-Marshall lines, mainly  8.a4  where Black can now simply go  8...Bd7  . }
8. c3
{ White is preparing d2-d4 but also securing his light-squared Bishop against  8...Na5  - we can now go  9.Bc2  . }
8... O-O 9. h3
{ Before advancing the d-pawn it is useful to cover the g4-square. The immediate  9.d4  allows  9...Bg4  leading to interesting play but - once again speaking in concepts - it would be a small victory for Black. }
9... Be6
{ A solid line but overall it is slightly outdated. Black intends to swap the light-squared Bishops in order to neutralize White's pressure in the center. At the same time, however, his light squares will get weakened. }
10. d4 { 10.Bxe6  is another possibility. } 10... Bxb3 11. axb3 exd4
{ Otherwise White was ready to close the position with d4-d5 leaving Black with a passive dark-squared Bishop and some weak light squares. }
12. cxd4 Nb4 { Black wants to play c7-c5. } 13. d5
{ Interfering with Black's plans - he will have to go c7-c5 anyway but then we will do en passant. }
13... c5 14. dxc6 { As promised. } 14... Nxc6 15. Nc3
{ Doubled pawns are compensated with the semi-open a-file. Black has a typical weak d6-pawn restricting his own Bishop. We can move the Knight to d4 or just develop the Bishop to f4. In any case, White has a slight advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. Ruy Lopez (9...Rb8)"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez 9...Rb8 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Be7
{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6.Re1 is better than 6.d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6.d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 d6
{ A general rule is that if Black doesn't want to go for the Marshall Gambit, he should play 7...d6 before castling as it avoids some Anti-Marshall lines, mainly  8.a4  where Black can now simply go  8...Bd7  . }
8. c3
{ White is preparing d2-d4 but also securing his light-squared Bishop against  8...Na5  - we can now go  9.Bc2  . }
8... O-O 9. h3
{ Before advancing the d-pawn it is useful to cover the g4-square. The immediate  9.d4  allows  9...Bg4  leading to interesting play but - once again speaking in concepts - it would be a small victory for Black. }
9... Rb8
{ This is my first contribution to Ruy Lopez's theory. Black's last move looks pointless so allow me to explain - my initial idea was to answer  10.d4  with  10...exd4  11.cxd4  d5  . After  12.e5  Ne4  the black Knight has occupied a nice outpost in the center while the light-squared Bishop can be developed to f5. The concept was ready. All I had to do was to find the best move for Black while waiting for d2-d4. This is where the problems started to appear.   At first, I wanted to go  9...Re8  but it quickly turned out that by leaving the Pawn on f7 defended only by the King, Black is creating additional tactical possibilities for White:  10.d4  exd4  11.cxd4  d5  12.Ne5!  and White is much better already.   9...Bb7  was another try but I quickly realized that after  10.d4  exd4  11.cxd4  d5  12.e5  Ne4  13.Nc3  Nxc3  14.bxc3  the Bishop can't move from b7 to f5!   I also tried  9...h6  but in one of the key lines that h6-pawn was captured. Eventually, out of despair,  9...Rb8  was played. And it wasn't that bad! }
10. d4 exd4 11. cxd4 d5 12. exd5
{ In the beginning, I neglected this move - how could willingly going for an isolani structure be the refutation? With time I understood - White's activity is the key. }
12... Nxd5
{ 12...Na5  13.Bc2  Nxd5  14.Nc3  would be even nicer - White has a powerful initiative. After  14...Bb7  15.Ne5  it is already hard to find a move for Black. }
13. Bxd5
{ It looks like a positional mistake at first but this is all about the dynamics. White will be able to develop the Knight with tempo. }
13... Qxd5 14. Nc3 Qd8
{ Or  14...Qd7  15.d5  Na5  16.Ne5  with a strong initiative. } 15. d5 Na5
{ Black is forced to bring the Knight to the edge of the board. } 16. Bf4
{ All our pieces are harmoniously placed. } 16... Bb7 17. Nd4
{ White is threatening 18.Nf5  17...Nc4  is met with  18.Nc6!  Bxc6  19.dxc6  and Black is in great trouble.   17...Qd7  will be answered with  18.Qg4!  Qxg4  19.hxg4  . Both the dark-squared Bishop and the c7-pawn are attacked so Black is forced to go  19...Bd6  20.Bxd6  cxd6  and after  21.Nf5  Nc4  22.b3  Nb6  23.Rad1  White has an enormous advantage in the endgame. }
