10... c5 11. d4 cxd4
{ This is too early, although if Black wants to get a potentially interesting position then it might try that. }
12. cxd4 Bb7 { This only provokes our strong answer... } 13. d5
{ It was hard for me to believe that in my database I could find close to a thousand games after 12...Bb7. }
13... Bc8 { Why not? The Bishop wasn't doing anything on b7 anyway. } 14. Bd3
{ This is the best diagonal for the light-squared Bishop. } 14... Bd7 15. Na3
{ We are now threatening b2-b4. } 15... Nb7 16. b4 a5
{ Naturally, Black wants to get rid of our b4-Pawn in order to get the c5-square back. }
17. Bd2 axb4 18. Bxb4
{ White is better - our pieces are more active and Black has a clear weakness on b5. We can now double on the b-file - Ra1-b1-b3 and Qd1-b1 or Qd1-e2 and Re1-b1. }
