{ The Knight chases away the Bishop to a less active square while making c7-c5 possible.   Black's intention is to challenge White's Pawn center but the current theoretical status is that Black has to release the tension in the center very early, or allow White to close the position with d4-d5, giving White the more comfortable position in either case.  The Chigorin Defense is, in my opinion, slightly outdated in a sense that it is not a bad line but there are better ones. }
10... c5 11. d4 Re8
{ It used to be a specialty of British grandmaster, Mark Hebden. However, the line didn't even make it to the modern engines' era. }
12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Nxe5
{ Black is hoping for counterplay but the problem is - there is none. } 13...
Bd6 { Hebden's early try. He was punished by Sax Gulya in London 1993: } 14.
Nxf7 Kxf7 15. e5 Qe7
{ Otherwise White would be a Pawn up in a better position, which basically means - White is winning. }
16. Bf4 Bc7
{ 16...Nc4  17.Bb3!  Sax played the weaker  17.Re3?!  which was not so clear after  17...Qd7! }
17. Nd2 Bb7 18. Nf3
{ It turns out that White doesn't need to win the piece back - his attack is just too strong. Whether it's  18...Rad8  or  18...Nd5  -  19.Ng5+  should win rather easily. }
