13... g6 { Still dreaming of f7-f5... } 14. Nf1 f5
{ This line has some practical value as it is forcing us to play accurately. }
15. Bh6 Rf7
{ In the game Sadhwani, R - Kovalev, V, Sharjah Masters 2018,  15...Rf6  was played and after  16.b3  White was better although  16.a4!  would be even stronger. }
16. exf5 { Black's Pawns are not really strong, they are just targets. } 16...
gxf5 17. Ng3 e4
{ After something 'normal' like  17...Bd7  White would just play  18.b3  restricting Black's Knights. }
18. Bxe4
{ There is no forced mate or anything but most of the black pieces are so far away from the King that they have no chance of coming back in time. }
18... fxe4 19. Rxe4 Kh8
{ 19...Bb7  would be met with  20.Rg4+  Kh8  21.Nh5  . } 20. Qe2
{ Black can't take  20...Nxd5  due to  21.Ng5!  which is our threat anyway. }
20... Bd7 { Covering the back rank. } 21. Rd1
{ White calmly defends the Pawn. We don't need to be in a hurry - the black Knights are not coming anyway - there is just no way. We want to go b2-b3 taking the important c4-square under control and then - attack! We might use h3-h4 to get control over the g5-square. }
