10... c5 11. d4 Qc7
{ The main continuation. I remain faithful to my strategy and will once again close the position with d4-d5. Here I would like to clarify - it is not just my personal preference - the main continuation,  12.Nbd2  turns out to be less promising. }
12. d5 Nc4 { Other moves would allow White to get an easy game with b2-b3. }
13. b3 Nb6 14. a4 { We want to play a4-a5. } 14... c4
{ It's not very popular but it definitely deserves some more tests so I took it seriously. Black is kicking back on the Queenside and he is ready to sacrifice a Pawn in order to gain some activity. }
15. bxc4 Bd7
{ This is stronger than  15...Nxc4  16.axb5  while @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/2q1bppp/pn1p1n2/1p1Pp3/P1P1P3/2P2N1P/2B2PP1/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...bxa4?  16.c5!  would be just wrong. }
16. axb5 axb5 17. Rxa8 Rxa8
{ Black definitely has some compensation for the Pawn - most of its pieces are now quite active. On the other hand, White is very solid and it is a Pawn. }
18. cxb5 Bxb5 19. Bd3
{ I honestly don't know if this is the best try but I am certain it is practical - exchanging the light-squared Bishops is strategically desirable for White as Black's most important Pawns are placed on the dark squares = weak light squares. }
19... Bxd3 20. Qxd3 Nfd7
{ The Knight is heading to c5.  20...Ra2  would be nothing special - White can just reply with  21.Re2  . }
21. Ba3
{ This is more accurate than  21.Be3  as after  21...Nc4  White has  22.Bc1  . }
21... Nc5 22. Qc2
{ If this were the main line then I would not yet be satisfied, but since it is not, we can stop here.   It's an interesting line which we don't really expect so we just want to make sure that - in case it does happen - we will not only avoid being surprised but that we will actually manage to put some pressure on Black.   Our plan is to go Ba3-b4 and Nb1-a3. }
