{ The main problem for White - he can't move the Knight as the Pawn on e4 needs protection. Instinctively, we might want to go  12.Ng5  as 12...Rf8 is not possible. However,  12...Re7  turns out to be good enough to fight off White's little attack. }
12. a4
{ The most aggressive continuation which also happens to be the main move in the position. While making a generally useful move White creates a real threat, for instance:  12...g6?  13.Ng5!  Re7  14.Bxf7+  @@StartBracket@@not the only way but it proves our point@@EndBracket@@  14...Rxf7  15.Qb3  and, apart from the Rook, Black will also lose the b5-pawn.   The main downside of 12.a4 is that it weakens the b4-square which will determine the course of Black's play. }
12... exd4 13. cxd4
{ Now  13...h6  14.Bc2  would directlytranspose to 12...h6. } 13... Qd7
{ This line is not very well known but it's definitely an important one. I first saw it in the game between Wesley So and Ivan Saric in Wijk Aan Zee 2015. Black provokes White to take action with Nf3-g5 but he is actually ready for it - he now has Nc6-d8. }
14. axb5
{ There is no reason to delay it especially since in some cases Black may surprise us with b5xa4. }
14... axb5 15. Rxa8 Bxa8 16. Ng5
{ This was So's reaction. I think it is useful to learn the key ideas from that game. }
16... Nd8
{ Black is now threatening with h7-h6 which provokes further action. } 17. e5
Nd5 18. Ndf3 h6 { There was no reason to tolerate that Knight. } 19. Ne4
{ There is a real threat now which can be best illustrated with a following line:  19...Ne6?  20.Bxh6!  and Black can't go  20...gxh6  because after  21.Bxd5  Bxd5  22.Nf6+  White wins the Queen. }
19... Nb4
{ Now  20.Bxh6?  would be easily refuted with  20...Bxe4  21.Rxe4  gxh6  . }
20. Qd2
{ The funny thing is that there is no real threat @@StartBracket@@as we will see@@EndBracket@@ and yet the hanging Knight provoked Saric's wrong reaction.   He now played  20...dxe5?  and after  21.Nxe5  Qf5  22.Nc5  White was already close to winning. Four years later the same line was tested in Zhigalko, A - Erdos, V - European Championship, Skopje 2019. The Hungarian grandmaster was well prepared as he continued with... }
20... Bd5
{ More or less forcing White to take the Knight as  21.Bxd5  Nxd5  would be just fine for Black. }
21. Qxb4 Bxe4 22. Rxe4 d5
{ The point. After losing the Knight, Black wins the whole Rook in return. }
23. Qe1 dxe4 24. Qxe4
{ Naturally, White's compensation is huge and precise play is required from Black but as I wrote - Erdos was well prepared. }
24... c5
{ It might seem a bit risky but White's central Pawns will be as powerful as vulnerable. }
25. d5 g6 { It was necessary to prevent any mating threats on b1-h7 diagonal. }
26. Bc2 f5
{ Even more controversial than 24...c5 but it just works tactically. } 27. Qd3
{ Only here Black erred by going  27...c4?!  a move too early. After  28.Qd4  Bg7  White could have played  29.h4!  preventing what will turn out to be Black's crucial idea. Therefore, Black should now deviate from Zhigalko-Erdos. }
27... Bg7
{ Black isn't afraid of  28.e6  - after  28...Nxe6!  29.dxe6  Qxd3  30.Bxd3  c4!  it is White who should be afraid. }
28. Bf4 c4
{ It is different now - dragging the Bishop to f4 first gives Black additional resources. }
29. Qd4 g5
{ Both  30.Be3  and  30.Bd2  can be answered with both  30...Nf7  and  30...g4  . In each case, the position should simplify leading to a drawn endgame. This is the status of 16.Ng5 - an interesting move that can be used as a safe way of testing the opponent's memory but otherwise I see no interesting tries for White, hence I consider the line inactive. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Ruy Lopez Zaitsev"]
[Black "Zaitsev 9...Bb7 − 12...exd4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Be7
{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6.Re1 is better than 6.d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6.d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 d6
{ A general rule is that if Black doesn't want to go for the Marshall Gambit, he should play 7...d6 before castling as it avoids some Anti-Marshall lines, mainly  8.a4  where Black can now simply go  8...Bd7  . }
8. c3
{ White is preparing d2-d4 but also securing his light-squared Bishop against  8...Na5  - we can now go  9.Bc2  . }
8... O-O 9. h3
{ Before advancing the d-pawn it is useful to cover the g4-square. The immediate  9.d4  allows  9...Bg4  leading to interesting play but - once again speaking in concepts - it would be a small victory for Black. }
9... Bb7
{ The Zaitsev System - for me this is the most ambitious of all the Ruy Lopez variations. Black wants to achieve as much as possible without any trade-offs.   The Bishop goes to b7, the Rook will come to e8. The Knight, however, for a moment stays on c6. This creates tension as White always has to consider exd4/cxd4/Nb4!   Overall this is a good but very complicated line and there is one thing I really don't like about the Zaitsev: White can choose if he wants to go for a quiet game or a sharp one. In the majority of cases, Black has to adjust, which is not very practical. }
10. d4 Re8 { The role of black Rook is identical as in the Breyer. } 11. Nbd2
{ Literally, thousands of games have ended with a repetition after  11.Ng5  Rf8  12.Nf3  . Recommending this line for White is probably the easiest way to become the worst Chessable author ever. }
11... Bf8
{ The main problem for White - he can't move the Knight as the Pawn on e4 needs protection. Instinctively, we might want to go  12.Ng5  as 12...Rf8 is not possible. However,  12...Re7  turns out to be good enough to fight off White's little attack. }
12. a4
{ The most aggressive continuation which also happens to be the main move in the position. While making a generally useful move White creates a real threat, for instance:  12...g6?  13.Ng5!  Re7  14.Bxf7+  @@StartBracket@@not the only way but it proves our point@@EndBracket@@  14...Rxf7  15.Qb3  and, apart from the Rook, Black will also lose the b5-pawn.   The main downside of 12.a4 is that it weakens the b4-square which will determine the course of Black's play. }
12... exd4 13. cxd4
{ Now  13...h6  14.Bc2  would directlytranspose to 12...h6. } 13... Qd7
{ This line is not very well known but it's definitely an important one. I first saw it in the game between Wesley So and Ivan Saric in Wijk Aan Zee 2015. Black provokes White to take action with Nf3-g5 but he is actually ready for it - he now has Nc6-d8. }
14. axb5
{ There is no reason to delay it especially since in some cases Black may surprise us with b5xa4. }
14... axb5 15. Rxa8 Bxa8 16. Ba2
{ Astute readers will notice that White's last move is technically not a novelty as it was once played in a correspondence game a couple of years ago. White wants to regroup the Bishop to b1 while he still can - once Nc6-b4 is played, a2 and c2 will be beyond our control. }
16... Nb4
{ 16...g6  doesn't change much as we have the same plan:  17.Bb1  and he anyway should play  17...Nb4  as  17...Bg7  allows  18.Nf1  with advantage. }
17. Bb1 g6
{ 17...c5  18.d5  , as usually in this case we are profiting from the awkward position of Black's light-squared Bishop. }
18. b3 Bg7 19. Ba3
{ 19.Bb2  runs into typical problem:  19...c5  and we can't play  20.d5  because of  20...Nxe4! }
19... c5
{ After  20...Na6  White can play  21.b4!?  and  21...c5  22.bxc5  dxc5  23.d5  looks promising. }
20. d5 Qd8
{ Black improves the position of his Queen but also releases the square for the Knight. }
21. Nf1 Nd7 22. Bc1
{ The Bishop is much stronger here and it might also go to f4 or g5. Furthermore, it will be a part of White's main plan: bringing the Knight from f1 to g4 and creating some serious pressure on the dark squares around the black King. }
