12. a4
{ The most aggressive continuation which also happens to be the main move in the position. While making a generally useful move White creates a real threat, for instance:  12...g6?  13.Ng5!  Re7  14.Bxf7+  @@StartBracket@@not the only way but it proves our point@@EndBracket@@  14...Rxf7  15.Qb3  and, apart from the Rook, Black will also lose the b5-pawn.   The main downside of 12.a4 is that it weakens the b4-square which will determine the course of Black's play. }
12... Na5
{ This line was quite popular in years 2006-2009 but then it seemed to have lost its appeal. I have chosen a simple and effective solution - we try to be practical whenever possible. }
13. Bc2 { 13.Ba2  c5  14.d5  c4  seems okay for Black. } 13... b4
{ Sure, the simple  14.d5  will give White a space advantage. However, after  14...bxc3  15.bxc3  c6  , followed by Qd8-c7 and Bb7-c8-d7 Black's position looks very solid and also not that difficult to handle. Therefore, I prefer the text move. }
14. cxb4 Nc6
{ The pawn sacrifice was temporary - Black will win it back almost immediately. }
15. Nb3 { Defending d4-pawn but it's not really the plan. } 15... Nxb4 16. Na5
{ It is a rare opportunity for the white Knight to reach a5. Exchanging the light-squared Bishop is a good trade for White in almost every case in Ruy Lopez. }
16... Rb8 17. Nxb7 Rxb7 18. dxe5
{ 18.d5  would be an interesting alternative but our choice is simpler. } 18...
dxe5 19. Qe2
{ Black has to take the Bishop now - if we manage to move it to b3, White's advantage will become very serious. }
19... Nxc2 20. Qxc2
{ We want to move the Pawn to b3 and try to keep this structure. Ideally, we could place one Rook on d3 and the other one on the c-file. White has a better Pawn structure and for as long as we manage to keep it, we will enjoy a slight edge. }
