12. a4
{ The most aggressive continuation which also happens to be the main move in the position. While making a generally useful move White creates a real threat, for instance:  12...g6?  13.Ng5!  Re7  14.Bxf7+  @@StartBracket@@not the only way but it proves our point@@EndBracket@@  14...Rxf7  15.Qb3  and, apart from the Rook, Black will also lose the b5-pawn.   The main downside of 12.a4 is that it weakens the b4-square which will determine the course of Black's play. }
12... h6
{ The main continuation @@StartBracket@@ or  12...exd4  13.cxd4  h6  @@EndBracket@@. With the last move Black prevented Nf3-g5 so we have to think of some other plan. }
13. Bc2
{ Black was already threatening exd4 and Nb4 so the Bishop should move away from c2 while it still can. }
13... b4
{ I am not sure why anyone would want to play this but since some people do, I feel compelled to provide an answer. }
14. a5
{ A typical response. One benefit from a4-a5 is that the white Bishop can go to a4. Another one is that now Black can't play a6-a5. This is important because in many cases Nb4 will be impossible without support from the a-pawn. }
14... Rb8 15. Ba4 Re7
{ The Rook had to leave that diagonal. This is Polgar, J - Sokolov, I from Hoogoven 2003. Now we are improving with the text move }
16. d5 bxc3 { Black can't go  16...Nxa5  as  17.cxb4  would win a piece. } 17.
dxc6 { But not  17.bxc3?  Nxa5  . } 17... cxd2 18. Bxd2 Bc8 19. Bc3
{ We want to play b2-b4 and transfer our light-squared Bishop to d3 or ideally - f1. }
