{ White is preparing d2-d4 but also securing his light-squared Bishop against  8...Na5  - we can now go  9.Bc2  . }
8... O-O 9. h3
{ Before advancing the d-pawn it is useful to cover the g4-square. The immediate  9.d4  allows  9...Bg4  leading to interesting play but - once again speaking in concepts - it would be a small victory for Black. }
9... Bb7
{ The Zaitsev System - for me this is the most ambitious of all the Ruy Lopez variations. Black wants to achieve as much as possible without any trade-offs.   The Bishop goes to b7, the Rook will come to e8. The Knight, however, for a moment stays on c6. This creates tension as White always has to consider exd4/cxd4/Nb4!   Overall this is a good but very complicated line and there is one thing I really don't like about the Zaitsev: White can choose if he wants to go for a quiet game or a sharp one. In the majority of cases, Black has to adjust, which is not very practical. }
10. d4 Re8 { The role of black Rook is identical as in the Breyer. } 11. Nbd2
{ Literally, thousands of games have ended with a repetition after  11.Ng5  Rf8  12.Nf3  . Recommending this line for White is probably the easiest way to become the worst Chessable author ever. }
11... Bf8
{ The main problem for White - he can't move the Knight as the Pawn on e4 needs protection. Instinctively, we might want to go  12.Ng5  as 12...Rf8 is not possible. However,  12...Re7  turns out to be good enough to fight off White's little attack. }
12. a4
{ The most aggressive continuation which also happens to be the main move in the position. While making a generally useful move White creates a real threat, for instance:  12...g6?  13.Ng5!  Re7  14.Bxf7+  @@StartBracket@@not the only way but it proves our point@@EndBracket@@  14...Rxf7  15.Qb3  and, apart from the Rook, Black will also lose the b5-pawn.   The main downside of 12.a4 is that it weakens the b4-square which will determine the course of Black's play. }
12... h6
{ The main continuation @@StartBracket@@ or  12...exd4  13.cxd4  h6  @@EndBracket@@. With the last move Black prevented Nf3-g5 so we have to think of some other plan. }
13. Bc2
{ Black was already threatening exd4 and Nb4 so the Bishop should move away from c2 while it still can. }
13... exd4 14. cxd4 Nb4
{ The powerful Knight on b4 is the core of Zaitsev's main line. } 15. Bb1 g6
{ Black tries to be super clever as he doesn't really want to commit to anything. Notice his pawns on g6 and h6 - it is not a very good combination - with either e4-e5-e6 or h3-h4-h5 White can weaken the light squares around the black King. None of these advances would be that effective with the black Pawn on h7 instead of h6. }
16. Ra3
{ I didn't mention this earlier but Ra1-a3 is the common idea of this line and one of the benefits of a2-a4. White's Bishops on b1 and c1 might be passive now but their potential is great and they are aiming at the Black's King position. Hence, it makes sense to activate the queen's Rook so it could join the potential attack on the kingside. }
16... Bg7 17. e5
{ It is about time to strike as Black was ready to go Nf6-d7 stopping e4-e5 for good. }
17... dxe5 18. dxe5 Nh5
{ Both  18...Nd7  and  18...Nh7  would be met with  19.e6! } 19. axb5 axb5 20.
Qb3 c5 21. Ne4
{ White should play energetically as Black is also quite active. } 21... Bxe5
{ I can't see anything else for Black. } 22. Nxc5 Bxf3 23. Qxf3
{ Black can't really take the Rook as after  23...Rxa3  24.bxa3  the Knight wouldn't have a good square to retreat to -  24...Nd5  25.Rd1  . }
23... Rc8 24. Ne4
{ Not only the Knight was hanging but Black was also threatening Be5-h2+. Now he has to defend the h6-Pawn. }
24... Kg7
{ So far we were following the game between Anand Viswanathan and Gata Kamsky from the Candidates tournament in Las Palmas 1995. Now White was supposed to play: }
25. g4 Nf6 26. Rd1 { White's point behind g4 will become clear soon! } 26...
Qe7 27. Bxh6+ Kxh6 28. g5+ Kg7 29. gxf6+ Bxf6 30. Nd6
{ White wins an exchange achieving a winning position. } *

