{ The powerful Knight on b4 is the core of Zaitsev's main line. } 15. Bb1 bxa4
{ This is an old line, not very popular these days though it's not so easy to crack it. Black wants to skip the c7-c5 - d4-d5 sequence to keep his light-squared bishop active. The Knight on b4 will be defended from the other side. }
16. Rxa4 a5 17. Ra3 { The Rook was useless on a4. } 17... Ra6
{ This is an old line introduced by Karpov. The point is that Black wants to play d6-d5 after which the Rook will come into play via the 6th rank. The line doesn't really work: }
18. Rae3 a4
{ 18...d5  19.e5  Ne4  would just drop a Pawn without sufficient compensation. }
19. Nh2
{ White would like to play  19.Nf1  however there's  19...d5  20.e5  Ne4  . The text move prepares 20.Ndf1 as after Nf6-e4 White will now have f2-f3. }
19... d5 { Trying to play d6-d5 while it's still possible. } 20. e5 Ne4 21. Ng4
{ The Knight joins the attack. White has a couple of ideas - f2-f3 is there but also we can take Nd2xe4 and then either win the Pawn or sac an exchange with Re3xe4!? Black seems to be in real trouble here. }
