{ The only way to equality. White can't take the Pawn due to Re8-e1+. } 28. Be3
{ I didn't like the idea of giving up the a file with  28.Rxa8  Rxa8  . } 28...
fxe4
{ This is stronger than  28...Qxb2  29.Rxa8  Rxa8  30.exf5  with advantage. }
29. Qe2 { Black's Queen has surprisingly little squares. } 29... Qb7
{ We can do the same after  29...Qc7  - it should transpose. } 30. Rxa8 Rxa8
31. b4
{ White has a very simple and dangerous plan - b4-b5-b6. Once again, Black has only one good response. }
31... Qf7 { It is essential to start with the Queen move. } 32. Qc4
{ Defending and attacking. } 32... Be7
{ Actually  32...Ra1+  33.Kh2  Rd1  should hold too although after  34.Nd4  I still prefer White. With the text move, Black is preparing a Bishop trade. }
33. Qxe4 Bg5
{ Never mind the Pawn structure - White's Bishop was protecting the King and supporting the b-Pawn while Black's Bishop was totally useless on f8. }
34. Bxg5 hxg5
{ Black has enough compensation - he can use the ranks and the files so it is about time to take the draw. }
35. Ne7+ { With perpetual check. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Ruy Lopez Zaitsev"]
[Black "Zaitsev  #23"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Be7
{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6.Re1 is better than 6.d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6.d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 d6
{ A general rule is that if Black doesn't want to go for the Marshall Gambit, he should play 7...d6 before castling as it avoids some Anti-Marshall lines, mainly  8.a4  where Black can now simply go  8...Bd7  . }
8. c3
{ White is preparing d2-d4 but also securing his light-squared Bishop against  8...Na5  - we can now go  9.Bc2  . }
8... O-O 9. h3
{ Before advancing the d-pawn it is useful to cover the g4-square. The immediate  9.d4  allows  9...Bg4  leading to interesting play but - once again speaking in concepts - it would be a small victory for Black. }
9... Bb7
{ The Zaitsev System - for me this is the most ambitious of all the Ruy Lopez variations. Black wants to achieve as much as possible without any trade-offs.   The Bishop goes to b7, the Rook will come to e8. The Knight, however, for a moment stays on c6. This creates tension as White always has to consider exd4/cxd4/Nb4!   Overall this is a good but very complicated line and there is one thing I really don't like about the Zaitsev: White can choose if he wants to go for a quiet game or a sharp one. In the majority of cases, Black has to adjust, which is not very practical. }
10. d4 Re8 { The role of black Rook is identical as in the Breyer. } 11. Nbd2
{ Literally, thousands of games have ended with a repetition after  11.Ng5  Rf8  12.Nf3  . Recommending this line for White is probably the easiest way to become the worst Chessable author ever. }
11... Bf8
{ The main problem for White - he can't move the Knight as the Pawn on e4 needs protection. Instinctively, we might want to go  12.Ng5  as 12...Rf8 is not possible. However,  12...Re7  turns out to be good enough to fight off White's little attack. }
12. a4
{ The most aggressive continuation which also happens to be the main move in the position. While making a generally useful move White creates a real threat, for instance:  12...g6?  13.Ng5!  Re7  14.Bxf7+  @@StartBracket@@not the only way but it proves our point@@EndBracket@@  14...Rxf7  15.Qb3  and, apart from the Rook, Black will also lose the b5-pawn.   The main downside of 12.a4 is that it weakens the b4-square which will determine the course of Black's play. }
12... h6
{ The main continuation @@StartBracket@@ or  12...exd4  13.cxd4  h6  @@EndBracket@@. With the last move Black prevented Nf3-g5 so we have to think of some other plan. }
13. Bc2
{ Black was already threatening exd4 and Nb4 so the Bishop should move away from c2 while it still can. }
13... exd4 14. cxd4 Nb4
{ The powerful Knight on b4 is the core of Zaitsev's main line. } 15. Bb1 c5
{ The Pawn on c5 not only attacks the center but also supports the Knight. It can also be advanced to c4 which creates another outpost for the Knight - d3. }
16. d5 { At least Black's light-squared Bishop is locked out now. } 16... Nd7
{ This move has many points:   a@@EndBracket@@ Black can now play f7-f5!?   b@@EndBracket@@ the Knight controls e5 and once c5-c4 has been played it might go to c5-d3   c@@EndBracket@@ it uncovers the long diagonal which will be useful if Black fianchettoes the Bishop. }
17. Ra3
{ We would normally play  17.Nf1  but then  17...f5!  is strong. The Rook lift is useful - it controls the fragile d3-square and the rook can also join the other one on the e-file. }
17... c4
{ Currently, this is a clear main line. Black intends to use the d3-square for building counterplay. }
18. Nd4
{ 18.axb5  is the main move, while a renowned expert in this line - Alexei Kuzmin recommends  18.Ree3  in his book The Zaitsev System, Fresh Ideas and New Weapons for Black.   This is also a good try but I am a bit worried that - of all of the Zaitsev players - at least a few, might actually own a top book on Zaitsev... }
18... Nc5 { This time the c5-square is a bit unfortunate. } 19. axb5 Nbd3
{ After  19...axb5  we can just take the Pawn with  20.Nxb5  . } 20. b4
{ Now it is clear why the Knight would be better on e5, but also the normal  20.Re3  would be strong - compared to 18...Ne5, Black's Pawn on c4 is not defended. }
20... cxb3 { After this Black will be just a Pawn down. } 21. Bxd3
{ This way White is eliminating the defender of b3-Pawn. } 21... Nxd3 22. Re3
Nxc1 23. Qxc1 axb5 24. Raxb3 Qf6 25. N2f3
{ The Pawn on b5 will fall and we will get to choose when. } *

