{ 18.axb5  is the main move, while a renowned expert in this line - Alexei Kuzmin recommends  18.Ree3  in his book The Zaitsev System, Fresh Ideas and New Weapons for Black.   This is also a good try but I am a bit worried that - of all of the Zaitsev players - at least a few, might actually own a top book on Zaitsev... }
18... Qf6
{ This is the main move and it is also recommended by Kuzmin. Its aim is not only to attack the Knight. The queen is also looking at the Pawns on f2 and b2. }
19. N2f3 Nd3 { It practically forces a good exchange sacrifice. } 20. Bxd3 b4
{ 21.Bxc4  is possible but there is a better move. } 21. Rb3 cxb3 22. Nxb3
{ White has a Pawn and excellent compensation for the exchange. Notice that both black Bishops are very passive, the Queen is exposed on f6 and the b4-Pawn is just weak. }
22... Qd8
{ Kuzmin suggested  22...Rab8  , although he well understood, that after  23.Nfd4  White had a very pleasant position. With text move, the Queen comes back to cover the a5-square before the Knight jumps onto it. It also makes room for the dark-squared Bishop and quietly enables f7-f5! }
23. Nfd4 { Simple and strong - the Knight is perfectly placed in the center. }
23... g6
{ Black is planning to activate the dark-squared Bishop but covering f5 is also useful. }
24. Bd2 Nc5
{ Defending the Pawn with  24...a5  would have terrible consequences: after  25.Bb5  White gets control over the c6-square gaining a clear advantage. }
25. Bxb4 Nxa4 26. Qa1 a5
{ After the immediate  26...Nc5  White has  27.Nxc5  dxc5  28.Ba5  which is a small upgrade. }
27. Bd2 Nc5 28. Nxc5 dxc5
{ For the Rook, White has a Knight and fantastic Pawn center. Even though the position is not clear, it is definitely much more fun to play with White. }
29. Nf3
{ If Black allows it, then we should just place the Bishop on c3. If Black goes  29...Bg7  first @@StartBracket@@which is very likely@@EndBracket@@ then  30.Qc1  attacking both c5 and h6 looks good. }
*

