{ Black can't take  26...Bxd5  because of  27.Nc7  . It is now facing another challenge. }
26... Qd8 { The Queen is covering c7 but it might also come to b8 or b6. } 27.
Nc3
{ The Knight was no longer useful on b5. We are giving up on the Pawn on d5 but it was no longer possible to save it anyway. }
27... Nxc3 28. Bxc3 Rxe1+ 29. Nxe1
{ After  29.Bxe1  Qc8  the Pawn would fall anyway and the Knight wouldn't be comfortable on f3. }
29... Qg5 30. b5 Qxd5
{ The desire to simplify the position is understandable but White can still press in the endgame. }
31. Qxd5 Bxd5 32. Nc2
{ The Knight is coming to b4 which means  32.Nd3  was also possible. } 32... f6
{ The best move - Black is preparing a King's march. } 33. Nb4 Ba8
{ This is more accurate than  33...Bb7  as Nc6-a5 will not attack the Bishop. }
34. Nc6
{ White is threatening Nc6-a5 and b5-b6 and there is only one defense. } 34...
d5 35. Na5
{ After  35...Bc5  we can play  36.Nb3  followed by 37.Bd4 blocking the d5-pawn. Black should hold but this position remains unpleasant - we shall put the Pawn on f3 and bring the King to the center. }
