20... Nbd3 { These knights cannot be tolerated for long. } 21. Bxd3 Nxd3 22.
Re3 Qg6
{ So far the position after White's 22nd move has been reached a couple of times @@StartBracket@@in correspondence chess@@EndBracket@@ and each time Black reacted with 22...Qg6. The point is quite simple - Black attacks the e4-Pawn. }
23. bxc4 { A fresh idea. White opens the 3rd rank for the Rook. } 23... bxc4
24. Raxd3
{ The strength of Black's Knight makes this sacrifice quite logical. } 24...
cxd3 25. Qxd3
{ For an exchange, White has a Pawn, great center, and active pieces, whereas Black's pieces are in the opposite situation. }
25... Bc8 { The Bishop was terrible on b7 and now it controls f5. } 26. Bb2
{ The Bishop on the long diagonal can be a real monster! } 26... Bd7
{ 26...Rb8  achieves nothing. After  27.Bc3  Bd7  28.a5  Black has to solve the problems with the Pawn on a6. }
27. Nf5
{ If White wants to avoid simplifications he might also try  27.a5  with a good compensation for the Pawn. }
27... Rxe4
{ Definitely the most practical reaction. Black not only returns the material but sacrifices a Pawn himself. }
28. Nxh6+ gxh6 { 28...Qxh6  29.Qxe4  would be better for White. } 29. Qxe4 Qxe4
30. Rxe4 Rc8
{ The endgame is close to a draw as Black has some decent counterplay - a4 and d5 are weak. }
31. Rb4 { A good try though, unfortunately, Black has a good answer too. }
31... a5 32. Rb6 { White gives back the Pawn in order to activate his pieces. }
32... Bxa4 33. Ba3 Ra8
{ By placing the Rook behind the Pawn, Black makes a potential pawn advance far more dangerous. }
34. Nd4
{ There is no point taking on d6 right now as it would only allow Black to push the a-Pawn as far as possible. Black should be okay but I still think that White is a bit better - let's play f2-f3 and bring the King a bit closer to the center and then see how Black reacts. }
