8. c3
{ White is preparing d2-d4 but also securing his light-squared Bishop against  8...Na5  - we can now go  9.Bc2  . }
8... O-O 9. h3
{ Before advancing the d-pawn it is useful to cover the g4-square. The immediate  9.d4  allows  9...Bg4  leading to interesting play but - once again speaking in concepts - it would be a small victory for Black. }
9... Nb8
{ The Breyer Variation has always been considered one of the most solid openings for Black. But solidity is not its only virtue - it is also very flexible. Therefore it quickly became one of the favorite shelters for players who wanted to avoid a sharp fight right after the opening without compromising Black's position.   The main idea of Black's last move is to improve the position of the Knight as it will be much safer and sounder on d7. It is also good news for the light-squared Bishop as, once it is developed on b7, it won't be covered by that Knight.   But all of this, along with the further follow-up @@StartBracket@@Rf8-e8 and Be7-f8 and very likely g7-g6 and Bf8-g7@@EndBracket@@ has been well known for decades. I see this as one of the main disadvantages of the Breyer - its once hidden and often misunderstood subtleties are now comprehensible for the majority of players.   The other one is purely chess-related - The line is simply passive. }
10. d4 { As usual, we take control over the center when we are allowed to. }
10... Nbd7 11. Nbd2
{ This is a temporary square for the Knight as it is heading to g3. } 11... c5
{ This is quite an interesting version of Breyer with a pinch of Chigorin. Black is in no hurry with developing his light-squared Bishop because, once d4-d5 is played, he prefers to keep on the h3-c8 diagonal. }
12. Nf1
{ On the other hand, White doesn't need to prepare Nf1-g3 now as the Pawn on e4 is only attacked by the black Knight and not by the Bishop. }
12... Re8
{ I can't think of any other move with an independent value. The black Rook makes room for the Bishop but it will be also very useful on e8 where it can defend the Pawn on e5 and potentially attack the Pawn on e4. }
13. Ng3 Bf8 { It's time to make a call, how shall we continue? } 14. d5
{ A pragmatic decision. Black might have saved a tempo @@StartBracket@@by skipping Bc8-b7@@EndBracket@@ but he will still suffer looking for any other plan than defending. }
14... c4
{ We will later discuss that c5-c4 is usually stronger when White had already played a2-a4. }
15. Bc2 Qc7 16. Be3 a5
{ Black's plan of advancing an a Pawn makes a lot of sense but I will explain it soon. }
17. Nd2 a4
{ Stopping a2-a4. White has a tough choice now - if he decides to close the queenside with a2-a3 then it will not be so easy to attack on the Kingside. Notice that Black hasn't played g7-g6 so there are no obvious targets. }
18. b3
{ Of course, this does not come for free as the position will simplify. But at the end of the day, Black will always be slightly worse as he has to deal with the passivity of his pieces as well as a weak Pawn on d6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. Ruy Lopez Breyer"]
[Black "Breyer 9...Nb8 − 11...Re8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Be7
{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6.Re1 is better than 6.d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6.d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 d6
{ A general rule is that if Black doesn't want to go for the Marshall Gambit, he should play 7...d6 before castling as it avoids some Anti-Marshall lines, mainly  8.a4  where Black can now simply go  8...Bd7  . }
8. c3
{ White is preparing d2-d4 but also securing his light-squared Bishop against  8...Na5  - we can now go  9.Bc2  . }
8... O-O 9. h3
{ Before advancing the d-pawn it is useful to cover the g4-square. The immediate  9.d4  allows  9...Bg4  leading to interesting play but - once again speaking in concepts - it would be a small victory for Black. }
9... Nb8
{ The Breyer Variation has always been considered one of the most solid openings for Black. But solidity is not its only virtue - it is also very flexible. Therefore it quickly became one of the favorite shelters for players who wanted to avoid a sharp fight right after the opening without compromising Black's position.   The main idea of Black's last move is to improve the position of the Knight as it will be much safer and sounder on d7. It is also good news for the light-squared Bishop as, once it is developed on b7, it won't be covered by that Knight.   But all of this, along with the further follow-up @@StartBracket@@Rf8-e8 and Be7-f8 and very likely g7-g6 and Bf8-g7@@EndBracket@@ has been well known for decades. I see this as one of the main disadvantages of the Breyer - its once hidden and often misunderstood subtleties are now comprehensible for the majority of players.   The other one is purely chess-related - The line is simply passive. }
10. d4 { As usual, we take control over the center when we are allowed to. }
10... Nbd7 11. Nbd2
{ This is a temporary square for the Knight as it is heading to g3. } 11... Re8
{ Boris Spassky, the tenth World Champion, was the first famous player to get away with this tragic blunder in the last game of his training match against Judit Polgar in 1993. Alexei Shirov was not so lucky as he lost the queen to Greg Shahade in Titled Tuesday, 2020. }
12. Bxf7+ Kxf7 13. Ng5+ Kg8 14. Ne6
{ White's follow-up is pretty clear, I think. } *

