6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 d6
{ A general rule is that if Black doesn't want to go for the Marshall Gambit, he should play 7...d6 before castling as it avoids some Anti-Marshall lines, mainly  8.a4  where Black can now simply go  8...Bd7  . }
8. c3
{ White is preparing d2-d4 but also securing his light-squared Bishop against  8...Na5  - we can now go  9.Bc2  . }
8... O-O 9. h3
{ Before advancing the d-pawn it is useful to cover the g4-square. The immediate  9.d4  allows  9...Bg4  leading to interesting play but - once again speaking in concepts - it would be a small victory for Black. }
9... Nb8
{ The Breyer Variation has always been considered one of the most solid openings for Black. But solidity is not its only virtue - it is also very flexible. Therefore it quickly became one of the favorite shelters for players who wanted to avoid a sharp fight right after the opening without compromising Black's position.   The main idea of Black's last move is to improve the position of the Knight as it will be much safer and sounder on d7. It is also good news for the light-squared Bishop as, once it is developed on b7, it won't be covered by that Knight.   But all of this, along with the further follow-up @@StartBracket@@Rf8-e8 and Be7-f8 and very likely g7-g6 and Bf8-g7@@EndBracket@@ has been well known for decades. I see this as one of the main disadvantages of the Breyer - its once hidden and often misunderstood subtleties are now comprehensible for the majority of players.   The other one is purely chess-related - The line is simply passive. }
10. d4 { As usual, we take control over the center when we are allowed to. }
10... Nbd7 11. Nbd2
{ This is a temporary square for the Knight as it is heading to g3. } 11... Bb7
{ The main continuation. Black is developing the Bishop to a natural square targeting our central Pawn. }
12. Bc2
{ It is necessary to do this as we want to be able to move the Knight from d2. }
12... c5
{ The main point of advancing c7-c5 before moving the dark-squared Bishop to g7 is that after d4-d5 it can be moved to b6 instead which, I admit, makes a lot of sense. However, at the same time, White can skip the whole plan of moving the Knight to g3 as it will be more useful on the queenside. }
13. d5 c4 { Otherwise White would play b2-b3. } 14. b3
{ This is much stronger than  14.Nf1  Qc7  - notice that Black can now move the f8-Rook to the queenside instead of the cliché Rf8-e8. }
14... cxb3 15. axb3 Qc7 { The Pawn is hanging. } 16. Bb2 Rfb8
{ Black wants to move the Bishop to c8 and later to d7 so that explains why 16...Rfc8 would be wrong. }
17. Rc1
{ A couple of plans were possible here but this is my favorite - White is preparing b3-b4 and c3-c4.   The immediate  17.b4  would be met with  17...Nb6  , but now @@StartFEN@@rr4k1/1bqnbppp/p2p1n2/1p1Pp3/4P3/1PP2N1P/1BBN1PP1/R2QR1K1 w - - 3 17@@EndFEN@@  17.Rc1  Nb6?!  can be answered with  18.Bd3!  followed by c3-c4. It means that the Knight should remain on d7. }
17... Bc8
{ 17...a5  was also possible - after  18.b4  Nb6  19.Bd3  Bc8  we would transpose to the main line. }
18. b4 { There was no point waiting any longer. } 18... Nb6 19. Bd3
{ White's Bishop has covered c4 and we are now threatening Nb3-a5. } 19... Bd7
{ This is too passive. } 20. Nb3 Nc4
{ Otherwise the Knight would come to a5 followed by Nf3-d2 and c3-c4. } 21.
Bxc4 bxc4 22. Na5
{ The Rook shall come back to a1 which will allow us to improve the Bishop's position with Bb2-c1. Black has no active plan and he needs to watch out for his c4-Pawn and also for a possible attack on the Kingside @@StartBracket@@g2-g4 might be possible at some point@@EndBracket@@. }
