{ Why develop the Bishop to such a strange square? Let me answer this one -  15.Be3  is not really an option because the Bishop is covering the Rook so after  15...exd4  White can't recapture  16.cxd4  as it would cost us the Pawn on e4.   15.Bg5!?  h6  16.Bd2  is another interesting line, where White wants to provoke h7-h6 as it weakens the position of the black King. We, however, don't want to provoke it but rather prevent it as then both Bh6 and Bg5 will be at our disposal and both of them can be useful.   It is also worth noting that tempi are not so important anymore because both sides don't really have a lot of good moves - almost every choice is connected with creating some target for the opponent: a2-a4 weakens a4 and b3, c7-c5 weakens d5, d6, and also allows d4-d5 @@StartBracket@@otherwise there would be c7-c6@@EndBracket@@ and so on... }
15... Bg7
{ I will not discuss  15...h6  as it simply transposes to the 15.Bg5 h6 16.Bd2 line with an extra tempo for White. }
16. Qc1
{ So we have got it! If Black doesn't do anything we will simply play Bd2-h6. Strategically, it is a good trade for White as Black will not be able to cover some dark squares in his camp: h6, f6 but also a5 will become weak. In case of c7-c5, he would also have to deal with the weakness on d6. }
16... d5
{ Firm reaction but Black will now have to be accurate all the way to the end. }
17. Bg5 { White is increasing the pressure in the center. } 17... dxe4
{ The desire to release the tension is understandable but Black shouldn't have succumbed to it. }
18. Bxe4
{ Usually we don't have this luxury so the move might seem odd but Black's light-squared Bishop is his strongest piece so why not get rid of it? }
18... c6 { 18...Bxe4  19.Nxe4  would be clearly better for White. } 19. Nh5
{ This is a great shot!  19.Bxg6  might look like a simple choice but after  19...hxg6  20.dxe5  Nxe5  21.Nxe5  Qd5  22.Qf4  c5  White is forced to retreat the Knight. After  23.Nf3  Ne4  would give Black at least a partial compensation for the Pawn. }
19... gxh5 20. dxe5 Nxe5 { Or  20...Rxe5  leading to the same position. } 21.
Nxe5 Rxe5 22. Bxh7+
{ 19.Nh5 might have seen elaborate but it was laid on pretty basic foundations. }
22... Kxh7 23. Rxe5
{ Materially, the position is balanced but all of White's pieces are superior to the opponent's. }
23... Qd6 24. Qc2+ { It is hard for the black King to find a good shelter. }
24... Kg8 25. Bf4
{ As soon as the Queen escaped from the pin it is getting x-rayed. } 25... Rf8
{ This stops 26.Re8+ while managing to keep the pieces in play.   25...Qf8  would be much worse as after  26.Rae1  the dominance of the white pieces would become overwhelming. }
26. Rd1 { Finally the rook comes into play. } 26... Nd5
{ There was no choice, after  26...Qc7  many moves would win for White. The simple and logical  27.Rd3  , planning 28.Rg3, would be one of them. }
27. Rexd5 Qxf4 28. Rxh5
{ White is threatening mate in one so Black doesn't really have a choice. }
28... Re8 29. Qh7+ Kf8 30. Rf5
{ Notice how energetic White's play is, Black has no time to catch a breath! }
30... Qh6 31. Qxh6 Bxh6 32. f4
{ White has both material and positional advantage. We should continue with g2-g4 anticipating a possible activation of the light-squared Bishop via c8. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. Ruy Lopez Breyer"]
[Black "Breyer 9...Nb8 − 11...Bb7 #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ Besides the obvious idea - winning the Bishop - Black's last move is useful for another reason - sooner or later Black might want to go b7-b5, making the b7-square available for his light-squared Bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ Black is developing the Knight to the most natural square. The Knight is already attacking the e4-pawn. }
5. O-O
{ For the author, of course, it is much easier to recommend  5.d3  , thus eliminating all the big scary systems. When preparing for this course, I had two main goals in mind:   1. I wanted the presented variations to be a real challenge for Black. The widespread availability of chess engines showing equality in each line does not mean that we have to give up the fight for an advantage in the opening. It only makes this task more difficult.   2. Playing the main systems is an extremely important factor in chess development. Due to the multitude of variations, the Ruy Lopez is an extremely developing opening.   No other opening has so many different plans, pawn structures, etc. It would be a great pity to deprive you of all of that with some clever dodge. I want this course not only to help you understand the Ruy Lopez @@StartBracket@@and other openings@@EndBracket@@ but also to help you become better players. }
5... Be7
{ No more Open, no more Moller-Arkhangelsk, but still this natural move doesn't really show Black's intentions, besides castling. }
6. Re1
{ Once again, many would recommend  6.d3  but we are not trying to avoid anything. Speaking in concepts - 6.Re1 is better than 6.d3 because the perfect setup for White is to build a strong pawn center with c2-c3 and d2-d4.   6.d3 doesn't really help much in this matter. One more thing to notice - White is now threatening Bxc6 and Nxe5. }
6... b5
{ It's about time to do this, as I said - White was already threatening 7.Bxc6. }
7. Bb3 d6
{ A general rule is that if Black doesn't want to go for the Marshall Gambit, he should play 7...d6 before castling as it avoids some Anti-Marshall lines, mainly  8.a4  where Black can now simply go  8...Bd7  . }
8. c3
{ White is preparing d2-d4 but also securing his light-squared Bishop against  8...Na5  - we can now go  9.Bc2  . }
8... O-O 9. h3
{ Before advancing the d-pawn it is useful to cover the g4-square. The immediate  9.d4  allows  9...Bg4  leading to interesting play but - once again speaking in concepts - it would be a small victory for Black. }
9... Nb8
{ The Breyer Variation has always been considered one of the most solid openings for Black. But solidity is not its only virtue - it is also very flexible. Therefore it quickly became one of the favorite shelters for players who wanted to avoid a sharp fight right after the opening without compromising Black's position.   The main idea of Black's last move is to improve the position of the Knight as it will be much safer and sounder on d7. It is also good news for the light-squared Bishop as, once it is developed on b7, it won't be covered by that Knight.   But all of this, along with the further follow-up @@StartBracket@@Rf8-e8 and Be7-f8 and very likely g7-g6 and Bf8-g7@@EndBracket@@ has been well known for decades. I see this as one of the main disadvantages of the Breyer - its once hidden and often misunderstood subtleties are now comprehensible for the majority of players.   The other one is purely chess-related - The line is simply passive. }
10. d4 { As usual, we take control over the center when we are allowed to. }
10... Nbd7 11. Nbd2
{ This is a temporary square for the Knight as it is heading to g3. } 11... Bb7
{ The main continuation. Black is developing the Bishop to a natural square targeting our central Pawn. }
12. Bc2
{ It is necessary to do it as we want to be able to move the Knight from d2. }
12... Re8 { Starting a typical maneuver of fianchettoing the Bishop. } 13. Nf1
{ Finally the Knight can move. } 13... Bf8 14. Ng3 g6
{ Apart from a couple of sidelines which we had already seen, this is basically the starting position of the Breyer with thousands of games and numerous plans for both sides.   Learning and understanding those plans should be an important part of development for every chess player. Nonetheless, this is not the topic of the course so let's move on. }
15. Bd2
{ Why develop the Bishop to such a strange square? Let me answer this one -  15.Be3  is not really an option because the Bishop is covering the Rook so after  15...exd4  White can't recapture  16.cxd4  as it would cost us the Pawn on e4.   15.Bg5!?  h6  16.Bd2  is another interesting line, where White wants to provoke h7-h6 as it weakens the position of the black King. We, however, don't want to provoke it but rather prevent it as then both Bh6 and Bg5 will be at our disposal and both of them can be useful.   It is also worth noting that tempi are not so important anymore because both sides don't really have a lot of good moves - almost every choice is connected with creating some target for the opponent: a2-a4 weakens a4 and b3, c7-c5 weakens d5, d6, and also allows d4-d5 @@StartBracket@@otherwise there would be c7-c6@@EndBracket@@ and so on... }
15... Bg7
{ I will not discuss  15...h6  as it simply transposes to the 15.Bg5 h6 16.Bd2 line with an extra tempo for White. }
16. Qc1
{ So we have got it! If Black doesn't do anything we will simply play Bd2-h6. Strategically, it is a good trade for White as Black will not be able to cover some dark squares in his camp: h6, f6 but also a5 will become weak. In case of c7-c5, he would also have to deal with the weakness on d6. }
16... d5
{ Firm reaction but Black will now have to be accurate all the way to the end. }
17. Bg5 { White is increasing the pressure in the center. } 17... h6
{ This is a classical example of distraction but also a very risky-looking decision. I assume that whoever plays this novelty first, it will not be an effect of over the board contemplation. }
18. Bxh6 dxe4 19. Bxe4
{ White could try  19.Nxe5  Nxe5  20.dxe5  Rxe5  21.Bf4  but our line is simpler. }
19... Nxe4 20. Bxg7 { 20.Nxe4  exd4  21.Bxg7  Kxg7  is the same. } 20... Kxg7
{ 20...Nxg3??  would instantly lose to  21.Qh6! } 21. Nxe4 exd4
{ 21...f5  22.Neg5  e4  23.Nh2  and Black would be nowhere near a decent compensation. Now White can't recapture on d4 as the Knight is hanging. }
22. Neg5 Bxf3 { The Knight on g5 was too powerful so Black drags it to f3. }
23. Nxf3 Rxe1+
{ Black is trying to simplify the position hoping that the limited material will make it easier for him. This is quite often a good approach but not in this case. White will now smoothly activate his pieces forcing his opponent to a passive defense. }
24. Qxe1 dxc3 25. Qxc3+ Nf6 26. Rc1
{ Dragging the black Rook to a passive square. } 26... Rc8 27. g4
{ We are threatening to win a piece so the King has to retreat. } 27... Kg8 28.
Qc6
{ The point of White's previous move, Black can't really move any of the pieces so the Pawn on a6 will fall. }
*

