4. d3 Bc5
{ This is the main continuation and you are twice as likely to meet it, compared with  4...d6  . Black develops the Bishop to the best possible square. }
5. Bxc6
{ By taking on c6 in this particular moment, we are forcing Black to recapture with the d7-Pawn. The resulting Pawn structure will favor White who only has one Pawn island but it won't be easy to take advantage of it due to the closed character of the position.   What I really like about this line is that we actually can forget our moves and still get a decent position. Let's not cheat ourselves - The Berlin Defense might be the hottest choice out there for the 2700 club but the lower we get the less popular it becomes.   Therefore, having a good but not-too-difficult line seems like the perfect choice. But don't get me wrong - I am very serious about challenging the Berlin so there will be no shortcuts in our repertoire. }
5... dxc6
{ 5...bxc6?  is possible in some lines but here it simply drops a Pawn after  6.Nxe5  . The main assumption of this line @@StartBracket@@after 5...dxc6@@EndBracket@@ is that White has a better Pawn structure.   Perhaps it's an exaggeration but it's easier to navigate White's Pawns. On the other hand, Black has a Bishop pair, which should not be underestimated even in a rather closed position. }
6. O-O
{ This has become very popular in recent years - almost all the top 1.e4 players in the world have included this move into their repertoire!   Before we go through Black's possible answers, let's discuss the main differences between  6.O-O  and the 'normal'  6.Nbd2  , which historically has been a much more popular continuation. The first and obvious difference is: White can no longer castle queenside.   This is actually quite a serious drawback as the biggest development in the 6.Nbd2 line in recent years was precisely the long castle plan.   The second difference: the Pawn on e5 is hanging - Black no longer has Qd8-d4 so he has to do something about it.   The third one is: the Knight is still on b1. It might sound dull but we can actually benefit from it - White can put the Bishop on g5 or try c3-d4 in some cases. Now moving on to Black's replies, he can defend the Pawn in five ways:  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2ppp/2p2n2/2b1p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bd6  ,  6...Qd6  ,  6...Qe7  ,  6...Nd7  and  6...Bg4  . We will consider them all. }
6... Qe7 { This move is usually connected with Bc8-g4. } 7. Nbd2 a5
{ A rare but interesting continuation - a7-a5 is a useful move but Black's point is more than that - he wants to play Nd7 while avoiding the c2-c3 and d3-d4 plan. }
8. Nc4 { 8.c3  would be answered with  8...Bg4  . } 8... Nd7 9. Ne3 f6
{ Black doesn't want to exchange his dark-squared Bishop so he prefers to anticipate our next move. }
10. Nf5 Qf7 11. Re1
{ We are deliberately delaying Bc1-e3 - after the immediate  11.Be3  g6!  would be fine for Black. He can now place the Knight on b6 or f8. We will consider both these possibilities. }
11... Nb6
{ There is nothing special about the Knight on b6 but it is certainly a faster way of finishing development. }
12. Bd2
{ Black's intention was to take on f5 and then castle long. Therefore, we are attacking the Pawn on a5 in advance. }
12... Bxf5
{ 12...O-O  could be replied with  13.N3h4  or even  13.g4!?  with good chances on the kingside. }
13. exf5 O-O 14. Be3
{ The Bishop did its job on d2. If Black takes  14...Bxe3  then we recapture with  15.fxe3  . We can then play e3-e4 and start thinking about g2-g4-g5. Claiming that White is better might be an exaggeration here but our position is definitely nicer and easier to handle. }
