1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ @@StartBlockQuote@@The Berlin Defense - one of the most hated openings among White players. @@EndBlockQuote@@   Let me explain how I choose the line and why I rejected the alternatives. The most natural attempt to challenge the Berlin Wall would be to go for the endgame after  4.O-O  Nxe4  5.d4  Nd6  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  . I quickly rejected it for a couple of reasons:   a@@EndBracket@@ Due to the specific Pawn structure the endgame is incredibly complex and hence requires deep understanding. This means that absorbing even the best opening lines will not be enough to succeed. Long story short, in order to do it right I would have to make a separate course for the Berlin Defense alone.   b@@EndBracket@@ Let's say we analyze the Caro-Kann Defense. While going through the lines we slowly begin to understand the Pawn structures. We actually realize that in some lines the structures resemble the ones we had learned from playing the Slav Defense. There are some nuances that might favor White or Black, depending on the position. Understanding these nuances makes us feel stronger, we actually feel that by learning the Caro-Kann structures we are becoming a better player in other openings too! This won't be the case for the Berlin Endgame. Its Pawn structure is simply too unique, and we are not really going to see it in other openings.   c@@EndBracket@@ The amount of theory is staggering. Black has plenty of playable lines which makes doing all this work even less practical.   d@@EndBracket@@ We are deliberately going for an endgame before move 10. I imagine for quite a good part of you this is a 'no-go'. :-@@EndBracket@@   The second possible line would be  4.O-O  Nxe4  5.Re1  . That was also an easy decision - most of the lines are simply boring. The engines might get excited once in a while screaming 'it's +0.31!' but really it's just symmetry and even if White does get an initiative once in a while it is usually faint.   I was seriously considering  4.d3  Bc5  5.c3  but the problem is that Black is just doing okay in the d7-d5 lines and it is not easy to challenge it. This left me with only one choice left. }
4. d3 Bc5
{ This is the main continuation and you are twice as likely to meet it, compared with  4...d6  . Black develops the Bishop to the best possible square. }
5. Bxc6
{ By taking on c6 in this particular moment, we are forcing Black to recapture with the d7-Pawn. The resulting Pawn structure will favor White who only has one Pawn island but it won't be easy to take advantage of it due to the closed character of the position.   What I really like about this line is that we actually can forget our moves and still get a decent position. Let's not cheat ourselves - The Berlin Defense might be the hottest choice out there for the 2700 club but the lower we get the less popular it becomes.   Therefore, having a good but not-too-difficult line seems like the perfect choice. But don't get me wrong - I am very serious about challenging the Berlin so there will be no shortcuts in our repertoire. }
5... dxc6
{ 5...bxc6?  is possible in some lines but here it simply drops a Pawn after  6.Nxe5  . The main assumption of this line @@StartBracket@@after 5...dxc6@@EndBracket@@ is that White has a better Pawn structure.   Perhaps it's an exaggeration but it's easier to navigate White's Pawns. On the other hand, Black has a Bishop pair, which should not be underestimated even in a rather closed position. }
6. O-O
{ This has become very popular in recent years - almost all the top 1.e4 players in the world have included this move into their repertoire!   Before we go through Black's possible answers, let's discuss the main differences between  6.O-O  and the 'normal'  6.Nbd2  , which historically has been a much more popular continuation. The first and obvious difference is: White can no longer castle queenside.   This is actually quite a serious drawback as the biggest development in the 6.Nbd2 line in recent years was precisely the long castle plan.   The second difference: the Pawn on e5 is hanging - Black no longer has Qd8-d4 so he has to do something about it.   The third one is: the Knight is still on b1. It might sound dull but we can actually benefit from it - White can put the Bishop on g5 or try c3-d4 in some cases. Now moving on to Black's replies, he can defend the Pawn in five ways:  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2ppp/2p2n2/2b1p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bd6  ,  6...Qd6  ,  6...Qe7  ,  6...Nd7  and  6...Bg4  . We will consider them all. }
6... Qe7 { This move is usually connected with Bc8-g4. } 7. Nbd2 Bg4 8. h3 Bh5
{ 8...Bxf3  9.Qxf3  would be better for White - I think I have already mentioned that exchanging the light-squared Bishop is generally not recommended for Black. }
9. a3
{ This is one of the recent developments in the line. White wants to play b2-b4 and he can't really be stopped! }
9... a6
{ An interesting choice with quite a lot of potential as Black keeps long castle as an option. }
10. Qe2
{ The beginning of a new plan in this position. It is important to start with 10.Qe2 - after  10.b4  Ba7  11.Qe2?!  Black has the surprising  11...g5! }
10... Nd7 { Black is doing his typical maneuver - Nd7-f8-e6. } 11. b4 Ba7 12.
Nb3
{ After  12.Nc4  f6  the Knight is not really useful so I figured maybe we can try Nb3-c5 instead? }
12... f6
{ We can now demonstrate why the Knight is more useful on b3 than c4. } 13. Be3
Bxe3 14. Qxe3 { White is threatening Nf3-h4 so... } 14... Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Nf8
{ Imagine that the Knight is on c4 instead of b3 - quite a difference, isn't it? }
16. d4
{ Opening up the position makes sense as White is ahead in development. } 16...
exd4 17. Nxd4
{ White has a slight advantage. After  17...O-O-O  we can go  18.Nf5  Qf7  and then we can either try  19.a4  or the calmer  19.Qg4  Rd7  20.Rad1  - remember that we do have a better pawn structure with 4 vs. 3 on the kingside. }
*

