6... Bg4
{ Objectively, this might be the strongest continuation. However, it is inextricably linked with the piece sacrifice and not everybody likes starting the game with piece sacs even if they are correct.   Besides, choosing such a sharp line results in a smaller margin of error, again - not to everyone's taste. Probably for these reasons we don't really see this line in practice.   We are not actually allowing this sacrifice as I want to propose another possibility, something a bit less extreme. }
7. Bg5
{ I see no reason why this can't be played - Black pinned our Knight, let's do the same with his. }
7... h6
{ Anyway this will be played sooner or later so no point in delaying it. } 8.
Bh4 Qe7
{ The most precise way of developing the pieces for Black - wait with g7-g5. }
9. Nbd2 O-O-O 10. Bg3
{ I didn't really see any other move for White. It is also worth noticing that  10.h3  Bh5  11.Bg3  wouldn't be as accurate - Black can try  11...g5!?  12.Bxe5  Rhg8  with nice compensation for the pawn. }
10... Nd7
{ Now Black is threatening h6-h5-h4 so it's the perfect time to go h2-h3. } 11.
h3 Bh5 12. c3
{ If you were wondering what Black can gain from skipping g7-g5 then here comes the answer... }
12... a6
{ I am not really sure if this is an improvement for Black but it's certainly an additional option and something we should reckon with as the Bishop on g1-a7 diagonal is quite strong. }
13. b4 Ba7 14. a4
{ What I like about this line is that - apart from a couple of nuances - White basically has one, simple plan. }
14... g5 { Black has to start his own attack. } 15. Qc2
{ 15.b5  Nc5  would be unclear, we should remember that d3 is a weakness. }
15... Bxf3
{ Not the nicest move I can think of but it allows Black to move the Pawns. }
16. Nxf3 h5 17. h4
{ A typical way of stopping Black's attack on the Kingside. } 17... f6
{ After  17...Rdg8  instead of  18.Nxg5??  dropping the piece after  18...f6!  19.Nf3  Rxg3  , we would react with calm @@StartFEN@@2k3rr/bppnqp2/p1p5/4p1pp/PP2P2P/2PP1NB1/2Q2PP1/R4RK1 w - - 1 18@@EndFEN@@  18.Kh1!  gxh4  19.Nxh4  with advantage. }
18. Rfd1
{ White is slightly better. We can hope for one of two ideas: b4-b5 or d3-d4 or perhaps both of them. Black's attack is more or less stopped so he has to start anticipating our plans. }
