d4 { Black can't take on d4 due to e4-e5. } 8... Bg4
{ Using the pin Black manages to keep the Pawn on e5. It is worth noting that  8...Nd7  would be terrible now. After  9.Nbd2  White has an overwhelming advantage. }
9. Nbd2 { Threatening Nd2-c4. } 9... Nd7
{ By developing the Knight Black also protects the Pawns. It is now possible for him to castle queenside as well. }
10. Nc4 Qe6
{ It might be tempting for Black to attack the Knight back. However, by retreating to e6 Black missed a little trick. }
11. Nxb6 axb6 12. Ng5
{ The punishment is limited as we are not really winning any material but the resulting endgame will be nice enough. }
12... Bxd1 { There was no alternative to this one. } 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. Rxd1
{ White has a very nice Pawn center and virtually no weaknesses. The black Knight struggles to find the right place on board while the black queenside Pawns, especially the one on c7, might become good targets at some point. We can finish the development with 15.Be3.   Strengthening the control over the center with f2-f3 seems like a good idea as well. Notice that seemingly active f2-f4 would only weaken the light squares - the critical Pawn on e4 could no longer be defended by another Pawn making it a great target for the Knight. }
