{ This is an important moment - Black's position looks solid and if we don't come up with something, he will finish his development and basically equalize. }
11. a4
{ This move combines two ideas. The first one is pretty clear - White threatens a4-a5 winning the Bishop. The other one is not so obvious - in case of short castle we want to have b2-b3 and Bc1-a3 and for this, it is very useful to include a4 and a5.  The Bishop will be defended by the Rook as well and also in some lines we can take on b6 and Black can't recapture with the a7-Pawn. In order to fully understand these nuances see theline after 11.h3. }
11... exd4
{ This is wrong on a fundamental basis - Black gives away the center while getting nothing in return. }
12. a5
{ Important intermezzo - after  12.cxd4  Bxf3  13.gxf3  a5  Black would be fine. }
12... Bxf3 13. gxf3
{ 13.Qxf3  Bc5  14.b4  would also be nice, but I think the text move is stronger. }
13... Bc5 14. cxd4
{ White has a huge advantage in the center and is ahead of in development. But for Black the main problem is that he cannot stop a5-a6 weakening his pawn structure. }
14... Qe6 { Or  14...Bd6  15.a6  with a big advantage. } 15. Qd3 Bd6 16. a6
{ Black has no good answer to this one - after  16...b5  both  17.Nxd6+  and  17.Na5  are strong.   16...b6  can be answered with  17.f4!  and 18.f5 is a serious threat. In all these lines White preserves solid advantage. }
