{ This has become very popular in recent years - almost all the top 1.e4 players in the world have included this move into their repertoire!   Before we go through Black's possible answers, let's discuss the main differences between  6.O-O  and the 'normal'  6.Nbd2  , which historically has been a much more popular continuation. The first and obvious difference is: White can no longer castle queenside.   This is actually quite a serious drawback as the biggest development in the 6.Nbd2 line in recent years was precisely the long castle plan.   The second difference: the Pawn on e5 is hanging - Black no longer has Qd8-d4 so he has to do something about it.   The third one is: the Knight is still on b1. It might sound dull but we can actually benefit from it - White can put the Bishop on g5 or try c3-d4 in some cases. Now moving on to Black's replies, he can defend the Pawn in five ways:  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2ppp/2p2n2/2b1p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bd6  ,  6...Qd6  ,  6...Qe7  ,  6...Nd7  and  6...Bg4  . We will consider them all. }
6... Qd6 { In my opinion, this is not really a good square for the Queen. } 7.
c3
{ Now d3-d4 is a threat. This, relatively fresh plan, is especially strong against the Queen on d6 as normally Black puts the Knight on d7 and after d3-d4 retreats with the Bishop to d6. As we know, two pieces cannot occupy the same square. }
7... Bg4 8. Nbd2 Qxd3
{ This line is technically correct though it has a major practical downside - Black can only play for a draw from now on. }
9. Nxe5 { Using an old trick. } 9... Qe2 { Other moves lose instantly. } 10.
Nxg4 { 10.Qxe2  Bxe2  11.Re1  would be weaker as Black has  11...Ng4! } 10...
Qxg4 11. Qxg4
{ 11.e5  might be one more reason for Black to choose some other line instead:  11...Qxd1  12.Rxd1  Nd7  13.Nf3  O-O-O  14.Bg5  Rde8  15.Bf4  and White has achieved quite a decent version of the Berlin wall - these structures are usually riskier for Black when the King is on the queenside as it is easier for White to advance his kingside Pawns. }
11... Nxg4 12. Nb3 Bb6
{ This is stronger than  12...Be7  13.Bf4  O-O-O  14.f3  with advantage. } 13.
c4 { The Black Bishop is too strong to tolerate it. } 13... a5
{ Not only making room for the Bishop but also preparing a strong counterplay - a5-a4. }
14. c5 Ba7 { We can't keep the Pawn on c5 for long. } 15. h3 Nf6
{ 15...Ne5  16.Nxa5  O-O-O  17.Be3  would be easily better for White. } 16.
Nxa5 Bxc5 17. Nxb7 { No need to worry about the Knight. } 17... Be7
{ Retreating the Bishop to a passive square is counterintuitive but it makes perfect sense - Black doesn't need any pieces on the b-file other than his own Rook.   Let's quickly see the alternatives:  17...Nxe4  is possible but after  18.Nxc5  Nxc5  19.Be3  White is slightly better.   Trying to catch the Knight with  17...Bb6?  would only cause Black problems after  18.a4! }
18. Be3
{ There was no point in defending the Pawn on e4 - after  18.Re1  O-O  followed by 19...Rfb8 Black has no problems. }
18... Nxe4 19. Rfe1 O-O
{ There is no way to benefit from this x-ray but also this is not obvious for Black. After  19...Nd6  20.Nc5  White could still hope for an advantage. }
20. Bd4 f5 21. f3
{ After  21...c5  22.Bc3  or  21...Bf6  22.Bxf6  Nxf6  23.Nxc5  White is slightly better but Black has another way. }
21... Ra4 22. Bf2 Rb8 23. fxe4 Rxb7 24. exf5
{ White preserves a small pressure but Black should be able to maintain the balance with careful play. The 3 vs. 2 Rook endgame seems quite likely. }
