{ 14...Qd7  would give White a pleasant edge after  15.Nxg4  Nxg4  16.Nh4  taking control over the critical d5 square. }
15. Bh4 Qe7 16. Nf5
{ 16.g3!?  intending 17.Kg2 is also possible if one has a more positional approach. }
16... Bxf5 17. exf5 O-O-O
{ White has a superior pawn structure but we have to careful - Black's position has some potential - there is a g-file as well as e5-e4. }
18. Re1
{ Black's Knight is pinned and it can't be easily unpinned. We now want to play Re1-e4! and then slowly improve with Qd1-e2. Black has to come up with something extraordinary in order to stay in the game. }
18... Rg4
{ Now not only 19...Rdg8 is a threat but also 19...e4!? Additionally White has to reckon with possible Rg4xh4 ideas for example:  19.Kf1?!  Rxh4!  20.Nxh4  Ng4  21.Nf3  Bc5  with a strong initiative. }
19. Re4 { It's nice to have this one! } 19... Rxh4 { Nevertheless! } 20. Rxh4
e4
{ The point. We shouldn't try to keep the exchange as Black's compensation is real. }
21. dxe4 Bh2+ { Quite primitive but effective. } 22. Kxh2 Rxd1 23. Rxd1 Nxe4
24. Rxh5
{ The last couple of moves were forced so there was no need to comment. White's chances are slightly preferable simply because we have a material advantage.   Instead of trying to improve let's just try to keep control - Black's Queen is passive now but it can become active fairly easily so it's better to be prepared.   Our next move @@StartBracket@@assuming Black doesn't blunder mate on h8@@EndBracket@@ should be 25.Re1. }
