{ It seems like the only reasonable independent plan. The Knight is not so well placed on b6 but on the other hand it restricts the white Knight as well. }
12. Re1
{ This is not an automatic developing move - the Rook protects the central Pawn, makes room for the Knight, but also prevents a typical plan that for instance  12.Bg3  would allow:  12...exd4  13.cxd4  f5! }
12... a5
{ This strong move was played by the Iranian talent Maghsadloo during his 2020 Speed Chess Match against Grischuk. }
13. Bg3 a4
{ Black is gaining space on the queenside and is also taking control over the b3-square. }
14. h3
{ This move is not necessary but it is useful. It is exactly the kind of position where we should be making useful moves since for both sides it is very difficult to advance. }
14... c5 15. b3
{ Another useful move - the Pawn takes control over the c4-square supporting the possible d4xe5 and c3-c4 idea. Also, the Rook can now leave a1 not worrying about the Pawn on a2 @@StartBracket@@after something like Bc8-e6 or Qe8-f7@@EndBracket@@. We can now take on e5, put the Queen on e2, and then choose between c3-c4 and Nf3-h4.   Another idea is to place the Rook on c1 increasing the pressure on Black - he has to constantly look after his Pawn on e5 and he does not really want to take on d4, especially with our Rook on c1. }
