{ A few years back we would call this plan 'unusual' but not anymore. White is preparing c3-d4. }
7... O-O 8. d4 Bd6 { The center is ours but Black's position remains solid. }
9. Bg5
{ Black now has to decide whether he will go f7-f6 or try to avoid it. Our Bishop will end up on g3 regardless. }
9... f6 10. Bh4 Qe7
{ It is not the main move but just to keep clarity I will anyway use this move order in the lines involving Rf8-e8 plans. }
11. Nbd2 Re8
{ I will show this line as an example of how we can react if Black decides to skip a7-a5. }
12. Qc2 { We develop the same way. } 12... Qf7 13. Bg3
{ Again the Bishop is no longer useful on h4 so we retreat. Now  13...a5  14.Rfe1  would transpose to our line. But what if Black skips a7-a5? }
13... Nf8 14. dxe5 fxe5 15. Ng5 { We are going to use the a2-g8 diagonal now. }
15... Qe7 16. Qb3+ Ne6 { Basically the only move. } 17. Nxe6 Qxe6
{ 17...Bxe6  would be met by  18.Qxb7  with advantage. You might now ask 'Hey, why won't we go Nf3-g5 with Rf1-e1 and a7-a5 included?!'. }
18. Nc4 a5 { It's a bit late now... } 19. Nxd6 { A transformation... } 19...
cxd6 20. Rfd1
{ Attacking the Pawn on d6. After  20...a4  it's best to go  21.Qb4  c5  22.Qb5  . We will double the Rooks on the d-file and enjoy a long-term advantage as the weakness on d6 can't be easily liquidated. }
