{ This is a normal continuation that usually leads to typical Ruy Lopez structures. I believe Black mostly chooses it over  4...Bc5  for one of three reasons:   1. Black simply prefers more classical structures.   2. Black is afraid of the amount of theory after 4...Bc5.   3. Black wants to play for a win and he believes he can outplay his opponent thanks to his superior understanding of Ruy Lopez structures. }
5. O-O
{ We are starting with an important nuance: after  5.c3  Black can play  5...g6  and compared with a normal Steinitz he gained a whole tempo. Therefore, in my opinion,  5.O-O  is more accurate. }
5... g6
{ Some players nevertheless try to develop the Bishop to g7 but it is not so strong anymore. }
6. d4
{ We did waste a tempo for d2-d3 and d3-d4 but we will be able to win it back by playing c2-c4 in one move. }
6... Bd7 7. d5 Nb8
{ After 8.Bxd7+ Black intends to recapture with the Knight. } 8. Bd3
{ Not the only plan but I like it here. It will take some time for Black to regroup. }
8... Bg7 9. c4
{ In the spirit of the King's Indian Defense - our long-term plan will be b2-b4. }
9... a5 { Also quite typical - b2-b4 will be much harder now. } 10. Nc3 Na6 11.
a3 O-O 12. Bc2 Nc5
{ The Knight occupies a perfect square. The question is - for how long? } 13.
b3 { It was necessary to stop a5-a4 first. } 13... Ne8
{ Played with a clear intention - f7-f5. We will discuss the c7-c6 plan in the next variation. }
14. Rb1 f5 15. exf5
{ This is stronger than  15.b4  axb4  16.axb4  Nxe4  17.Nxe4  fxe4  18.Bxe4  Nf6  with mutual chances. }
15... gxf5 16. b4 { Finally... } 16... axb4 17. axb4 e4
{ Black is kicking! After  17...Na6  18.Ng5  White would have a great advantage on both sides. }
18. Bg5 Qc8
{ 18...Bf6  19.bxc5!  Bxg5  20.Nxg5  Qxg5  21.cxd6  would leave Black with an unpleasant choice between  21...Nxd6  22.c5  and @@StartFEN@@r3nrk1/1ppb3p/3P4/3P1pq1/2P1p3/2N5/2B2PPP/1R1Q1RK1 b - - 0 21@@EndFEN@@  21...cxd6  22.Rxb7  . }
19. Nd4 Nd3 { This was Black's hope.  20.Bxd3  will be met with  20...Bxd4  . }
20. Nce2
{ Cool reaction. The Knight on d3 is somewhere between a strength and a problem as it requires protection. }
20... Ra3 21. Bc1
{ Keeping things under control. The more aggressive  21.c5  was also possible. }
21... Nxc1 22. Qxc1 Ra8 { So much for the activity of Black's pieces. } 23. c5
{ White has a clear advantage and he is ready to push the Pawn to c6. } *

