4. d3 d6
{ This is a normal continuation that usually leads to typical Ruy Lopez structures. I believe Black mostly chooses it over  4...Bc5  for one of three reasons:   1. Black simply prefers more classical structures.   2. Black is afraid of the amount of theory after 4...Bc5.   3. Black wants to play for a win and he believes he can outplay his opponent thanks to his superior understanding of Ruy Lopez structures. }
5. O-O
{ We are starting with an important nuance: after  5.c3  Black can play  5...g6  and compared with a normal Steinitz he gained a whole tempo. Therefore, in my opinion,  5.O-O  is more accurate. }
5... g6
{ Some players nevertheless try to develop the Bishop to g7 but it is not so strong anymore. }
6. d4
{ We did waste a tempo for d2-d3 and d3-d4 but we will be able to win it back by playing c2-c4 in one move. }
6... Bd7 7. d5 Ne7 { The most natural retreat. } 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7
{ Recapturing with the Queen might look odd at first - isn't Black trying to play f7-f5? It has however a one advantage - the Knight attacks the Pawn on e4. }
9. Re1 { Not the best square for the Rook but we need to defend our own. } 9...
Bg7 10. c4 O-O 11. Nc3 h6
{ Black wants to move the Knight to h7 and then play f7-f5. } 12. a4 Nh7
{ Moving on with Black's own plan. } 13. a5 f5 14. b4 Nf6 15. Nd2
{ It is important to control the Pawn on e4 but also the Knight might come to c4 one day. The light-squared Bishops are gone which means that Black's attack will never be that strong.   Right now there is no rush for White - we can improve our position with 16.Qb3, 16.Bb2 or even 16.h3. Once f5-f4 is played we can then push the Pawn to c5 - doing it without f5-f4 might cost us the Pawn on d5. }
