{ It is not easy to crack this line but on the other hand Black's position will not be too attractive. }
6. Bxc6+
{ 6.Ba4  b5  7.Bb3  Na5  would be easily fine for Black. If we are to give away our Bishop, let's at least break his pawn structure. }
6... bxc6 7. Re1
{ We don't want to play d3-d4 to early:  7.d4  exd4  8.Nxd4  c5!  is okay for Black. }
7... c5 { Black stops d3-d4 - at least for one move. } 8. c3 Bg4
{ Basically the same as Kramnik did but with the Pawns on c3 and c5 instead of c2 and c6. }
9. h3 Bh5 10. d4 Nd7
{ 11.d5  is weaker  now as White has already committed to c2-c3. } 11. Be3
{ With the Pawn on c5, this is much stronger. Black can now choose which inferior pawn structure he prefers. After  11...Be7  we can just take  12.dxc5  dxc5  and move the Knight to d2 with a nice advantage thanks to Black's doubled pawns. }
