[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ @@StartBlockQuote@@The Berlin Defense - one of the most hated openings among White players. @@EndBlockQuote@@   Let me explain how I choose the line and why I rejected the alternatives. The most natural attempt to challenge the Berlin Wall would be to go for the endgame after  4.O-O  Nxe4  5.d4  Nd6  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  . I quickly rejected it for a couple of reasons:   a@@EndBracket@@ Due to the specific Pawn structure the endgame is incredibly complex and hence requires deep understanding. This means that absorbing even the best opening lines will not be enough to succeed. Long story short, in order to do it right I would have to make a separate course for the Berlin Defense alone.   b@@EndBracket@@ Let's say we analyze the Caro-Kann Defense. While going through the lines we slowly begin to understand the Pawn structures. We actually realize that in some lines the structures resemble the ones we had learned from playing the Slav Defense. There are some nuances that might favor White or Black, depending on the position. Understanding these nuances makes us feel stronger, we actually feel that by learning the Caro-Kann structures we are becoming a better player in other openings too! This won't be the case for the Berlin Endgame. Its Pawn structure is simply too unique, and we are not really going to see it in other openings.   c@@EndBracket@@ The amount of theory is staggering. Black has plenty of playable lines which makes doing all this work even less practical.   d@@EndBracket@@ We are deliberately going for an endgame before move 10. I imagine for quite a good part of you this is a 'no-go'. :-@@EndBracket@@   The second possible line would be  4.O-O  Nxe4  5.Re1  . That was also an easy decision - most of the lines are simply boring. The engines might get excited once in a while screaming 'it's +0.31!' but really it's just symmetry and even if White does get an initiative once in a while it is usually faint.   I was seriously considering  4.d3  Bc5  5.c3  but the problem is that Black is just doing okay in the d7-d5 lines and it is not easy to challenge it. This left me with only one choice left. }
4. d3 d6
{ This is a normal continuation that usually leads to typical Ruy Lopez structures. I believe Black mostly chooses it over  4...Bc5  for one of three reasons:   1. Black simply prefers more classical structures.   2. Black is afraid of the amount of theory after 4...Bc5.   3. Black wants to play for a win and he believes he can outplay his opponent thanks to his superior understanding of Ruy Lopez structures. }
5. O-O
{ We are starting with an important nuance: after  5.c3  Black can play  5...g6  and compared with a normal Steinitz he gained a whole tempo. Therefore, in my opinion,  5.O-O  is more accurate. }
5... Be7
{ Black's logic is that since White has already played d2-d3, any classical Ruy Lopez System such as the Breyer should be an upgrade for Black now. However, this is that not simple and White has strong arguments:  a@@EndBracket@@ the Pawn can stay on d3; it's a perfectly healthy setup that is frequently used from the other move orders as well;   b@@EndBracket@@ h2-h3 can often be skipped which makes d3-d4 possible in some cases;   c@@EndBracket@@ in many cases we can go Bb5-a4-c2 directly instead of Bb5-a4-b3-c2. }
6. c3
{ Once Black has moved his dark-squared Bishop we can freely make this move as he can no longer use the g7-g6 setup. }
6... O-O 7. Re1
{ In most cases, it doesn't make any difference whether we start with  7.Re1  or  7.Nbd2  . However, there are one or two cases @@StartBracket@@Black moving the Bishop or the Knight to d7@@EndBracket@@ when it is better to start with 7.Re1 so let's stick with that. }
7... Bd7
{ This setup has been quite popular recently, something I can't really understand as White doesn't seem to have any difficulties gaining a small positional advantage. }
8. Ba4
{ Preparing d3-d4. The immediate  8.d4?!  would be met with  8...Nxd4!  9.Nxd4  exd4  10.Bxd7  Qxd7  11.cxd4  d5  and Black should be OK. }
8... Re8 9. d4 Bf8
{ After  9...h6  10.d5  Nb8  Black keeps the Bishop on e7 from where it could potentially move to g5 or d8-b6.   Therefore for White it would be more accurate to play  9...h6  10.h3  just to wait for  10...Bf8  and only then go  11.d5!  This is a nuance but always worth remembering. }
10. d5
{ Compared with the g7-g6 setup this really doesn't look convincing for Black. }
10... Ne7 11. Bxd7 Qxd7 12. c4
{ It just looks like an easier version of the g7-g6 setups. White's plan remains the same - we want to push the Pawns on the queenside. }
