1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ @@StartBlockQuote@@The Berlin Defense - one of the most hated openings among White players. @@EndBlockQuote@@   Let me explain how I choose the line and why I rejected the alternatives. The most natural attempt to challenge the Berlin Wall would be to go for the endgame after  4.O-O  Nxe4  5.d4  Nd6  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  . I quickly rejected it for a couple of reasons:   a@@EndBracket@@ Due to the specific Pawn structure the endgame is incredibly complex and hence requires deep understanding. This means that absorbing even the best opening lines will not be enough to succeed. Long story short, in order to do it right I would have to make a separate course for the Berlin Defense alone.   b@@EndBracket@@ Let's say we analyze the Caro-Kann Defense. While going through the lines we slowly begin to understand the Pawn structures. We actually realize that in some lines the structures resemble the ones we had learned from playing the Slav Defense. There are some nuances that might favor White or Black, depending on the position. Understanding these nuances makes us feel stronger, we actually feel that by learning the Caro-Kann structures we are becoming a better player in other openings too! This won't be the case for the Berlin Endgame. Its Pawn structure is simply too unique, and we are not really going to see it in other openings.   c@@EndBracket@@ The amount of theory is staggering. Black has plenty of playable lines which makes doing all this work even less practical.   d@@EndBracket@@ We are deliberately going for an endgame before move 10. I imagine for quite a good part of you this is a 'no-go'. :-@@EndBracket@@   The second possible line would be  4.O-O  Nxe4  5.Re1  . That was also an easy decision - most of the lines are simply boring. The engines might get excited once in a while screaming 'it's +0.31!' but really it's just symmetry and even if White does get an initiative once in a while it is usually faint.   I was seriously considering