{ This is the point. We are now threatening with winning a Pawn but without exchanging the Queens. }
22... Bb4
{ Objectively the strongest but the lines are too computer-ish to be worried about it. }
23. Red1 Nc3 24. Qd3 Ne4
{ The Rook was untouchable:  24...Nxd1??  25.Qh7+  Kf8  26.Nf5  with mate in one. But then again - to waste two moves just to drag the Queen to d3? }
25. Bd4 { The Bishop covers the g1-a7 diagonal so now 26.f3 is a threat. }
25... Bb7 { Black needs to control the c3-square. } 26. f3 Bc3
{ Both 27...Bxa1 and 27...Bxd4 are the threats so we have no time to capture the Knight. }
27. Ne2
{ We are just to trying to keep the game alive. After  27.Rac1  Bxd4+  28.Qxd4  Nxg3  29.hxg3  Qg5  Black wins the Pawn and the compensation is only enough for a draw:  30.f4  Qxg3  31.Bf5  Rxc1  32.Rxc1  g6  33.Bd7  Re7  34.Rc7  Qe1  +=. }
27... Bxd4+
{ 27...Bxa1  28.Bxa1  would give White real compensation for the exchange. }
28. Nxd4 Rc3 { Chasing the Queen away from the diagonal. } 29. Qe2 Ng5 30. f4
Ne6 { 30...Ne4  31.Bxe4  dxe4  32.Nf5  would be promising for White. } 31. Nxe6
Rxe6 32. Bd3
{ Objectively this is unclear but I always prefer the side with a Pawn chain as it is easier to handle the position - all we have to do is push Pawns. :-@@EndBracket@@ }
