{ Not the most popular continuation but I liked it more than the others. Usually, they go  12.Qe2  Qc8  . After 12.h3  , Black has to reckon with 13.Ng5 as we are about to see. }
12... Nd7
{ By relocating the Knight Black is preparing some active counterplay on the queenside. }
13. Nf1 Nb6 14. Qe2
{ For now, we are focused on the Kingside which means the Queen has to stay in the game. }
14... Bc4
{ Trying to disturb White's plan. After the normal  14...f6  we could just play  15.Ne3  . The other Knight can go to h4 and then we have all kinds of ideas involving Ne3-d5@@StartBracket@@f5@@EndBracket@@ or Nh4-f5. }
15. Qe3 Be6 { Black managed to take away the e3-square from our Knight. } 16.
Ng3 { But g3 will do. } 16... f6 17. Nf5
{ Black's position is as solid as unpleasant. I see two possible plans:  continue on the Kingside with h3-h4-h5 @@StartBracket@@and possibly h5-h6@@EndBracket@@; try to exploit the c5-square - we take the Bishop on e7, move the Rook to d1 and then transfer the Knight to d3. }
