{ Black's logic is that since White has already played d2-d3, any classical Ruy Lopez System such as the Breyer should be an upgrade for Black now. However, this is that not simple and White has strong arguments:  a@@EndBracket@@ the Pawn can stay on d3; it's a perfectly healthy setup that is frequently used from the other move orders as well;   b@@EndBracket@@ h2-h3 can often be skipped which makes d3-d4 possible in some cases;   c@@EndBracket@@ in many cases we can go Bb5-a4-c2 directly instead of Bb5-a4-b3-c2. }
6. c3
{ Once Black has moved his dark-squared Bishop we can freely make this move as he can no longer use the g7-g6 setup. }
6... O-O 7. Re1
{ In most cases, it doesn't make any difference whether we start with  7.Re1  or  7.Nbd2  . However, there are one or two cases @@StartBracket@@Black moving the Bishop or the Knight to d7@@EndBracket@@ when it is better to start with 7.Re1 so let's stick with that. }
7... a6 8. Ba4 b5
{ The idea of starting with b7-b5 is to force Ba4-c2 -  9.Bb3  Na5  gives Black a decent game. }
9. Bc2 Re8
{ If you prefer the Ba4-c2 setup you can use it in every move order. } 10. Nbd2
Bf8 11. Nf1 d5
{ This is quite a decent line for Black but for some reason it is not very popular @@StartBracket@@I hope I will not make it one :-@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@. }
12. exd5 Nxd5 { 12...Qxd5  wasn't really an option because of  13.Bg5! } 13.
Bb3
{ A novelty. We are trying to use x-rays on the e-file and the a2-g8 diagonal. }
13... h6 { Black is stopping Bc1-g5 and Nf3-g5. } 14. d4
{ Black can't that Pawn as it would cost him the Knight on d5. } 14... e4 15.
N3d2 { As soon as the Pawn moved to e4 it is becoming a target there too. }
15... Nf6
{ 15...f5?  would just lose a Pawn after  16.Ne3  Be6  17.Bxd5!  Bxd5  18.Nxf5  . }
16. Ng3 Bg4
{ If Black wants to solve our idea than he should follow this path. } 17. Qc2
Bd6 18. Ndxe4
{ 18.Ngxe4?!  Bf5  would this time give Black very serious compensation for the Pawn. }
18... Bxg3
{ This is much stronger than  18...Nxe4  19.Rxe4  and White is better. } 19.
hxg3 Rxe4
{ The point of the whole operation. Black is using combining motifs here: the pin on the b1-h7 diagonal and the back-rank weakness. }
20. Rxe4 Bf5 21. f3 Na5
{ This is a very important nuance as after  21...Qd7  White had  22.Qe2!  Nxe4  23.fxe4  and the Bishop can always come to c2 to protect our central Pawn. }
22. Bf4 Qd7
{ No reason for Black to rush things although  22...Nxe4  would be perfectly fine too. }
23. Qd3
{ The position is equal. There is no doubt that Black can win the Pawn back but at the same time, White has nothing to worry about either, just bring the Rook to e1. }
