{ We are starting with an important nuance: after  5.c3  Black can play  5...g6  and compared with a normal Steinitz he gained a whole tempo. Therefore, in my opinion,  5.O-O  is more accurate. }
5... Be7
{ Black's logic is that since White has already played d2-d3, any classical Ruy Lopez System such as the Breyer should be an upgrade for Black now. However, this is that not simple and White has strong arguments:  a@@EndBracket@@ the Pawn can stay on d3; it's a perfectly healthy setup that is frequently used from the other move orders as well;   b@@EndBracket@@ h2-h3 can often be skipped which makes d3-d4 possible in some cases;   c@@EndBracket@@ in many cases we can go Bb5-a4-c2 directly instead of Bb5-a4-b3-c2. }
6. c3
{ Once Black has moved his dark-squared Bishop we can freely make this move as he can no longer use the g7-g6 setup. }
6... O-O 7. Re1
{ In most cases, it doesn't make any difference whether we start with  7.Re1  or  7.Nbd2  . However, there are one or two cases @@StartBracket@@Black moving the Bishop or the Knight to d7@@EndBracket@@ when it is better to start with 7.Re1 so let's stick with that. }
7... a6 8. Ba4 b5
{ The idea of starting with b7-b5 is to force Ba4-c2 -  9.Bb3  Na5  gives Black a decent game. }
9. Bc2 Re8
{ If you prefer the Ba4-c2 setup you can use it in every move order. } 10. Nbd2
Bf8 11. Nf1 d5
{ This is quite a decent line for Black but for some reason it is not very popular @@StartBracket@@I hope I will not make it one :-@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@. }
12. a4
{ This is a good choice if you want to get a playable position without entering forced lines. }
12... dxe4 13. dxe4 Be6
{ Logical reply, the Bishop is better placed here than on b7.  13...b4  would be premature -  14.a5  and Black has to watch out for Bc2-a4. }
14. b4
{ Taking control over c5 but also preventing b5-b4 which could be played at any moment. }
14... h6 15. Be3
{ White is a bit better mainly because Black has to deal with his Knight on c6 - it is not very well placed but before improving his position, e5 has to be secured first.   The Queen trade is very likely, in the endgame we can move the Bishop to the f1-a6 diagonal, putting pressure on b5.   We can also try improving the position of our Knight on f3 - it would be best placed on d3. The f1-Knight can go either to g3@@StartBracket@@f5@@EndBracket@@ or back to d2 @@StartBracket@@b3@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Ruy Lopez Anti-Berlin (4.d3 d6)"]
[Black "Anti-Berlin 7...a6 8.Ba4 b5 #22 | 12.a4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ @@StartBlockQuote@@The Berlin Defense - one of the most hated openings among White players. @@EndBlockQuote@@   Let me explain how I choose the line and why I rejected the alternatives. The most natural attempt to challenge the Berlin Wall would be to go for the endgame after  4.O-O  Nxe4  5.d4  Nd6  6.Bxc6  dxc6  7.dxe5  Nf5  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  . I quickly rejected it for a couple of reasons:   a@@EndBracket@@ Due to the specific Pawn structure the endgame is incredibly complex and hence requires deep understanding. This means that absorbing even the best opening lines will not be enough to succeed. Long story short, in order to do it right I would have to make a separate course for the Berlin Defense alone.   b@@EndBracket@@ Let's say we analyze the Caro-Kann Defense. While going through the lines we slowly begin to understand the Pawn structures. We actually realize that in some lines the structures resemble the ones we had learned from playing the Slav Defense. There are some nuances that might favor White or Black, depending on the position. Understanding these nuances makes us feel stronger, we actually feel that by learning the Caro-Kann structures we are becoming a better player in other openings too! This won't be the case for the Berlin Endgame. Its Pawn structure is simply too unique, and we are not really going to see it in other openings.   c@@EndBracket@@ The amount of theory is staggering. Black has plenty of playable lines which makes doing all this work even less practical.   d@@EndBracket@@ We are deliberately going for an endgame before move 10. I imagine for quite a good part of you this is a 'no-go'. :-@@EndBracket@@   The second possible line would be  4.O-O  Nxe4  5.Re1  . That was also an easy decision - most of the lines are simply boring. The engines might get excited once in a while screaming 'it's +0.31!' but really it's just symmetry and even if White does get an initiative once in a while it is usually faint.   I was seriously considering  4.d3  Bc5  5.c3  but the problem is that Black is just doing okay in the d7-d5 lines and it is not easy to challenge it. This left me with only one choice left. }
4. d3 d6
{ This is a normal continuation that usually leads to typical Ruy Lopez structures. I believe Black mostly chooses it over  4...Bc5  for one of three reasons:   1. Black simply prefers more classical structures.   2. Black is afraid of the amount of theory after 4...Bc5.   3. Black wants to play for a win and he believes he can outplay his opponent thanks to his superior understanding of Ruy Lopez structures. }
5. O-O
{ We are starting with an important nuance: after  5.c3  Black can play  5...g6  and compared with a normal Steinitz he gained a whole tempo. Therefore, in my opinion,  5.O-O  is more accurate. }
5... Be7
{ Black's logic is that since White has already played d2-d3, any classical Ruy Lopez System such as the Breyer should be an upgrade for Black now. However, this is that not simple and White has strong arguments:  a@@EndBracket@@ the Pawn can stay on d3; it's a perfectly healthy setup that is frequently used from the other move orders as well;   b@@EndBracket@@ h2-h3 can often be skipped which makes d3-d4 possible in some cases;   c@@EndBracket@@ in many cases we can go Bb5-a4-c2 directly instead of Bb5-a4-b3-c2. }
6. c3
{ Once Black has moved his dark-squared Bishop we can freely make this move as he can no longer use the g7-g6 setup. }
6... O-O 7. Re1
{ In most cases, it doesn't make any difference whether we start with  7.Re1  or  7.Nbd2  . However, there are one or two cases @@StartBracket@@Black moving the Bishop or the Knight to d7@@EndBracket@@ when it is better to start with 7.Re1 so let's stick with that. }
7... a6 8. Ba4 b5
{ The idea of starting with b7-b5 is to force Ba4-c2 -  9.Bb3  Na5  gives Black a decent game. }
9. Bc2 Re8
{ If you prefer the Ba4-c2 setup you can use it in every move order. } 10. Nbd2
Bf8 11. Nf1 d5
{ This is quite a decent line for Black but for some reason it is not very popular @@StartBracket@@I hope I will not make it one :-@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@. }
12. a4
{ This is a good choice if you want to get a playable position without entering forced lines. }
12... b4 { The most logical continuation but it has its own drawbacks. } 13. a5
{ It would a pity not to make this move. } 13... h6
{ The Bc1-g5 threat had to be dealt with. } 14. Ba4 Bd7 15. exd5 Nxd5 16. Bd2
{ White is not better but his position is easier to play. At the moment Black has to defend e5 so he will most likely go 16...Bd6. We can then bring the Knight to g3 and play h2-h3, which is one of those little useful moves that should be made from time to time.   Whenever Black comes back with the Knight to f6 we can offer him a trade with Ng3-e4. After Nf6xe4 - d3xe4, we will reach a well-known structure with a small but long-lasting pressure on Black's position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28. Petroff Defense"]
[Black "Petroff  3.Nxe5 Nxe4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petroff Defense has always been one of the most solid lines out there but it has also had a reputation of boring. I think today it would be unfair to call it boring.   Sure, it is not the Najdorf Variation but still many lines are really sharp and dynamic. Hence, it should not surprise us that there are many strong and aggressive players, that use it as part of their repertoire. }
3. Nxe5 Nxe4
{ It is a weak line but we should know a couple of moves as over the board every move looks better for White and this is not really the case. }
4. Qe2 Qe7 { Any other move would be just lost. } 5. Qxe4 d6
{ Black wins the piece back. } 6. d4 dxe5 7. dxe5 { Now we are a Pawn up. }
7... Nc6 { Black is threatening to win the Pawn back. } 8. Nc3
{ And we should let him! The whole point of this line is that if White gets greedy then after something like  8.f4?!  Bg4  or @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/ppp1qppp/2n5/4P3/4Q3/8/PPP2PPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Bb5  Bd7  in both cases followed by long castle, Black can get decent compensation for the Pawn and an interesting position overall. }
8... Qxe5 9. Qxe5+ Nxe5 10. Bf4 { The Knight can't move as c7 would fall. }
10... Bd6
{ Trying to bypass Bf8-d6 with  10...f6  11.O-O-O  Bd7  doesn't really help -  12.Nb5  and White is clearly better. }
11. Bg3 { This had to be played as Black was threatening Ne5-f3+. } 11... f6
{ Once again - Black didn't really have a choice. After  11...Bd7  12.Ne4  Black can't stop Ne4xd6+. White's advantage would be even greater there. }
12. O-O-O Bd7 13. Nb5
{ After  13...Bxb5  14.Bxb5+  White has a clear advantage - Bishop pair in an open position is a perfect scenario. Even if Black manages to swap the dark-squared Bishops it will still be a Bishop vs. Knight.   We could go deeper trying to maximize the profit but I don't think it would be practical - this is a very rare line and most of us might never see it over the board. }
*

