{ One of many examples of Ian Nepomniachtchi's opening preparation. He used this novelty against Wang Hao in the Candidates Tournament 2020 so we can be certain that this is serious. }
13... Nc7 14. Ng5
{ The point of White's previous move. Black now has a choice - he can either weaken his position with  14...Bxg5  15.Bxg5  f6  or weaken his King's position with @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppn1bppp/2pn4/3p2N1/3P1B1P/3Q4/PPP2PP1/R3RNK1 b - - 2 14@@EndFEN@@  14...g6  . }
14... Bxg5
{ Solid response but by no means a concession - I believe that White should be slightly better here. }
15. Bxg5 f6 { Due to the Re1-e7 threat Black had no choice. } 16. Bf4 Qd7
{ Black's setup is quite reasonable - the f6-Pawn restricts our Bishop while the Knights cover the light squares. However, it is a defensive setup. Black can develop the Rooks and wait while White has quite a few ways of improving the position. }
17. Ne3
{ I think this is more accurate than  17.Ng3  played by Nepomniachtchi. It was already tested this year in Van Forest, J - Humpy, K - Chessable Masters 2021. }
17... Rae8 { This would be inaccurate - White can go: } 18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19. Nf5
Qd7 20. Qh3
{ This is how Van Foreest played, however, Humpy had the Rooks on a8 and e8 so she solved her problems with Kg8-f8! Here this is not possible. Assuming that Black will notice that his Queen might fall after Nf5-h6+ we will continue with h4-h5 putting a nice pressure on Black's position. }
