13... Nc7 14. Ng5
{ The point of White's previous move. Black now has a choice - he can either weaken his position with  14...Bxg5  15.Bxg5  f6  or weaken his King's position with @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppn1bppp/2pn4/3p2N1/3P1B1P/3Q4/PPP2PP1/R3RNK1 b - - 2 14@@EndFEN@@  14...g6  . }
14... g6 15. Nh2
{ A novelty. So went  15.Ne3  Qd7  16.h5  but after  16...Bxg5!?  @@StartBracket@@Duda played weaker 16...Nce8@@EndBracket@@  17.Bxg5  f5!  I wasn't sure what to do, despite the weakened dark squares, Black's position seemed just OK. }
15... Qd7 16. h5 Bxg5 17. Bxg5
{ White is threatening Re1-e7 so there is no time for f7-f5. Black can now move both Rooks to e8 and, since there are subtle but important differences between both moves, we will go through them slowly. }
17... Rae8
{ After  17...Rfe8  18.Re5  Black would have the simple  18...Ne4  .   However,  17...Rae8  18.Re5  Ne4?  is met with  19.Bh6!  and Black is in trouble -  19...Rxe5  20.dxe5  Re8  21.f3!  This allows White to go: }
18. Re5 Ne4
{ This would be strong with 17...Rfe8 played instead of 17...Rae8. What is the difference? }
19. Bh6 { It's pretty simple, really. } 19... Rxe5
{ 19...f6  would be the lesser evil but anyway after  20.Rxe8  Rxe8  21.f3  White wins the Pawn. }
20. dxe5 Re8 21. f3
{ Black is basically lost -  21...Nc5  22.Qd2!  and 23.Ng4 is coming.   And if  21...Ng3  22.hxg6  ,  the Knight is also coming to g4. }
