{ Strategically, Black's setup is very sound - swapping the light-squared Bishops weakens our light squares - this is all determined by the placement of our central Pawns - d4 vs. d5.   The downside? It takes time, which will allow us to activate our pieces, whereas Black's position will remain passive for some time. }
10. Nf1 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 c6
{ Black is preparing Nb8-a6-c7 - a very solid setup but it can be challenged. }
12. Bf4 Na6 13. h4
{ One of many examples of Ian Nepomniachtchi's opening preparation. He used this novelty against Wang Hao in the Candidates Tournament 2020 so we can be certain that this is serious. }
13... Nc7 14. Ng5
{ The point of White's previous move. Black now has a choice - he can either weaken his position with  14...Bxg5  15.Bxg5  f6  or weaken his King's position with @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/ppn1bppp/2pn4/3p2N1/3P1B1P/3Q4/PPP2PP1/R3RNK1 b - - 2 14@@EndFEN@@  14...g6  . }
