{ White is threatening Re1-e7 so there is no time for f7-f5. Black can now move both Rooks to e8 and, since there are subtle but important differences between both moves, we will go through them slowly. }
17... Rfe8 { This is safer - Black won't have to deal with Bg5-h6. } 18. Qg3
{ The best try - White is trying to make good use of those dark squares. }
18... Rxe1+ 19. Rxe1 Re8
{ Black is trying to simplify the position but also  20.Rxe8+  Ncxe8  would allow him to cover some of the dark squares. }
20. Re5
{ If we really have to trade Rooks then at least let's get something in return. }
20... Rxe5 21. dxe5 Ne4 22. Qh4
{ 22.e6  looked like the move but it turned out that  22...Nxe6  23.Qb8  Nf8  24.Bh6  Qd6  was rock solid. }
22... Nxg5 23. Qxg5 Ne6
{ All these moves don't look too difficult but they are actually the only ones allowing Black to maintain the balance. In any case, we should bring our Knight to g4 creating some real threats to Black's King. }
24. Qh6
{ It seems like a good moment to stop. It is very close to equality but Black still has to be careful. After  24...Ng7  we can go  25.hxg6  hxg6  26.Qh4  .   24...Nf8  should be responded with  25.f3!  preparing 26.g4. }
