{ A novelty. So went  15.Ne3  Qd7  16.h5  but after  16...Bxg5!?  @@StartBracket@@Duda played weaker 16...Nce8@@EndBracket@@  17.Bxg5  f5!  I wasn't sure what to do, despite the weakened dark squares, Black's position seemed just OK. }
15... f6
{ It is always tempting to clear out the situation even if it requires some concessions. }
16. Ne6
{ After  16.Ngf3  Qd7  17.h5  Black can safely respond with  17...g5  . } 16...
Nxe6 17. Rxe6 Qd7
{ Black's whole idea is based on the assumption that the white Rook won't be able to hold on e6. Let's see... }
18. Rae1 Rae8
{ Black is threatening 19...Ne4 potentially winning our e6-Rook, so shall we go back? }
19. h5 { Nah... } 19... Ne4
{ But not  19...g5?  20.Bxd6  Bxd6  21.Qf5  and White is winning. } 20. Qh3
{ The only way to defend the Rook but it's also creating some real challenges in Black's position. White is threatening the simple f2-f3 @@StartBracket@@as well as Nh2-g4@@EndBracket@@. }
20... g5
{ Actually this is the only move that allows Black to stay in the game. } 21.
Ng4
{ 21...gxf4??  will be now punished with  22.R6xe4!  and Black can't take the Rook due to Ng4-h6+ winning the Queen. }
21... Kg7
{ Again this is the only move -  22...Kh8  loses to  23.Ne5!  Qc8  24.Ng6+!  And @@StartFEN@@4rr1k/pp1qb2p/2p1Rp2/3pN1pP/3PnB2/7Q/PPP2PP1/4R1K1 b - - 3 22@@EndFEN@@  23...fxe5  24.Bxe5+  is even simpler. }
22. h6+ Kh8 23. Ne5
{ But this won't be as effective now as there is no Ne5-g6+. } 23... Qc8 24.
Bh2 fxe5 { It is totally not obvious why Black can't do it. } 25. Rxe4
{ Brilliant strike. } 25... Bf6
{ It is better than  25...dxe4  as Black is not getting mated but it's the only good news for him. }
26. Rxe8 Qxe8 27. Re2 e4
{ Actually here we are quite lucky - Black's position would have been just fine if not for that one little detail... }
28. Bd6
{ After  28...Rg8  White will go  29.c4!  and Black's Pawn center may collapse, for instance  29...Bxd4  30.Qf5  .   And  28...Rf7  can be simply answered with  29.c3  - Black pieces have no coordination. }
