1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petroff Defense has always been one of the most solid lines out there but it has also had a reputation of boring. I think today it would be unfair to call it boring.   Sure, it is not the Najdorf Variation but still many lines are really sharp and dynamic. Hence, it should not surprise us that there are many strong and aggressive players, that use it as part of their repertoire. }
3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4
{ 5.Nc3  is another fashionable possibility but I wouldn't recommend it to everyone. The lines can often be quite difficult and computer-ish and - if I have a choice - I prefer something more natural. }
5... d5 6. Bd3 Bf5
{ For many years White had to deal with two serious lines -  6...Nc6  7.O-O  Be7  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/3Pn3/3B1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Bd6  .  6...Bf5  has always been somewhat neglected. In 2016 it was used by the Russian grandmaster Vadim Zvjaginsev in his games against Alexander Predke in Russian Higher League.   A year later it was picked up by the Chinese star, Yu Yangyi, and then it went fast. Today the 6...Bf5 setup is equally serious @@StartBracket@@and popular!@@EndBracket@@ as the other two lines.   By the way, since the early 90s, Zvjagnisev has been one of the most influential players, especially in the opening stage so it didn't surprise me to see his name here as well. }
7. O-O Be7 8. Re1
{ The other possible continuation is  8.c4  but I think that our choice is more promising. }
8... O-O 9. Nbd2 { Once again  9.c4  was also possible. } 9... Nd6
{ Strategically, Black's setup is very sound - swapping the light-squared Bishops weakens our light squares - this is all determined by the placement of our central Pawns - d4 vs. d5.   The downside? It takes time, which will allow us to activate our pieces, whereas Black's position will remain passive for some time. }
10. Nf1 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 c6
{ Black is preparing Nb8-a6-c7 - a very solid setup but it can be challenged. }
12. Bf4 Na6 13. h4
