{ The only way to defend the Rook but it's also creating some real challenges in Black's position. White is threatening the simple f2-f3 @@StartBracket@@as well as Nh2-g4@@EndBracket@@. }
20... g5
{ Actually this is the only move that allows Black to stay in the game. } 21.
Ng4
{ 21...gxf4??  will be now punished with  22.R6xe4!  and Black can't take the Rook due to Ng4-h6+ winning the Queen. }
21... Kg7
{ Again this is the only move -  22...Kh8  loses to  23.Ne5!  Qc8  24.Ng6+!  And @@StartFEN@@4rr1k/pp1qb2p/2p1Rp2/3pN1pP/3PnB2/7Q/PPP2PP1/4R1K1 b - - 3 22@@EndFEN@@  23...fxe5  24.Bxe5+  is even simpler. }
22. h6+ Kh8 23. Ne5
{ But this won't be as effective now as there is no Ne5-g6+. } 23... Qc8 24.
Bh2 Bb4
{ This is how Black should react. He could not win the Rook so at least he can swap it. }
25. Rxe8 Qxe8
{ 25...Rxe8  26.Qxc8  Rxc8  27.c3  Bf8  28.f3  would be much better for White. }
26. c3 fxe5 27. Bxe5+ Kg8 28. f3
{ Black is really lucky - after  28.cxb4  the only reason for him not being lost is  28...Nxf2! }
28... Nxc3 { Again the only move. } 29. bxc3
{ Black miraculously stays in the game. A sample line is  29...Bxc3  30.Re3  Bd2  31.Re2  Bf4  32.Kf2  when I would still rather be White due to Black's exposed king and the pressure we have on the e-file. }
