[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petroff Defense has always been one of the most solid lines out there but it has also had a reputation of boring. I think today it would be unfair to call it boring.   Sure, it is not the Najdorf Variation but still many lines are really sharp and dynamic. Hence, it should not surprise us that there are many strong and aggressive players, that use it as part of their repertoire. }
3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4
{ 5.Nc3  is another fashionable possibility but I wouldn't recommend it to everyone. The lines can often be quite difficult and computer-ish and - if I have a choice - I prefer something more natural. }
5... d5 6. Bd3 Bd6
{ This is, no doubt, the most interesting line in 5.d4 Petroff, but it is also the least solid one. }
7. O-O O-O 8. c4
{ Undermining Black's position in the center. Other moves don't really matter. }
8... c6 { No other move deserved even an honorable mention. } 9. Nc3
{ In recent years it has become the most topical continuation in the 6...Bd6 variation. White immediately challenges the black Knight. }
9... Re8
{ This move was first played in 1887 in a game between George Gossip and John Witton - Austrian Championship. The second time was more than a hundred years later... }
10. Qc2 Bf5 11. Re1 Na6 { Basically the only move. } 12. a3
{ Via transposition we have reached the position from Anand, V - Kasimdzhanov, R from the World Cup final 2002. }
12... h6 { Now after  13.Nxe4  dxe4  14.Bxe4  Black has  14...Qe7! } 13. b4
{ I think it's the best try. Initially, I wanted to repeat Vishy's  13.c5  but after  13...Bb8!  @@StartBracket@@13...Bc7 was played in the game@@EndBracket@@  14.b4  Bg6!  it's not easy to prove White's advantage. }
13... Bxb4
{ It is more or less forced - after  13...Nc7  14.Bb2  Black will just lose the Pawn. }
14. axb4 Nxb4 15. Qb1 Nxd3
{ But not  15...Nxc3??  16.Rxe8+  Qxe8  17.Qxb4  Bxd3  18.Qxc3  and White is winning. }
16. Qxd3 Nd6 17. Rxe8+ Qxe8 { Black will get three Pawns for a piece. } 18. Qe3
Qxe3 19. fxe3 { The best try, although  19.Bxe3  is also possible. } 19... Nxc4
20. Ne5
{ Whether Black takes the Knight or retreats his own Knight to b6, our plan is to place the Bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal.   Thanks to the control over the dark squares, White has a slight advantage as it will be virtually impossible for Black to make good use of his Queenside Pawns. }
