[Black "Petroff 6...Bd6 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petroff Defense has always been one of the most solid lines out there but it has also had a reputation of boring. I think today it would be unfair to call it boring.   Sure, it is not the Najdorf Variation but still many lines are really sharp and dynamic. Hence, it should not surprise us that there are many strong and aggressive players, that use it as part of their repertoire. }
3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4
{ 5.Nc3  is another fashionable possibility but I wouldn't recommend it to everyone. The lines can often be quite difficult and computer-ish and - if I have a choice - I prefer something more natural. }
5... d5 6. Bd3 Bd6
{ This is, no doubt, the most interesting line in 5.d4 Petroff, but it is also the least solid one. }
7. O-O O-O 8. c4
{ Undermining Black's position in the center. Other moves don't really matter. }
8... c6 { No other move deserved even an honorable mention. } 9. Nc3
{ In recent years it has become the most topical continuation in the 6...Bd6 variation. White immediately challenges the black Knight. }
9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 dxc4 11. Bxc4 Bg4
{ This continuation is so unattractive that I can't believe people use it voluntarily. }
12. h3 Bh5 13. g4 { Quite loose but our Knight will now get to e5. } 13... Bg6
14. Ne5 Bxe5 15. dxe5 Qa5
{ 15...Nd7  16.f4  Nb6  17.Bb3  would be clearly better for White. } 16. f4
{ I have decided no to take this line too seriously - as I mentioned earlier it's so ugly for Black that I can't really see anyone going for it.   Caruana did once in Crypto Cup 2021 and he got badly beaten by Nepomniachtchi @@StartBracket@@even though Ian forgot the line right away and played rather weak 16.Qd4@@EndBracket@@.   The move I am suggesting has only been played once so far - in correspondence chess. White sacrifices a Pawn for a long-term compensation. }
16... Be4
{ Sensible choice, Black ignores the Pawn choosing to improve his position instead. }
17. Qd4 Bd5 18. Be2
{ This is stronger than  18.Bxd5  cxd5  and the Knight gets a new square - c6. }
18... Rd8 19. Qe3 { Black has to anticipate c3-c4. } 19... b5 20. a4
{ Our plan is to go 21.Ba3 next. } 20... Bc4
{ Good, disturbing move.  21.Ba3  makes no sense now because of  21...Bxe2  and White should already catch the draw with  22.Bb4  Qb6  23.Bc5  . }
21. f5 { We sacrifice the Pawn again. } 21... Bxe2 22. Qxe2 Qxc3 23. Bf4
{ White has good compensation for the Pawn. We want to go e5-e6 and create a passed Pawn - such Pawns in the center can be really dangerous as they restrain the opponent's Rooks and occasionally get promoted. }
