1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petroff Defense has always been one of the most solid lines out there but it has also had a reputation of boring. I think today it would be unfair to call it boring.   Sure, it is not the Najdorf Variation but still many lines are really sharp and dynamic. Hence, it should not surprise us that there are many strong and aggressive players, that use it as part of their repertoire. }
3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4
{ 5.Nc3  is another fashionable possibility but I wouldn't recommend it to everyone. The lines can often be quite difficult and computer-ish and - if I have a choice - I prefer something more natural. }
5... d5 6. Bd3 Nc6
{ Historically, this is the main continuation. The point of developing the Knight to c6 is to be able to react to c2-c4 with Nc6-b4. }
7. O-O Be7 8. Nbd2
{ One of the changes in the modern theory - for years  8.c4  has been considered topical but in the last decade  8.Nbd2  came into play. White is basically saying that symmetrical structure doesn't mean equality. }
8... Nd6 { In the spirit of the Berlin Defense. } 9. c3 Bf5 10. Be2
{ The Knight on d6 is not as well placed as it looks - the Pawn on d5 is not defended and his dark-squared Bishop is passive. Our plan is to bring the Knight to g3. }
10... O-O 11. Re1 Nb8
{ Black is trying to improve the position of the Knight and also secure the d5-Pawn. }
12. Nf1 c6 13. Bf4 Nd7 14. Ng3 Bg6
{ Both sides have completed their developments. Our Knights are slightly better placed. }
15. Qb3
{ White is slightly better. Black's main problem is that it's difficult to make moves and has to look after the b7-Pawn which is not easy. }
