[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petroff Defense has always been one of the most solid lines out there but it has also had a reputation of boring. I think today it would be unfair to call it boring.   Sure, it is not the Najdorf Variation but still many lines are really sharp and dynamic. Hence, it should not surprise us that there are many strong and aggressive players, that use it as part of their repertoire. }
3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4
{ 5.Nc3  is another fashionable possibility but I wouldn't recommend it to everyone. The lines can often be quite difficult and computer-ish and - if I have a choice - I prefer something more natural. }
5... d5 6. Bd3 Nc6
{ Historically, this is the main continuation. The point of developing the Knight to c6 is to be able to react to c2-c4 with Nc6-b4. }
7. O-O Be7 8. Nbd2
{ One of the changes in the modern theory - for years  8.c4  has been considered topical but in the last decade  8.Nbd2  came into play. White is basically saying that symmetrical structure doesn't mean equality. }
8... Bf5 9. Re1 Nxd2 10. Qxd2 Bg6
{ Interesting try, based on the reasonable assumption that after  11.Bxg6  hxg6  it will be a bit easier to defend as the Pawn on g6 controls h5 and f5. It is not very popular but it was spotted by Yu Yangyi who played it against Dominguez Perez in Pro League 2020. }
11. Bxg6 { Nevertheless... } 11... hxg6 12. Qd3
{ The Cuban grandmaster playing under the American flag played the less accurate  12.c3  and after  12...Qd7  he could not prevent long castle. }
12... Qd7
{ Black is thinking about castling long, which makes sense - the h-file is open. }
13. Bg5
{ If Black goes  13...O-O-O  now then there is  14.Bxe7  Nxe7  15.Ne5  Qd6  16.h3  with a clear advantage for White. }
13... O-O
{ The exchange of the dark-squared Bishops is OK for Black but on the other hand, we will play Nf3-e5 with tempo. }
14. Bxe7 Nxe7 15. Ne5 Qd6
{ It makes more sense than  15...Qf5  16.Qc3!  and Black can't go  16...c6  because of  17.Qb4  . }
16. h4 { Now the black Pawns won't be able to move. } 16... Rae8 17. g3
{ White has a small advantage but more importantly, it can't be easily neutralized. We will slowly improve - we can put the King on g2, Pawn on c3.   Whenever Black tries to swap the Knights with Ne7-c6 we can come back, Ne5-f3. If he ever tries f7-f6 then the Knight can be always rerouted to f4 @@StartBracket@@Ne5-f3-g1-h3@@EndBracket@@ targeting e6 and g6.   One more idea that can be sometimes useful - Re1-h1 and h4-h5. }
