1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ The Petroff Defense has always been one of the most solid lines out there but it has also had a reputation of boring. I think today it would be unfair to call it boring.   Sure, it is not the Najdorf Variation but still many lines are really sharp and dynamic. Hence, it should not surprise us that there are many strong and aggressive players, that use it as part of their repertoire. }
3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4
{ 5.Nc3  is another fashionable possibility but I wouldn't recommend it to everyone. The lines can often be quite difficult and computer-ish and - if I have a choice - I prefer something more natural. }
5... d5 6. Bd3 Nc6
{ Historically, this is the main continuation. The point of developing the Knight to c6 is to be able to react to c2-c4 with Nc6-b4. }
7. O-O Be7 8. Nbd2
{ One of the changes in the modern theory - for years  8.c4  has been considered topical but in the last decade  8.Nbd2  came into play. White is basically saying that symmetrical structure doesn't mean equality. }
8... Bf5 9. Re1 Nxd2 10. Qxd2 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 O-O 12. c3
{ This is always useful but also we are delaying Bc1-f4 on purpose - after  12.Bf4  Black could go  12...Bd6  so let him move the Queen first. }
12... Qd7 13. Bf4 Rfe8
{ Not a popular move but it is possible. Black wants to hide the Bishop on f8. }
14. h4
{ A novelty - I think it is a better try than  14.Re2  Bf8  ,  the e-file is not that important for us. }
14... Bf8
{ The most natural response. Black could also play something like  14...a6  but after  15.h5  h6  16.Re2  the same plans apply as after 14...Bf8 and Black's position remains unpleasant. }
15. h5 h6 { Nf3-g5 had to be stopped. } 16. Rxe8 Rxe8 17. Qb5
{ It is important not to get too attached to the Kingside. Attacking Black's Queenside Pawns is actually quite typical in this line. }
17... Rb8
{ If it's possible, then Black should avoid b7-b6 - placing the Pawn on b6 would create targets on the Queenside - c7, a7, and b6. }
18. Re1 a6 19. Qe2
{ White maintains a slight advantage - we control the e-file and I now think about improving the position of the Knight with g3 and Nh4-g2-e3. From e3 the Knight attacks the d5-Pawn but it can also move to f5. }
