{ The Philidor Defense has recently gained some popularity partially thanks to the modern engines as new ideas have been generated.  The other reason is a boom of chess on the Internet - shorter time controls create opportunities to experiment with openings as the objective evaluation is not that relevant. }
3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 Nbd7
{ I was never an admirer of this line - Black's setup is as solid as passive. }
5. Bc4 { The most natural square for the Bishop. } 5... Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4
{ This is a very useful move - White anticipates b7-b5 while also making room for the Bishop. We can start with  7.Re1  too, though I slightly prefer  7.a4  - in some lines, we can put the Queen on e2, and then the Rook will move to d1. }
7... exd4 8. Nxd4 Ne5
{ It was played by Jordan Van Foreest, one of the most innovative players I can currently think of. }
9. Be2
{ We would normally go  9.Ba2  but then  9...Nc6  followed by Nc6-b4 was Black's idea. }
9... c5 { Trying to grab some activity but there is a price on d5. } 10. Nf3
Nc6
{ 10...Ng6  11.Bc4  wouldn't change anything. And if @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2bppp/3p1n2/2p1n3/P3P3/2N2N2/1PP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Be6  then  11.Ng5  . }
11. Re1 h6 { 11...Be6  12.Ng5  . } 12. Bc4
{ The Bishop comes back to its natural position. } 12... Be6 13. b3
{ We are not worried about breaking our Pawn structure - the light squares are more important. We will develop the Bishop to b2 and probably Nc3-d5 will soon have to be played. Black will manage to simplify the position a bit but it will still have to deal with the weak d6-Pawn. }
