[White "29. Philidor Hanham Variation"]
[Black "Philidor Hanham 3...Nf6 − 7...b6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Philidor Defense has recently gained some popularity partially thanks to the modern engines as new ideas have been generated.  The other reason is a boom of chess on the Internet - shorter time controls create opportunities to experiment with openings as the objective evaluation is not that relevant. }
3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 Nbd7
{ I was never an admirer of this line - Black's setup is as solid as passive. }
5. Bc4 { The most natural square for the Bishop. } 5... Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4
{ This is a very useful move - White anticipates b7-b5 while also making room for the Bishop. We can start with  7.Re1  too, though I slightly prefer  7.a4  - in some lines, we can put the Queen on e2, and then the Rook will move to d1. }
7... b6 { Let's see how we can react if Black simply fianchettoes the Bishop. }
8. Qe2 { This is more accurate than  8.a5  bxa5!? } 8... Bb7 9. a5 a6
{ 9...bxa5  would be met with  10.dxe5  dxe5  11.Rxa5  attacking the Pawn on e5. Here I should note that  11...Bb4?  would be answered with  12.Rb5!  - this is the tactical explanation of why it was better to wait with a4-a5 for Bc8-b7 - who would have thought?! }
10. axb6 cxb6 11. Rxa6
{ That's a really nice positional sacrifice. For an exchange, we will get a Pawn and all the light squares we want. }
11... Bxa6 12. Bxa6 Ra7 { 12...exd4  13.Nxd4  would only help White. } 13. d5
{ White has a great advantage. After  13...Qa8  we can retreat the Bishop to b5 - it can't be chased away from there. Then we can bring the Knight to c4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29. Philidor Hanham Variation"]
[Black "Philidor Hanham 3...Nf6 − 7...c6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Philidor Defense has recently gained some popularity partially thanks to the modern engines as new ideas have been generated.  The other reason is a boom of chess on the Internet - shorter time controls create opportunities to experiment with openings as the objective evaluation is not that relevant. }
3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 Nbd7
{ I was never an admirer of this line - Black's setup is as solid as passive. }
5. Bc4 { The most natural square for the Bishop. } 5... Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4
{ This is a very useful move - White anticipates b7-b5 while also making room for the Bishop. We can start with  7.Re1  too, though I slightly prefer  7.a4  - in some lines, we can put the Queen on e2, and then the Rook will move to d1. }
7... c6
{ The main move in the position. Black makes the room for the Queen and also controls the sensitive d5-square. }
8. Re1
{ If 7.a4 was more accurate than 8.Re1 then 8.Re1 is slightly more accurate than  8.h3  , which allows  8...exd4  9.Nxd4  Re8  @@StartBracket@@with the Rook on e1 we would just go Nd4-f5@@EndBracket@@. }
8... b6 { Black intends to fianchetto the Bishop. } 9. Bg5
{ The most typical way of fighting against b7-b6 is to advance the Pawn to d5 and fight for the light squares. Before we do that we develop the dark-squared Bishop - in the right moment we will be able to swap it for the Knight.   The important part: if Black continues with  9...Bb7  then we have  10.Bxf6!  and he can't recapture with Knight as it would cost him a Pawn. After  10...Bxf6  11.d5  White is much better. }
9... Qc7 { Now we can execute our plan. } 10. d5 Bb7 11. dxc6 Bxc6 12. Qe2
{ White controls the light squares and has a much easier game. Of course, our ideal setup is the Knight on d5 vs. the Bishop on d8 but there is still a long way before we can achieve that. Improving the position of the f3-Knight will surely be part of the plan. }
*

