1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Philidor Defense has recently gained some popularity partially thanks to the modern engines as new ideas have been generated.  The other reason is a boom of chess on the Internet - shorter time controls create opportunities to experiment with openings as the objective evaluation is not that relevant. }
3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 Nbd7
{ I was never an admirer of this line - Black's setup is as solid as passive. }
5. Bc4 { The most natural square for the Bishop. } 5... Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4
{ This is a very useful move - White anticipates b7-b5 while also making room for the Bishop. We can start with  7.Re1  too, though I slightly prefer  7.a4  - in some lines, we can put the Queen on e2, and then the Rook will move to d1. }
7... c6
{ The main move in the position. Black makes the room for the Queen and also controls the sensitive d5-square. }
8. Re1
{ If 7.a4 was more accurate than 8.Re1 then 8.Re1 is slightly more accurate than  8.h3  , which allows  8...exd4  9.Nxd4  Re8  @@StartBracket@@with the Rook on e1 we would just go Nd4-f5@@EndBracket@@. }
8... a5
{ This is an old line and today it feels slightly outdated yet it still has some followers. Black grabs control over the b4-square which means c5 will be his too. }
9. h3 exd4 10. Qxd4 Nc5
{ This setup makes a lot of sense - the Knight is very solid on c5 and there are often some tactical opportunities for Black involving Nxe4 and d6-d5. }
11. Bf4 Be6
{ The most popular move in the position but definitely not the best one. White is easily better. }
12. Rad1 Qb6
{ Other moves were equally bad, at least this one is active. The Queen attacks the Pawn on b2. }
13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Bxd6
{ Not only we have won the key Pawn but there is another weakness in Black's camp - e6. }
14... Bxd6 15. Qxd6 Rad8 16. Qe5 Nfd7
{ Defending the Knight with tempo will at least allow Black to win the b2-Pawn. }
17. Qd4 Qxb2 18. Qe3
{ White is much better - the black pieces lack coordination and the Queen is exposed. He can't take  18...Qxc2  as after  19.Rd2  Qb3  20.Rb1!  @@StartBracket@@dragging the Queen to c4 first so it wouldn't come back to b6@@EndBracket@@  20...Qc4  21.Rbd1  White will win material - at least an exchange with Nf3-e5. }
