1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Philidor Defense has recently gained some popularity partially thanks to the modern engines as new ideas have been generated.  The other reason is a boom of chess on the Internet - shorter time controls create opportunities to experiment with openings as the objective evaluation is not that relevant. }
3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ I am not a big fan of this setup. It feels like a Dragon but with some joker playing a prank on Black by moving a Pawn from e7 to c7.   The e-file will be less useful than the c-file - there will be no exchange sacrifice on c3, no Knight jumping to c4 and the dark squares around the black King will be weakened. }
6. Be3
{ I think it is the most natural choice here as with Black fianchettoing the Bishop, we will need to protect the Knight on d4. My only doubt was whether White should start with  6.Be3  or  6.f3  . In the end I decided it is better not to allow  6.f3  Bg7  7.Qd2  d5!?  8.e5  Nfd7  where a lot of accuracy is required from White. }
6... Bg7 { After this White should be able to gain a big advantage. } 7. Qd2
O-O 8. O-O-O Nc6 9. f3 Nxd4
{ This is an easy line for White. We will have no problems on the Queenside and a freeroll on the Kingside. }
10. Bxd4 Be6 11. g4 c5
{ 11...c6  would be too slow -  12.h4  b5  13.h5  b4  14.Na4  and White's attack is far more dangerous. }
12. Be3 Qa5
{ We won't even consider capturing the Pawn on d6, it is just not tasty. } 13.
Bh6
{ This not only strengthens our attack but also weakens Black's initiative. }
13... Bxh6 14. Qxh6 b5 { Black has to distract White as h4-h5 was coming. } 15.
Bxb5 Rab8 16. Qf4
{ There's no need for us to try to mate Black anymore, a Pawn up and a better position is more than enough. }
16... Ne8 17. Bxe8
{ The Bishop might be the stronger piece but the Knight was covering important dark squares. }
17... Rfxe8 18. Rxd6 Bxa2 19. Qf6
{ White's pieces are beautifully coordinated and the Queen is the skeleton - it protects everything. }
19... Bc4 20. Rhd1 Qa1+ 21. Kd2 Qxb2 22. h4
{ This is a very instructive position. At first sight, White's King is more exposed but if you take a closer look it becomes clear that it's actually the opposite! }
