1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Philidor Defense has recently gained some popularity partially thanks to the modern engines as new ideas have been generated.  The other reason is a boom of chess on the Internet - shorter time controls create opportunities to experiment with openings as the objective evaluation is not that relevant. }
3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ I am not a big fan of this setup. It feels like a Dragon but with some joker playing a prank on Black by moving a Pawn from e7 to c7.   The e-file will be less useful than the c-file - there will be no exchange sacrifice on c3, no Knight jumping to c4 and the dark squares around the black King will be weakened. }
6. Be3
{ I think it is the most natural choice here as with Black fianchettoing the Bishop, we will need to protect the Knight on d4. My only doubt was whether White should start with  6.Be3  or  6.f3  . In the end I decided it is better not to allow  6.f3  Bg7  7.Qd2  d5!?  8.e5  Nfd7  where a lot of accuracy is required from White. }
6... Ng4
{ Our choice has its price as well but I think this is anyway okay for White. }
7. Bf4 { Of course the Bishop is too expensive for such a trade. } 7... Bg7 8.
f3 Ne5
{ This is slightly unusual - it actually cost Black a tempo to transfer the Knight to e5 but it was only a target on f6... }
9. Qd2 Nbc6 10. Nxc6
{ The b-file is only an asset if Black can keep the light-squared Bishop on the board. }
10... bxc6 11. Bg5 { But not  11.Bh6??  Qh4+  and Black wins the Bishop. }
11... f6
{ Black won't be needing the diagonal anyway.  11...Qd7  is no different as we continue in the same way. }
12. Bh6 Bxh6 13. Qxh6 Qe7 14. O-O-O
{ Black might actually consider castling long and therefore we might want to move our Queen back to e3 to make this more difficult. Then the regular plans like h2-h4 or f3-f4 will be strong. }
