1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Philidor Defense has recently gained some popularity partially thanks to the modern engines as new ideas have been generated.  The other reason is a boom of chess on the Internet - shorter time controls create opportunities to experiment with openings as the objective evaluation is not that relevant. }
3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ This move has been played hundreds of times but I still don't get its point. It's not Najdorf! }
6. Bf4 { It makes even more sense now than after 5...Be7. } 6... b5
{ Clearly Black is too optimistic with this one. White's main problem is which way to an advantage he should choose. }
7. Qf3 { 7.Qe2  or  7.g3  were noteworthy alternatives. } 7... Bb7 8. O-O-O
Nbd7 { The immediate  8...g6  would be answered with  9.Nb3! } 9. g4 g6 10. h4
{ Black has a difficult decision to make, can he allow 11.h5? } 10... h5
{ 10...Bg7  11.h5  would be just horrible. It is also useful that White needs not to be afraid of b5-b4 as he has Nc3-d5. }
11. gxh5 Nxh5 12. Bg5 Be7 13. Rg1
{ Black's main problem is that both of his flanks are weak so the King will never feel safe. White might consider Nd4-b3 threatening Nb3-a5. }
