1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Philidor Defense has recently gained some popularity partially thanks to the modern engines as new ideas have been generated.  The other reason is a boom of chess on the Internet - shorter time controls create opportunities to experiment with openings as the objective evaluation is not that relevant. }
3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6
{ This move has been played hundreds of times but I still don't get its point. It's not Najdorf! }
6. Bf4 { It makes even more sense now than after 5...Be7. } 6... Be7 7. Qf3
{ White is trying to gain as much as possible. After  7.Qd2  d5!?  makes sense though the position should anyway be better for White. }
7... O-O { This natural move has a specific problem. } 8. Nf5
{ The Knight is powerful on f5 but if Black takes  8...Bxf5  9.exf5  the Pawn will be powerful as well. }
8... b5 9. O-O-O Bb7
{ It is basically a losing mistake. The Knight can't be left undisturbed. } 10.
h4 b4
{ 10...Nbd7  11.h5  would be hopeless for Black. White would play 12.Qg3 on the next move. }
11. Bh6 bxc3
{ Black can of course play  11...Ne8  instead however the simple  12.Qg4  followed by 13.Nd5 would give White a winning position. }
12. Bxg7 cxb2+ 13. Kb1 Bxe4 { All Black's hopes were based on this shot. } 14.
Bxf6 { But this leaves no doubt. Black can't take the Queen due to Nf5-h6#. }
14... Bxf5 15. Bxb2
{ The worst thing about Black's position is that he can't even sacrifice the Rook for an illusion of compensation. For example: }
15... Qd7 16. Bd3 Bxd3 17. Rxd3 { And the Rook will fall for free. } *

