{ This is the most ambitious response. White intends to castle long and start a kingside attack. f4 looks like a perfect square for the Bishop - we don't need to worry about Nf6-g4 @@StartBracket@@compared with Be3@@EndBracket@@, it also controls e5 so e4-e5 might be possible on some occasions. }
6... O-O
{ I didn't find any alternatives here, at least not the ones with a separate value - Black might of course play  6...Nc6  or  6...c6  but soon he has to castle anyway. }
7. Qd2 Nc6
{ This is the most popular continuation for Black. However, it doesn't mean it's the best. }
8. O-O-O
{ Since we castle long, opening the b-file with  8.Nxc6  bxc6  was not in our interest. }
8... Nxd4 { Other moves wouldn't change White's plan - f2-f3 and g2-g4. } 9.
Qxd4 Be6 10. f3 a6 { Black is preparing counterplay on the queenside. } 11. g4
{ This is a typical scenario for the opposite-side castling. Both sides push their Pawns to destroy the opponent's King's defense. }
11... b5 12. h4 c5 { Black has to act quickly or he will get squashed. } 13.
Qe3
{ 13.Qd2  is more popular but less accurate. After  13...b4  14.Na4   @@StartBracket@@  14.Nd5  Nxd5  15.exd5  Bd7  with unclear position.@@EndBracket@@  14...Qa5  15.b3  c4!  Black gets a decent counterplay. But how is our choice different? }
13... b4 14. Na4
{ 14.Nd5  wouldn't be that strong now as after  14...Nxd5  15.exd5  Bd7  Black  can use the a-Pawn - compare it with the13...Qa5 line where the Queen was blocking its own Pawn. With our last move, we have attacked the Pawn on c5. }
14... Qc7
{ 14...Qa5  is not so strong now -  15.b3  and if  15...c4  then there is  16.Qb6! }
15. b3 Qc6 { Black wants to play d6-d5. } 16. g5 { Why not? } 16... Nh5
{ At least this way Black can slow down White's attack. } 17. Bh2 Rfe8 18. f4
{ In this kind of position one's side advantage is almost always based on tempo. This case is no different and therefore White should play dynamically. }
18... Bf8 19. Bg2
{ White has to remove the Queen from the e-file, preferably to f2 or f3. After that, he can freely push the f-Pawn, maybe the e-Pawn as well. }
