[White "30. Philidor (3...exd4)"]
[Black "Philidor 5...Be7 − 7...c6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Philidor Defense has recently gained some popularity partially thanks to the modern engines as new ideas have been generated.  The other reason is a boom of chess on the Internet - shorter time controls create opportunities to experiment with openings as the objective evaluation is not that relevant. }
3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7
{ Summarizing Black's main plan - he might have started passively but his intentions are quite active - he would like to counterattack in the center with d6-d5 or on the Queenside with c7-c5 and b7-b5. }
6. Bf4
{ This is the most ambitious response. White intends to castle long and start a kingside attack. f4 looks like a perfect square for the Bishop - we don't need to worry about Nf6-g4 @@StartBracket@@compared with Be3@@EndBracket@@, it also controls e5 so e4-e5 might be possible on some occasions. }
6... O-O
{ I didn't find any alternatives here, at least not the ones with a separate value - Black might of course play  6...Nc6  or  6...c6  but soon he has to castle anyway. }
7. Qd2 c6 8. O-O-O d5
{ This is a lesser evil but definitely not something Black should be looking for. }
9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 { The Queen is Black's only active piece. } 11. Kb1
{ The engine prefers c2-c4, however, I don't like this move - it weakens the King, the dark squares and its strength is only based on specific lines and those can be easily forgotten. }
11... Bf6 12. Be2 Rd8
{ Black needs to chase the Knight away from d4 in order to develop the light-squared Bishop. }
13. Nb3
{ We don't mind the endgame - White is more active and his King is placed better than the opponent's. }
13... Qxd2 14. Nxd2 { The Knight is coming back to the center. } 14... Be6
{ 14...Bf5  with the idea of stopping Nd2-e4 wouldn't help - after  15.Nc4  the Knight is coming to d6 with tempo. }
15. Ne4
{ Black has to allow the trade as after  15...Be7?  16.Rxd8+  Bxd8  17.Nc5  White's initiative would become unbearable. With the Bishop pair, White will enjoy a slight but long-lasting edge.   Our long-term plan will concentrate on creating weaknesses in Black's camp and we will try to achieve that by pushing our Pawns - preferably on the queenside as there they can be supported by our King while the opposite King will struggle to join the game. }
