[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30. Philidor (3...exd4)"]
[Black "Philidor 5...Be7 − 7...c6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Philidor Defense has recently gained some popularity partially thanks to the modern engines as new ideas have been generated.  The other reason is a boom of chess on the Internet - shorter time controls create opportunities to experiment with openings as the objective evaluation is not that relevant. }
3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7
{ Summarizing Black's main plan - he might have started passively but his intentions are quite active - he would like to counterattack in the center with d6-d5 or on the Queenside with c7-c5 and b7-b5. }
6. Bf4
{ This is the most ambitious response. White intends to castle long and start a kingside attack. f4 looks like a perfect square for the Bishop - we don't need to worry about Nf6-g4 @@StartBracket@@compared with Be3@@EndBracket@@, it also controls e5 so e4-e5 might be possible on some occasions. }
6... O-O
{ I didn't find any alternatives here, at least not the ones with a separate value - Black might of course play  6...Nc6  or  6...c6  but soon he has to castle anyway. }
7. Qd2 c6 8. O-O-O b5
{ This ambitious move doesn't work. With accurate play White should be able to get a decisive advantage. }
9. f3 { Defending the central Pawn is necessary. } 9... b4
{ Where should the Knight go? } 10. Na4
{ A very important decision. White has to play actively or Black will obtain worthy counterplay. In Dominguez, L - Carlsen, M, Saint Louis Rapid and Blitz 2020,  10.Nb1?  was played and after  10...Qb6  Black's position was already great. }
10... Qa5
{ White only has a one way to defend the Knight but it's a good way. } 11. b3
{ Black's problem lies in the fact that, while he wants to play c6-c5, he has to do this now or else White will go g2-g4 and then the Knight will come to f5. After Bxf5/gxf5, the g-file will open and that should decide. }
11... c5 12. Nb5 { The immediate c6-c5 has its own flaws - d6 will fall. }
12... Bd7 13. Bxd6 { The white Knight is hanging but so is the black Bishop. }
13... Bxd6 14. Nxd6 Bxa4 15. bxa4
{ White's Pawns around the King are broken but that's okay. The Knight on d6 is effectively paralyzing the black forces while the Bishop will become a dream piece on c4. }
15... Nc6 { 15...Qxa4  16.Bc4  would be even simpler. } 16. Bc4 Nd4
{ The Knight on d4 is annoying but it's not enough to give Black real chances. }
17. Bb3
{ Now we don't need to worry about the Knight as it can always return to c4. White can continue with e4-e5 and f3-f4 with a big advantage. }
