{ The Philidor Defense has recently gained some popularity partially thanks to the modern engines as new ideas have been generated.  The other reason is a boom of chess on the Internet - shorter time controls create opportunities to experiment with openings as the objective evaluation is not that relevant. }
3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7
{ Summarizing Black's main plan - he might have started passively but his intentions are quite active - he would like to counterattack in the center with d6-d5 or on the Queenside with c7-c5 and b7-b5. }
6. Bf4
{ This is the most ambitious response. White intends to castle long and start a kingside attack. f4 looks like a perfect square for the Bishop - we don't need to worry about Nf6-g4 @@StartBracket@@compared with Be3@@EndBracket@@, it also controls e5 so e4-e5 might be possible on some occasions. }
6... O-O
{ I didn't find any alternatives here, at least not the ones with a separate value - Black might of course play  6...Nc6  or  6...c6  but soon he has to castle anyway. }
7. Qd2 d5
{ This is a very important line, perhaps a critical one - White has to be very precise but in the end he should be rewarded with a nice and safe advantage. }
8. Ndb5
{ Clearly the most critical although  8.O-O-O!?  would be a practical alternative. }
8... c6
{ Black invites the white Knight hoping to trap it on a8.  8...Na6  is practically lost after  9.exd5  c6  10.O-O-O!  and if  10...cxb5  then simply  11.d6  . }
9. Nc7 d4 { Counterattacking in the center. } 10. Nxa8
{ 10.Ne2?!  g5!  would become messy. } 10... dxc3 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. bxc3
{ I have to mention that  12.Bxb8??  would be a terrible mistake. After  12...cxb2  13.Rb1  Bb4+  14.Ke2  Nxe4  the white King finds himself in a mating net and even an extra Rook won't save him. }
12... Nxe4 13. Bd3 { Now both Knights are hanging. } 13... Bd6
{ Exchanging the darks-squared Bishop might look like an achievement as the white Bishop was controlling some critical squares - d6, c7, and b8. }
14. Bxd6 Nxd6 15. O-O-O
{ Nonetheless Black's position is hopeless - the central files are in White's hands and this will be the decisive factor. }
15... Kf8 16. Rhe1
{ I guess the most important part is not to try to escape with the Knight at any cost. Instead, White can just improve his position with a4-a5 and - if Black stays put - start pushing the Pawns on the Kingside. }
