9. O-O-O
{ Black was clearly hoping for  9.Nxc7?  d4!  Now  9...Nxe4  loses to  10.Qxd5  . }
9... Ba5
{ This is inconsistent and as such it will not be any good for Black. } 10.
exd5 a6 11. Nd4 { 11...Nxd5  will lose on the spot after  12.Nb3! } 11... Re8
{ This was tried in Edouard, R - Bauer, C - French Championship 2010. Black is strengthening the threat of Nf6-e4. }
12. Bg5 { White cuts out this possibility completely. } 12... h6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6
14. Bc4 b5
{ As Edouard pointed out in his comments to the game, this was Black's only chance. In the game Bauer went  14...Nd7  and after  15.Rhe1  White was just winning. }
15. Rhe1
{ White wants to invade the back rank using the lack of connection between the black Rooks. }
15... Rd8 { Allowing the white Rook to the 8th rank was out of the question. }
16. Be2
{ Even now White had to be careful - the rash  16.Bb3?  would create an unexpected opportunity for Black:  16...c5!  17.dxc6  Nxc6  18.Bd5!  White is lucky to have this move.  18...Qxd4  19.Qxd4  Nxd4  20.Rxd4  Ra7  with good chances of defending the endgame.   The text move leaves the b3-square for the Knight. }
16... Bb7 17. Nb3 Bb6 { The Bishop needs to cover a5 and c5. } 18. Ne4
{ This is the most straightforward although  18.f4  was also strong. } 18...
Qf5 19. Nec5 Bxd5 20. Nb7
{ Black has to give up an exchange as  20...Rd7  loses to  21.Bd3  . } *

