{ Black is winning the central Pawn with tempo - this actually looks scary! }
11. Qd4
{ It is important to understand why  11.Qe3  wouldn't be as strong - you will find an explanation to that in the comments to  11...Nxc3  12.bxc3  Ba3+  13.Kb1  Na6  . }
11... Nxc3 { Black will try to use his Bishop pair. } 12. bxc3 Ba3+ 13. Kb1 Be6
{ 13...Bg4  14.f3  Be6  wouldn't make any difference as White reacts in the same way. }
14. Nxa8 Qa5 { Black is threatening c6-c5. } 15. Bd2
{ Other moves lead to complete chaos. White intends to play c3-c4 basically after anything. }
15... Na6
{ In accordance with my statement - on  15...c5  go  16.c4!  and on @@StartFEN@@Nn3rk1/pp3ppp/2p1b3/q2p4/3Q4/b1P5/P1PB1PPP/1K1R1B1R b - - 2 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Bc5  we go  16.c4!  as well. }
16. c4 Bb4
{ 16...Nb4  17.Bc3  is just winning for White. After  17...f6  18.Bd3  @@StartBracket@@which is far from the only move@@EndBracket@@ Black's pieces on the Queenside only disturb each other. }
17. cxd5
{ The attack fizzles out and White will be able to simplify the position. }
17... Bxd5 18. Bxb4 Nxb4 19. Bc4
{ So the dust has settled and Black is left with material losses. There's still some practical compensation, bad it's no longer scary for White. }
19... Bxc4
{ After  19...Rxa8  White simply replies with  20.Bxd5  Nxd5  21.Kb2  with big advantage. }
20. Qxc4 b5 21. Qb3 Nd5 { This is stronger than  21...Rxa8  22.Rd6! } 22. Rd3
Rxa8 23. c4
{ Breaking up the black Pawns is very important. Now c6 will be weak and this is not just a Pawn - it supports the Knight on d5 or - if I can put it in more descriptive way - it maintains Black's hopes of staying alive...  It is also important that we don't really weaken the position of the King as the Rook covers all the important squares on the 3rd rank and it is also ready to cover the b-file as well. }
23... bxc4 24. Qxc4
{ White will hide the King on a1 and then the other Rook may join the game. } *

