12. bxc3 Qe7 { The Queen wants to come to a3. } 13. Kb2
{ This is a huge mistake. Do you remember g7-g5? Let's try it again. } 13... g5
14. Bg3 Nxg3 15. hxg3 Qxc7 16. Qf6
{ So the only difference, compared with 12...g5 is that White has his King on b2 instead of c1. How relevant can it be?! }
16... Qb6+ 17. Kc1 c5 { Quite relevant, it appears. } 18. Qxg5+ Qg6
{ White has almost no compensation for the piece. It is a really nice example of how little nuances can decide the outcome of a game. It is also another proof of why the ability to calculate lines precisely @@StartBracket@@and studying my opening courses ;@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@ is essential in chess. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30. Philidor (3...exd4)"]
[Black "Philidor 5...Be7 − 7...d5 #14"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Philidor Defense has recently gained some popularity partially thanks to the modern engines as new ideas have been generated.  The other reason is a boom of chess on the Internet - shorter time controls create opportunities to experiment with openings as the objective evaluation is not that relevant. }
3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7
{ Summarizing Black's main plan - he might have started passively but his intentions are quite active - he would like to counterattack in the center with d6-d5 or on the Queenside with c7-c5 and b7-b5. }
6. Bf4
{ This is the most ambitious response. White intends to castle long and start a kingside attack. f4 looks like a perfect square for the Bishop - we don't need to worry about Nf6-g4 @@StartBracket@@compared with Be3@@EndBracket@@, it also controls e5 so e4-e5 might be possible on some occasions. }
6... O-O
{ I didn't find any alternatives here, at least not the ones with a separate value - Black might of course play  6...Nc6  or  6...c6  but soon he has to castle anyway. }
7. Qd2 d5
{ This is a very important line, perhaps a critical one - White has to be very precise but in the end he should be rewarded with a nice and safe advantage. }
8. Ndb5
{ Clearly the most critical although  8.O-O-O!?  would be a practical alternative. }
8... Bb4
{ The sharpest and the strongest continuation. Remembering this line is a key element of our Philidor repertoire.   Otherwise, you might experience thoughts that I know too well from my experience - 'but what if he goes for the 7...d5 line??'. It is very important to feel confident about our opening especially when the line is sharp. }
9. O-O-O
{ Black was clearly hoping for  9.Nxc7?  d4!  Now  9...Nxe4  loses to  10.Qxd5  . }
9... c6 { This is critical. } 10. Nc7 Nxe4
{ Black is winning the central Pawn with tempo - this actually looks scary! }
11. Qd4
{ It is important to understand why  11.Qe3  wouldn't be as strong - you will find an explanation to that in the comments to  11...Nxc3  12.bxc3  Ba3+  13.Kb1  Na6  . }
11... Bxc3
{ The main line of the main line. Black will try to use his powerful Knight. }
12. bxc3 Qe7 { The Queen wants to come to a3. } 13. c4
{ We are trying to undermine Black's position in the center. At the same time the Queen can now defend the King. }
13... Qa3+
{ 13...g5  doesn't work now as White can simply play  14.cxd5  gxf4  15.d6!  with a winning position. }
14. Qb2 Qa5 { Black can't allow to trade Queens. } 15. cxd5
{ There are a few good moves here but this is the cleanest one. } 15... Nxf2
16. Be2 Nxh1 { This is inaccurate. } 17. Rxh1
{ Now Black can't go  17...Na6  as White would simply take  18.Bxa6  bxa6  19.Nxa8  . In other words White benefits from keeping the Knight on c7 for a bit longer. }
17... Bf5 { The only way to stay in the game. } 18. Nxa8 Re8
{ White still has to be precise in order to get the most of the position. } 19.
Bf3 Na6 { 19...Re1+  is not a problem -  20.Rxe1  Qxe1  21.Bd1  . } 20. Bd2
{ This way we will be able to activate our Rook. } 20... Qc5
{ It might seem as Black can stay in the game with this - our Queen is tied to the Pawn and therefore the Knight seems lost. }
21. Re1 { White is using his time to activate the Rook. } 21... Rxa8 22. Re5
{ One might think that White is simply lucky to have this shot but I believe this is the essence of chess. Had the Knight been on the more natural d7-square, White wouldn't have had the square on e5 for the Rook.   Had the Bishop been protected... White's latest move is the result of a few nuances that are now working in White's favor.   The beauty of this move makes it look like a happy coincidence but this is just our perception - mathematically it is not different than any other move. }
22... Qg1+ 23. Bd1
{ If Black moves  23...Bg4  then the Rook comes back, after  24.Re1  Black can resign as Qb2xb7 is on the way. }
*

