[Black "Pirc/Modern 2...g6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7
{ The main point of the Modern Defense is to delay Ng8-f6. Whether it's useful is another story. }
4. Be3
{ The exclamation mark is for the integrity of our repertoire - in many lines Modern will transpose directly to Pirc which makes absorbing these lines easier. }
4... a6
{ Usually, this is the point of delaying Ng8-f6. Black wants to go b7-b5 but avoid e4-e5. }
5. Qd2
{ Of course there are other moves too but it seemed so simple for White and Wesley So did it too, I mean he can't be wrong, can he? }
5... b5 6. O-O-O Nd7
{ Black is trying to be as flexible as possible but at the same time he forgot to provoke f2-f3. }
7. h4
{ Already first differences appear -  7...Ngf6  would be met with  8.e5!  Ng4  9.h5  with a very strong attack. }
7... h5 8. Nh3
{ Maybe we can even skip f2-f3 completely? By the way, developing the Knight to h3 is one of the key ideas of this system. }
8... Nb6
{ 8...Bb7  9.Ng5  would be just better for White. The point of Black's last move is that after b4/Ne2 he wants to have Nc4. }
9. Bd3 { The previous note explains why we want the Bishop on d3. } 9... Nf6
10. f3
{ If Black doesn't take on h3 then we bring the Knight to g5. If he does - we will try to achieve e4-e5 - blocking his dark-squared Bishop. }
