1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3
{ The Classical System has never been doing better against the Pirc. Black seems to be struggling everywhere, while the main challenge for White is that it is quite easy to mix up some moves in the beginning.   With his last move, White develops the piece to a natural square. We can feel that the exciting long castle is coming, but what I like about this line is its flexibility - we can easily adapt to Black's plans so whenever it suits us, we can also castle short. }
4... c6 5. h3 Bg7
{ I don't think that including c7-c6 and h2-h3 is a success for Black. } 6. f4
{ As usual, this is not the only good continuation.  6.a4  e5  7.Nf3  is also possible, leading to a different game. }
6... O-O 7. Nf3
{ Black's opening is a failure - he can't stop e4-e5 which makes c7-c6 pointless. }
7... Nbd7 8. e5 Nd5 9. Nxd5 cxd5 10. Bd3 Qb6
{ Attacking on b2 and also dreaming of White blundering on e5. } 11. Qc1
{ Defending both Pawns. The more aggressive  11.Qd2  would be also possible - if Black takes the Pawn with  11...Qxb2  then we castle short and attack on the Kingside. If not - then we can castle long. }
11... dxe5 12. dxe5 Nc5 13. O-O
{ We want to move the Rook to d1 for instance  13...Bd7  14.Rd1  , threatening Bd3-e2,  14...Nxd3  15.Rxd3  the Rook is well placed on d3. }
13... Nxd3 14. cxd3 Qa6 15. Qd2
{ White is clearly better - we are not afraid of  15...Bf5  16.Rfd1  . The Bishop won't hold on f5 - we should block the d4-square - in my opinion, it's better to use the Bishop, then we can think of g2-g4. Black has weak dark squares and both his Bishops are passive. One more thing - if he ever plays e7-e6 then Nh2-g4 may be useful. }
