[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31. Pirc/Modern Defense"]
[Black "Pirc/Modern 2...Nf6 − 4...c6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3
{ The Classical System has never been doing better against the Pirc. Black seems to be struggling everywhere, while the main challenge for White is that it is quite easy to mix up some moves in the beginning.   With his last move, White develops the piece to a natural square. We can feel that the exciting long castle is coming, but what I like about this line is its flexibility - we can easily adapt to Black's plans so whenever it suits us, we can also castle short. }
4... c6 5. h3 b5
{ The point of this move is to put the Pawn on b5 before White prevents it with a2-a4. }
6. a3
{ 6.e5  b4!  turns out to be quite playable for Black but what I like about the whole line is that after some natural move like 6.Bd3 White is just better, it feels like choosing a cookie from the cookie jar. }
6... Nbd7 7. f4 { 7.Nf3  would be also fine. } 7... e5 8. Nf3
{ The e5-Pawn requires protection. } 8... Qc7 9. Qd2
{ We might castle long but this is not the purpose of our last move. The Queen is simply useful on d2. }
9... Bg7 10. g4 { There is no attack yet but we are gaining space. } 10... O-O
{ It's the best thing Black can do. } 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. f5
{ After  12...Rd8  the Queen can go to g2. If Black tries  12...a5  then it's best to go  13.Bd3  and castle long. The Queen can be placed on f2 from where it controls c5 and creates some pressure on the f-file. It can also move to h4. We should be very careful with g4-g4 and f5-f6 - as nice as it looks it won't do any good if Black can retreat the Bishop to f8. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31. Pirc/Modern Defense"]
[Black "Pirc/Modern 2...Nf6 − 4...a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3
{ The Classical System has never been doing better against the Pirc. Black seems to be struggling everywhere, while the main challenge for White is that it is quite easy to mix up some moves in the beginning.   With his last move, White develops the piece to a natural square. We can feel that the exciting long castle is coming, but what I like about this line is its flexibility - we can easily adapt to Black's plans so whenever it suits us, we can also castle short. }
4... a6
{ Black wants to start a fight on the Queenside with b7-b5. One of my favorite bullet plans @@StartBracket@@naturally scores badly@@EndBracket@@. }
5. h3
{ It is a rare case for Pirc players when they are invited to play b7-b5 but can't really accept the invitation. With our last move, we have covered the g4-square making e4-e5 a serious idea. }
5... Nbd7
{ Black gives up on b7-b5 @@StartBracket@@for now@@EndBracket@@ and switches to the e7-e5 plan. }
6. Nf3
{ 4.Be3 was flexible and so is 5.h3 - covering g4 is useful for a short castle setup as Black won't be able to harass us with Nf6-g4. }
6... e5
{ It was already too late for  6...b5  -  7.e5!  Black has no good reply. } 7.
Bc4
{ Those of you who would prefer to see some fire on the board are free to go  7.g4!? }
7... b5 { This leads to serious troubles for Black. } 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Bd5 Rb8
{ Naturally Black can't take  9...Nxd5  as  10.Qxd5  forks the Rook and the e5-Pawn. }
10. Bc6 { Because of the Nf3xe5 threat Black has to give up on fianchettoing. }
10... Bd6 11. Bh6
{ It was already possible to grab an exchange with  11.Ba7  but after  11...O-O  12.Bxd7  Bxd7  13.Bxb8  Qxb8  Black would get some practical compensation. }
11... Rb6
{ Or  11...Bb7  12.Bxb7  Rxb7  13.O-O  with a practically winning advantage. }
12. Bxd7+ Nxd7 { 13...Bxd7??  14.Bg7!  Rg8  15.Bxf6  Qxf6  16.Nd5  +- } 13. Nd5
Rb8 14. Qd2
{ We will make the long castle after all. White has an enormous advantage as Black is struggling to finish his development without material losses. }
