[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31. Pirc/Modern Defense"]
[Black "Pirc/Modern 2...Nf6 − 4...a6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3
{ The Classical System has never been doing better against the Pirc. Black seems to be struggling everywhere, while the main challenge for White is that it is quite easy to mix up some moves in the beginning.   With his last move, White develops the piece to a natural square. We can feel that the exciting long castle is coming, but what I like about this line is its flexibility - we can easily adapt to Black's plans so whenever it suits us, we can also castle short. }
4... a6
{ Black wants to start a fight on the Queenside with b7-b5. One of my favorite bullet plans @@StartBracket@@naturally scores badly@@EndBracket@@. }
5. h3
{ It is a rare case for Pirc players when they are invited to play b7-b5 but can't really accept the invitation. With our last move, we have covered the g4-square making e4-e5 a serious idea. }
5... b5
{ We will now learn a cool thing abut Be3 and h3, that we don't really see in other lines. }
6. e5 Nfd7 7. Qf3
{ Quite an unusual square for the Queen! It is now attacking the Rook and preventing Bc8-b7. }
7... Nb6
{ 7...c6  8.Qg3  and White can support the e5-Pawn with f2-f4. Black's position is ugly. }
8. a4
{ After eight moves Black still has almost all his pieces in the starting positions. Still has managed to create some weak squares in his camp. We will take advantage of that. }
8... bxa4
{ 8...b4?  9.Ne4  would be even worse - White is threatening 10.Ng5 as well as 10.a5. }
9. Nxa4 c6
{ Black has secured the Rook and covered some light squares too but now we will use the dark ones. }
10. exd6 exd6 11. Nxb6 Qxb6 12. Qf6 { Black is doing badly on both sides. }
12... Qxb2 13. Rc1 Rg8 14. Nf3
{ I don't think that the term 'compensation' fully reflects our position. We will simply finish our development with Bd3 or Be2 and castle short. }
