{ It is not a very good plan - White is more than ready to meet e7-e5. } 6. f3
O-O { This makes everything even easier than it already was. } 7. O-O-O e5 8.
d5 Nd4 { 8...Ne7  9.g4  would be strategically winning for White. } 9. Nge2
{ We can never take on d4 with the Bishop - the dark squares are too important. }
9... c5
{ A Pawn sacrifice - Black is hoping to get some compensation on the Queenside. The alternative  9...Nxe2+  10.Nxe2  would be hopeless as White would simply advance the Pawns on the Kingside with Black left without any counterplay. }
10. dxc6 bxc6 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Bxd4 Be6
{ White's position looks great but we still need to be careful - one lousy move such as  13.Be2?!  and after  13...Rb8  White is not doing so well any longer. }
13. Na4
{ There are a couple of arguments supporting this weird-looking move. The Knight is freeing up the c3-square for the Bishop which might be useful in case of c6-c5. Our Queen now controls the a5-square which means that Black can't activate his own Queen.   We want to place the Pawn on b3 which works well with Na4 - it might come to b2 at some point, protecting the c4-square  @@StartBracket@@preventing Black from playing c5-c4@@EndBracket@@. }
