1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3
{ The Classical System has never been doing better against the Pirc. Black seems to be struggling everywhere, while the main challenge for White is that it is quite easy to mix up some moves in the beginning.   With his last move, White develops the piece to a natural square. We can feel that the exciting long castle is coming, but what I like about this line is its flexibility - we can easily adapt to Black's plans so whenever it suits us, we can also castle short. }
4... Bg7
{ The coolest reaction to 4.Be3 - Black keeps all options on the table while making the move that has to be made anyway. }
5. Qd2
{ We are intending to castle long but this move does not burn any bridges so - depending on Black's reaction - we can still castle short too! }
5... Nc6
{ It is not a very good plan - White is more than ready to meet e7-e5. } 6. f3
e5 7. d5 Ne7
{ It makes a bit more sense now as White can't simply attack on the Kingside.  7...Nd4  8.Nge2  c5  wouldn't make any sense as we didn't even castle yet. }
8. O-O-O { Stopping c7-c6 is a nice bonus. } 8... a6
{ Now Black doesn't need to worry about Bb5+ - remember, that the exchange of the light-squared Bishop is good for White. }
9. Bh6
{ I would normally prefer to keep the dark-squared Bishops on the board but it's the best way to make progress. }
9... Bxh6 10. Qxh6 Nh5
{ Black is hoping to neutralize White's initiative using the dark squares. }
11. Nge2 { But it's not enough, his pieces are too passive. } 11... f5 12. exf5
Nxf5 13. Qd2
{ After  13...Nf6  we can go  14.h4!  preparing 15.g4. It is actually a very nice positional exercise.   13...Nf6  14.g4?!  Nh4!  would spoil everything - Black is actually setting up a successful blockade using just one dark square - h4. }
