1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3
{ The Classical System has never been doing better against the Pirc. Black seems to be struggling everywhere, while the main challenge for White is that it is quite easy to mix up some moves in the beginning.   With his last move, White develops the piece to a natural square. We can feel that the exciting long castle is coming, but what I like about this line is its flexibility - we can easily adapt to Black's plans so whenever it suits us, we can also castle short. }
4... Bg7
{ The coolest reaction to 4.Be3 - Black keeps all options on the table while making the move that has to be made anyway. }
5. Qd2
{ We are intending to castle long but this move does not burn any bridges so - depending on Black's reaction - we can still castle short too! }
5... Ng4
{ Played over a thousand times yet poses no real challenge for White. } 6. Bg5
h6 7. Bh4
{ OK, one thing that Black has achieved is that now we have to forget about the h2-h4 plan. We do have other ideas, though. }
7... g5
{ According to my sources this move has been played at least 226 times, that's 226 too many. }
8. Bg3
{ Black has already weakened some light squares and in order to stay in the game he has to weaken some more. }
8... e5 { Otherwise we would kick the Knight back with f2-f3. } 9. d5
{ The Bishop on g7 is not exactly a monster. } 9... h5
{ Black does whatever he can to get some activity. } 10. h4 Bh6 11. Qe2
{ It's a rare case to see - the ugliest square for the Queen turns out to be the best. The point is that we will want to castle long soon so Qd1 had to be rejected. As for the Qd3 - I didn't like Nb8-a6-c5 attacking the Queen. }
11... Qf6 { Black is anticipating our next move. } 12. Nf3 gxh4 13. Bxh4
{ This would be a much bigger problem for Black if his Queen was still on d8. }
13... Qg6 14. Nd2
{ We will finally castle and hide the King on b1 unpinning the Knight. Black's position is horrible. }
